[3609.234974, "o", "BASH(1)              General Commands Manual             BASH(1)\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[1mNAME\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n       bash - GNU Bourne-Again SHell\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[1mSYNOPSIS\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n       \u001b[1mbash\u001b[0m [options] [command_string | file]\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[1mCOPYRIGHT\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n       Bash  is  Copyright  (C)  1989-2022  by the Free Software\u001b[m\r\n       Foundation, Inc.\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[1mDESCRIPTION\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n       \u001b[1mBash\u001b[0m is an  \u001b[1msh\u001b[0m-compatible  command  language  interpreter\u001b[m\r\n       that  executes  commands  read from the standard input or\u001b[m\r\n       from a file.  \u001b[1mBash\u001b[0m also incorporates useful features from\u001b[m\r\n       the \u001b[4mKorn\u001b[24m and \u001b[4mC\u001b[24m shells (\u001b[1mksh\u001b[0m and \u001b[1mcsh\u001b[0m).\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[7m Manual page bash(1) line 1 (press h for help or q to quit)\u001b[27m\u001b[K"]
[3612.5524, "o", "...skipping...\r\nBASH(1)              General Commands Manual             BASH(1)\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[1mNAME\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n       bash - GNU Bourne-Again SHell\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[1mSYNOPSIS\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n       \u001b[1mbash\u001b[0m [options] [command_string | file]\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[1mCOPYRIGHT\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n       Bash  is  Copyright  (C)  1989-2022  by the Free Software\u001b[m\r\n       Foundation, Inc.\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[1mDESCRIPTION\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n       \u001b[1mBash\u001b[0m is an  \u001b[1msh\u001b[0m-compatible  command  language  interpreter\u001b[m\r\n       that  executes  commands  read from the standard input or\u001b[m\r\n       from a file.  \u001b[1mBash\u001b[0m also incorporates useful features from\u001b[m\r\n       the \u001b[4mKorn\u001b[24m and \u001b[4mC\u001b[24m shells (\u001b[1mksh\u001b[0m and \u001b[1mcsh\u001b[0m).\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n       \u001b[1mBash\u001b[0m is intended to be a conformant implementation of the\u001b[m\r\n       Shell and Utilities portion of the IEEE POSIX  specifica‐\u001b[m\r\n       tion  (IEEE  Standard 1003.1).  \u001b[1mBash\u001b[0m can be configured to\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[7m Manual page bash(1) line 1 (press h for help or q to quit)\u001b[27m\u001b[K"]
[3612.653671, "o", "\u001b[H\u001b[2J\u001b[H\u001b[H\u001b[2J\u001b[HBASH(1)              General Commands Manual             BASH(1)\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[1mNAME\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n       bash - GNU Bourne-Again SHell\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[1mSYNOPSIS\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n       \u001b[1mbash\u001b[0m [options] [command_string | file]\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[1mCOPYRIGHT\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n       Bash  is  Copyright  (C)  1989-2022  by the Free Software\u001b[m\r\n       Foundation, Inc.\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[1mDESCRIPTION\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n       \u001b[1mBash\u001b[0m is an  \u001b[1msh\u001b[0m-compatible  command  language  interpreter\u001b[m\r\n       that  executes  commands  read from the standard input or\u001b[m\r\n       from a file.  \u001b[1mBash\u001b[0m also incorporates useful features from\u001b[m\r\n       the \u001b[4mKorn\u001b[24m and \u001b[4mC\u001b[24m shells (\u001b[1mksh\u001b[0m and \u001b[1mcsh\u001b[0m).\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n       \u001b[1mBash\u001b[0m is intended to be a conformant implementation of the\u001b[m\r\n       Shell and Utilities portion of the IEEE POSIX  specifica‐\u001b[m\r\n       tion  (IEEE  Standard 1003.1).  \u001b[1mBash\u001b[0m can be configured to\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[7m Manual page bash(1) line 1 (press h for help or q to quit)\u001b[27m\u001b[K"]
[3613.442806, "o", "...skipping...\r\nBASH(1)              General Commands Manual             BASH(1)\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[1mNAME\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n       bash - GNU Bourne-Again SHell\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[1mSYNOPSIS\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n       \u001b[1mbash\u001b[0m [options] [command_string | file]\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[1mCOPYRIGHT\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n       Bash  is  Copyright  (C)  1989-2022  by the Free Software\u001b[m\r\n       Foundation, Inc.\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[1mDESCRIPTION\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n       \u001b[1mBash\u001b[0m is an  \u001b[1msh\u001b[0m-compatible  command  language  interpreter\u001b[m\r\n       that  executes  commands  read from the standard input or\u001b[m\r\n       from a file.  \u001b[1mBash\u001b[0m also incorporates useful features from\u001b[m\r\n       the \u001b[4mKorn\u001b[24m and \u001b[4mC\u001b[24m shells (\u001b[1mksh\u001b[0m and \u001b[1mcsh\u001b[0m).\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n       \u001b[1mBash\u001b[0m is intended to be a conformant implementation of the\u001b[m\r\n       Shell and Utilities portion of the IEEE POSIX  specifica‐\u001b[m\r\n       tion  (IEEE  Standard 1003.1).  \u001b[1mBash\u001b[0m can be configured to\u001b[m\r\n       be POSIX-conformant by default.\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[1mOPTIONS\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n       All of the single-cha"]
[3613.442919, "o", "racter shell options  documented  in\u001b[m\r\n       the description of the \u001b[1mset\u001b[0m builtin command, including \u001b[1m-o\u001b[0m,\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[7m Manual page bash(1) line 1 (press h for help or q to quit)\u001b[27m\u001b[K"]
[3613.546486, "o", "\u001b[H\u001b[2J\u001b[H\u001b[H\u001b[2J\u001b[HBASH(1)              General Commands Manual             BASH(1)\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[1mNAME\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n       bash - GNU Bourne-Again SHell\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[1mSYNOPSIS\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n       \u001b[1mbash\u001b[0m [options] [command_string | file]\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[1mCOPYRIGHT\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n       Bash  is  Copyright  (C)  1989-2022  by the Free Software\u001b[m\r\n       Foundation, Inc.\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[1mDESCRIPTION\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n       \u001b[1mBash\u001b[0m is an  \u001b[1msh\u001b[0m-compatible  command  language  interpreter\u001b[m\r\n       that  executes  commands  read from the standard input or\u001b[m\r\n       from a file.  \u001b[1mBash\u001b[0m also incorporates useful features from\u001b[m\r\n       the \u001b[4mKorn\u001b[24m and \u001b[4mC\u001b[24m shells (\u001b[1mksh\u001b[0m and \u001b[1mcsh\u001b[0m).\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n       \u001b[1mBash\u001b[0m is intended to be a conformant implementation of the\u001b[m\r\n       Shell and Utilities portion of the IEEE POSIX  specifica‐\u001b[m\r\n       tion  (IEEE  Standard 1003.1).  \u001b[1mBash\u001b[0m can be configured to\u001b[m\r\n       be POSIX-conformant by default.\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[1mOPTIONS\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n       All of the single"]
[3613.546512, "o", "-character shell options  documented  in\u001b[m\r\n       the description of the \u001b[1mset\u001b[0m builtin command, including \u001b[1m-o\u001b[0m,\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[7m Manual page bash(1) line 1 (press h for help or q to quit)\u001b[27m\u001b[K"]
[3617.409136, "o", "\r\u001b[K"]
[3617.409278, "o", "       can be used as options when the shell is invoked.  In ad‐\u001b[m\r\n       dition,  \u001b[1mbash\u001b[0m interprets the following options when it is\u001b[m\r\n       invoked:\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n       \u001b[1m-c\u001b[0m        If the \u001b[1m-c\u001b[0m option is present, then commands  are\u001b[m\r\n                 read  from  the  first non-option argument \u001b[4mcom‐\u001b[24m\u001b[m\r\n                 \u001b[4mmand_string\u001b[24m.  If there are arguments after  the\u001b[m\r\n                 \u001b[4mcommand_string\u001b[24m,  the first argument is assigned\u001b[m\r\n                 to \u001b[1m$0\u001b[0m and any remaining arguments are  assigned\u001b[m\r\n                 to  the  positional parameters.  The assignment\u001b[m\r\n                 to \u001b[1m$0\u001b[0m sets the name of the shell, which is used\u001b[m\r\n                 in warning and error messages.\u001b[m\r\n       \u001b[1m-i\u001b[0m        If  the  \u001b[1m-i\u001b[0m option is present, the shell is \u001b[4min‐\u001b[24m\u001b[m\r\n                 \u001b[4mteractive\u001b[24m.\u001b[m\r\n       \u001b[1m-l\u001b[0m        Make \u001b[1mbash\u001b[0m act as if it had been  invoked  as  a\u001b[m\r\n                 login shell (see"]
[3617.409293, "o", " \u001b[1mINVOCATION\u001b[0m below).\u001b[m\r\n       \u001b[1m-r\u001b[0m        If  the \u001b[1m-r\u001b[0m option is present, the shell becomes\u001b[m\r\n                 \u001b[4mrestricted\u001b[24m (see \u001b[1mRESTRICTED\u001b[0m \u001b[1mSHELL\u001b[0m below).\u001b[m\r\n       \u001b[1m-s\u001b[0m        If the \u001b[1m-s\u001b[0m option is present, or if no arguments\u001b[m\r\n                 remain  after  option processing, then commands\u001b[m\r\n                 are read from the standard input.  This  option\u001b[m\r\n                 allows the positional parameters to be set when\u001b[m\r\n                 invoking an interactive shell or  when  reading\u001b[m\r\n                 input through a pipe.\u001b[m\r\n       \u001b[1m-v\u001b[0m        Print shell input lines as they are read.\u001b[m\r\n       \u001b[1m-x\u001b[0m        Print  commands and their arguments as they are\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[7m Manual page bash(1) line 27 (press h for help or q to quit)\u001b[27m\u001b[K"]
[3617.520618, "o", "\r\u001b[K"]
[3617.520651, "o", "                 executed.\u001b[m\r\n       \u001b[1m-D\u001b[0m        A list of all double-quoted strings preceded by\u001b[m\r\n                 \u001b[1m$\u001b[0m is printed on the standard output.  These are\u001b[m\r\n                 the strings that are subject to language trans‐\u001b[m\r\n                 lation  when  the  current  locale  is not \u001b[1mC\u001b[0m or\u001b[m\r\n                 \u001b[1mPOSIX\u001b[0m.  This implies the \u001b[1m-n\u001b[0m option; no commands\u001b[m\r\n                 will be executed.\u001b[m\r\n       \u001b[1m[-+]O\u001b[0m \u001b[1m[\u001b[0m\u001b[4mshopt_option\u001b[24m\u001b[1m]\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n                 \u001b[4mshopt_option\u001b[24m  is  one  of the shell options ac‐\u001b[m\r\n                 cepted by the \u001b[1mshopt\u001b[0m builtin (see \u001b[1mSHELL\u001b[0m  \u001b[1mBUILTIN\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n                 \u001b[1mCOMMANDS\u001b[0m  below).   If \u001b[4mshopt_option\u001b[24m is present,\u001b[m\r\n                 \u001b[1m-O\u001b[0m sets the value of that option; \u001b[1m+O\u001b[0m unsets it.\u001b[m\r\n                 If  \u001b[4mshopt_option\u001b[24m is not supplied, the names and\u001b[m\r\n                 values of the shell options accepted  by  \u001b[1mshopt\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n   "]
[3617.520655, "o", "              are printed on the standard output.  If the in‐\u001b[m\r\n                 vocation option is \u001b[1m+O\u001b[0m, the output is  displayed\u001b[m\r\n                 in a format that may be reused as input.\u001b[m\r\n       \u001b[1m--\u001b[0m        A  \u001b[1m--\u001b[0m  signals  the end of options and disables\u001b[m\r\n                 further option processing.  Any arguments after\u001b[m\r\n                 the  \u001b[1m--\u001b[0m are treated as filenames and arguments.\u001b[m\r\n                 An argument of \u001b[1m-\u001b[0m is equivalent to \u001b[1m--\u001b[0m.\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n       \u001b[1mBash\u001b[0m also interprets a number of multi-character options.\u001b[m\r\n       These  options must appear on the command line before the\u001b[m\r\n       single-character options to be recognized.\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[7m Manual page bash(1) line 53 (press h for help or q to quit)\u001b[27m\u001b[K"]
[3618.128734, "o", "\r\u001b[K       \u001b[1m--debugger\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n              Arrange for the debugger profile  to  be  executed\u001b[m\r\n              before the shell starts.  Turns on extended debug‐\u001b[m\r\n              ging mode (see the description of the \u001b[1mextdebug\u001b[0m op‐\u001b[m\r\n              tion to the \u001b[1mshopt\u001b[0m builtin below).\u001b[m\r\n       \u001b[1m--dump-po-strings\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n              Equivalent  to  \u001b[1m-D\u001b[0m,  but  the output is in the GNU\u001b[m\r\n              \u001b[4mgettext\u001b[24m \u001b[1mpo\u001b[0m (portable object) file format.\u001b[m\r\n       \u001b[1m--dump-strings\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n              Equivalent to \u001b[1m-D\u001b[0m.\u001b[m\r\n       \u001b[1m--help\u001b[0m Display a usage message  on  standard  output  and\u001b[m\r\n              exit successfully.\u001b[m\r\n       \u001b[1m--init-file\u001b[0m \u001b[4mfile\u001b[24m\u001b[m\r\n       \u001b[1m--rcfile\u001b[0m \u001b[4mfile\u001b[24m\u001b[m\r\n              Execute  commands  from \u001b[4mfile\u001b[24m instead of the system\u001b[m\r\n              wide initialization file \u001b[4m/etc/bash.bashrc\u001b[24m and  the\u001b[m\r\n              standard personal initialization file \u001b[4m~/.bashrc\u001b[24m if\u001b[m\r\n       "]
[3618.128763, "o", "       the shell is interactive (see \u001b[1mINVOCATION\u001b[0m below).\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n       \u001b[1m--login\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n              Equivalent to \u001b[1m-l\u001b[0m.\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n       \u001b[1m--noediting\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n              Do not use the GNU \u001b[1mreadline\u001b[0m library to  read  com‐\u001b[m\r\n              mand lines when the shell is interactive.\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[7m Manual page bash(1) line 79 (press h for help or q to quit)\u001b[27m\u001b[K"]
[3618.630123, "o", "\r\u001b[K       \u001b[1m--noprofile\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n              Do  not  read  either the system-wide startup file\u001b[m\r\n              \u001b[4m/etc/profile\u001b[24m or any of the personal initialization\u001b[m\r\n              files  \u001b[4m~/.bash_profile\u001b[24m,  \u001b[4m~/.bash_login\u001b[24m, or \u001b[4m~/.pro‐\u001b[24m\u001b[m\r\n              \u001b[4mfile\u001b[24m.  By default, \u001b[1mbash\u001b[0m reads these files when  it\u001b[m\r\n              is  invoked  as  a login shell (see \u001b[1mINVOCATION\u001b[0m be‐\u001b[m\r\n              low).\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n       \u001b[1m--norc\u001b[0m Do not read and execute the system  wide  initial‐\u001b[m\r\n              ization  file  \u001b[4m/etc/bash.bashrc\u001b[24m  and  the personal\u001b[m\r\n              initialization file \u001b[4m~/.bashrc\u001b[24m if the shell is  in‐\u001b[m\r\n              teractive.   This  option  is on by default if the\u001b[m\r\n              shell is invoked as \u001b[1msh\u001b[0m.\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n       \u001b[1m--posix\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n              Change the behavior of \u001b[1mbash\u001b[0m where the default  op‐\u001b[m\r\n              eration  differs  from the POSIX standard to match\u001b[m\r\n              "]
[3618.630149, "o", "the standard (\u001b[4mpo"]
[3618.630215, "o", "six\u001b[24m \u001b[4mmode\u001b[24m).  See \u001b[1mSEE\u001b[0m \u001b[1mALSO\u001b[0m below for\u001b[m\r\n              a  reference  to a document that details how posix\u001b[m\r\n              mode affects bash's behavior.\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n       \u001b[1m--restricted\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n              The shell becomes restricted (see \u001b[1mRESTRICTED\u001b[0m \u001b[1mSHELL\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n              below).\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n       \u001b[1m--verbose\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[7m Manual page bash(1) line 105 (press h for help or q to quit)\u001b[27m\u001b[K"]
[3618.661474, "o", "\r\u001b[K"]
[3618.661638, "o", "              Equivalent to \u001b[1m-v\u001b[0m.\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n       \u001b[1m--version\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n              Show version information for this instance of \u001b[1mbash\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n              on the standard output and exit successfully.\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[1mARGUMENTS\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n       If arguments remain after option processing, and  neither\u001b[m\r\n       the \u001b[1m-c\u001b[0m nor the \u001b[1m-s\u001b[0m option has been supplied, the first ar‐\u001b[m\r\n       gument is assumed to be the name  of  a  file  containing\u001b[m\r\n       shell  commands.   If \u001b[1mbash\u001b[0m is invoked in this fashion, \u001b[1m$0\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n       is set to the name of the file, and the positional param‐\u001b[m\r\n       eters are set to the remaining arguments.  \u001b[1mBash\u001b[0m reads and\u001b[m\r\n       executes commands from this  file,  then  exits.   \u001b[1mBash\u001b[0m's\u001b[m\r\n       exit  status  is the exit status of the last command exe‐\u001b[m\r\n       cuted in the script.  If no commands  are  executed,  the\u001b[m\r\n       exit  status  is 0.  An attempt is first made to open the\u001b[m\r\n       file in the current directo"]
[3618.661684, "o", "ry, and, if no file is  found,\u001b[m\r\n       then  the  shell searches the directories in \u001b[1mPATH\u001b[0m for the\u001b[m\r\n       script.\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[1mINVOCATION\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n       A \u001b[4mlogin\u001b[24m \u001b[4mshell\u001b[24m is one whose first  character  of  argument\u001b[m\r\n       zero is a \u001b[1m-\u001b[0m, or one started with the \u001b[1m--login\u001b[0m option.\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n       An  \u001b[4minteractive\u001b[24m  shell  is one started without non-option\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[7m Manual page bash(1) line 131 (press h for help or q to quit)\u001b[27m\u001b[K"]
[3618.693609, "o", "\r\u001b[K"]
[3618.693719, "o", "       arguments (unless \u001b[1m-s\u001b[0m is specified) and without the \u001b[1m-c\u001b[0m op‐\u001b[m\r\n       tion,  whose  standard input and error are both connected\u001b[m\r\n       to terminals (as determined by \u001b[4misatty\u001b[24m(3)), or one started\u001b[m\r\n       with the \u001b[1m-i\u001b[0m option.  \u001b[1mPS1\u001b[0m is set and \u001b[1m$-\u001b[0m includes \u001b[1mi\u001b[0m if \u001b[1mbash\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n       is interactive, allowing a shell script or a startup file\u001b[m\r\n       to test this state.\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n       The  following  paragraphs describe how \u001b[1mbash\u001b[0m executes its\u001b[m\r\n       startup files.  If any of the files exist but  cannot  be\u001b[m\r\n       read,  \u001b[1mbash\u001b[0m  reports  an  error.   Tildes are expanded in\u001b[m\r\n       filenames as described below under \u001b[1mTilde\u001b[0m \u001b[1mExpansion\u001b[0m in the\u001b[m\r\n       \u001b[1mEXPANSION\u001b[0m section.\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n       When \u001b[1mbash\u001b[0m is invoked as an interactive login shell, or as\u001b[m\r\n       a non-interactive shell with the \u001b[1m--login\u001b[0m option, it first\u001b[m\r\n       reads  and  executes commands from the file \u001b[4m/etc/profile\u001b[24"]
[3618.693734, "o", "m,\u001b[m\r\n       i"]
[3618.693818, "o", "f that file exists.  After reading that file,  it  looks\u001b[m\r\n       for  \u001b[4m~/.bash_profile\u001b[24m,  \u001b[4m~/.bash_login\u001b[24m,  and \u001b[4m~/.profile\u001b[24m, in\u001b[m\r\n       that order, and reads  and  executes  commands  from  the\u001b[m\r\n       first  one  that exists and is readable.  The \u001b[1m--noprofile\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n       option may be used when the shell is started  to  inhibit\u001b[m\r\n       this behavior.\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n       When  an interactive login shell exits, or a non-interac‐\u001b[m\r\n       tive login shell executes the \u001b[1mexit\u001b[0m builtin command,  \u001b[1mbash\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n       reads and executes commands from the file \u001b[4m~/.bash_logout\u001b[24m,\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[7m Manual page bash(1) line 157 (press h for help or q to quit)\u001b[27m\u001b[K"]
[3618.725691, "o", "\r\u001b[K"]
[3618.725797, "o", "       if it exists.\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n       When an interactive shell that is not a  login  shell  is\u001b[m\r\n       started,   \u001b[1mbash\u001b[0m   reads   and   executes   commands  from\u001b[m\r\n       \u001b[4m/etc/bash.bashrc\u001b[24m and \u001b[4m~/.bashrc\u001b[24m,  if  these  files  exist.\u001b[m\r\n       This  may  be  inhibited by using the \u001b[1m--norc\u001b[0m option.  The\u001b[m\r\n       \u001b[1m--rcfile\u001b[0m \u001b[4mfile\u001b[24m option will force \u001b[1mbash\u001b[0m to read and  execute\u001b[m\r\n       commands   from  \u001b[4mfile\u001b[24m  instead  of  \u001b[4m/etc/bash.bashrc\u001b[24m  and\u001b[m\r\n       \u001b[4m~/.bashrc\u001b[24m.\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n       When \u001b[1mbash\u001b[0m is started non-interactively, to  run  a  shell\u001b[m\r\n       script,  for  example, it looks for the variable \u001b[1mBASH_ENV\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n       in the environment,  expands  its  value  if  it  appears\u001b[m\r\n       there,  and uses the expanded value as the name of a file\u001b[m\r\n       to read and execute.  \u001b[1mBash\u001b[0m behaves as  if  the  following\u001b[m\r\n       command were executed:\u001b[m\r\n              if [ -n \"$BASH_ENV\" ]; then . \"$BASH_ENV\"; fi\u001b[m\r\n"]
[3618.725837, "o", "       but  the value of the \u001b[1mPATH\u001b[0m variable is not used to search\u001b[m\r\n       for the filename.\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n       If \u001b[1mbash\u001b[0m is invoked with the name \u001b[1msh\u001b[0m, it  tries  to  mimic\u001b[m\r\n       the  startup  behavior  of  historical  versions of \u001b[1msh\u001b[0m as\u001b[m\r\n       closely as possible, while conforming to the POSIX  stan‐\u001b[m\r\n       dard  as  well.   When  invoked  as  an interactive login\u001b[m\r\n       shell, or a non-interactive shell with  the  \u001b[1m--login\u001b[0m  op‐\u001b[m\r\n       tion, it first attempts to read and execute commands from\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[7m Manual page bash(1) line 183 (press h for help or q to quit)\u001b[27m\u001b[K"]
[3618.757722, "o", "\r\u001b[K"]
[3618.757827, "o", "       \u001b[4m/etc/profile\u001b[24m and \u001b[4m~/.profile\u001b[24m, in that order.  The \u001b[1m--nopro‐\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n       \u001b[1mfile\u001b[0m  option  may be used to inhibit this behavior.  When\u001b[m\r\n       invoked as an interactive shell with the  name  \u001b[1msh\u001b[0m,  \u001b[1mbash\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n       looks  for  the  variable \u001b[1mENV\u001b[0m, expands its value if it is\u001b[m\r\n       defined, and uses the expanded value as  the  name  of  a\u001b[m\r\n       file  to  read  and execute.  Since a shell invoked as \u001b[1msh\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n       does not attempt to read and execute  commands  from  any\u001b[m\r\n       other  startup  files, the \u001b[1m--rcfile\u001b[0m option has no effect.\u001b[m\r\n       A non-interactive shell invoked with the name \u001b[1msh\u001b[0m does not\u001b[m\r\n       attempt to read any other startup files.  When invoked as\u001b[m\r\n       \u001b[1msh\u001b[0m, \u001b[1mbash\u001b[0m enters \u001b[4mposix\u001b[24m mode after the  startup  files  are\u001b[m\r\n       read.\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n       When  \u001b[1mbash\u001b[0m  is started in \u001b[4mposix\u001b[24m mode, as with the \u001b[1m--posix\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n       command line option, it follows t"]
[3618.75786, "o", "he  POSIX  standard  for\u001b[m\r\n       startup  files.   In this mode, interactive shells expand\u001b[m\r\n       the \u001b[1mENV\u001b[0m variable and commands are read and executed  from\u001b[m\r\n       the  file  whose  name  is  the expanded value.  No other\u001b[m\r\n       startup files are read.\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n       \u001b[1mBash\u001b[0m attempts to determine when it is being run with  its\u001b[m\r\n       standard input connected to a network connection, as when\u001b[m\r\n       executed by the historical remote shell  daemon,  usually\u001b[m\r\n       \u001b[4mrshd\u001b[24m,  or  the  secure shell daemon \u001b[4msshd\u001b[24m.  If \u001b[1mbash\u001b[0m deter‐\u001b[m\r\n       mines it is being run non-interactively in this  fashion,\u001b[m\r\n       it  reads and executes commands from \u001b[4m/etc/bash.bashrc\u001b[24m and\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[7m Manual page bash(1) line 209 (press h for help or q to quit)\u001b[27m\u001b[K"]
[3618.788254, "o", "\r\u001b[K       \u001b[4m~/.bashrc\u001b[24m, if these files exist  and  are  readable.   It\u001b[m\r\n       will not do this if invoked as \u001b[1msh\u001b[0m.  The \u001b[1m--norc\u001b[0m option may\u001b[m\r\n       be used to inhibit this behavior, and the \u001b[1m--rcfile\u001b[0m option\u001b[m\r\n       may be used to force another file to be read, but neither\u001b[m\r\n       \u001b[4mrshd\u001b[24m nor \u001b[4msshd\u001b[24m generally invoke the shell with  those  op‐\u001b[m\r\n       tions or allow them to be specified.\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n       If  the  shell is started with the effective user (group)\u001b[m\r\n       id not equal to the real user (group) id, and the \u001b[1m-p\u001b[0m  op‐\u001b[m\r\n       tion  is  not  supplied, no startup files are read, shell\u001b[m\r\n       functions are not inherited  from  the  environment,  the\u001b[m\r\n       \u001b[1mSHELLOPTS\u001b[0m, \u001b[1mBASHOPTS\u001b[0m, \u001b[1mCDPATH\u001b[0m, and \u001b[1mGLOBIGNORE\u001b[0m variables, if\u001b[m\r\n       they appear in the environment, are ignored, and the  ef‐\u001b[m\r\n       fective  user  id  is set to the real user id.  If the \u001b[1m-p\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n       option is supplied at invoc"]
[3618.788281, "o", "ation, the startup behavior is\u001b[m\r\n       the same, but the effective user id is not reset.\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[1mDEFINITIONS\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n       The following definitions are used throughout the rest of\u001b[m\r\n       this document.\u001b[m\r\n       \u001b[1mblank\u001b[0m  A space or tab.\u001b[m\r\n       \u001b[1mword\u001b[0m   A sequence of characters considered  as  a  single\u001b[m\r\n              unit by the shell.  Also known as a \u001b[1mtoken\u001b[0m.\u001b[m\r\n       \u001b[1mname\u001b[0m   A  \u001b[4mword\u001b[24m consisting only of alphanumeric characters\u001b[m\r\n              and underscores, and beginning with an  alphabetic\u001b[m\r\n              character  or  an underscore.  Also referred to as\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[7m Manual page bash(1) line 235 (press h for help or q to quit)\u001b[27m\u001b[K"]
[3618.820162, "o", "\r\u001b[K"]
[3618.820194, "o", "              an \u001b[1midentifier\u001b[0m.\u001b[m\r\n       \u001b[1mmetacharacter\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n              A character that, when unquoted, separates  words.\u001b[m\r\n              One of the following:\u001b[m\r\n              \u001b[1m|\u001b[0m  \u001b[1m&\u001b[0m \u001b[1m;\u001b[0m \u001b[1m(\u001b[0m \u001b[1m)\u001b[0m \u001b[1m<\u001b[0m \u001b[1m>\u001b[0m \u001b[1mspace\u001b[0m \u001b[1mtab\u001b[0m \u001b[1mnewline\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n       \u001b[1mcontrol\u001b[0m \u001b[1moperator\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n              A  \u001b[4mtoken\u001b[24m  that performs a control function.  It is\u001b[m\r\n              one of the following symbols:\u001b[m\r\n              \u001b[1m||\u001b[0m \u001b[1m&\u001b[0m \u001b[1m&&\u001b[0m \u001b[1m;\u001b[0m \u001b[1m;;\u001b[0m \u001b[1m;&\u001b[0m \u001b[1m;;&\u001b[0m \u001b[1m(\u001b[0m \u001b[1m)\u001b[0m \u001b[1m|\u001b[0m \u001b[1m|&\u001b[0m \u001b[1m<newline>\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[1mRESERVED\u001b[0m \u001b[1mWORDS\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n       \u001b[4mReserved\u001b[24m \u001b[4mwords\u001b[24m are words that have a special  meaning  to\u001b[m\r\n       the  shell.   The  following  words are recognized as re‐\u001b[m\r\n       served when unquoted and either the first word of a  com‐\u001b[m\r\n       mand  (see \u001b[1mSHELL\u001b[0m \u001b[1mGRAMMAR\u001b[0m below), the third word of a \u001b[1mcase\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n       or \u001b[1mselect\u001b[0m "]
[3618.820203, "o", "command (only \u001b[1min\u001b[0m is valid), or the  third  word\u001b[m\r\n       of a \u001b[1mfor\u001b[0m command (only \u001b[1min\u001b[0m and \u001b[1mdo\u001b[0m are valid):\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n"]
[3618.820352, "o", "       \u001b[1m!\u001b[0m \u001b[1mcase\u001b[0m  \u001b[1mcoproc\u001b[0m  \u001b[1mdo\u001b[0m \u001b[1mdone\u001b[0m \u001b[1melif\u001b[0m \u001b[1melse\u001b[0m \u001b[1mesac\u001b[0m \u001b[1mfi\u001b[0m \u001b[1mfor\u001b[0m \u001b[1mfunction\u001b[0m \u001b[1mif\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n       \u001b[1min\u001b[0m \u001b[1mselect\u001b[0m \u001b[1mthen\u001b[0m \u001b[1muntil\u001b[0m \u001b[1mwhile\u001b[0m \u001b[1m{\u001b[0m \u001b[1m}\u001b[0m \u001b[1mtime\u001b[0m \u001b[1m[[\u001b[0m \u001b[1m]]\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[1mSHELL\u001b[0m \u001b[1mGRAMMAR\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n       This section describes the syntax of the various forms of\u001b[m\r\n       shell commands.\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n   \u001b[1mSimple\u001b[0m \u001b[1mCommands\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[7m Manual page bash(1) line 261 (press h for help or q to quit)\u001b[27m\u001b[K"]
[3618.851293, "o", "\r\u001b[K"]
[3618.851488, "o", "       A  \u001b[4msimple\u001b[24m  \u001b[4mcommand\u001b[24m is a sequence of optional variable as‐\u001b[m\r\n       signments followed by \u001b[1mblank\u001b[0m-separated words and  redirec‐\u001b[m\r\n       tions,  and  terminated by a \u001b[4mcontrol\u001b[24m \u001b[4moperator\u001b[24m.  The first\u001b[m\r\n       word specifies the command to be executed, and is  passed\u001b[m\r\n       as  argument zero.  The remaining words are passed as ar‐\u001b[m\r\n       guments to the invoked command.\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n       The return value of a \u001b[4msimple\u001b[24m \u001b[4mcommand\u001b[24m is its exit  status,\u001b[m\r\n       or 128+\u001b[4mn\u001b[24m if the command is terminated by signal \u001b[4mn\u001b[24m.\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n   \u001b[1mPipelines\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n       A  \u001b[4mpipeline\u001b[24m  is  a sequence of one or more commands sepa‐\u001b[m\r\n       rated by one of the control operators \u001b[1m|\u001b[0m or \u001b[1m|&\u001b[0m.  The  for‐\u001b[m\r\n       mat for a pipeline is:\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n              [\u001b[1mtime\u001b[0m [\u001b[1m-p\u001b[0m]] [ ! ] \u001b[4mcommand1\u001b[24m [ [\u001b[1m|\u001b[0m⎪\u001b[1m|&\u001b[0m] \u001b[4mcommand2\u001b[24m ... ]\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n       The  standard  output of \u001b[4mcommand1\u001b[24m is"]
[3618.851503, "o", " connected via a pipe\u001b[m\r\n       to the standard input of \u001b[4mcommand2\u001b[24m.   This  connection  is\u001b[m\r\n       performed  before  any redirections specified by the \u001b[4mcom‐\u001b[24m\u001b[m\r\n       \u001b[4mmand1\u001b[24m(see \u001b[1mREDIRECTION\u001b[0m below).  If \u001b[1m|&\u001b[0m is used,  \u001b[4mcommand1\u001b[24m's\u001b[m\r\n       standard  error,  in  addition to its standard output, is\u001b[m\r\n       connected to \u001b[4mcommand2\u001b[24m's standard input through the  pipe;\u001b[m\r\n       it is shorthand for \u001b[1m2>&1\u001b[0m \u001b[1m|\u001b[0m.  This implicit redirection of\u001b[m\r\n       the standard error to the standard  output  is  performed\u001b[m\r\n       after any redirections specified by \u001b[4mcommand1\u001b[24m.\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[7m Manual page bash(1) line 287 (press h for help or q to quit)\u001b[27m\u001b[K"]
[3618.888186, "o", "\r\u001b[K"]
[3618.888309, "o", "\u001b[m\r\n       The return status of a pipeline is the exit status of the\u001b[m\r\n       last command, unless the \u001b[1mpipefail\u001b[0m option is enabled.   If\u001b[m\r\n       \u001b[1mpipefail\u001b[0m  is enabled, the pipeline's return status is the\u001b[m\r\n       value of the last (rightmost) command to exit with a non-\u001b[m\r\n       zero  status,  or zero if all commands exit successfully.\u001b[m\r\n       If the reserved word \u001b[1m!\u001b[0m  precedes  a  pipeline,  the  exit\u001b[m\r\n       status  of  that  pipeline is the logical negation of the\u001b[m\r\n       exit status as described above.  The shell waits for  all\u001b[m\r\n       commands  in the pipeline to terminate before returning a\u001b[m\r\n       value.\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n       If the  \u001b[1mtime\u001b[0m  reserved  word  precedes  a  pipeline,  the\u001b[m\r\n       elapsed  as  well as user and system time consumed by its\u001b[m\r\n       execution are reported when the pipeline terminates.  The\u001b[m\r\n       \u001b[1m-p\u001b[0m  option changes the output format to that specified by\u001b[m\r\n       POSIX.  When the shell is in \u001b[4mposix\u001b[24m \u001b[4mmode"]
[3618.888365, "o", "\u001b[24m, it does "]
[3618.888379, "o", "not rec‐\u001b[m\r\n       ognize  \u001b[1mtime\u001b[0m  as a reserved word if the next token begins\u001b[m\r\n       with a `-'.  The \u001b[1mTIMEFORMAT\u001b[0m variable may be set to a for‐\u001b[m\r\n       mat  string  that  specifies  how  the timing information\u001b[m\r\n       should be displayed; see the  description  of  \u001b[1mTIMEFORMAT\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n       under \u001b[1mShell\u001b[0m \u001b[1mVariables\u001b[0m below.\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n       When  the shell is in \u001b[4mposix\u001b[24m \u001b[4mmode\u001b[24m, \u001b[1mtime\u001b[0m may be followed by\u001b[m\r\n       a newline.  In this case, the shell  displays  the  total\u001b[m\r\n       user  and system time consumed by the shell and its chil‐\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[7m Manual page bash(1) line 313 (press h for help or q to quit)\u001b[27m\u001b[K"]
[3618.914539, "o", "\r\u001b[K       dren.  The \u001b[1mTIMEFORMAT\u001b[0m variable may be used to specify the\u001b[m\r\n       format of the time information.\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n       Each command in a multi-command pipeline, where pipes are\u001b[m\r\n       created, is executed in a \u001b[4msubshell\u001b[24m, which is  a  separate\u001b[m\r\n       process.   See  \u001b[1mCOMMAND\u001b[0m  \u001b[1mEXECUTION\u001b[0m  \u001b[1mENVIRONMENT\u001b[0m for a de‐\u001b[m\r\n       scription of subshells and a  subshell  environment.   If\u001b[m\r\n       the  \u001b[1mlastpipe\u001b[0m  option  is enabled using the \u001b[1mshopt\u001b[0m builtin\u001b[m\r\n       (see the description of \u001b[1mshopt\u001b[0m below), the last element of\u001b[m\r\n       a  pipeline may be run by the shell process when job con‐\u001b[m\r\n       trol is not active.\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n   \u001b[1mLists\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n       A \u001b[4mlist\u001b[24m is a sequence of one or more  pipelines  separated\u001b[m\r\n       by  one  of the operators \u001b[1m;\u001b[0m, \u001b[1m&\u001b[0m, \u001b[1m&&\u001b[0m, or \u001b[1m||\u001b[0m, and optionally\u001b[m\r\n       terminated by one of \u001b[1m;\u001b[0m, \u001b[1m&\u001b[0m, or \u001b[1m<newline>\u001b[0m.\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n       Of these list operators, \u001b["]
[3618.914569, "o", "1m&&\u001b[0m and \u001b[1m||\u001b[0m have equal precedence,\u001b[m\r\n       followed by \u001b[1m;\u001b[0m and \u001b[1m&\u001b[0m, which have equal precedence.\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n       A  sequence  of one or more newlines may appear in a \u001b[4mlist\u001b[24m\u001b[m\r\n       instead of a semicolon to delimit commands.\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n       If a command is terminated by the control operator \u001b[1m&\u001b[0m, the\u001b[m\r\n       shell  executes  the  command in the \u001b[4mbackground\u001b[24m in a sub‐\u001b[m\r\n       shell.  The shell does not wait for the command  to  fin‐\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[7m Manual page bash(1) line 339 (press h for help or q to quit)\u001b[27m\u001b[K"]
[3618.945309, "o", "\r\u001b[K"]
[3618.945445, "o", "       ish,  and  the return status is 0.  These are referred to\u001b[m\r\n       as \u001b[4masynchronous\u001b[24m commands.  Commands separated by a \u001b[1m;\u001b[0m  are\u001b[m\r\n       executed  sequentially;  the shell waits for each command\u001b[m\r\n       to terminate in turn.  The return status is the exit sta‐\u001b[m\r\n       tus of the last command executed.\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n       AND  and  OR lists are sequences of one or more pipelines\u001b[m\r\n       separated by the \u001b[1m&&\u001b[0m and  \u001b[1m||\u001b[0m  control  operators,  respec‐\u001b[m\r\n       tively.  AND and OR lists are executed with left associa‐\u001b[m\r\n       tivity.  An AND list has the form\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n              \u001b[4mcommand1\u001b[24m \u001b[1m&&\u001b[0m \u001b[4mcommand2\u001b[24m\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n       \u001b[4mcommand2\u001b[24m is executed if, and only if, \u001b[4mcommand1\u001b[24m returns an\u001b[m\r\n       exit status of zero (success).\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n       An OR list has the form\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n              \u001b[4mcommand1\u001b[24m \u001b[1m||\u001b[0m \u001b[4mcommand2\u001b[24m\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n       \u001b[4mcommand2\u001b[24m  is executed if, and only if, \u001b[4mcommand1\u001b[24m returns a\u001b[m\r\n "]
[3618.94546, "o", "      non-zero exit status.  The return status of  AND  and  OR\u001b[m\r\n       lists  is the exit status of the last command executed in\u001b[m\r\n       the list.\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n   \u001b[1mCompound\u001b[0m \u001b[1mCommands\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[7m Manual page bash(1) line 365 (press h for help or q to quit)\u001b[27m\u001b[K"]
[3618.976531, "o", "\r\u001b[K"]
[3618.976561, "o", "       A \u001b[4mcompound\u001b[24m \u001b[4mcommand\u001b[24m is one  of  the  following.   In  most\u001b[m\r\n       cases  a \u001b[4mlist\u001b[24m in a command's description may be separated\u001b[m\r\n       from the rest of the command by one or more newlines, and\u001b[m\r\n       may be followed by a newline in place of a semicolon.\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n       (\u001b[4mlist\u001b[24m) \u001b[4mlist\u001b[24m is executed in a subshell (see \u001b[1mCOMMAND\u001b[0m \u001b[1mEXECU‐\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n              \u001b[1mTION\u001b[0m \u001b[1mENVIRONMENT\u001b[0m below for a description of a sub‐\u001b[m\r\n              shell   environment).   Variable  assignments  and\u001b[m\r\n              builtin commands that affect the shell's  environ‐\u001b[m\r\n              ment  do  not  remain  in effect after the command\u001b[m\r\n              completes.  The return status is the  exit  status\u001b[m\r\n              of \u001b[4mlist\u001b[24m.\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n       { \u001b[4mlist\u001b[24m; }\u001b[m\r\n              \u001b[4mlist\u001b[24m is simply executed in the current shell envi‐\u001b[m\r\n              ronment.  \u001b[4mlist\u001b[24m must be terminated with  a  newline\u001b[m\r\n              or  sem"]
[3618.976569, "o", "icolon.   This is known as a \u001b[4mgroup\u001b[24m \u001b[4mcommand\u001b[24m.\u001b[m\r\n              The return status is  the  exit  status  of  \u001b[4mlist\u001b[24m.\u001b[m\r\n"]
[3618.976577, "o", "              Note that unlike the metacharacters \u001b[1m(\u001b[0m and \u001b[1m)\u001b[0m, \u001b[1m{\u001b[0m and\u001b[m\r\n              \u001b[1m}\u001b[0m are \u001b[4mreserved\u001b[24m \u001b[4mwords\u001b[24m and must occur  where  a  re‐\u001b[m\r\n              served  word is permitted to be recognized.  Since\u001b[m\r\n              they do not cause a word break, they must be sepa‐\u001b[m\r\n              rated  from  \u001b[4mlist\u001b[24m  by  whitespace or another shell\u001b[m\r\n              metacharacter.\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n       ((\u001b[4mexpression\u001b[24m))\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[7m Manual page bash(1) line 391 (press h for help or q to quit)\u001b[27m\u001b[K"]
[3619.008129, "o", "\r\u001b[K"]
[3619.008161, "o", "              The \u001b[4mexpression\u001b[24m is evaluated according to the rules\u001b[m\r\n              described  below  under \u001b[1mARITHMETIC\u001b[0m \u001b[1mEVALUATION\u001b[0m.  If\u001b[m\r\n              the value of the expression is non-zero,  the  re‐\u001b[m\r\n              turn  status  is 0; otherwise the return status is\u001b[m\r\n              1.  The \u001b[4mexpression\u001b[24m undergoes the  same  expansions\u001b[m\r\n"]
[3619.008301, "o", "              as  if  it  were  within double quotes, but double\u001b[m\r\n              quote characters in  \u001b[4mexpression\u001b[24m  are  not  treated\u001b[m\r\n              specially and are removed.\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n       \u001b[1m[[\u001b[0m \u001b[4mexpression\u001b[24m \u001b[1m]]\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n              Return a status of 0 or 1 depending on the evalua‐\u001b[m\r\n              tion of  the  conditional  expression  \u001b[4mexpression\u001b[24m.\u001b[m\r\n              Expressions  are  composed  of  the  primaries de‐\u001b[m\r\n              scribed below under \u001b[1mCONDITIONAL\u001b[0m \u001b[1mEXPRESSIONS\u001b[0m.   The\u001b[m\r\n              words  between  the  \u001b[1m[[\u001b[0m and \u001b[1m]]\u001b[0m do not undergo word\u001b[m\r\n              splitting and pathname expansion.  The shell  per‐\u001b[m\r\n              forms  tilde expansion, parameter and variable ex‐\u001b[m\r\n              pansion, arithmetic expansion,  command  substitu‐\u001b[m\r\n              tion,  process  substitution, and quote removal on\u001b[m\r\n              those words (the expansions that  would  occur  if\u001b[m\r\n              the words were encl"]
[3619.00831, "o", "osed in double quotes).  Condi‐\u001b[m\r\n              tional operators such as \u001b[1m-f\u001b[0m must be unquoted to be\u001b[m\r\n              recognized as primaries.\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n              When used with \u001b[1m[[\u001b[0m, the \u001b[1m<\u001b[0m and \u001b[1m>\u001b[0m operators sort lex‐\u001b[m\r\n              icographically using the current locale.\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[7m Manual page bash(1) line 417 (press h for help or q to quit)\u001b[27m\u001b[K"]
[3619.039701, "o", "\r\u001b[K"]
[3619.039729, "o", "\u001b[m\r\n       See the description of the \u001b[4mtest\u001b[24m builtin command  (section\u001b[m\r\n       SHELL BUILTIN COMMANDS below) for the handling of parame‐\u001b[m\r\n       ters (i.e.  missing parameters).\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n       When the \u001b[1m==\u001b[0m and \u001b[1m!=\u001b[0m operators are used, the string to  the\u001b[m\r\n       right of the operator is considered a pattern and matched\u001b[m\r\n       according to the  rules  described  below  under  \u001b[1mPattern\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n       \u001b[1mMatching\u001b[0m,  as  if  the \u001b[1mextglob\u001b[0m shell option were enabled.\u001b[m\r\n       The \u001b[1m=\u001b[0m operator is equivalent to \u001b[1m==\u001b[0m.  If  the  \u001b[1mnocasematch\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n       shell  option  is enabled, the match is performed without\u001b[m\r\n       regard to the case of alphabetic characters.  The  return\u001b[m\r\n       value  is  0 if the string matches (\u001b[1m==\u001b[0m) or does not match\u001b[m\r\n       (\u001b[1m!=\u001b[0m) the pattern, and 1 otherwise.  Any part of the  pat‐\u001b[m\r\n       tern  may  be  quoted  to  force the quoted portion to be\u001b[m\r\n       matched as a string.\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n       An ad"]
[3619.039734, "o", "ditional binary operator, \u001b[1m=~\u001b[0m, is available, with the\u001b[m\r\n       same  precedence  as  \u001b[1m==\u001b[0m  and  \u001b[1m!=\u001b[0m.   When it is used, the\u001b[m\r\n       string to the right of the operator is considered a POSIX\u001b[m\r\n       extended  regular expression and matched accordingly (us‐\u001b[m\r\n       ing the POSIX \u001b[4mregcomp\u001b[24m and \u001b[4mregexec\u001b[24m interfaces usually  de‐\u001b[m\r\n       scribed  in  \u001b[4mregex\u001b[24m(3)).   The  return  value  is 0 if the\u001b[m\r\n       string matches the pattern, and 1 otherwise.  If the reg‐\u001b[m\r\n       ular  expression  is  syntactically incorrect, the condi‐\u001b[m\r\n       tional expression's return value is 2.   If  the  \u001b[1mnocase‐\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[7m Manual page bash(1) line 443 (press h for help or q to quit)\u001b[27m\u001b[K"]
[3619.070901, "o", "\r\u001b[K"]
[3619.070943, "o", "       \u001b[1mmatch\u001b[0m  shell  option  is  enabled, the match is performed\u001b[m\r\n       without regard to the case of alphabetic characters.   If\u001b[m\r\n       any  part of the pattern is quoted, the quoted portion is\u001b[m\r\n       matched literally.  This means  every  character  in  the\u001b[m\r\n       quoted portion matches itself, instead of having any spe‐\u001b[m\r\n       cial pattern matching meaning.  If the pattern is  stored\u001b[m\r\n       in  a  shell  variable,  quoting  the  variable expansion\u001b[m\r\n       forces the entire pattern to be matched literally.  Treat\u001b[m\r\n       bracket  expressions  in  regular  expressions carefully,\u001b[m\r\n       since normal quoting and pattern  characters  lose  their\u001b[m\r\n       meanings between brackets.\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n       The  pattern  will  match  if  it matches any part of the\u001b[m\r\n       string.  Anchor the pattern using the \u001b[1m^\u001b[0m and \u001b[1m$\u001b[0m regular ex‐\u001b[m\r\n       pression  operators  to  force  it  to  match  the entire\u001b[m\r\n       string.  The array variable  \u001b[1mBASH_REMATCH\u001b[0m"]
[3619.070952, "o", "  records  which\u001b[m\r\n       parts  of the string matched the pattern.  The element of\u001b[m\r\n       \u001b[1mBASH_REMATCH\u001b[0m with index 0 contains  the  portion  of  the\u001b[m\r\n       string  matching  the  entire  regular  expression.  Sub‐\u001b[m\r\n       strings matched by  parenthesized  subexpressions  within\u001b[m\r\n       the   regular  expression  are  saved  in  the  remaining\u001b[m\r\n       \u001b[1mBASH_REMATCH\u001b[0m indices. The element  of  \u001b[1mBASH_REMATCH\u001b[0m  with\u001b[m\r\n       index  \u001b[4mn\u001b[24m  is  the  portion of the string matching the \u001b[4mn\u001b[24mth\u001b[m\r\n       parenthesized subexpression.  Bash sets  \u001b[1mBASH_REMATCH\u001b[0m  in\u001b[m\r\n       the  global  scope; declaring it as a local variable will\u001b[m\r\n       lead to unexpected results.\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[7m Manual page bash(1) line 469 (press h for help or q to quit)\u001b[27m\u001b[K"]
[3619.1023, "o", "\r\u001b[K\u001b[m\r\n       Expressions may be combined using  the  following  opera‐\u001b[m\r\n       tors, listed in decreasing order of precedence:\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n              \u001b[1m(\u001b[0m \u001b[4mexpression\u001b[24m \u001b[1m)\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n                     Returns  the value of \u001b[4mexpression\u001b[24m.  This may\u001b[m\r\n                     be used to override the  normal  precedence\u001b[m\r\n                     of operators.\u001b[m\r\n              \u001b[1m!\u001b[0m \u001b[4mexpression\u001b[24m\u001b[m\r\n                     True if \u001b[4mexpression\u001b[24m is false.\u001b[m\r\n              \u001b[4mexpression1\u001b[24m \u001b[1m&&\u001b[0m \u001b[4mexpression2\u001b[24m\u001b[m\r\n                     True  if  both  \u001b[4mexpression1\u001b[24m and \u001b[4mexpression2\u001b[24m\u001b[m\r\n                     are true.\u001b[m\r\n              \u001b[4mexpression1\u001b[24m \u001b[1m||\u001b[0m \u001b[4mexpression2\u001b[24m\u001b[m\r\n                     True if either \u001b[4mexpression1\u001b[24m  or  \u001b[4mexpression2\u001b[24m\u001b[m\r\n                     is true.\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n              The  \u001b[1m&&\u001b[0m  and  \u001b[1m||\u001b[0m operators do not evaluate \u001b[4mexpres‐\u001b[24m\u001b[m\r\n              \u001b[4msion2\u001b[24m if the val"]
[3619.102326, "o", "ue of \u001b[4mexpression1\u001b[24m is sufficient to\u001b[m\r\n              determine  the  return  value of the entire condi‐\u001b[m\r\n              tional expression.\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n       \u001b[1mfor\u001b[0m \u001b[4mname\u001b[24m [ [ \u001b[1min\u001b[0m [ \u001b[4mword\u001b[24m \u001b[4m...\u001b[24m ] ] ; ] \u001b[1mdo\u001b[0m \u001b[4mlist\u001b[24m ; \u001b[1mdone\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n              The list of words following \u001b[1min\u001b[0m is expanded, gener‐\u001b[m\r\n              ating  a  list of items.  The variable \u001b[4mname\u001b[24m is set\u001b[m\r\n              to each element of this list in turn, and \u001b[4mlist\u001b[24m  is\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[7m Manual page bash(1) line 495 (press h for help or q to quit)\u001b[27m\u001b[K"]
[3619.132992, "o", "\r\u001b[K"]
[3619.133023, "o", "              executed  each  time.   If the \u001b[1min\u001b[0m \u001b[4mword\u001b[24m is omitted,\u001b[m\r\n              the \u001b[1mfor\u001b[0m command executes \u001b[4mlist\u001b[24m once for each  posi‐\u001b[m\r\n              tional  parameter  that is set (see \u001b[1mPARAMETERS\u001b[0m be‐\u001b[m\r\n              low).  The return status is the exit status of the\u001b[m\r\n              last  command  that executes.  If the expansion of\u001b[m\r\n              the items following \u001b[1min\u001b[0m results in an  empty  list,\u001b[m\r\n              no commands are executed, and the return status is\u001b[m\r\n              0.\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n       \u001b[1mfor\u001b[0m (( \u001b[4mexpr1\u001b[24m ; \u001b[4mexpr2\u001b[24m ; \u001b[4mexpr3\u001b[24m )) ; \u001b[1mdo\u001b[0m \u001b[4mlist\u001b[24m ; \u001b[1mdone\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n              First, the arithmetic expression \u001b[4mexpr1\u001b[24m  is  evalu‐\u001b[m\r\n              ated  according to the rules described below under\u001b[m\r\n              \u001b[1mARITHMETIC\u001b[0m \u001b[1mEVALUATION\u001b[0m.  The arithmetic  expression\u001b[m\r\n              \u001b[4mexpr2\u001b[24m is then evaluated repeatedly until it evalu‐\u001b[m\r\n              ates to zero."]
[3619.133031, "o", "  Each time \u001b"]
[3619.133046, "o", "[4mexpr2\u001b[24m evaluates to a non-\u001b[m\r\n              zero  value,  \u001b[4mlist\u001b[24m  is executed and the arithmetic\u001b[m\r\n              expression \u001b[4mexpr3\u001b[24m is evaluated.  If any  expression\u001b[m\r\n              is  omitted,  it  behaves as if it evaluates to 1.\u001b[m\r\n              The return value is the exit status  of  the  last\u001b[m\r\n              command  in \u001b[4mlist\u001b[24m that is executed, or false if any\u001b[m\r\n              of the expressions is invalid.\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n       \u001b[1mselect\u001b[0m \u001b[4mname\u001b[24m [ \u001b[1min\u001b[0m \u001b[4mword\u001b[24m ] ; \u001b[1mdo\u001b[0m \u001b[4mlist\u001b[24m ; \u001b[1mdone\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n              The list of words following \u001b[1min\u001b[0m is expanded, gener‐\u001b[m\r\n              ating  a  list  of  items, and the set of expanded\u001b[m\r\n              words is printed on the standard error, each  pre‐\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[7m Manual page bash(1) line 521 (press h for help or q to quit)\u001b[27m\u001b[K"]
[3619.164364, "o", "\r\u001b[K              ceded by a number.  If the \u001b[1min\u001b[0m \u001b[4mword\u001b[24m is omitted, the\u001b[m\r\n              positional parameters are printed (see  \u001b[1mPARAMETERS\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n              below).   \u001b[1mselect\u001b[0m  then displays the \u001b[1mPS3\u001b[0m prompt and\u001b[m\r\n              reads a line from the standard input.  If the line\u001b[m\r\n"]
[3619.164434, "o", "              consists  of  a number corresponding to one of the\u001b[m\r\n              displayed words, then the value of \u001b[4mname\u001b[24m is set  to\u001b[m\r\n              that  word.   If  the line is empty, the words and\u001b[m\r\n              prompt are displayed again.  If EOF is  read,  the\u001b[m\r\n              \u001b[1mselect\u001b[0m command completes and returns 1.  Any other\u001b[m\r\n              value read causes \u001b[4mname\u001b[24m to be  set  to  null.   The\u001b[m\r\n              line  read  is  saved  in the variable \u001b[1mREPLY\u001b[0m.  The\u001b[m\r\n              \u001b[4mlist\u001b[24m is executed  after  each  selection  until  a\u001b[m\r\n              \u001b[1mbreak\u001b[0m command is executed.  The exit status of \u001b[1mse‐\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n              \u001b[1mlect\u001b[0m is the exit status of the last  command  exe‐\u001b[m\r\n              cuted  in  \u001b[4mlist\u001b[24m,  or zero if no commands were exe‐\u001b[m\r\n              cuted.\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n       \u001b[1mcase\u001b[0m \u001b[4mword\u001b[24m \u001b[1min\u001b[0m [ [(] \u001b[4mpattern\u001b[24m [ \u001b[1m|\u001b[0m \u001b[4mpattern\u001b[24m ] ... ) \u001b[4mlist\u001b[24m ;;  ]\u001b[m\r\n       ... \u001b[1mesac\u001b[0m\u001b"]
[3619.164458, "o", "[m\r\n              A  \u001b[1mcase\u001b[0m  command  first expands \u001b[4mword\u001b[24m, and tries to\u001b[m\r\n              match it against each \u001b[4mpattern\u001b[24m in turn,  using  the\u001b[m\r\n              matching  rules  described  under \u001b[1mPattern\u001b[0m \u001b[1mMatching\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n              below.  The \u001b[4mword\u001b[24m is expanded  using  tilde  expan‐\u001b[m\r\n              sion, parameter and variable expansion, arithmetic\u001b[m\r\n              expansion, command substitution, process substitu‐\u001b[m\r\n              tion  and quote removal.  Each \u001b[4mpattern\u001b[24m examined is\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[7m Manual page bash(1) line 547 (press h for help or q to quit)\u001b[27m\u001b[K"]
[3619.195757, "o", "\r\u001b[K              expanded  using  tilde  expansion,  parameter  and\u001b[m\r\n              variable  expansion, arithmetic expansion, command\u001b[m\r\n              substitution, process substitution, and quote  re‐\u001b[m\r\n              moval.   If  the  \u001b[1mnocasematch\u001b[0m  shell option is en‐\u001b[m\r\n              abled, the match is performed  without  regard  to\u001b[m\r\n              the  case  of alphabetic characters.  When a match\u001b[m\r\n              is found, the corresponding \u001b[4mlist\u001b[24m is executed.   If\u001b[m\r\n              the \u001b[1m;;\u001b[0m operator is used, no subsequent matches are\u001b[m\r\n              attempted after the first pattern match.  Using \u001b[1m;&\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n              in  place  of \u001b[1m;;\u001b[0m causes execution to continue with\u001b[m\r\n              the \u001b[4mlist\u001b[24m associated with the next set of patterns.\u001b[m\r\n              Using  \u001b[1m;;&\u001b[0m in place of \u001b[1m;;\u001b[0m causes the shell to test\u001b[m\r\n              the next pattern list in the  statement,  if  any,\u001b[m\r\n              and  execute  any  associated \u001b[4mlist\u001b"]
[3619.195779, "o", "[24m on a successful\u001b[m\r\n              match, continuing the case statement execution  as\u001b[m\r\n              if  the  pattern  list  had not matched.  The exit\u001b[m\r\n              status is zero if no pattern matches.   Otherwise,\u001b[m\r\n              it is the exit status of the last command executed\u001b[m\r\n              in \u001b[4mlist\u001b[24m.\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n       \u001b[1mif\u001b[0m \u001b[4mlist\u001b[24m; \u001b[1mthen\u001b[0m \u001b[4mlist\u001b[24m; [ \u001b[1melif\u001b[0m \u001b[4mlist\u001b[24m; \u001b[1mthen\u001b[0m \u001b[4mlist\u001b[24m; ] ... [  \u001b[1melse\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n       \u001b[4mlist\u001b[24m; ] \u001b[1mfi\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n              The  \u001b[1mif\u001b[0m  \u001b[4mlist\u001b[24m  is executed.  If its exit status is\u001b[m\r\n              zero, the \u001b[1mthen\u001b[0m \u001b[4mlist\u001b[24m is executed.  Otherwise,  each\u001b[m\r\n              \u001b[1melif\u001b[0m  \u001b[4mlist\u001b[24m  is  executed  in turn, and if its exit\u001b[m\r\n              status is zero, the corresponding \u001b[1mthen\u001b[0m \u001b[4mlist\u001b[24m is ex‐\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[7m Manual page bash(1) line 573 (press h for help or q to quit)\u001b[27m\u001b[K"]
[3619.226527, "o", "\r\u001b[K"]
[3619.226556, "o", "              ecuted  and the command completes.  Otherwise, the\u001b[m\r\n              \u001b[1melse\u001b[0m \u001b[4mlist\u001b[24m is executed, if present.  The exit  sta‐\u001b[m\r\n              tus  is  the  exit status of the last command exe‐\u001b[m\r\n              cuted, or zero if no condition tested true.\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n       \u001b[1mwhile\u001b[0m \u001b[4mlist-1\u001b[24m; \u001b[1mdo\u001b[0m \u001b[4mlist-2\u001b[24m; \u001b[1mdone\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n       \u001b[1muntil\u001b[0m \u001b[4mlist-1\u001b[24m; \u001b[1mdo\u001b[0m \u001b[4mlist-2\u001b[24m; \u001b[1mdone\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n              The \u001b[1mwhile\u001b[0m command continuously executes  the  list\u001b[m\r\n              \u001b[4mlist-2\u001b[24m  as  long  as  the last command in the list\u001b[m\r\n              \u001b[4mlist-1\u001b[24m returns an exit status of zero.  The  \u001b[1muntil\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n              command  is identical to the \u001b[1mwhile\u001b[0m command, except\u001b[m\r\n              that the test is negated: \u001b[4mlist-2\u001b[24m  is  executed  as\u001b[m\r\n              long  as the last command in \u001b[4mlist-1\u001b[24m returns a non-\u001b[m\r\n              zero exit status.  The exit status  of  the  \u001b[1mwhile\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n            "]
[3619.226561, "o", "  and  \u001b[1muntil\u001b[0m commands is the exit status of the last\u001b[m\r\n              command executed in \u001b[4mlist-2\u001b[24m, or zero  if  none  was\u001b[m\r\n              executed.\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n   \u001b[1mCoprocesses\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n       A \u001b[4mcoprocess\u001b[24m is a shell command preceded by the \u001b[1mcoproc\u001b[0m re‐\u001b[m\r\n       served word.  A coprocess is executed asynchronously in a\u001b[m\r\n       subshell,  as if the command had been terminated with the\u001b[m\r\n       \u001b[1m&\u001b[0m control operator, with a two-way pipe  established  be‐\u001b[m\r\n       tween the executing shell and the coprocess.\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n       The syntax for a coprocess is:\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[7m Manual page bash(1) line 599 (press h for help or q to quit)\u001b[27m\u001b[K"]
[3619.257807, "o", "\r\u001b[K"]
[3619.257908, "o", "\u001b[m\r\n              \u001b[1mcoproc\u001b[0m [\u001b[4mNAME\u001b[24m] \u001b[4mcommand\u001b[24m [\u001b[4mredirections\u001b[24m]\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n       This  creates a coprocess named \u001b[4mNAME\u001b[24m.  \u001b[4mcommand\u001b[24m may be ei‐\u001b[m\r\n       ther a simple command or a compound command (see  above).\u001b[m\r\n       \u001b[4mNAME\u001b[24m  is a shell variable name.  If \u001b[4mNAME\u001b[24m is not supplied,\u001b[m\r\n       the default name is \u001b[1mCOPROC\u001b[0m.\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n       The recommended form to use for a coprocess is\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n              \u001b[1mcoproc\u001b[0m \u001b[4mNAME\u001b[24m { \u001b[4mcommand\u001b[24m [\u001b[4mredirections\u001b[24m]; }\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n       This form is recommended because simple  commands  result\u001b[m\r\n       in  the  coprocess  always  being named \u001b[1mCOPROC\u001b[0m, and it is\u001b[m\r\n       simpler to use and more complete than the other  compound\u001b[m\r\n       commands.\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n       If  \u001b[4mcommand\u001b[24m  is a compound command, \u001b[4mNAME\u001b[24m is optional. The\u001b[m\r\n       word following \u001b[1mcoproc\u001b[0m determines whether that word is in‐\u001b[m\r\n       terpreted  as  a variable name: it is interpreted as"]
[3619.257931, "o", " \u001b[4mNAME\u001b[24m\u001b[m\r\n       if it is not a reserved word that introduces  a  compound\u001b[m\r\n       command.  If \u001b[4mcommand\u001b[24m is a simple command, \u001b[4mNAME\u001b[24m is not al‐\u001b[m\r\n       lowed; this is to avoid confusion between  \u001b[4mNAME\u001b[24m  and  the\u001b[m\r\n       first word of the simple command.\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n       When  the coprocess is executed, the shell creates an ar‐\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[7m Manual page bash(1) line 625 (press h for help or q to quit)\u001b[27m\u001b[K"]
[3619.288958, "o", "\r\u001b[K"]
[3619.289049, "o", "       ray variable (see \u001b[1mArrays\u001b[0m below) named \u001b[4mNAME\u001b[24m in the context\u001b[m\r\n       of  the  executing shell.  The standard output of \u001b[4mcommand\u001b[24m\u001b[m\r\n       is connected via a pipe to a file descriptor in the  exe‐\u001b[m\r\n       cuting  shell,  and  that  file descriptor is assigned to\u001b[m\r\n       \u001b[4mNAME\u001b[24m[0].  The standard input of \u001b[4mcommand\u001b[24m is connected  via\u001b[m\r\n       a  pipe  to a file descriptor in the executing shell, and\u001b[m\r\n       that file descriptor is assigned to \u001b[4mNAME\u001b[24m[1].   This  pipe\u001b[m\r\n       is  established  before any redirections specified by the\u001b[m\r\n       command (see \u001b[1mREDIRECTION\u001b[0m below).   The  file  descriptors\u001b[m\r\n       can  be utilized as arguments to shell commands and redi‐\u001b[m\r\n       rections using  standard  word  expansions.   Other  than\u001b[m\r\n       those  created  to  execute command and process substitu‐\u001b[m\r\n       tions, the file descriptors are  not  available  in  sub‐\u001b[m\r\n       shells.\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n       The process ID of the shell"]
[3619.289071, "o", " spawned to execute the copro‐\u001b[m\r\n       cess is available as the value of the variable  \u001b[4mNAME\u001b[24m_PID.\u001b[m\r\n       The  \u001b[1mwait\u001b[0m builtin command may be used to wait for the co‐\u001b[m\r\n       process to terminate.\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n       Since the coprocess is created as  an  asynchronous  com‐\u001b[m\r\n       mand, the \u001b[1mcoproc\u001b[0m command always returns success.  The re‐\u001b[m\r\n       turn status of a coprocess is the exit status of \u001b[4mcommand\u001b[24m.\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n   \u001b[1mShell\u001b[0m \u001b[1mFunction\u001b[0m \u001b[1mDefinitions\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n       A shell function is an object that is called like a  sim‐\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[7m Manual page bash(1) line 651 (press h for help or q to quit)\u001b[27m\u001b[K"]
[3619.320068, "o", "\r\u001b[K"]
[3619.320171, "o", "       ple  command  and  executes a compound command with a new\u001b[m\r\n       set of positional parameters.  Shell  functions  are  de‐\u001b[m\r\n       clared as follows:\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n       \u001b[4mfname\u001b[24m () \u001b[4mcompound-command\u001b[24m [\u001b[4mredirection\u001b[24m]\u001b[m\r\n       \u001b[1mfunction\u001b[0m \u001b[4mfname\u001b[24m [()] \u001b[4mcompound-command\u001b[24m [\u001b[4mredirection\u001b[24m]\u001b[m\r\n              This defines a function named \u001b[4mfname\u001b[24m.  The reserved\u001b[m\r\n              word \u001b[1mfunction\u001b[0m is optional.  If  the  \u001b[1mfunction\u001b[0m  re‐\u001b[m\r\n              served  word  is supplied, the parentheses are op‐\u001b[m\r\n              tional.  The \u001b[4mbody\u001b[24m of the function is the  compound\u001b[m\r\n              command  \u001b[4mcompound-command\u001b[24m  (see  \u001b[1mCompound\u001b[0m \u001b[1mCommands\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n              above).  That command is usually a  \u001b[4mlist\u001b[24m  of  com‐\u001b[m\r\n              mands  between  {  and  },  but may be any command\u001b[m\r\n              listed under  \u001b[1mCompound\u001b[0m  \u001b[1mCommands\u001b[0m  above.   If  the\u001b[m\r\n              \u001b[1mfunction\u001b[0m  "]
[3619.320202, "o", "reserved word is used, but the parenthe‐\u001b[m\r\n              ses are not supplied, the braces are  recommended.\u001b[m\r\n              \u001b[4mcompound-command\u001b[24m  is  executed  whenever  \u001b[4mfname\u001b[24m is\u001b[m\r\n              specified as the name of a simple  command.   When\u001b[m\r\n              in  \u001b[4mposix\u001b[24m  \u001b[4mmode\u001b[24m,  \u001b[4mfname\u001b[24m must be a valid shell \u001b["]
[3619.320249, "o", "4mname\u001b[24m\u001b[m\r\n              and may not be the name of one of the  POSIX  \u001b[4mspe‐\u001b[24m\u001b[m\r\n              \u001b[4mcial\u001b[24m  \u001b[4mbuiltins\u001b[24m.   In default mode, a function name\u001b[m\r\n              can be any unquoted shell word that does not  con‐\u001b[m\r\n              tain  \u001b[1m$\u001b[0m.  Any redirections (see \u001b[1mREDIRECTION\u001b[0m below)\u001b[m\r\n              specified when a function is defined are performed\u001b[m\r\n              when the function is executed.  The exit status of\u001b[m\r\n              a function definition is zero unless a syntax  er‐\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[7m Manual page bash(1) line 677 (press h for help or q to quit)\u001b[27m\u001b[K"]
[3619.35229, "o", "\r\u001b[K              ror  occurs  or  a readonly function with the same\u001b[m\r\n              name already exists.  When executed, the exit sta‐\u001b[m\r\n              tus  of  a function is the exit status of the last\u001b[m\r\n              command executed in the body.  (See \u001b[1mFUNCTIONS\u001b[0m  be‐\u001b[m\r\n              low.)\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[1mCOMMENTS\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n       In  a  non-interactive  shell, or an interactive shell in\u001b[m\r\n       which  the  \u001b[1minteractive_comments\u001b[0m  option  to  the   \u001b[1mshopt\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n       builtin  is enabled (see \u001b[1mSHELL\u001b[0m \u001b[1mBUILTIN\u001b[0m \u001b[1mCOMMANDS\u001b[0m below), a\u001b[m\r\n       word beginning with \u001b[1m#\u001b[0m causes that word and all  remaining\u001b[m\r\n       characters  on  that  line to be ignored.  An interactive\u001b[m\r\n       shell without  the  \u001b[1minteractive_comments\u001b[0m  option  enabled\u001b[m\r\n       does not allow comments.  The \u001b[1minteractive_comments\u001b[0m option\u001b[m\r\n       is on by default in interactive shells.\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[1mQUOTING\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n       \u001b[4mQuoting\u001b[24m is used to remove the special meani"]
[3619.352318, "o", "ng of  certain\u001b[m\r\n  "]
[3619.352336, "o", "     characters or words to the shell.  Quoting can be used to\u001b[m\r\n       disable special treatment for special characters, to pre‐\u001b[m\r\n       vent reserved words from being recognized as such, and to\u001b[m\r\n       prevent parameter expansion.\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n       Each of the \u001b[4mmetacharacters\u001b[24m listed above under \u001b[1mDEFINITIONS\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n       has special meaning to the shell and must be quoted if it\u001b[m\r\n       is to represent itself.\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[7m Manual page bash(1) line 703 (press h for help or q to quit)\u001b[27m\u001b[K"]
[3619.383598, "o", "\r\u001b[K"]
[3619.383655, "o", "\u001b[m\r\n       When the command history expansion facilities  are  being\u001b[m\r\n       used (see \u001b[1mHISTORY\u001b[0m \u001b[1mEXPANSION\u001b[0m below), the \u001b[4mhistory\u001b[24m \u001b[4mexpansion\u001b[24m\u001b[m\r\n       character, usually \u001b[1m!\u001b[0m, must be quoted to  prevent  history\u001b[m\r\n       expansion.\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n       There are three quoting mechanisms: the \u001b[4mescape\u001b[24m \u001b[4mcharacter\u001b[24m,\u001b[m\r\n       single quotes, and double quotes.\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n       A non-quoted backslash (\u001b[1m\\\u001b[0m) is the \u001b[4mescape\u001b[24m  \u001b[4mcharacter\u001b[24m.   It\u001b[m\r\n       preserves  the  literal  value of the next character that\u001b[m\r\n       follows, with the exception of <newline>.   If  a  \u001b[1m\\\u001b[0m<new‐\u001b[m\r\n       line>  pair  appears,  and  the  backslash  is not itself\u001b[m\r\n       quoted, the \u001b[1m\\\u001b[0m<newline> is treated as a line  continuation\u001b[m\r\n       (that  is, it is removed from the input stream and effec‐\u001b[m\r\n       tively ignored).\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n       Enclosing characters in single quotes preserves the  lit‐\u001b[m\r\n       eral value of each character within"]
[3619.383767, "o", " the quotes.  A single\u001b[m\r\n       quote may not occur between single quotes, even when pre‐\u001b[m\r\n       ceded by a backslash.\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n       Enclosing  characters in double quotes preserves the lit‐\u001b[m\r\n       eral value of all characters within the quotes, with  the\u001b[m\r\n       exception  of \u001b[1m$\u001b[0m, \u001b[1m`\u001b[0m, \u001b[1m\\\u001b[0m, and, when history expansion is en‐\u001b[m\r\n       abled, \u001b[1m!\u001b[0m.  When the shell is in \u001b[4mposix\u001b[24m \u001b[4mmode\u001b[24m, the \u001b[1m!\u001b[0m has  no\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[7m Manual page bash(1) line 729 (press h for help or q to quit)\u001b[27m\u001b[K"]
[3619.414788, "o", "\r\u001b[K       special  meaning  within double quotes, even when history\u001b[m\r\n       expansion is enabled.  The  characters  \u001b[1m$\u001b[0m  and  \u001b[1m`\u001b[0m  retain\u001b[m\r\n       their  special  meaning  within double quotes.  The back‐\u001b[m\r\n       slash retains its special meaning only when  followed  by\u001b[m\r\n       one  of  the  following  characters: \u001b[1m$\u001b[0m, \u001b[1m`\u001b[0m, \u001b[1m\"\u001b[0m, \u001b[1m\\\u001b[0m, or \u001b[1m<new‐\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n       \u001b[1mline>\u001b[0m.  A double quote may be quoted within double quotes\u001b[m\r\n       by  preceding  it  with a backslash.  If enabled, history\u001b[m\r\n       expansion will be performed unless  an  \u001b[1m!\u001b[0m   appearing  in\u001b[m\r\n       double  quotes  is  escaped using a backslash.  The back‐\u001b[m\r\n       slash preceding the \u001b[1m!\u001b[0m  is not removed.\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n       The special parameters \u001b[1m*\u001b[0m and \u001b[1m@\u001b[0m have special meaning  when\u001b[m\r\n       in double quotes (see \u001b[1mPARAMETERS\u001b[0m below).\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n       Character  sequences of the form \u001b[1m$\u001b[0m'\u001b[4mstring\u001b[24m' are treated as\u001b[m\r\n       a special varia"]
[3619.414822, "o", "nt of single quotes.  The sequence expands\u001b[m\r\n       to  \u001b[4mstring\u001b[24m,  with  backslash-escaped characters in \u001b[4mstring\u001b[24m\u001b[m\r\n       replaced as specified by the ANSI C standard.   Backslash\u001b[m\r\n       escape sequences, if present, are decoded as follows:\u001b[m\r\n              \u001b[1m\\a\u001b[0m     alert (bell)\u001b[m\r\n              \u001b[1m\\b\u001b[0m     backspace\u001b[m\r\n              \u001b[1m\\e\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n              \u001b[1m\\E\u001b[0m     an escape character\u001b[m\r\n              \u001b[1m\\f\u001b[0m     form feed\u001b[m\r\n              \u001b[1m\\n\u001b[0m     new line\u001b[m\r\n              \u001b[1m\\r\u001b[0m     carriage return\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[7m Manual page bash(1) line 755 (press h for help or q to quit)\u001b[27m\u001b[K"]
[3619.44686, "o", "\r\u001b[K"]
[3619.446893, "o", "              \u001b[1m\\t\u001b[0m     horizontal tab\u001b[m\r\n              \u001b[1m\\v\u001b[0m     vertical tab\u001b[m\r\n              \u001b[1m\\\\\u001b[0m     backslash\u001b[m\r\n              \u001b[1m\\'\u001b[0m     single quote\u001b[m\r\n              \u001b[1m\\\"\u001b[0m     double quote\u001b[m\r\n              \u001b[1m\\?\u001b[0m     question mark\u001b[m\r\n              \u001b[1m\\\u001b[0m\u001b[4mnnn\u001b[24m   the  eight-bit character whose value is the\u001b[m\r\n                     octal value \u001b[4mnnn\u001b[24m (one to three octal digits)\u001b[m\r\n              \u001b[1m\\x\u001b[0m\u001b[4mHH\u001b[24m   the eight-bit character whose value is  the\u001b[m\r\n                     hexadecimal  value  \u001b[4mHH\u001b[24m (one or two hex dig‐\u001b[m\r\n                     its)\u001b[m\r\n              \u001b[1m\\u\u001b[0m\u001b[4mHHHH\u001b[24m the Unicode (ISO/IEC 10646) character whose\u001b[m\r\n                     value is the hexadecimal value \u001b[4mHHHH\u001b[24m (one to\u001b[m\r\n                     four hex digits)\u001b[m\r\n              \u001b[1m\\U\u001b[0m\u001b[4mHHHHHHHH\u001b[24m\u001b[m\r\n                     the Unicode (ISO/IEC 10646) character whose\u001b[m\r\n                     value  is  the  hexadecimal  value \u001b[4mHHHHHHH"]
[3619.446902, "o", "H\u001b[24m\u001b[m\r\n                     (one to eight hex digits)\u001b[m\r\n              \u001b[1m\\c\u001b[0m\u001b[4mx\u001b[24m    a control-\u001b[4mx\u001b[24m character\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n       The expanded result is single-quoted, as  if  the  dollar\u001b[m\r\n       sign had not been present.\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n       A   double-quoted   string  preceded  by  a  dollar  sign\u001b[m\r\n       (\u001b[1m$\u001b[0m\"\u001b[4mstring\u001b[24m\") will cause the string to  be  translated  ac‐\u001b[m\r\n       cording  to  the current locale.  The \u001b[4mgettext\u001b[24m infrastruc‐\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[7m Manual page bash(1) line 781 (press h for help or q to quit)\u001b[27m\u001b[K"]
[3619.477343, "o", "\r\u001b[K       ture performs  the  lookup  and  translation,  using  the\u001b[m\r\n       \u001b[1mLC_MESSAGES\u001b[0m,  \u001b[1mTEXTDOMAINDIR\u001b[0m,  and  \u001b[1mTEXTDOMAIN\u001b[0m shell vari‐\u001b[m\r\n       ables.  If the current locale is \u001b[1mC\u001b[0m or \u001b[1mPOSIX\u001b[0m, if there are\u001b[m\r\n       no translations available, or if the string is not trans‐\u001b[m\r\n       lated, the dollar sign is ignored.  This  is  a  form  of\u001b[m\r\n       double  quoting,  so  the string remains double-quoted by\u001b[m\r\n       default, whether or not it is  translated  and  replaced.\u001b[m\r\n       If  the  \u001b[1mnoexpand_translation\u001b[0m option is enabled using the\u001b[m\r\n       \u001b[1mshopt\u001b[0m builtin, translated strings are  single-quoted  in‐\u001b[m\r\n       stead of double-quoted.  See the description of \u001b[1mshopt\u001b[0m be‐\u001b[m\r\n       low under \u001b[1mSHELL\u001b[0mBUILTIN\u001b[1mCOMMANDS\u001b[0m.\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n"]
[3619.477522, "o", "\u001b[1mPARAMETERS\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n       A \u001b[4mparameter\u001b[24m is an entity that stores values.  It can be a\u001b[m\r\n       \u001b[4mname\u001b[24m,  a  number, or one of the special characters listed\u001b[m\r\n       below under \u001b[1mSpecial\u001b[0m \u001b[1mParameters\u001b[0m.  A \u001b[4mvariable\u001b[24m is a  parame‐\u001b[m\r\n       ter  denoted  by a \u001b[4mname\u001b[24m.  A variable has a \u001b[4mvalue\u001b[24m and zero\u001b[m\r\n       or more \u001b[4mattributes\u001b[24m.  Attributes are  assigned  using  the\u001b[m\r\n       \u001b[1mdeclare\u001b[0m  builtin  command  (see  \u001b[1mdeclare\u001b[0m  below  in \u001b[1mSHELL\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n       \u001b[1mBUILTIN\u001b[0m \u001b[1mCOMMANDS\u001b[0m).\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n       A parameter is set if it has been assigned a value.   The\u001b[m\r\n       null string is a valid value.  Once a variable is set, it\u001b[m\r\n       may be unset only by using the \u001b[1munset\u001b[0m builtin command (see\u001b[m\r\n       \u001b[1mSHELL\u001b[0m \u001b[1mBUILTIN\u001b[0m \u001b[1mCOMMANDS\u001b[0m below).\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[7m Manual page bash(1) line 807 (press h for help or q to quit)\u001b[27m\u001b[K"]
[3619.509394, "o", "\r\u001b[K"]
[3619.509511, "o", "       A \u001b[4mvariable\u001b[24m may be assigned to by a statement of the form\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n              \u001b[4mname\u001b[24m=[\u001b[4mvalue\u001b[24m]\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n       If  \u001b[4mvalue\u001b[24m is not given, the variable is assigned the null\u001b[m\r\n       string.  All \u001b[4mvalues\u001b[24m undergo  tilde  expansion,  parameter\u001b[m\r\n       and  variable expansion, command substitution, arithmetic\u001b[m\r\n       expansion, and quote removal (see \u001b[1mEXPANSION\u001b[0m  below).   If\u001b[m\r\n       the variable has its \u001b[1minteger\u001b[0m attribute set, then \u001b[4mvalue\u001b[24m is\u001b[m\r\n       evaluated  as  an  arithmetic  expression  even  if   the\u001b[m\r\n       $((...))  expansion is not used (see \u001b[1mArithmetic\u001b[0m \u001b[1mExpansion\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n       below).  Word splitting and pathname  expansion  are  not\u001b[m\r\n       performed.   Assignment statements may also appear as ar‐\u001b[m\r\n       guments to the \u001b[1malias\u001b[0m, \u001b[1mdeclare\u001b[0m, \u001b[1mtypeset\u001b[0m, \u001b[1mexport\u001b[0m, \u001b[1mreadonly\u001b[0m,\u001b[m\r\n       and  \u001b[1mlocal\u001b[0m builtin commands (\u001b[4mdeclaration\u001b[24m commands).  When\u001b[m\r\n       in \u001b"]
[3619.509546, "o", "[4mposix\u001b[24m \u001b[4mmode\u001b[24m, these builtins may appear in a command af‐\u001b[m\r\n       ter  one or more instances of the \u001b[1mcommand\u001b[0m builtin and re‐\u001b[m\r\n       tain these assignment statement properties.\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n       In the context where an assignment statement is assigning\u001b[m\r\n       a value to a shell variable or array index, the += opera‐\u001b[m\r\n       tor can be used to append to or  add  to  the  variable's\u001b[m\r\n       previous  value.  This includes arguments to builtin com‐\u001b[m\r\n       mands such as \u001b[1mdeclare\u001b[0m that accept  assignment  statements\u001b[m\r\n       (\u001b[4mdeclaration\u001b[24m commands).  When += is applied to a variable\u001b[m\r\n       for which the \u001b[1minteger\u001b[0m attribute has been  set,  \u001b[4mvalue\u001b[24m  is\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[7m Manual page bash(1) line 833 (press h for help or q to quit)\u001b[27m\u001b[K"]
[3619.541446, "o", "\r\u001b[K"]
[3619.541534, "o", "       evaluated  as  an  arithmetic expression and added to the\u001b[m\r\n       variable's current value, which is also evaluated.   When\u001b[m\r\n       += is applied to an array variable using compound assign‐\u001b[m\r\n       ment (see \u001b[1mArrays\u001b[0m below), the variable's value is not  un‐\u001b[m\r\n       set  (as it is when using =), and new values are appended\u001b[m\r\n       to the array beginning at one greater  than  the  array's\u001b[m\r\n       maximum index (for indexed arrays) or added as additional\u001b[m\r\n       key-value pairs in an associative array.  When applied to\u001b[m\r\n       a  string-valued variable, \u001b[4mvalue\u001b[24m is expanded and appended\u001b[m\r\n       to the variable's value.\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n       A variable can be assigned the  \u001b[4mnameref\u001b[24m  attribute  using\u001b[m\r\n       the  \u001b[1m-n\u001b[0m  option  to the \u001b[1mdeclare\u001b[0m or \u001b[1mlocal\u001b[0m builtin commands\u001b[m\r\n       (see the descriptions of \u001b[1mdeclare\u001b[0m and \u001b[1mlocal\u001b[0m below) to cre‐\u001b[m\r\n       ate  a \u001b[4mnameref\u001b[24m, or a reference to another variable.  This\u001b[m\r\n     "]
[3619.541578, "o", "  allows variables to be manipulated indirectly.   Whenever\u001b[m\r\n       the  nameref  variable is referenced, assigned to, unset,\u001b[m\r\n       or has its  attributes  modified  (other  than  using  or\u001b[m\r\n       changing  the \u001b[4mnameref\u001b[24m attribute itself), the operation is\u001b[m\r\n       actually performed  on  the  variable  specified  by  the\u001b[m\r\n       nameref  variable's  value.   A  nameref is commonly used\u001b[m\r\n       within shell functions to refer to a variable whose  name\u001b[m\r\n       is  passed as an argument to the function.  For instance,\u001b[m\r\n       if a variable name is passed to a shell function  as  its\u001b[m\r\n       first argument, running\u001b[m\r\n              declare -n ref=$1\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[7m Manual page bash(1) line 859 (press h for help or q to quit)\u001b[27m\u001b[K"]
[3619.572929, "o", "\r\u001b[K"]
[3619.572961, "o", "       inside  the function creates a nameref variable \u001b[1mref\u001b[0m whose\u001b[m\r\n       value is the variable name passed as the first  argument.\u001b[m\r\n       References and assignments to \u001b[1mref\u001b[0m, and changes to its at‐\u001b[m\r\n       tributes, are treated as references, assignments, and at‐\u001b[m\r\n       tribute  modifications  to  the  variable  whose name was\u001b[m\r\n       passed as \u001b[1m$1\u001b[0m.  If the control variable in a \u001b[1mfor\u001b[0m loop  has\u001b[m\r\n       the nameref attribute, the list of words can be a list of\u001b[m\r\n       shell variables, and a name reference will be established\u001b[m\r\n       for each word in the list, in turn, when the loop is exe‐\u001b[m\r\n       cuted.  Array variables cannot be given the  \u001b[1mnameref\u001b[0m  at‐\u001b[m\r\n       tribute.   However, nameref variables can reference array\u001b[m\r\n       variables and subscripted array variables.  Namerefs  can\u001b[m\r\n       be  unset using the \u001b[1m-n\u001b[0m option to the \u001b[1munset\u001b[0m builtin.  Oth‐\u001b[m\r\n       erwise, if \u001b[1munset\u001b[0m is executed with the name of "]
[3619.57297, "o", " a  nameref\u001b"]
[3619.573095, "o", "[m\r\n       variable  as  an argument, the variable referenced by the\u001b[m\r\n       nameref variable will be unset.\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n   \u001b[1mPositional\u001b[0m \u001b[1mParameters\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n       A \u001b[4mpositional\u001b[24m \u001b[4mparameter\u001b[24m is a parameter denoted by  one  or\u001b[m\r\n       more  digits,  other than the single digit 0.  Positional\u001b[m\r\n       parameters are assigned from the shell's  arguments  when\u001b[m\r\n       it  is  invoked,  and  may  be  reassigned  using the \u001b[1mset\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n       builtin command.  Positional parameters may  not  be  as‐\u001b[m\r\n       signed to with assignment statements.  The positional pa‐\u001b[m\r\n       rameters are temporarily replaced when a  shell  function\u001b[m\r\n       is executed (see \u001b[1mFUNCTIONS\u001b[0m below).\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[7m Manual page bash(1) line 885 (press h for help or q to quit)\u001b[27m\u001b[K"]
[3619.604127, "o", "\r\u001b[K"]
[3619.604225, "o", "\u001b[m\r\n       When  a  positional  parameter  consisting of more than a\u001b[m\r\n       single digit is expanded, it must be enclosed  in  braces\u001b[m\r\n       (see \u001b[1mEXPANSION\u001b[0m below).\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n   \u001b[1mSpecial\u001b[0m \u001b[1mParameters\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n       The shell treats several parameters specially.  These pa‐\u001b[m\r\n       rameters may only be referenced; assignment  to  them  is\u001b[m\r\n       not allowed.\u001b[m\r\n       \u001b[1m*\u001b[0m      Expands  to  the  positional  parameters, starting\u001b[m\r\n              from one.  When the expansion is not within double\u001b[m\r\n              quotes,  each  positional  parameter  expands to a\u001b[m\r\n              separate word.  In contexts where it is performed,\u001b[m\r\n              those  words are subject to further word splitting\u001b[m\r\n              and pathname expansion.  When the expansion occurs\u001b[m\r\n              within  double quotes, it expands to a single word\u001b[m\r\n              with the value of each parameter separated by  the\u001b[m\r\n              first character of the \u001b[1mIFS\u001b[0m special variable.  "]
[3619.604259, "o", "That\u001b[m\r\n              is, \"\u001b[1m$*\u001b[0m\" is equivalent to \"\u001b[1m$1\u001b[0m\u001b[4mc\u001b[24m\u001b[1m$2\u001b[0m\u001b[4mc\u001b[24m\u001b[1m...\u001b[0m\", where \u001b[4mc\u001b[24m  is\u001b[m\r\n              the  first character of the value of the \u001b[1mIFS\u001b[0m vari‐\u001b[m\r\n              able.  If \u001b[1mIFS\u001b[0m is unset, the parameters  are  sepa‐\u001b[m\r\n              rated  by  spaces.  If \u001b[1mIFS\u001b[0m is null, the parameters\u001b[m\r\n              are joined without intervening separators.\u001b[m\r\n       \u001b[1m@\u001b[0m      Expands to  the  positional  parameters,  starting\u001b[m\r\n              from  one.   In  contexts  where word splitting is\u001b[m\r\n              performed, this expands each positional  parameter\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[7m Manual page bash(1) line 911 (press h for help or q to quit)\u001b[27m\u001b[K"]
[3619.635581, "o", "\r\u001b[K              to  a  separate word; if not within double quotes,\u001b[m\r\n              these words are subject  to  word  splitting.   In\u001b[m\r\n              contexts  where  word  splitting is not performed,\u001b[m\r\n              this expands to a single word with each positional\u001b[m\r\n              parameter  separated  by a space.  When the expan‐\u001b[m\r\n              sion occurs within double quotes,  each  parameter\u001b[m\r\n              expands  to  a  separate  word.   That is, \"\u001b[1m$@\u001b[0m\" is\u001b[m\r\n              equivalent to \"\u001b[1m$1\u001b[0m\" \"\u001b[1m$2\u001b[0m\" ...  If the  double-quoted\u001b[m\r\n              expansion  occurs  within a word, the expansion of\u001b[m\r\n"]
[3619.635619, "o", "              the first parameter is joined with  the  beginning\u001b[m\r\n              part  of  the  original word, and the expansion of\u001b[m\r\n              the last parameter is joined with the last part of\u001b[m\r\n              the  original  word.  When there are no positional\u001b[m\r\n              parameters, \"\u001b[1m$@\u001b[0m\" and \u001b[1m$@\u001b[0m expand to  nothing  (i.e.,\u001b[m\r\n              they are removed).\u001b[m\r\n       \u001b[1m#\u001b[0m      Expands  to the number of positional parameters in\u001b[m\r\n              decimal.\u001b[m\r\n       \u001b[1m?\u001b[0m      Expands to the exit status of  the  most  recently\u001b[m\r\n              executed foreground pipeline.\u001b[m\r\n       \u001b[1m-\u001b[0m      Expands  to  the current option flags as specified\u001b[m\r\n              upon invocation, by the \u001b[1mset\u001b[0m  builtin  command,  or\u001b[m\r\n              those  set by the shell itself (such as the \u001b[1m-i\u001b[0m op‐\u001b[m\r\n              tion).\u001b[m\r\n       \u001b[1m$\u001b[0m      Expands to the process ID of the shell. In a  sub‐\u001b[m\r\n              shell, it expands to the process ID of the cur"]
[3619.635628, "o", "rent\u001b[m\r\n              shell, not the subshell.\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[7m Manual page bash(1) line 937 (press h for help or q to quit)\u001b[27m\u001b[K"]
[3619.666094, "o", "\r\u001b[K"]
[3619.666123, "o", "       \u001b[1m!\u001b[0m      Expands to the process ID of the job most recently\u001b[m\r\n              placed into the background, whether executed as an\u001b[m\r\n              asynchronous command or using the \u001b[1mbg\u001b[0m builtin  (see\u001b[m\r\n              \u001b[1mJOB\u001b[0m \u001b[1mCONTROL\u001b[0m below).\u001b[m\r\n       \u001b[1m0\u001b[0m      Expands  to the name of the shell or shell script.\u001b[m\r\n              This is set at shell initialization.  If  \u001b[1mbash\u001b[0m  is\u001b[m\r\n              invoked  with a file of commands, \u001b[1m$0\u001b[0m is set to the\u001b[m\r\n              name of that file.  If \u001b[1mbash\u001b[0m is started with the \u001b[1m-c\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n              option, then \u001b[1m$0\u001b[0m is set to the first argument after\u001b[m\r\n              the string to be  executed,  if  one  is  present.\u001b[m\r\n              Otherwise,  it  is set to the filename used to in‐\u001b[m\r\n              voke \u001b[1mbash\u001b[0m, as given by argument zero.\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n   \u001b[1mShell\u001b[0m \u001b[1mVariables\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n       The following variables are set by the shell:\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n       \u001b[1m_\u001b[0m      At shell startup, set "]
[3619.666129, "o", "to the pathname used to  in‐\u001b[m\r\n              voke  the  shell or shell script being executed as\u001b[m\r\n              passed in the environment or argument list.   Sub‐\u001b[m\r\n              sequently,  expands  to  the  last argument to the\u001b[m\r\n              previous simple  command  executed  in  the  fore‐\u001b[m\r\n              ground,  after  expansion.   Also  set to the full\u001b[m\r\n              pathname used to invoke each command executed  and\u001b[m\r\n              placed  in  the  environment exported to that com‐\u001b[m\r\n              mand.  When checking mail,  this  parameter  holds\u001b[m\r\n              the name of the mail file currently being checked.\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[7m Manual page bash(1) line 963 (press h for help or q to quit)\u001b[27m\u001b[K"]
[3619.696914, "o", "\r\u001b[K"]
[3619.697006, "o", "       \u001b[1mBASH\u001b[0m   Expands  to  the full filename used to invoke this\u001b[m\r\n              instance of \u001b[1mbash\u001b[0m.\u001b[m\r\n       \u001b[1mBASHOPTS\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n              A colon-separated list of enabled  shell  options.\u001b[m\r\n              Each  word in the list is a valid argument for the\u001b[m\r\n              \u001b[1m-s\u001b[0m option to the \u001b[1mshopt\u001b[0m builtin command (see  \u001b[1mSHELL\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n              \u001b[1mBUILTIN\u001b[0m \u001b[1mCOMMANDS\u001b[0m below).  The options appearing in\u001b[m\r\n              \u001b[1mBASHOPTS\u001b[0m are those reported as \u001b[4mon\u001b[24m  by  \u001b[1mshopt\u001b[0m.   If\u001b[m\r\n              this  variable  is  in  the  environment when \u001b[1mbash\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n              starts up, each shell option in the list  will  be\u001b[m\r\n              enabled  before  reading  any startup files.  This\u001b[m\r\n              variable is read-only.\u001b[m\r\n       \u001b[1mBASHPID\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n              Expands to the process  ID  of  the  current  \u001b[1mbash\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n              process.   This differs from \u001b[1m$$\u001b[0m under certain cir‐\u001b[m\r\n              cumstances, "]
[3619.697011, "o", "such as subshe"]
[3619.697052, "o", "lls that do not  require\u001b[m\r\n              \u001b[1mbash\u001b[0m to be re-initialized.  Assignments to \u001b[1mBASHPID\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n              have no effect.  If \u001b[1mBASHPID\u001b[0m is unset, it loses its\u001b[m\r\n              special properties, even if it is subsequently re‐\u001b[m\r\n              set.\u001b[m\r\n       \u001b[1mBASH_ALIASES\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n              An associative array variable whose members corre‐\u001b[m\r\n"]
[3619.697087, "o", "              spond  to  the  internal  list of aliases as main‐\u001b[m\r\n              tained by the \u001b[1malias\u001b[0m builtin.   Elements  added  to\u001b[m\r\n              this  array appear in the alias list; however, un‐\u001b[m\r\n              setting array elements currently  does  not  cause\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[7m Manual page bash(1) line 989 (press h for help or q to quit)\u001b[27m\u001b[K"]
[3619.728627, "o", "\r\u001b[K"]
[3619.728704, "o", "              aliases  to  be  removed  from the alias list.  If\u001b[m\r\n              \u001b[1mBASH_ALIASES\u001b[0m is unset, it loses its special  prop‐\u001b[m\r\n              erties, even if it is subsequently reset.\u001b[m\r\n       \u001b[1mBASH_ARGC\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n              An  array  variable whose values are the number of\u001b[m\r\n              parameters in each frame of the current \u001b[1mbash\u001b[0m  exe‐\u001b[m\r\n              cution  call  stack.   The number of parameters to\u001b[m\r\n              the current subroutine (shell function  or  script\u001b[m\r\n              executed  with  \u001b[1m.\u001b[0m  or \u001b[1msource\u001b[0m) is at the top of the\u001b[m\r\n              stack.  When a subroutine is executed, the  number\u001b[m\r\n              of  parameters  passed  is  pushed onto \u001b[1mBASH_ARGC\u001b[0m.\u001b[m\r\n              The shell sets \u001b[1mBASH_ARGC\u001b[0m only when in extended de‐\u001b[m\r\n              bugging  mode (see the description of the \u001b[1mextdebug\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n              option  to  the  \u001b[1mshopt\u001b[0m  builtin  below).   Setting\u001b[m\r\n              \u001b[1mextdebug\u001b[0m  after"]
[3619.728727, "o", " the shell ha"]
[3619.728745, "o", "s started to execute a\u001b[m\r\n              script, or referencing this variable when \u001b[1mextdebug\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n              is not set, may result in inconsistent values.\u001b[m\r\n       \u001b[1mBASH_ARGV\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n              An array variable containing all of the parameters\u001b[m\r\n              in the current \u001b[1mbash\u001b[0m execution call stack.  The fi‐\u001b[m\r\n              nal  parameter  of  the last subroutine call is at\u001b[m\r\n              the top of the stack; the first parameter  of  the\u001b[m\r\n              initial  call is at the bottom.  When a subroutine\u001b[m\r\n              is executed, the parameters  supplied  are  pushed\u001b[m\r\n              onto  \u001b[1mBASH_ARGV\u001b[0m.   The  shell  sets \u001b[1mBASH_ARGV\u001b[0m only\u001b[m\r\n              when in extended debugging mode (see the  descrip‐\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[7m Manual page bash(1) line 1015 (press h for help or q to quit)\u001b[27m\u001b[K"]
[3619.759863, "o", "\r\u001b[K              tion  of  the \u001b[1mextdebug\u001b[0m option to the \u001b[1mshopt\u001b[0m builtin\u001b[m\r\n              below).  Setting  \u001b[1mextdebug\u001b[0m  after  the  shell  has\u001b[m\r\n              started  to  execute a script, or referencing this\u001b[m\r\n              variable when \u001b[1mextdebug\u001b[0m is not set, may  result  in\u001b[m\r\n              inconsistent values.\u001b[m\r\n       \u001b[1mBASH_ARGV0\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n              When referenced, this variable expands to the name\u001b[m\r\n              of the shell or shell script (identical to \u001b[1m$0\u001b[0m; see\u001b[m\r\n              the  description  of  special  parameter 0 above).\u001b[m\r\n              Assignment to \u001b[1mBASH_ARGV0\u001b[0m causes the value assigned\u001b[m\r\n              to  also  be assigned to \u001b[1m$0\u001b[0m.  If \u001b[1mBASH_ARGV0\u001b[0m is un‐\u001b[m\r\n              set, it loses its special properties, even  if  it\u001b[m\r\n              is subsequently reset.\u001b[m\r\n       \u001b[1mBASH_CMDS\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n              An associative array variable whose members corre‐\u001b[m\r\n              spond to the internal hash table  of  co"]
[3619.760005, "o", "mmands  as\u001b[m\r\n    "]
[3619.760025, "o", "          maintained by the \u001b[1mhash\u001b[0m builtin.  Elements added to\u001b[m\r\n              this array appear in the hash table; however,  un‐\u001b[m\r\n              setting  array  elements  currently does not cause\u001b[m\r\n              command names to be removed from the  hash  table.\u001b[m\r\n              If  \u001b[1mBASH_CMDS\u001b[0m is unset, it loses its special prop‐\u001b[m\r\n              erties, even if it is subsequently reset.\u001b[m\r\n       \u001b[1mBASH_COMMAND\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n              The command currently being executed or  about  to\u001b[m\r\n              be  executed, unless the shell is executing a com‐\u001b[m\r\n              mand as the result of a trap, in which case it  is\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[7m Manual page bash(1) line 1041 (press h for help or q to quit)\u001b[27m\u001b[K"]
[3619.791068, "o", "\r\u001b[K              the command executing at the time of the trap.  If\u001b[m\r\n              \u001b[1mBASH_COMMAND\u001b[0m is unset, it loses its special  prop‐\u001b[m\r\n              erties, even if it is subsequently reset.\u001b[m\r\n       \u001b[1mBASH_EXECUTION_STRING\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n              The command argument to the \u001b[1m-c\u001b[0m invocation option.\u001b[m\r\n       \u001b[1mBASH_LINENO\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n              An  array variable whose members are the line num‐\u001b[m\r\n"]
[3619.791134, "o", "              bers in source files where each corresponding mem‐\u001b[m\r\n              ber  of  \u001b[1mFUNCNAME\u001b[0m was invoked.  \u001b[1m${BASH_LINENO[\u001b[0m\u001b[4m$i\u001b[24m\u001b[1m]}\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n              is  the   line   number   in   the   source   file\u001b[m\r\n              (\u001b[1m${BASH_SOURCE[\u001b[0m\u001b[4m$i+1\u001b[24m\u001b[1m]}\u001b[0m)  where  \u001b[1m${FUNCNAME[\u001b[0m\u001b[4m$i\u001b[24m\u001b[1m]}\u001b[0m was\u001b[m\r\n              called  (or  \u001b[1m${BASH_LINENO[\u001b[0m\u001b[4m$i-1\u001b[24m\u001b[1m]}\u001b[0m  if   referenced\u001b[m\r\n              within another shell function).  Use \u001b[1mLINENO\u001b[0m to ob‐\u001b[m\r\n              tain the current line number.\u001b[m\r\n       \u001b[1mBASH_LOADABLES_PATH\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n              A colon-separated list of directories in which the\u001b[m\r\n              shell  looks  for  dynamically  loadable  builtins\u001b[m\r\n              specified by the \u001b[1menable\u001b[0m command.\u001b[m\r\n       \u001b[1mBASH_REMATCH\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n              An array variable whose members  are  assigned  by\u001b[m\r\n              the  \u001b[1m=~\u001b[0m binary operator to the \u001b[1m[[\u001b[0m conditional com‐\u001b[m\r\n              mand"]
[3619.791226, "o", ".  The element with index 0 is the portion  of\u001b[m\r\n              the string matching the entire regular expression.\u001b[m\r\n              The element with index \u001b[4mn\u001b[24m is  the  portion  of  the\u001b[m\r\n              string  matching  the \u001b[4mn\u001b[24mth parenthesized subexpres‐\u001b[m\r\n              sion.\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[7m Manual page bash(1) line 1067 (press h for help or q to quit)\u001b[27m\u001b[K"]
[3619.822081, "o", "\r\u001b[K       \u001b[1mBASH_SOURCE\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n              An array variable whose  members  are  the  source\u001b[m\r\n              filenames  where  the corresponding shell function\u001b[m\r\n              names in the \u001b[1mFUNCNAME\u001b[0m array variable are  defined.\u001b[m\r\n              The  shell  function \u001b[1m${FUNCNAME[\u001b[0m\u001b[4m$i\u001b[24m\u001b[1m]}\u001b[0m is defined in\u001b[m\r\n              the  file  \u001b[1m${BASH_SOURCE[\u001b[0m\u001b[4m$i\u001b[24m\u001b[1m]}\u001b[0m  and   called   from\u001b[m\r\n              \u001b[1m${BASH_SOURCE[\u001b[0m\u001b[4m$i+1\u001b[24m\u001b[1m]}\u001b[0m.\u001b[m\r\n       \u001b[1mBASH_SUBSHELL\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n              Incremented  by  one  within each subshell or sub‐\u001b[m\r\n              shell environment when the shell begins  executing\u001b[m\r\n              in  that environment.  The initial value is 0.  If\u001b[m\r\n              \u001b[1mBASH_SUBSHELL\u001b[0m is unset, it loses its special prop‐\u001b[m\r\n              erties, even if it is subsequently reset.\u001b[m\r\n       \u001b[1mBASH_VERSINFO\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n              A  readonly array variable whose members hold ver‐\u001b[m\r\n              sion information for t"]
[3619.82211, "o", "his instance of  \u001b[1mbash\u001b[0m.   The\u001b[m\r\n              values  assigned  to the array members are as fol‐\u001b[m\r\n              lows:\u001b[m\r\n              \u001b[1mBASH_VERSINFO[\u001b[0m0\u001b[1m]\u001b[0m        The major  version  number\u001b[m\r\n                                      (the \u001b[4mrelease\u001b[24m).\u001b[m\r\n              \u001b[1mBASH_VERSINFO[\u001b[0m1\u001b[1m]\u001b[0m        The  minor  version number\u001b[m\r\n"]
[3619.822121, "o", "                                      (the \u001b[4mversion\u001b[24m).\u001b[m\r\n              \u001b[1mBASH_VERSINFO[\u001b[0m2\u001b[1m]\u001b[0m        The patch level.\u001b[m\r\n              \u001b[1mBASH_VERSINFO[\u001b[0m3\u001b[1m]\u001b[0m        The build version.\u001b[m\r\n              \u001b[1mBASH_VERSINFO[\u001b[0m4\u001b[1m]\u001b[0m        The release status  (e.g.,\u001b[m\r\n                                      \u001b[4mbeta1\u001b[24m).\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[7m Manual page bash(1) line 1093 (press h for help or q to quit)\u001b[27m\u001b[K"]
[3619.853608, "o", "\r\u001b[K"]
[3619.853727, "o", "              \u001b[1mBASH_VERSINFO[\u001b[0m5\u001b[1m]\u001b[0m        The value of \u001b[1mMACHTYPE\u001b[0m.\u001b[m\r\n       \u001b[1mBASH_VERSION\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n              Expands to a string describing the version of this\u001b[m\r\n              instance of \u001b[1mbash\u001b[0m.\u001b[m\r\n       \u001b[1mCOMP_CWORD\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n              An index into \u001b[1m${COMP_WORDS}\u001b[0m of the word containing\u001b[m\r\n              the  current  cursor  position.   This variable is\u001b[m\r\n              available only in shell functions invoked  by  the\u001b[m\r\n              programmable  completion  facilities (see \u001b[1mProgram‐\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n              \u001b[1mmable\u001b[0m \u001b[1mCompletion\u001b[0m below).\u001b[m\r\n       \u001b[1mCOMP_KEY\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n              The key (or final key of a key sequence)  used  to\u001b[m\r\n              invoke the current completion function.\u001b[m\r\n       \u001b[1mCOMP_LINE\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n              The current command line.  This variable is avail‐\u001b[m\r\n              able only in shell functions and external commands\u001b[m\r\n              invoked  by the programmable completion facilities\u001b[m\r\n              "]
[3619.85376, "o", "(see \u001b[1mProgrammable\u001b[0m \u001b[1mCompletion\u001b[0m below).\u001b[m\r\n       \u001b[1mCOMP_POINT\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n              The index of the current cursor position  relative\u001b[m\r\n              to  the  beginning of the current command.  If the\u001b[m\r\n              current cursor position is at the end of the  cur‐\u001b[m\r\n              rent  command, the value of this variable is equal\u001b[m\r\n              to \u001b[1m${#COMP_LINE}\u001b[0m.  This variable is available only\u001b[m\r\n              in  shell  functions and external commands invoked\u001b[m\r\n              by the  programmable  completion  facilities  (see\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[7m Manual page bash(1) line 1119 (press h for help or q to quit)\u001b[27m\u001b[K"]
[3619.885242, "o", "\r\u001b[K              \u001b[1mProgrammable\u001b[0m \u001b[1mCompletion\u001b[0m below).\u001b[m\r\n       \u001b[1mCOMP_TYPE\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n              Set  to an integer value corresponding to the type\u001b[m\r\n              of completion attempted that caused  a  completion\u001b[m\r\n              function to be called: \u001b[4mTAB\u001b[24m, for normal completion,\u001b[m\r\n              \u001b[4m?\u001b[24m, for listing completions after successive  tabs,\u001b[m\r\n              \u001b[4m!\u001b[24m,  for  listing alternatives on partial word com‐\u001b[m\r\n              pletion, \u001b[4m@\u001b[24m, to list completions if the word is not\u001b[m\r\n              unmodified, or \u001b[4m%\u001b[24m, for menu completion.  This vari‐\u001b[m\r\n              able is available only in shell functions and  ex‐\u001b[m\r\n              ternal  commands  invoked by the programmable com‐\u001b[m\r\n              pletion facilities  (see  \u001b[1mProgrammable\u001b[0m  \u001b[1mCompletion\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n"]
[3619.885271, "o", "              below).\u001b[m\r\n       \u001b[1mCOMP_WORDBREAKS\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n              The  set  of  characters that the \u001b[1mreadline\u001b[0m library\u001b[m\r\n              treats as word  separators  when"]
[3619.885309, "o", "  performing  word\u001b[m\r\n              completion.  If \u001b[1mCOMP_WORDBREAKS\u001b[0m is unset, it loses\u001b[m\r\n              its special properties, even if it is subsequently\u001b[m\r\n              reset.\u001b[m\r\n       \u001b[1mCOMP_WORDS\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n              An array variable (see \u001b[1mArrays\u001b[0m below) consisting of\u001b[m\r\n              the individual words in the current command  line.\u001b[m\r\n              The  line  is  split  into words as \u001b[1mreadline\u001b[0m would\u001b[m\r\n              split  it,  using  \u001b[1mCOMP_WORDBREAKS\u001b[0m  as   described\u001b[m\r\n              above.   This  variable is available only in shell\u001b[m\r\n              functions invoked by the  programmable  completion\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[7m Manual page bash(1) line 1145 (press h for help or q to quit)\u001b[27m\u001b[K"]
[3619.916507, "o", "\r\u001b[K"]
[3619.916536, "o", "              facilities (see \u001b[1mProgrammable\u001b[0m \u001b[1mCompletion\u001b[0m below).\u001b[m\r\n       \u001b[1mCOPROC\u001b[0m An  array  variable  (see \u001b[1mArrays\u001b[0m below) created to\u001b[m\r\n              hold the file descriptors for output from and  in‐\u001b[m\r\n              put  to  an  unnamed  coprocess  (see  \u001b[1mCoprocesses\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n              above).\u001b[m\r\n       \u001b[1mDIRSTACK\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n              An array variable (see  \u001b[1mArrays\u001b[0m  below)  containing\u001b[m\r\n              the  current contents of the directory stack.  Di‐\u001b[m\r\n              rectories appear in the stack in  the  order  they\u001b[m\r\n"]
[3619.916545, "o", "              are  displayed  by the \u001b[1mdirs\u001b[0m builtin.  Assigning to\u001b[m\r\n              members of this array variable may be used to mod‐\u001b[m\r\n              ify  directories  already  in  the  stack, but the\u001b[m\r\n              \u001b[1mpushd\u001b[0m and \u001b[1mpopd\u001b[0m builtins must be used  to  add  and\u001b[m\r\n              remove  directories.   Assignment to this variable\u001b[m\r\n              will  not  change  the  current   directory.    If\u001b[m\r\n            "]
[3619.916712, "o", "  \u001b[1mDIRSTACK\u001b[0m  is  unset,  it loses its special proper‐\u001b[m\r\n              ties, even if it is subsequently reset.\u001b[m\r\n       \u001b[1mEPOCHREALTIME\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n              Each time this parameter is referenced, it expands\u001b[m\r\n              to the number of seconds since the Unix Epoch (see\u001b[m\r\n              \u001b[4mtime\u001b[24m(3)) as a floating point value with micro-sec‐\u001b[m\r\n              ond granularity.  Assignments to \u001b[1mEPOCHREALTIME\u001b[0m are\u001b[m\r\n              ignored.  If \u001b[1mEPOCHREALTIME\u001b[0m is unset, it loses  its\u001b[m\r\n              special properties, even if it is subsequently re‐\u001b[m\r\n"]
[3619.916737, "o", "              set.\u001b[m\r\n       \u001b[1mEPOCHSECONDS\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[7m Manual page bash(1) line 1171 (press h for help or q to quit)\u001b[27m\u001b[K"]
[3619.947278, "o", "\r\u001b[K"]
[3619.947305, "o", "              Each time this parameter is referenced, it expands\u001b[m\r\n              to the number of seconds since the Unix Epoch (see\u001b[m\r\n              \u001b[4mtime\u001b[24m(3)).  Assignments  to  \u001b[1mEPOCHSECONDS\u001b[0m  are  ig‐\u001b[m\r\n              nored.   If  \u001b[1mEPOCHSECONDS\u001b[0m  is  unset, it loses its\u001b[m\r\n              special properties, even if it is subsequently re‐\u001b[m\r\n              set.\u001b[m\r\n       \u001b[1mEUID\u001b[0m   Expands  to  the  effective user ID of the current\u001b[m\r\n              user, initialized at shell startup.  This variable\u001b[m\r\n              is readonly.\u001b[m\r\n       \u001b[1mFUNCNAME\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n              An  array  variable  containing  the  names of all\u001b[m\r\n              shell functions currently in  the  execution  call\u001b[m\r\n              stack.   The  element  with index 0 is the name of\u001b[m\r\n              any currently-executing shell function.  The  bot‐\u001b[m\r\n              tom-most  element (the one with the highest index)\u001b[m\r\n              is \"main\".  This variable exists only when a shell\u001b[m\r\n      "]
[3619.94731, "o", "        functio"]
[3619.947518, "o", "n  is  executing.   Assignments to \u001b[1mFUNCNAME\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n              have no effect.  If \u001b[1mFUNCNAME\u001b[0m is  unset,  it  loses\u001b[m\r\n              its special properties, even if it is subsequently\u001b[m\r\n              reset.\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n              This variable can be  used  with  \u001b[1mBASH_LINENO\u001b[0m  and\u001b[m\r\n              \u001b[1mBASH_SOURCE\u001b[0m.   Each element of \u001b[1mFUNCNAME\u001b[0m has corre‐\u001b[m\r\n              sponding elements in \u001b[1mBASH_LINENO\u001b[0m  and  \u001b[1mBASH_SOURCE\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n              to describe the call stack.  For instance, \u001b[1m${FUNC‐\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n              \u001b[1mNAME[\u001b[0m\u001b[4m$i\u001b[24m\u001b[1m]}\u001b[0m    was    called    from    the     file\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[7m Manual page bash(1) line 1197 (press h for help or q to quit)\u001b[27m\u001b[K"]
[3619.978588, "o", "\r\u001b[K"]
[3619.978712, "o", "              \u001b[1m${BASH_SOURCE[\u001b[0m\u001b[4m$i+1\u001b[24m\u001b[1m]}\u001b[0m      at      line      number\u001b[m\r\n              \u001b[1m${BASH_LINENO[\u001b[0m\u001b[4m$i\u001b[24m\u001b[1m]}\u001b[0m.  The \u001b[1mcaller\u001b[0m  builtin  displays\u001b[m\r\n              the current call stack using this information.\u001b[m\r\n       \u001b[1mGROUPS\u001b[0m An array variable containing the list of groups of\u001b[m\r\n"]
[3619.978745, "o", "              which the current user is a  member.   Assignments\u001b[m\r\n              to  \u001b[1mGROUPS\u001b[0m have no effect.  If \u001b[1mGROUPS\u001b[0m is unset, it\u001b[m\r\n              loses its special properties, even if it is subse‐\u001b[m\r\n              quently reset.\u001b[m\r\n       \u001b[1mHISTCMD\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n              The  history number, or index in the history list,\u001b[m\r\n              of the current command.   Assignments  to  \u001b[1mHISTCMD\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n              are  ignored.   If  \u001b[1mHISTCMD\u001b[0m is unset, it loses its\u001b[m\r\n              special properties, even if it is subsequently re‐\u001b[m\r\n              set.\u001b[m\r\n       \u001b[1mHOSTNAME\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n              Automatically set to the name of the current host.\u001b[m\r\n  "]
[3619.978773, "o", "     \u001b[1mHOSTTYPE\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n              Automatically  set  to  a string that uniquely de‐\u001b[m\r\n              scribes the type of machine on which \u001b[1mbash\u001b[0m is  exe‐\u001b[m\r\n              cuting.  The default is system-dependent.\u001b[m\r\n       \u001b[1mLINENO\u001b[0m Each  time this parameter is referenced, the shell\u001b[m\r\n              substitutes a decimal number representing the cur‐\u001b[m\r\n              rent  sequential  line  number  (starting  with 1)\u001b[m\r\n              within a script or function.  When not in a script\u001b[m\r\n              or  function, the value substituted is not guaran‐\u001b[m\r\n              teed to be meaningful.  If  \u001b[1mLINENO\u001b[0m  is  unset,  it\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[7m Manual page bash(1) line 1223 (press h for help or q to quit)\u001b[27m\u001b[K"]
[3620.00979, "o", "\r\u001b[K"]
[3620.009883, "o", "              loses its special properties, even if it is subse‐\u001b[m\r\n              quently reset.\u001b[m\r\n       \u001b[1mMACHTYPE\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n              Automatically set to a string that fully describes\u001b[m\r\n              the system type on which \u001b[1mbash\u001b[0m is executing, in the\u001b[m\r\n              standard GNU \u001b[4mcpu-company-system\u001b[24m format.   The  de‐\u001b[m\r\n              fault is system-dependent.\u001b[m\r\n       \u001b[1mMAPFILE\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n              An  array  variable  (see \u001b[1mArrays\u001b[0m below) created to\u001b[m\r\n              hold the text read by the \u001b[1mmapfile\u001b[0m builtin when  no\u001b[m\r\n              variable name is supplied.\u001b[m\r\n       \u001b[1mOLDPWD\u001b[0m The  previous  working  directory as set by the \u001b[1mcd\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n              command.\u001b[m\r\n       \u001b[1mOPTARG\u001b[0m The value of the last option argument processed by\u001b[m\r\n              the  \u001b[1mgetopts\u001b[0m  builtin  command  (see \u001b[1mSHELL\u001b[0m \u001b[1mBUILTIN\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n              \u001b[1mCOMMANDS\u001b[0m below).\u001b[m\r\n       \u001b[1mOPTIND\u001b[0m The index of the next argument to be processed  "]
[3620.009904, "o", "by\u001b[m\r\n              the  \u001b[1mgetopts\u001b[0m  builtin  command  (see \u001b[1mSHELL\u001b[0m \u001b[1mBUILTIN\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n              \u001b[1mCOMMANDS\u001b[0m below).\u001b[m\r\n       \u001b[1mOSTYPE\u001b[0m Automatically set to a string that  describes  the\u001b[m\r\n              operating  system on which \u001b[1mbash\u001b[0m is executing.  The\u001b[m\r\n              default is system-dependent.\u001b[m\r\n       \u001b[1mPIPESTATUS\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n              An array variable (see \u001b[1mArrays\u001b[0m below) containing  a\u001b[m\r\n              list  of  exit status values from the processes in\u001b[m\r\n              the  most-recently-executed  foreground   pipeline\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[7m Manual page bash(1) line 1249 (press h for help or q to quit)\u001b[27m\u001b[K"]
[3620.040787, "o", "\r\u001b[K"]
[3620.040817, "o", "              (which may contain only a single command).\u001b[m\r\n       \u001b[1mPPID\u001b[0m   The  process ID of the shell's parent.  This vari‐\u001b[m\r\n              able is readonly.\u001b[m\r\n       \u001b[1mPWD\u001b[0m    The current working directory as  set  by  the  \u001b[1mcd\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n              command.\u001b[m\r\n       \u001b[1mRANDOM\u001b[0m Each time this parameter is referenced, it expands\u001b[m\r\n              to a random integer between 0 and 32767.   Assign‐\u001b[m\r\n              ing  a value to \u001b[1mRANDOM\u001b[0m initializes (seeds) the se‐\u001b[m\r\n              quence of random numbers.  If \u001b[1mRANDOM\u001b[0m is unset,  it\u001b[m\r\n              loses its special properties, even if it is subse‐\u001b[m\r\n              quently reset.\u001b[m\r\n       \u001b[1mREADLINE_ARGUMENT\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n              Any numeric argument given to a  readline  command\u001b[m\r\n              that  was  defined  using  \"bind  -x\"  (see  \u001b[1mSHELL\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n              \u001b[1mBUILTIN\u001b[0m \u001b[1mCOMMANDS\u001b[0m below) when it was invoked.\u001b[m\r\n       \u001b[1mREADLINE_LINE\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n              The contents of the"]
[3620.040822, "o", " \u001b[1mreadline\u001b["]
[3620.040982, "o", "0m line buffer, for  use\u001b[m\r\n              with \"bind -x\" (see \u001b[1mSHELL\u001b[0m \u001b[1mBUILTIN\u001b[0m \u001b[1mCOMMANDS\u001b[0m below).\u001b[m\r\n       \u001b[1mREADLINE_MARK\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n              The  position  of the mark (saved insertion point)\u001b[m\r\n              in the \u001b[1mreadline\u001b[0m line buffer, for  use  with  \"bind\u001b[m\r\n              -x\" (see \u001b[1mSHELL\u001b[0m \u001b[1mBUILTIN\u001b[0m \u001b[1mCOMMANDS\u001b[0m below).  The char‐\u001b[m\r\n              acters between the insertion point  and  the  mark\u001b[m\r\n              are often called the \u001b[4mregion\u001b[24m.\u001b[m\r\n       \u001b[1mREADLINE_POINT\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n              The  position  of the insertion point in the \u001b[1mread‐\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[7m Manual page bash(1) line 1275 (press h for help or q to quit)\u001b[27m\u001b[K"]
[3620.072211, "o", "\r\u001b[K              \u001b[1mline\u001b[0m line buffer, for  use  with  \"bind  -x\"  (see\u001b[m\r\n              \u001b[1mSHELL\u001b[0m \u001b[1mBUILTIN\u001b[0m \u001b[1mCOMMANDS\u001b[0m below).\u001b[m\r\n       \u001b[1mREPLY\u001b[0m  Set  to the line of input read by the \u001b[1mread\u001b[0m builtin\u001b[m\r\n              command when no arguments are supplied.\u001b[m\r\n       \u001b[1mSECONDS\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n              Each time this parameter is referenced, it expands\u001b[m\r\n              to  the  number of seconds since shell invocation.\u001b[m\r\n              If a value is assigned to \u001b[1mSECONDS\u001b[0m, the  value  re‐\u001b[m\r\n              turned upon subsequent references is the number of\u001b[m\r\n              seconds since the assignment plus  the  value  as‐\u001b[m\r\n              signed.  The number of seconds at shell invocation\u001b[m\r\n              and the current  time  are  always  determined  by\u001b[m\r\n              querying  the  system clock.  If \u001b[1mSECONDS\u001b[0m is unset,\u001b[m\r\n              it loses its special properties,  even  if  it  is\u001b[m\r\n              subsequently reset.\u001b[m\r\n       \u001b[1mSHELLOPTS\u001b"]
[3620.072242, "o", "[0m\u001b[m\r\n              A  colon-separated  list of enabled shell options.\u001b[m\r\n              Each word in the list is a valid argument for  the\u001b[m\r\n              \u001b[1m-o\u001b[0m  option  to  the \u001b[1mset\u001b[0m builtin command (see \u001b[1mSHELL\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n              \u001b[1mBUILTIN\u001b[0m \u001b[1mCOMMANDS\u001b[0m below).  The options appearing in\u001b[m\r\n"]
[3620.072453, "o", "              \u001b[1mSHELLOPTS\u001b[0m  are those reported as \u001b[4mon\u001b[24m by \u001b[1mset\u001b[0m \u001b[1m-o\u001b[0m.  If\u001b[m\r\n              this variable is  in  the  environment  when  \u001b[1mbash\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n              starts  up,  each shell option in the list will be\u001b[m\r\n              enabled before reading any  startup  files.   This\u001b[m\r\n              variable is read-only.\u001b[m\r\n       \u001b[1mSHLVL\u001b[0m  Incremented  by  one each time an instance of \u001b[1mbash\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[7m Manual page bash(1) line 1301 (press h for help or q to quit)\u001b[27m\u001b[K"]
[3620.103884, "o", "\r\u001b[K"]
[3620.103912, "o", "              is started.\u001b[m\r\n       \u001b[1mSRANDOM\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n              This variable expands to  a  32-bit  pseudo-random\u001b[m\r\n              number each time it is referenced. The random num‐\u001b[m\r\n              ber generator is not linear on systems  that  sup‐\u001b[m\r\n              port  /dev/urandom or \u001b[4marc4random\u001b[24m, so each returned\u001b[m\r\n              number has no relationship to the numbers  preced‐\u001b[m\r\n              ing  it.   The  random  number generator cannot be\u001b[m\r\n              seeded, so assignments to this  variable  have  no\u001b[m\r\n              effect.  If \u001b[1mSRANDOM\u001b[0m is unset, it loses its special\u001b[m\r\n              properties, even if it is subsequently reset.\u001b[m\r\n       \u001b[1mUID\u001b[0m    Expands to the user ID of the current  user,  ini‐\u001b[m\r\n              tialized at shell startup.  This variable is read‐\u001b[m\r\n              only.\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n       The following variables are used by the shell.   In  some\u001b[m\r\n       cases,  \u001b[1mbash\u001b[0m assigns a default value to a variable; these\u001b[m\r\n   "]
[3620.103922, "o", "    cases are no"]
[3620.103943, "o", "ted below.\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n       \u001b[1mBASH_COMPAT\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n              The value is used to set the shell's compatibility\u001b[m\r\n              level.   See  \u001b[1mSHELL\u001b[0m \u001b[1mCOMPATIBILITY\u001b[0m \u001b[1mMODE\u001b[0m below for a\u001b[m\r\n              description of the  various  compatibility  levels\u001b[m\r\n              and  their  effects.   The  value may be a decimal\u001b[m\r\n              number (e.g., 4.2) or an integer (e.g., 42) corre‐\u001b[m\r\n              sponding  to  the desired compatibility level.  If\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[7m Manual page bash(1) line 1327 (press h for help or q to quit)\u001b[27m\u001b[K"]
[3620.134657, "o", "\r\u001b[K"]
[3620.134798, "o", "              \u001b[1mBASH_COMPAT\u001b[0m is unset or set to the  empty  string,\u001b[m\r\n              the  compatibility level is set to the default for\u001b[m\r\n              the current version.  If \u001b[1mBASH_COMPAT\u001b[0m is set  to  a\u001b[m\r\n              value  that  is not one of the valid compatibility\u001b[m\r\n              levels, the shell prints an error message and sets\u001b[m\r\n              the  compatibility  level  to  the default for the\u001b[m\r\n              current version.  The valid values  correspond  to\u001b[m\r\n              the  compatibility  levels  described  below under\u001b[m\r\n              \u001b[1mSHELL\u001b[0m \u001b[1mCOMPATIBILITY\u001b[0m \u001b[1mMODE\u001b[0m.  For example, 4.2 and 42\u001b[m\r\n              are  valid  values that correspond to the \u001b[1mcompat42\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n              \u001b[1mshopt\u001b[0m option and set the  compatibility  level  to\u001b[m\r\n              42.  The current version is also a valid value.\u001b[m\r\n       \u001b[1mBASH_ENV\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n              If  this parameter is set when \u001b[1mbash\u001b[0m is executing a\u001b[m\r\n              shell script, its value "]
[3620.134812, "o", "is interpreted as a  file‐\u001b[m\r\n              name  containing commands to initialize the shell,\u001b[m\r\n              as in \u001b[4m~/.bashrc\u001b[24m.  The value of  \u001b[1mBASH_ENV\u001b[0m  is  sub‐\u001b[m\r\n              jected  to  parameter expansion, command substitu‐\u001b[m\r\n              tion, and arithmetic expansion before being inter‐\u001b[m\r\n              preted  as a filename.  \u001b[1mPATH\u001b[0m is not used to search\u001b[m\r\n              for the resultant filename.\u001b[m\r\n       \u001b[1mBASH_XTRACEFD\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n              If set to an integer corresponding to a valid file\u001b[m\r\n              descriptor,  \u001b[1mbash\u001b[0m will write the trace output gen‐\u001b[m\r\n              erated when \u001b[4mset\u001b[24m \u001b[4m-x\u001b[24m is enabled  to  that  file  de‐\u001b[m\r\n              scriptor.   The  file  descriptor  is  closed when\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[7m Manual page bash(1) line 1353 (press h for help or q to quit)\u001b[27m\u001b[K"]
[3620.166251, "o", "\r\u001b[K"]
[3620.166403, "o", "              \u001b[1mBASH_XTRACEFD\u001b[0m is unset or assigned  a  new  value.\u001b[m\r\n              Unsetting  \u001b[1mBASH_XTRACEFD\u001b[0m or assigning it the empty\u001b[m\r\n              string causes the trace output to be sent  to  the\u001b[m\r\n              standard  error.   Note that setting \u001b[1mBASH_XTRACEFD\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n              to 2 (the standard error file descriptor) and then\u001b[m\r\n              unsetting it will result in the standard error be‐\u001b[m\r\n              ing closed.\u001b[m\r\n       \u001b[1mCDPATH\u001b[0m The search path for the \u001b[1mcd\u001b[0m  command.   This  is  a\u001b[m\r\n              colon-separated  list  of directories in which the\u001b[m\r\n              shell looks for destination directories  specified\u001b[m\r\n              by the \u001b[1mcd\u001b[0m command.  A sample value is \".:~:/usr\".\u001b[m\r\n       \u001b[1mCHILD_MAX\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n              Set  the  number of exited child status values for\u001b[m\r\n              the shell to remember.  Bash will not  allow  this\u001b[m\r\n              value to be decreased below a POSIX-mandated mini‐\u001b[m\r\n              mum"]
[3620.166432, "o", ", and there is a maximum value (currently 8192)\u001b[m\r\n              that  this  may  not exceed.  The minimum value is\u001b[m\r\n              system-dependent.\u001b[m\r\n       \u001b[1mCOLUMNS\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n              Used by the \u001b[1mselect\u001b[0m compound command  to  determine\u001b[m\r\n              the  terminal width when printing selection lists.\u001b[m\r\n              Automatically set if the  \u001b[1mcheckwinsize\u001b[0m  option  is\u001b[m\r\n              enabled or in an interactive shell upon receipt of\u001b[m\r\n              a \u001b[1mSIGWINCH\u001b[0m.\u001b[m\r\n       \u001b[1mCOMPREPLY\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n              An array variable from which \u001b[1mbash\u001b[0m reads the possi‐\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[7m Manual page bash(1) line 1379 (press h for help or q to quit)\u001b[27m\u001b[K"]
[3620.197577, "o", "\r\u001b[K"]
[3620.197664, "o", "              ble  completions generated by a shell function in‐\u001b[m\r\n              voked by the programmable completion facility (see\u001b[m\r\n              \u001b[1mProgrammable\u001b[0m  \u001b[1mCompletion\u001b[0m  below).  Each array ele‐\u001b[m\r\n              ment contains one possible completion.\u001b[m\r\n       \u001b[1mEMACS\u001b[0m  If \u001b[1mbash\u001b[0m finds this  variable  in  the  environment\u001b[m\r\n              when  the  shell starts with value \"t\", it assumes\u001b[m\r\n              that the shell is running in an Emacs shell buffer\u001b[m\r\n              and disables line editing.\u001b[m\r\n       \u001b[1mENV\u001b[0m    Expanded  and  executed similarly to \u001b[1mBASH_ENV\u001b[0m (see\u001b[m\r\n              \u001b[1mINVOCATION\u001b[0m above) when an interactive shell is in‐\u001b[m\r\n              voked in \u001b[4mposix\u001b[24m \u001b[4mmode\u001b[24m.\u001b[m\r\n       \u001b[1mEXECIGNORE\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n"]
[3620.197687, "o", "              A colon-separated list of shell patterns (see \u001b[1mPat‐\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n              \u001b[1mtern\u001b[0m \u001b[1mMatching\u001b[0m) defining the list of  filenames  to\u001b[m\r\n              be  ignored  by  command search using \u001b[1mPATH\u001b[0m.  Fil"]
[3620.197748, "o", "es\u001b[m\r\n              whose full pathnames match one of  these  patterns\u001b[m\r\n              are  not  considered executable files for the pur‐\u001b[m\r\n              poses of completion and command execution via \u001b[1mPATH\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n              lookup.   This does not affect the behavior of the\u001b[m\r\n              \u001b[1m[\u001b[0m, \u001b[1mtest\u001b[0m, and \u001b[1m[[\u001b[0m commands.  Full pathnames  in  the\u001b[m\r\n              command  hash table are not subject to \u001b[1mEXECIGNORE\u001b[0m.\u001b[m\r\n              Use this variable to ignore shared  library  files\u001b[m\r\n              that have the executable bit set, but are not exe‐\u001b[m\r\n              cutable files.  The pattern  matching  honors  the\u001b[m\r\n              setting of the \u001b[1mextglob\u001b[0m shell option.\u001b[m\r\n       \u001b[1mFCEDIT\u001b[0m The default editor for the \u001b[1mfc\u001b[0m builtin command.\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[7m Manual page bash(1) line 1405 (press h for help or q to quit)\u001b[27m\u001b[K"]
[3620.229507, "o", "\r\u001b[K"]
[3620.229588, "o", "       \u001b[1mFIGNORE\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n              A  colon-separated list of suffixes to ignore when\u001b[m\r\n              performing filename completion (see  \u001b[1mREADLINE\u001b[0m  be‐\u001b[m\r\n              low).   A filename whose suffix matches one of the\u001b[m\r\n              entries in \u001b[1mFIGNORE\u001b[0m is excluded from  the  list  of\u001b[m\r\n              matched  filenames.   A  sample  value  is  \".o:~\"\u001b[m\r\n              (Quoting is needed when assigning a value to  this\u001b[m\r\n              variable, which contains tildes).\u001b[m\r\n       \u001b[1mFUNCNEST\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n              If  set to a numeric value greater than 0, defines\u001b[m\r\n              a maximum function nesting level.  Function  invo‐\u001b[m\r\n              cations  that exceed this nesting level will cause\u001b[m\r\n              the current command to abort.\u001b[m\r\n       \u001b[1mGLOBIGNORE\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n              A colon-separated list of  patterns  defining  the\u001b[m\r\n              set of file names to be ignored by pathname expan‐\u001b[m\r\n              sion.  If a file name matched by a pathname "]
[3620.229606, "o", "expan‐\u001b[m\r\n              sion  pattern  also matches one of the patterns in\u001b[m\r\n              \u001b[1mGLOBIGNORE\u001b[0m,  it  is  removed  from  the  list   of\u001b[m\r\n              matches.\u001b[m\r\n       \u001b[1mHISTCONTROL\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n              A  colon-separated  list of values controlling how\u001b[m\r\n              commands are saved on the history  list.   If  the\u001b[m\r\n              list  of  values includes \u001b[4mignorespace\u001b[24m, lines which\u001b[m\r\n              begin with a \u001b[1mspace\u001b[0m character are not saved in  the\u001b[m\r\n              history  list.  A value of \u001b[4mignoredups\u001b[24m causes lines\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[7m Manual page bash(1) line 1431 (press h for help or q to quit)\u001b[27m\u001b[K"]
[3620.260808, "o", "\r\u001b[K"]
[3620.260915, "o", "              matching the previous  history  entry  to  not  be\u001b[m\r\n              saved.  A value of \u001b[4mignoreboth\u001b[24m is shorthand for \u001b[4mig‐\u001b[24m\u001b[m\r\n              \u001b[4mnorespace\u001b[24m and \u001b[4mignoredups\u001b[24m.  A  value  of  \u001b[4merasedups\u001b[24m\u001b[m\r\n              causes  all  previous  lines  matching the current\u001b[m\r\n              line to be removed from the  history  list  before\u001b[m\r\n              that  line  is  saved.  Any value not in the above\u001b[m\r\n              list is ignored.  If \u001b[1mHISTCONTROL\u001b[0m is unset, or does\u001b[m\r\n              not  include  a valid value, all lines read by the\u001b[m\r\n              shell parser are saved on the history  list,  sub‐\u001b[m\r\n              ject  to  the value of \u001b[1mHISTIGNORE\u001b[0m.  The second and\u001b[m\r\n              subsequent lines of a multi-line compound  command\u001b[m\r\n              are  not  tested, and are added to the history re‐\u001b[m\r\n              gardless of the value of \u001b[1mHISTCONTROL\u001b[0m.\u001b[m\r\n       \u001b[1mHISTFILE\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n              The name of the file in"]
[3620.260971, "o", " which command  history  is\u001b[m\r\n              saved  (see  \u001b[1mHISTORY\u001b[0m below).  The default value is\u001b[m\r\n              \u001b[4m~/.bash_history\u001b[24m.  If unset, the command history is\u001b[m\r\n              not saved when a shell exits.\u001b[m\r\n       \u001b[1mHISTFILESIZE\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n              The  maximum number of lines contained in the his‐\u001b[m\r\n              tory file.   When  this  variable  is  assigned  a\u001b[m\r\n              value,  the  history  file is truncated, if neces‐\u001b[m\r\n              sary, to contain no more than that number of lines\u001b[m\r\n              by  removing the oldest entries.  The history file\u001b[m\r\n              is also truncated to this size  after  writing  it\u001b[m\r\n              when  a  shell exits.  If the value is 0, the his‐\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[7m Manual page bash(1) line 1457 (press h for help or q to quit)\u001b[27m\u001b[K"]
[3620.291976, "o", "\r\u001b[K"]
[3620.292109, "o", "              tory file is truncated to zero size.   Non-numeric\u001b[m\r\n              values  and  numeric values less than zero inhibit\u001b[m\r\n              truncation.  The shell sets the default  value  to\u001b[m\r\n              the  value  of  \u001b[1mHISTSIZE\u001b[0m after reading any startup\u001b[m\r\n              files.\u001b[m\r\n       \u001b[1mHISTIGNORE\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n              A colon-separated list of patterns used to  decide\u001b[m\r\n              which command lines should be saved on the history\u001b[m\r\n              list.  Each pattern is anchored at  the  beginning\u001b[m\r\n              of  the  line and must match the complete line (no\u001b[m\r\n              implicit `\u001b[1m*\u001b[0m' is appended).  Each pattern is tested\u001b[m\r\n              against  the  line  after  the checks specified by\u001b[m\r\n              \u001b[1mHISTCONTROL\u001b[0m are applied.  In addition to the  nor‐\u001b[m\r\n              mal shell pattern matching characters, `\u001b[1m&\u001b[0m' matches\u001b[m\r\n              the previous history line.  `\u001b[1m&\u001b[0m' may be escaped us‐\u001b[m\r\n              ing  a  backsl"]
[3620.292129, "o", "ash; the backslash is removed before\u001b[m\r\n              attempting a match.   The  second  and  subsequent\u001b[m\r\n              lines  of  a  multi-line  compound command are not\u001b[m\r\n              tested, and are added to the history regardless of\u001b[m\r\n              the  value  of  \u001b[1mHISTIGNORE\u001b[0m.   The pattern matching\u001b[m\r\n              honors the setting of the \u001b[1mextglob\u001b[0m shell option.\u001b[m\r\n       \u001b[1mHISTSIZE\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n              The number of commands to remember in the  command\u001b[m\r\n              history  (see  \u001b[1mHISTORY\u001b[0m below).  If the value is 0,\u001b[m\r\n              commands are not saved in the history  list.   Nu‐\u001b[m\r\n              meric  values  less than zero result in every com‐\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[7m Manual page bash(1) line 1483 (press h for help or q to quit)\u001b[27m\u001b[K"]
[3620.323177, "o", "\r\u001b[K"]
[3620.323203, "o", "              mand being saved on the history list (there is  no\u001b[m\r\n              limit).   The  shell sets the default value to 500\u001b[m\r\n              after reading any startup files.\u001b[m\r\n       \u001b[1mHISTTIMEFORMAT\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n              If this variable is set and not null, its value is\u001b[m\r\n              used  as  a format string for \u001b[4mstrftime\u001b[24m(3) to print\u001b[m\r\n              the time stamp associated with each history  entry\u001b[m\r\n              displayed  by  the \u001b[1mhistory\u001b[0m builtin.  If this vari‐\u001b[m\r\n"]
[3620.323208, "o", "              able is set, time stamps are written to  the  his‐\u001b[m\r\n              tory  file  so  they may be preserved across shell\u001b[m\r\n              sessions.  This uses the history comment character\u001b[m\r\n              to   distinguish  timestamps  from  other  history\u001b[m\r\n              lines.\u001b[m\r\n       \u001b[1mHOME\u001b[0m   The home directory of the current  user;  the  de‐\u001b[m\r\n              fault  argument  for  the \u001b[1mcd\u001b[0m builtin command.  The\u001b[m\r\n              value of this variable is also used when  perfo"]
[3620.32342, "o", "rm‐\u001b[m\r\n              ing tilde expansion.\u001b[m\r\n       \u001b[1mHOSTFILE\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n              Contains  the name of a file in the same format as\u001b[m\r\n              \u001b[4m/etc/hosts\u001b[24m that should  be  read  when  the  shell\u001b[m\r\n              needs  to complete a hostname.  The list of possi‐\u001b[m\r\n              ble hostname completions may be changed while  the\u001b[m\r\n              shell  is  running; the next time hostname comple‐\u001b[m\r\n              tion is attempted after the value is changed, \u001b[1mbash\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n              adds  the contents of the new file to the existing\u001b[m\r\n              list.  If \u001b[1mHOSTFILE\u001b[0m is set, but has  no  value,  or\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[7m Manual page bash(1) line 1509 (press h for help or q to quit)\u001b[27m\u001b[K"]
[3620.354322, "o", "\r\u001b[K              does  not  name  a readable file, \u001b[1mbash\u001b[0m attempts to\u001b[m\r\n              read \u001b[4m/etc/hosts\u001b[24m to obtain  the  list  of  possible\u001b[m\r\n              hostname completions.  When \u001b[1mHOSTFILE\u001b[0m is unset, the\u001b[m\r\n              hostname list is cleared.\u001b[m\r\n       \u001b[1mIFS\u001b[0m    The \u001b[4mInternal\u001b[24m \u001b[4mField\u001b[24m \u001b[4mSeparator\u001b[24m that is used for word\u001b[m\r\n              splitting  after expansion and to split lines into\u001b[m\r\n              words with the \u001b[1mread\u001b[0m builtin command.  The  default\u001b[m\r\n              value is ``<space><tab><newline>''.\u001b[m\r\n       \u001b[1mIGNOREEOF\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n              Controls the action of an interactive shell on re‐\u001b[m\r\n              ceipt of an \u001b[1mEOF\u001b[0m character as the sole  input.   If\u001b[m\r\n"]
[3620.35445, "o", "              set,  the  value  is the number of consecutive \u001b[1mEOF\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n              characters which must be typed as the first  char‐\u001b[m\r\n              acters on an input line before \u001b[1mbash\u001b[0m exits.  If the\u001b[m\r\n              variable exists but does not have a numer"]
[3620.354483, "o", "ic value,\u001b[m\r\n              or  has  no value, the default value is 10.  If it\u001b[m\r\n              does not exist, \u001b[1mEOF\u001b[0m signifies the end of input  to\u001b[m\r\n              the shell.\u001b[m\r\n       \u001b[1mINPUTRC\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n              The  filename for the \u001b[1mreadline\u001b[0m startup file, over‐\u001b[m\r\n              riding the default of \u001b[4m~/.inputrc\u001b[24m (see \u001b[1mREADLINE\u001b[0m be‐\u001b[m\r\n              low).\u001b[m\r\n       \u001b[1mINSIDE_EMACS\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n              If  this  variable appears in the environment when\u001b[m\r\n              the shell starts, \u001b[1mbash\u001b[0m assumes that it is  running\u001b[m\r\n              inside  an Emacs shell buffer and may disable line\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[7m Manual page bash(1) line 1535 (press h for help or q to quit)\u001b[27m\u001b[K"]
[3620.386231, "o", "\r\u001b[K"]
[3620.386257, "o", "              editing, depending on the value of \u001b[1mTERM\u001b[0m.\u001b[m\r\n       \u001b[1mLANG\u001b[0m   Used to determine the locale category for any cat‐\u001b[m\r\n              egory  not  specifically  selected with a variable\u001b[m\r\n              starting with \u001b[1mLC_\u001b[0m.\u001b[m\r\n       \u001b[1mLC_ALL\u001b[0m This variable overrides the value of \u001b[1mLANG\u001b[0m and  any\u001b[m\r\n              other \u001b[1mLC_\u001b[0m variable specifying a locale category.\u001b[m\r\n       \u001b[1mLC_COLLATE\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n              This  variable determines the collation order used\u001b[m\r\n              when sorting the results  of  pathname  expansion,\u001b[m\r\n              and  determines the behavior of range expressions,\u001b[m\r\n              equivalence  classes,  and   collating   sequences\u001b[m\r\n              within pathname expansion and pattern matching.\u001b[m\r\n       \u001b[1mLC_CTYPE\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n"]
[3620.386371, "o", "              This  variable  determines  the  interpretation of\u001b[m\r\n              characters and the behavior of  character  classes\u001b[m\r\n              within pathname expansion and pattern matching.\u001b[m\r\n       \u001b[1mLC_MESSAGES\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n              This variable determines the locale used to trans‐\u001b[m\r\n              late double-quoted strings preceded by a \u001b[1m$\u001b[0m.\u001b[m\r\n       \u001b[1mLC_NUMERIC\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n              This variable determines the locale category  used\u001b[m\r\n              for number formatting.\u001b[m\r\n       \u001b[1mLC_TIME\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n              This  variable determines the locale category used\u001b[m\r\n              for data and time formatting.\u001b[m\r\n       \u001b[1mLINES\u001b[0m  Used by the \u001b[1mselect\u001b[0m compound command  to  determine\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[7m Manual page bash(1) line 1561 (press h for help or q to quit)\u001b[27m\u001b[K"]
[3620.417447, "o", "\r\u001b[K              the  column  length  for printing selection lists.\u001b[m\r\n              Automatically set if the  \u001b[1mcheckwinsize\u001b[0m  option  is\u001b[m\r\n              enabled or in an interactive shell upon receipt of\u001b[m\r\n              a \u001b[1mSIGWINCH\u001b[0m.\u001b[m\r\n       \u001b[1mMAIL\u001b[0m   If this parameter is set to a  file  or  directory\u001b[m\r\n              name  and  the  \u001b[1mMAILPATH\u001b[0m variable is not set, \u001b[1mbash\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n              informs the user of the arrival  of  mail  in  the\u001b[m\r\n              specified file or Maildir-format directory.\u001b[m\r\n       \u001b[1mMAILCHECK\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n              Specifies  how  often (in seconds) \u001b[1mbash\u001b[0m checks for\u001b[m\r\n              mail.  The default is 60 seconds.  When it is time\u001b[m\r\n"]
[3620.417472, "o", "              to  check  for mail, the shell does so before dis‐\u001b[m\r\n              playing the primary prompt.  If this  variable  is\u001b[m\r\n              unset,  or  set  to  a  value that is not a number\u001b[m\r\n              greater than or equal to zero, the shell  disables\u001b[m\r\n              mail checking.\u001b[m\r\n       "]
[3620.41756, "o", "\u001b[1mMAILPATH\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n              A  colon-separated list of filenames to be checked\u001b[m\r\n              for mail.  The message to be printed when mail ar‐\u001b[m\r\n              rives  in  a  particular  file may be specified by\u001b[m\r\n              separating the filename from the  message  with  a\u001b[m\r\n              `?'.  When used in the text of the message, \u001b[1m$_\u001b[0m ex‐\u001b[m\r\n              pands to the name of the current mailfile.   Exam‐\u001b[m\r\n              ple:\u001b[m\r\n              \u001b[1mMAILPATH\u001b[0m='/var/mail/bfox?\"You                 have\u001b[m\r\n              mail\":~/shell-mail?\"$_ has mail!\"'\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[7m Manual page bash(1) line 1587 (press h for help or q to quit)\u001b[27m\u001b[K"]
[3620.449488, "o", "\r\u001b[K"]
[3620.449585, "o", "              \u001b[1mBash\u001b[0m can be configured to supply a  default  value\u001b[m\r\n              for  this variable (there is no value by default),\u001b[m\r\n              but the location of the user mail  files  that  it\u001b[m\r\n              uses is system dependent (e.g., /var/mail/\u001b[1m$USER\u001b[0m).\u001b[m\r\n       \u001b[1mOPTERR\u001b[0m If  set  to  the value 1, \u001b[1mbash\u001b[0m displays error mes‐\u001b[m\r\n              sages generated by  the  \u001b[1mgetopts\u001b[0m  builtin  command\u001b[m\r\n              (see  \u001b[1mSHELL\u001b[0m  \u001b[1mBUILTIN\u001b[0m  \u001b[1mCOMMANDS\u001b[0m  below).  \u001b[1mOPTERR\u001b[0m is\u001b[m\r\n              initialized to 1 each time the shell is invoked or\u001b[m\r\n              a shell script is executed.\u001b[m\r\n       \u001b[1mPATH\u001b[0m   The search path for commands.  It is a colon-sepa‐\u001b[m\r\n              rated list of directories in which the shell looks\u001b[m\r\n              for  commands  (see  \u001b[1mCOMMAND\u001b[0m  \u001b[1mEXECUTION\u001b[0m below).  A\u001b[m\r\n              zero-length (null) directory name in the value  of\u001b[m\r\n              \u001b[1mPATH\u001b[0m  indicates the current d"]
[3620.449591, "o", "irectory.  A"]
[3620.449625, "o", " null di‐\u001b[m\r\n              rectory name may appear as two adjacent colons, or\u001b[m\r\n              as an initial or trailing colon.  The default path\u001b[m\r\n              is system-dependent, and is set by the administra‐\u001b[m\r\n              tor who installs \u001b[1mbash\u001b[0m.  A common value is\u001b[m\r\n              ``/usr/local/bin:/usr/local/sbin:/usr/bin:\u001b[m\r\n              /usr/sbin:/bin:/sbin''.\u001b[m\r\n       \u001b[1mPOSIXLY_CORRECT\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n              If  this  variable is in the environment when \u001b[1mbash\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n              starts, the shell enters \u001b[4mposix\u001b[24m \u001b[4mmode\u001b[24m before reading\u001b[m\r\n"]
[3620.449643, "o", "              the  startup  files,  as if the \u001b[1m--posix\u001b[0m invocation\u001b[m\r\n              option had been supplied.  If it is set while  the\u001b[m\r\n              shell  is  running, \u001b[1mbash\u001b[0m enables \u001b[4mposix\u001b[24m \u001b[4mmode\u001b[24m, as if\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[7m Manual page bash(1) line 1613 (press h for help or q to quit)\u001b[27m\u001b[K"]
[3620.481016, "o", "\r\u001b[K"]
[3620.481048, "o", "              the command \u001b[4mset\u001b[24m \u001b[4m-o\u001b[24m \u001b[4mposix\u001b[24m had been executed.   When\u001b[m\r\n              the shell enters \u001b[4mposix\u001b[24m \u001b[4mmode\u001b[24m, it sets this variable\u001b[m\r\n              if it was not already set.\u001b[m\r\n       \u001b[1mPROMPT_COMMAND\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n              If this variable is set,  and  is  an  array,  the\u001b[m\r\n              value of each set element is executed as a command\u001b[m\r\n              prior to issuing each primary prompt.  If this  is\u001b[m\r\n              set  but  not an array variable, its value is used\u001b[m\r\n              as a command to execute instead.\u001b[m\r\n       \u001b[1mPROMPT_DIRTRIM\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n              If set to a number greater than zero, the value is\u001b[m\r\n              used  as  the  number of trailing directory compo‐\u001b[m\r\n              nents to retain  when  expanding  the  \u001b[1m\\w\u001b[0m  and  \u001b[1m\\W\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n              prompt   string  escapes  (see  \u001b[1mPROMPTING\u001b[0m  below).\u001b[m\r\n              Characters removed are replaced with an ellipsis.\u001b[m\r\n       \u001b[1mPS0\u001b[0m    The value"]
[3620.481052, "o", "  of  this  pa"]
[3620.481172, "o", "rameter  is  expanded  (see\u001b[m\r\n              \u001b[1mPROMPTING\u001b[0m  below)  and  displayed  by  interactive\u001b[m\r\n              shells after reading a command and before the com‐\u001b[m\r\n              mand is executed.\u001b[m\r\n       \u001b[1mPS1\u001b[0m    The  value  of  this  parameter  is  expanded (see\u001b[m\r\n              \u001b[1mPROMPTING\u001b[0m below) and used as  the  primary  prompt\u001b[m\r\n              string.  The default value is ``\u001b[1m\\s-\\v\\$\u001b[0m ''.\u001b[m\r\n       \u001b[1mPS2\u001b[0m    The  value  of  this parameter is expanded as with\u001b[m\r\n              \u001b[1mPS1\u001b[0m and used as the secondary prompt string.   The\u001b[m\r\n              default is ``\u001b[1m>\u001b[0m ''.\u001b[m\r\n       \u001b[1mPS3\u001b[0m    The  value of this parameter is used as the prompt\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[7m Manual page bash(1) line 1639 (press h for help or q to quit)\u001b[27m\u001b[K"]
[3620.512252, "o", "\r\u001b[K              for the \u001b[1mselect\u001b[0m command (see \u001b[1mSHELL\u001b[0m \u001b[1mGRAMMAR\u001b[0m above).\u001b[m\r\n       \u001b[1mPS4\u001b[0m    The value of this parameter is  expanded  as  with\u001b[m\r\n              \u001b[1mPS1\u001b[0m  and  the value is printed before each command\u001b[m\r\n              \u001b[1mbash\u001b[0m displays  during  an  execution  trace.   The\u001b[m\r\n              first  character  of  the expanded value of \u001b[1mPS4\u001b[0m is\u001b[m\r\n              replicated multiple times, as necessary, to  indi‐\u001b[m\r\n              cate  multiple levels of indirection.  The default\u001b[m\r\n              is ``\u001b[1m+\u001b[0m ''.\u001b[m\r\n       \u001b[1mSHELL\u001b[0m  This variable expands to the full pathname to  the\u001b[m\r\n              shell.   If  it  is not set when the shell starts,\u001b[m\r\n              \u001b[1mbash\u001b[0m assigns to it the full pathname of  the  cur‐\u001b[m\r\n              rent user's login shell.\u001b[m\r\n       \u001b[1mTIMEFORMAT\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n              The  value  of  this parameter is used as a format\u001b[m\r\n              string specifying how the timing  information  for\u001b[m\r\n       "]
[3620.512281, "o", "       pipelines  "]
[3620.512374, "o", "prefixed  with  the  \u001b[1mtime\u001b[0m reserved word\u001b[m\r\n              should be displayed.  The \u001b[1m%\u001b[0m  character  introduces\u001b[m\r\n              an  escape  sequence  that  is  expanded to a time\u001b[m\r\n              value or other information.  The escape  sequences\u001b[m\r\n              and  their meanings are as follows; the braces de‐\u001b[m\r\n              note optional portions.\u001b[m\r\n              \u001b[1m%%\u001b[0m        A literal \u001b[1m%\u001b[0m.\u001b[m\r\n              \u001b[1m%[\u001b[0m\u001b[4mp\u001b[24m\u001b[1m][l]R\u001b[0m  The elapsed time in seconds.\u001b[m\r\n              \u001b[1m%[\u001b[0m\u001b[4mp\u001b[24m\u001b[1m][l]U\u001b[0m  The number of CPU seconds spent in  user\u001b[m\r\n                        mode.\u001b[m\r\n              \u001b[1m%[\u001b[0m\u001b[4mp\u001b[24m\u001b[1m][l]S\u001b[0m  The  number of CPU seconds spent in sys‐\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[7m Manual page bash(1) line 1665 (press h for help or q to quit)\u001b[27m\u001b[K"]
[3620.543286, "o", "\r\u001b[K"]
[3620.543318, "o", "                        tem mode.\u001b[m\r\n              \u001b[1m%P\u001b[0m        The CPU percentage, computed  as  (%U  +\u001b[m\r\n                        %S) / %R.\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n              The  optional  \u001b[4mp\u001b[24m  is a digit specifying the \u001b[4mpreci‐\u001b[24m\u001b[m\r\n              \u001b[4msion\u001b[24m, the number of fractional digits after a dec‐\u001b[m\r\n              imal  point.  A value of 0 causes no decimal point\u001b[m\r\n              or fraction to be output.  At  most  three  places\u001b[m\r\n              after  the  decimal point may be specified; values\u001b[m\r\n              of \u001b[4mp\u001b[24m greater than 3 are changed to 3.  If \u001b[4mp\u001b[24m is not\u001b[m\r\n              specified, the value 3 is used.\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n              The  optional \u001b[1ml\u001b[0m specifies a longer format, includ‐\u001b[m\r\n"]
[3620.54354, "o", "              ing minutes, of the form \u001b[4mMM\u001b[24mm\u001b[4mSS\u001b[24m.\u001b[4mFF\u001b[24ms.  The value  of\u001b[m\r\n              \u001b[4mp\u001b[24m  determines  whether  or not the fraction is in‐\u001b[m\r\n              cluded.\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n              If this variable is not set, \u001b[1mbash\u001b[0m acts  as  if  it\u001b[m\r\n              had                    the                   value\u001b[m\r\n              \u001b[1m$'\\nreal\\t%3lR\\nuser\\t%3lU\\nsys\\t%3lS'\u001b[0m.   If   the\u001b[m\r\n              value is null, no timing information is displayed.\u001b[m\r\n              A trailing newline is added when the format string\u001b[m\r\n              is displayed.\u001b[m\r\n       \u001b[1mTMOUT\u001b[0m  If  set  to  a  value  greater than zero, \u001b[1mTMOUT\u001b[0m is\u001b[m\r\n              treated  as  the  default  timeout  for  the  \u001b[1mread\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n              builtin.   The  \u001b[1mselect\u001b[0m command terminates if input\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[7m Manual page bash(1) line 1691 (press h for help or q to quit)\u001b[27m\u001b[K"]
[3620.574521, "o", "\r\u001b[K"]
[3620.574615, "o", "              does not arrive after \u001b[1mTMOUT\u001b[0m seconds when input  is\u001b[m\r\n              coming  from a terminal.  In an interactive shell,\u001b[m\r\n              the value is interpreted as the number of  seconds\u001b[m\r\n              to wait for a line of input after issuing the pri‐\u001b[m\r\n              mary prompt.  \u001b[1mBash\u001b[0m terminates  after  waiting  for\u001b[m\r\n              that number of seconds if a complete line of input\u001b[m\r\n              does not arrive.\u001b[m\r\n       \u001b[1mTMPDIR\u001b[0m If set, \u001b[1mbash\u001b[0m uses its value as the name of  a  di‐\u001b[m\r\n              rectory  in which \u001b[1mbash\u001b[0m creates temporary files for\u001b[m\r\n              the shell's use.\u001b[m\r\n       \u001b[1mauto_resume\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n              This variable controls  how  the  shell  interacts\u001b[m\r\n              with  the  user and job control.  If this variable\u001b[m\r\n              is set, single word simple commands without  redi‐\u001b[m\r\n              rections  are treated as candidates for resumption\u001b[m\r\n              of an existing stopped job.  There "]
[3620.574718, "o", "is no ambiguity\u001b[m\r\n              allowed;  if  there is more than one job beginning\u001b[m\r\n              with the string typed, the job most  recently  ac‐\u001b[m\r\n              cessed is selected.  The \u001b[4mname\u001b[24m of a stopped job, in\u001b[m\r\n              this context, is the command line  used  to  start\u001b[m\r\n              it.   If  set  to the value \u001b[4mexact\u001b[24m, the string sup‐\u001b[m\r\n              plied must match the name of  a  stopped  job  ex‐\u001b[m\r\n              actly;  if  set  to \u001b[4msubstring\u001b[24m, the string supplied\u001b[m\r\n              needs to match  a  substring  of  the  name  of  a\u001b[m\r\n              stopped  job.   The \u001b[4msubstring\u001b[24m value provides func‐\u001b[m\r\n              tionality analogous to the \u001b[1m%?\u001b[0m  job identifier (see\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[7m Manual page bash(1) line 1717 (press h for help or q to quit)\u001b[27m\u001b[K"]
[3620.606483, "o", "\r\u001b[K"]
[3620.606578, "o", "              \u001b[1mJOB\u001b[0m  \u001b[1mCONTROL\u001b[0m  below).   If set to any other value,\u001b[m\r\n              the supplied string must be a prefix of a  stopped\u001b[m\r\n              job's  name; this provides functionality analogous\u001b[m\r\n              to the \u001b[1m%\u001b[0m\u001b[4mstring\u001b[24m job identifier.\u001b[m\r\n       \u001b[1mhistchars\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n              The two or three characters which control  history\u001b[m\r\n              expansion  and tokenization (see \u001b[1mHISTORY\u001b[0m \u001b[1mEXPANSION\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n              below).  The first character is the \u001b[4mhistory\u001b[24m \u001b[4mexpan‐\u001b[24m\u001b[m\r\n              \u001b[4msion\u001b[24m  character,  the  character which signals the\u001b[m\r\n              start of a history expansion, normally  `\u001b[1m!\u001b[0m'.   The\u001b[m\r\n              second character is the \u001b[4mquick\u001b[24m \u001b[4msubstitution\u001b[24m charac‐\u001b[m\r\n              ter, which is used as shorthand for re-running the\u001b[m\r\n              previous  command entered, substituting one string\u001b[m\r\n              for another in the command.  The default  is  `\u001b[1m^\u001b[0m'.\u001b[m\r\n    "]
[3620.606591, "o", "          The  optional  third  character  is  the character\u001b[m\r\n              which indicates that the remainder of the line  is\u001b[m\r\n              a  comment  when found as the first character of a\u001b[m\r\n              word, normally `\u001b[1m#\u001b[0m'.  The history comment character\u001b[m\r\n              causes  history substitution to be skipped for the\u001b[m\r\n              remaining words on the line.  It does  not  neces‐\u001b[m\r\n              sarily cause the shell parser to treat the rest of\u001b[m\r\n              the line as a comment.\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n   \u001b[1mArrays\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n       \u001b[1mBash\u001b[0m provides one-dimensional indexed and associative ar‐\u001b[m\r\n       ray  variables.   Any  variable may be used as an indexed\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[7m Manual page bash(1) line 1743 (press h for help or q to quit)\u001b[27m\u001b[K"]
[3620.637187, "o", "\r\u001b[K"]
[3620.637371, "o", "       array; the \u001b[1mdeclare\u001b[0m builtin will explicitly declare an ar‐\u001b[m\r\n       ray.   There is no maximum limit on the size of an array,\u001b[m\r\n       nor any requirement that members be indexed  or  assigned\u001b[m\r\n       contiguously.   Indexed arrays are referenced using inte‐\u001b[m\r\n       gers (including arithmetic  expressions)  and  are  zero-\u001b[m\r\n       based;  associative arrays are referenced using arbitrary\u001b[m\r\n       strings.  Unless otherwise noted, indexed  array  indices\u001b[m\r\n       must be non-negative integers.\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n       An indexed array is created automatically if any variable\u001b[m\r\n       is assigned to using  the  syntax  \u001b[4mname\u001b[24m[\u001b[4msubscript\u001b[24m]=\u001b[4mvalue\u001b[24m.\u001b[m\r\n       The \u001b[4msubscript\u001b[24m is treated as an arithmetic expression that\u001b[m\r\n       must evaluate to a number.  To explicitly declare an  in‐\u001b[m\r\n       dexed  array, use \u001b[1mdeclare\u001b[0m \u001b[1m-a\u001b[0m \u001b[4mname\u001b[24m (see \u001b[1mSHELL\u001b[0m \u001b[1mBUILTIN\u001b[0m \u001b[1mCOM‐\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n       \u001b[1mMANDS\u001b[0m below).  \u001b[1mdeclare\u001b[0m \u001b["]
[3620.637412, "o", "1m-a\u001b[0m  \u001b[4mname\u001b[24m\u001b[1m[\u001b[0m\u001b[4msubscript\u001b[24m\u001b[1m]\u001b[0m  is  also  ac‐\u001b[m\r\n       cepted; the \u001b[4msubscript\u001b[24m is ignored.\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n       Associative arrays are created using \u001b[1mdeclare\u001b[0m \u001b[1m-A\u001b[0m \u001b[4mname\u001b[24m.\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n       Attributes  may  be specified for an array variable using\u001b[m\r\n       the \u001b[1mdeclare\u001b[0m and \u001b[1mreadonly\u001b[0m builtins.   Each  attribute  ap‐\u001b[m\r\n       plies to all members of an array.\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n       Arrays  are assigned to using compound assignments of the\u001b[m\r\n       form \u001b[4mname\u001b[24m=\u001b[1m(\u001b[0mvalue\u001b[4m1\u001b[24m ... value\u001b[4mn\u001b[24m\u001b[1m)\u001b[0m, where each \u001b[4mvalue\u001b[24m may be of\u001b[m\r\n       the  form  [\u001b[4msubscript\u001b[24m]=\u001b[4mstring\u001b[24m.  Indexed array assignments\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[7m Manual page bash(1) line 1769 (press h for help or q to quit)\u001b[27m\u001b[K"]
[3620.668594, "o", "\r\u001b[K"]
[3620.668701, "o", "       do not require anything but \u001b[4mstring\u001b[24m.  Each  \u001b[4mvalue\u001b[24m  in  the\u001b[m\r\n       list is expanded using all the shell expansions described\u001b[m\r\n       below under \u001b[1mEXPANSION\u001b[0m.  When assigning to indexed arrays,\u001b[m\r\n       if the optional brackets and subscript are supplied, that\u001b[m\r\n       index is assigned to; otherwise the index of the  element\u001b[m\r\n       assigned  is  the last index assigned to by the statement\u001b[m\r\n       plus one.  Indexing starts at zero.\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n       When assigning to an associative array, the  words  in  a\u001b[m\r\n       compound  assignment may be either assignment statements,\u001b[m\r\n       for which the subscript is required, or a list  of  words\u001b[m\r\n       that is interpreted as a sequence of alternating keys and\u001b[m\r\n       values: \u001b[4mname\u001b[24m=\u001b[1m(\u001b[0m \u001b[4mkey1\u001b[24m \u001b[4mvalue1\u001b[24m \u001b[4mkey2\u001b[24m \u001b[4mvalue2\u001b[24m ...\u001b[1m)\u001b[0m.   These  are\u001b[m\r\n       treated identically to \u001b[4mname\u001b[24m=\u001b[1m(\u001b[0m [\u001b[4mkey1\u001b[24m]=\u001b[4mvalue1\u001b[24m [\u001b[4mkey2\u001b[24m]=\u001b[4mvalue2\u001b[24m\u001b[m\r\n    "]
[3620.668729, "o", "   ...\u001b[1m)\u001b["]
[3620.66875, "o", "0m.  The first word in the list determines how the  re‐\u001b[m\r\n       maining  words are interpreted; all assignments in a list\u001b[m\r\n       must be of the same type.  When  using  key/value  pairs,\u001b[m\r\n       the  keys  may  not  be missing or empty; a final missing\u001b[m\r\n       value is treated like the empty string.\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n       This syntax is also accepted by the \u001b[1mdeclare\u001b[0m builtin.  In‐\u001b[m\r\n       dividual  array  elements  may  be  assigned to using the\u001b[m\r\n       \u001b[4mname\u001b[24m[\u001b[4msubscript\u001b[24m]=\u001b[4mvalue\u001b[24m syntax introduced above.  When  as‐\u001b[m\r\n       signing  to an indexed array, if \u001b[4mname\u001b[24m is subscripted by a\u001b[m\r\n       negative number, that number is interpreted  as  relative\u001b[m\r\n       to  one  greater than the maximum index of \u001b[4mname\u001b[24m, so nega‐\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[7m Manual page bash(1) line 1795 (press h for help or q to quit)\u001b[27m\u001b[K"]
[3620.699692, "o", "\r\u001b[K"]
[3620.699741, "o", "       tive indices count back from the end of the array, and an\u001b[m\r\n       index of -1 references the last element.\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n       The += operator will append to an array variable when as‐\u001b[m\r\n       signing using the compound assignment syntax; see \u001b[1mPARAME‐\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n       \u001b[1mTERS\u001b[0m above.\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n       Any   element   of  an  array  may  be  referenced  using\u001b[m\r\n       ${\u001b[4mname\u001b[24m[\u001b[4msubscript\u001b[24m]}.  The braces  are  required  to  avoid\u001b[m\r\n       conflicts  with pathname expansion.  If \u001b[4msubscript\u001b[24m is \u001b[1m@\u001b[0m or\u001b[m\r\n       \u001b[1m*\u001b[0m, the word expands to all members of \u001b[4mname\u001b[24m.   These  sub‐\u001b[m\r\n"]
[3620.699862, "o", "       scripts  differ  only when the word appears within double\u001b[m\r\n       quotes.  If the word is double-quoted, ${\u001b[4mname\u001b[24m[*]} expands\u001b[m\r\n       to a single word with the value of each array member sep‐\u001b[m\r\n       arated by the first character of the  \u001b[1mIFS\u001b[0m  special  vari‐\u001b[m\r\n       able,  and  ${\u001b[4mname\u001b[24m[@]}  expands each element of \u001b[4mname\u001b[24m to a\u001b[m\r\n       separate  word.   When  there  are  no   array   members,\u001b[m\r\n       ${\u001b[4mname\u001b[24m[@]}  expands to nothing.  If the double-quoted ex‐\u001b[m\r\n       pansion occurs within a word, the expansion of the  first\u001b[m\r\n       parameter is joined with the beginning part of the origi‐\u001b[m\r\n       nal word, and the expansion  of  the  last  parameter  is\u001b[m\r\n       joined  with the last part of the original word.  This is\u001b[m\r\n       analogous to the expansion of the  special  parameters  \u001b[1m*\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n       and  \u001b[1m@\u001b[0m  (see  \u001b[1mSpecial\u001b[0m  \u001b[1mParameters\u001b[0m  above).   ${#\u001b[4mname\u001b[24m[\u001b[4msub‐\u001b[24m\u001b[m\r\n       \u001b[4mscript\u001b[24m]"]
[3620.699867, "o", "} expands to the length of ${\u001b[4mname\u001b[24m[\u001b[4msubscript\u001b[24m]}.  If\u001b[m\r\n       \u001b[4msubscript\u001b[24m  is \u001b[1m*\u001b[0m or \u001b[1m@\u001b[0m, the expansion is the number of ele‐\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[7m Manual page bash(1) line 1821 (press h for help or q to quit)\u001b[27m\u001b[K"]
[3620.731719, "o", "\r\u001b[K"]
[3620.731769, "o", "       ments in the array.  If the \u001b[4msubscript\u001b[24m used  to  reference\u001b[m\r\n       an element of an indexed array evaluates to a number less\u001b[m\r\n       than zero, it is interpreted as relative to  one  greater\u001b[m\r\n       than  the maximum index of the array, so negative indices\u001b[m\r\n       count back from the end of the array, and an index of  -1\u001b[m\r\n       references the last element.\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n       Referencing  an  array  variable  without  a subscript is\u001b[m\r\n       equivalent to referencing the array with a  subscript  of\u001b[m\r\n       0.   Any  reference to a variable using a valid subscript\u001b[m\r\n       is legal, and \u001b[1mbash\u001b[0m will create an array if necessary.\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n       An array variable is considered set if  a  subscript  has\u001b[m"]
[3620.731776, "o", "\r\n       been assigned a value.  The null string is a valid value.\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n       It  is  possible to obtain the keys (indices) of an array\u001b[m\r\n       as well as the values.  ${\u001b[1m!\u001b[0m\u001b[4mname\u001b[24m[\u001b[4m@\u001b[24m]} and  ${\u001b[1m!\u001b[0m\u001b[4mname\u001b[24m[\u001b[4m*\u001b[24m]}  ex‐\u001b[m\r\n       pand to the in"]
[3620.731921, "o", "dices assigned in array variable \u001b[4mname\u001b[24m.  The\u001b[m\r\n       treatment when in double quotes is similar to the  expan‐\u001b[m\r\n       sion  of  the  special  parameters  \u001b[4m@\u001b[24m and \u001b[4m*\u001b[24m within double\u001b[m\r\n       quotes.\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n       The \u001b[1munset\u001b[0m builtin  is  used  to  destroy  arrays.   \u001b[1munset\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n       \u001b[4mname\u001b[24m[\u001b[4msubscript\u001b[24m]  destroys the array element at index \u001b[4msub‐\u001b[24m\u001b[m\r\n       \u001b[4mscript\u001b[24m, for both indexed and associative  arrays.   Nega‐\u001b[m\r\n       tive  subscripts to indexed arrays are interpreted as de‐\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[7m Manual page bash(1) line 1847 (press h for help or q to quit)\u001b[27m\u001b[K"]
[3620.763233, "o", "\r\u001b[K"]
[3620.763321, "o", "       scribed above.  Unsetting the last element  of  an  array\u001b[m\r\n       variable  does not unset the variable.  \u001b[1munset\u001b[0m \u001b[4mname\u001b[24m, where\u001b[m\r\n       \u001b[4mname\u001b[24m is  an  array,  removes  the  entire  array.   \u001b[1munset\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n       \u001b[4mname\u001b[24m[\u001b[4msubscript\u001b[24m],  where \u001b[4msubscript\u001b[24m is \u001b[1m*\u001b[0m or \u001b[1m@\u001b[0m, behaves dif‐\u001b[m\r\n       ferently depending on whether \u001b[4mname\u001b[24m is an indexed or asso‐\u001b[m\r\n       ciative array.  If \u001b[4mname\u001b[24m is an associative array, this un‐\u001b[m\r\n       sets the element with subscript \u001b[1m*\u001b[0m or \u001b[1m@\u001b[0m.  If  \u001b[4mname\u001b[24m  is  an\u001b[m\r\n       indexed array, unset removes all of the elements but does\u001b[m\r\n       not remove the array itself.\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n       When using a variable name with a subscript as  an  argu‐\u001b[m\r\n       ment  to a command, such as with \u001b[1munset\u001b[0m, without using the\u001b[m\r\n       word expansion syntax described above,  the  argument  is\u001b[m\r\n       subject  to pathname expansion.  If pathname expansion is\u001b[m\r\n       not desi"]
[3620.763349, "o", "red, the argument should be quoted.\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n       The \u001b[1mdeclare\u001b[0m, \u001b[1mlocal\u001b[0m, and \u001b[1mreadonly\u001b[0m builtins each  accept  a\u001b[m\r\n       \u001b[1m-a\u001b[0m  option to specify an indexed array and a \u001b[1m-A\u001b[0m option to\u001b[m\r\n       specify an associative array.  If both options  are  sup‐\u001b[m\r\n       plied,  \u001b[1m-A\u001b[0m  takes precedence.  The \u001b[1mread\u001b[0m builtin accepts a\u001b[m\r\n       \u001b[1m-a\u001b[0m option to assign a list of words read from  the  stan‐\u001b[m\r\n       dard  input  to  an  array.  The \u001b[1mset\u001b[0m and \u001b[1mdeclare\u001b[0m builtins\u001b[m\r\n       display array values in a way  that  allows  them  to  be\u001b[m\r\n       reused as assignments.\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[1mEXPANSION\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n"]
[3620.763354, "o", "\u001b[7m Manual page bash(1) line 1873 (press h for help or q to quit)\u001b[27m\u001b[K"]
[3620.794824, "o", "\r\u001b[K"]
[3620.794919, "o", "       Expansion  is  performed on the command line after it has\u001b[m\r\n       been split into words.  There are seven kinds  of  expan‐\u001b[m\r\n       sion performed: \u001b[4mbrace\u001b[24m \u001b[4mexpansion\u001b[24m, \u001b[4mtilde\u001b[24m \u001b[4mexpansion\u001b[24m, \u001b[4mparame‐\u001b[24m\u001b[m\r\n       \u001b[4mter\u001b[24m \u001b[4mand\u001b[24m \u001b[4mvariable\u001b[24m \u001b[4mexpansion\u001b[24m, \u001b[4mcommand\u001b[24m \u001b[4msubstitution\u001b[24m,  \u001b[4marith‐\u001b[24m\u001b[m\r\n       \u001b[4mmetic\u001b[24m \u001b[4mexpansion\u001b[24m, \u001b[4mword\u001b[24m \u001b[4msplitting\u001b[24m, and \u001b[4mpathname\u001b[24m \u001b[4mexpansion\u001b[24m.\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n       The order of expansions is: brace expansion; tilde expan‐\u001b[m\r\n       sion, parameter and variable expansion, arithmetic expan‐\u001b[m\r\n       sion,  and  command substitution (done in a left-to-right\u001b[m\r\n       fashion); word splitting; and pathname expansion.\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n       On systems that can support it, there  is  an  additional\u001b[m\r\n       expansion  available: \u001b[4mprocess\u001b[24m \u001b[4msubstitution\u001b[24m.  This is per‐\u001b[m\r\n       formed at the same time as  tilde,  parameter,  variable,\u001b[m\r\n   "]
[3620.794961, "o", "    and arithmetic expansion and command substitution.\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n       After  these  expansions  are performed, quote characters\u001b[m\r\n       present in the original word are removed unless they have\u001b[m\r\n       been quoted themselves (\u001b[4mquote\u001b[24m \u001b[4mremoval\u001b[24m).\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n       Only brace expansion, word splitting, and pathname expan‐\u001b[m\r\n       sion can increase the number of words of  the  expansion;\u001b[m\r\n       other  expansions  expand a single word to a single word.\u001b[m\r\n       The only exceptions to this are the  expansions  of  \"\u001b[1m$@\u001b[0m\"\u001b[m\r\n       and  \"\u001b[1m${\u001b[0m\u001b[4mname\u001b[24m\u001b[1m[@]}\u001b[0m\",  and, in most cases, \u001b[1m$*\u001b[0m and \u001b[1m${\u001b[0m\u001b[4mname\u001b[24m\u001b[1m[*]}\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n       as explained above (see \u001b[1mPARAMETERS\u001b[0m).\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[7m Manual page bash(1) line 1899 (press h for help or q to quit)\u001b[27m\u001b[K"]
[3620.825988, "o", "\r\u001b[K"]
[3620.826022, "o", "\u001b[m\r\n   \u001b[1mBrace\u001b[0m \u001b[1mExpansion\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n       \u001b[4mBrace\u001b[24m \u001b[4mexpansion\u001b[24m is a mechanism by which arbitrary strings\u001b[m\r\n       may  be generated.  This mechanism is similar to \u001b[4mpathname\u001b[24m\u001b[m\r\n       \u001b[4mexpansion\u001b[24m, but the filenames generated  need  not  exist.\u001b[m\r\n       Patterns  to  be  brace  expanded take the form of an op‐\u001b[m\r\n       tional \u001b[4mpreamble\u001b[24m, followed by either a  series  of  comma-\u001b[m\r\n       separated strings or a sequence expression between a pair\u001b[m\r\n       of braces, followed by an optional \u001b[4mpostscript\u001b[24m.  The  pre‐\u001b[m\r\n       amble  is  prefixed  to  each string contained within the\u001b[m\r\n       braces, and the postscript is then appended to  each  re‐\u001b[m\r\n       sulting string, expanding left to right.\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n       Brace  expansions may be nested.  The results of each ex‐\u001b[m\r\n       panded string are not sorted; left to right order is pre‐\u001b[m\r\n       served.   For  example,  a\u001b[1m{\u001b[0md,c,b\u001b[1m}\u001b[0me  expands into `ade ace\u001b[m\r\n       abe'.\u001b[m"]
[3620.826027, "o", "\r\n\u001b[m\r\n       A s"]
[3620.826173, "o", "equence  expression  takes  the  form  \u001b[1m{\u001b[0m\u001b[4mx\u001b[24m\u001b[1m..\u001b[0m\u001b[4my\u001b[24m\u001b[1m[..\u001b[0m\u001b[4mincr\u001b[24m\u001b[1m]}\u001b[0m,\u001b[m\r\n       where  \u001b[4mx\u001b[24m and \u001b[4my\u001b[24m are either integers or single letters, and\u001b[m\r\n       \u001b[4mincr\u001b[24m, an optional increment, is an integer.   When  inte‐\u001b[m\r\n       gers  are supplied, the expression expands to each number\u001b[m\r\n       between \u001b[4mx\u001b[24m and \u001b[4my\u001b[24m, inclusive.   Supplied  integers  may  be\u001b[m\r\n       prefixed  with  \u001b[4m0\u001b[24m  to  force  each  term to have the same\u001b[m\r\n       width.  When either \u001b[4mx\u001b[24m or \u001b[4my\u001b[24m begins with a zero, the  shell\u001b[m\r\n       attempts to force all generated terms to contain the same\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[7m Manual page bash(1) line 1925 (press h for help or q to quit)\u001b[27m\u001b[K"]
[3620.857417, "o", "\r\u001b[K"]
[3620.857446, "o", "       number of digits,  zero-padding  where  necessary.   When\u001b[m\r\n       letters  are  supplied,  the  expression  expands to each\u001b[m\r\n       character lexicographically between \u001b[4mx\u001b[24m and  \u001b[4my\u001b[24m,  inclusive,\u001b[m\r\n       using  the default C locale.  Note that both \u001b[4mx\u001b[24m and \u001b[4my\u001b[24m must\u001b[m\r\n       be of the same type (integer or letter).  When the incre‐\u001b[m\r\n       ment  is  supplied,  it is used as the difference between\u001b[m\r\n       each term.  The default increment is 1 or -1 as appropri‐\u001b[m\r\n       ate.\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n       Brace expansion is performed before any other expansions,\u001b[m\r\n       and any characters special to other expansions  are  pre‐\u001b[m\r\n"]
[3620.857542, "o", "       served in the result.  It is strictly textual.  \u001b[1mBash\u001b[0m does\u001b[m\r\n       not apply any syntactic interpretation to the context  of\u001b[m\r\n       the expansion or the text between the braces.\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n       A  correctly-formed brace expansion must contain unquoted\u001b[m\r\n       opening and closing braces, and  at  least  one  unquoted\u001b[m\r\n       comma  or  a  valid sequence expression.  Any incorrectly\u001b[m\r\n       formed brace expansion is left unchanged.  A \u001b[1m{\u001b[0m or  \u001b[1m,\u001b[0m  may\u001b[m\r\n       be  quoted  with a backslash to prevent its being consid‐\u001b[m\r\n       ered part of a brace expression.  To avoid conflicts with\u001b[m\r\n       parameter expansion, the string \u001b[1m${\u001b[0m is not considered eli‐\u001b[m\r\n       gible for brace expansion, and inhibits  brace  expansion\u001b[m\r\n       until the closing \u001b[1m}\u001b[0m.\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n       This  construct  is  typically used as shorthand when the\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[7m Manual page bash(1) line 1951 (press h for help or q to quit)\u001b[27m\u001b[K"]
[3620.888391, "o", "\r\u001b[K       common prefix of the strings to be  generated  is  longer\u001b[m\r\n       than in the above example:\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n              mkdir /usr/local/src/bash/{old,new,dist,bugs}\u001b[m\r\n       or\u001b[m\r\n              chown                                         root\u001b[m\r\n              /usr/{ucb/{ex,edit},lib/{ex?.?*,how_ex}}\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n       Brace expansion introduces a slight incompatibility  with\u001b[m\r\n       historical  versions of \u001b[1msh\u001b[0m.  \u001b[1msh\u001b[0m does not treat opening or\u001b[m\r\n       closing braces specially when they appear as  part  of  a\u001b[m\r\n       word,  and  preserves  them  in the output.  \u001b[1mBash\u001b[0m removes\u001b[m\r\n       braces from words as a consequence  of  brace  expansion.\u001b[m\r\n       For  example,  a  word entered to \u001b[1msh\u001b[0m as \u001b[4mfile{1,2}\u001b[24m appears\u001b[m\r\n       identically in the output.  The same word  is  output  as\u001b[m\r\n       \u001b[4mfile1\u001b[24m  \u001b[4mfile2\u001b[24m after expansion by \u001b[1mbash\u001b[0m.  If strict compati‐\u001b[m\r\n       bility with \u001b[1msh\u001b[0m is desired, start \u001b[1mbash\u001b[0m with the \u001b[1m+B"]
[3620.888497, "o", "\u001b[0m  option\u001b[m\r\n       or  disable brace expansion with the \u001b[1m+B\u001b[0m option to the \u001b[1mset\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n       command (see \u001b[1mSHELL\u001b[0m \u001b[1mBUILTIN\u001b[0m \u001b[1mCOMMANDS\u001b[0m below).\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n   \u001b[1mTilde\u001b[0m \u001b[1mExpansion\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n       If a word begins with an unquoted tilde character  (`\u001b[1m~\u001b[0m'),\u001b[m\r\n       all  of the characters preceding the first unquoted slash\u001b[m\r\n       (or all characters, if there is no  unquoted  slash)  are\u001b[m\r\n       considered  a \u001b[4mtilde-prefix\u001b[24m.  If none of the characters in\u001b[m\r\n       the tilde-prefix are quoted, the characters in the tilde-\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[7m Manual page bash(1) line 1977 (press h for help or q to quit)\u001b[27m\u001b[K"]
[3620.919874, "o", "\r\u001b[K       prefix  following the tilde are treated as a possible \u001b[4mlo‐\u001b[24m\u001b[m\r\n       \u001b[4mgin\u001b[24m \u001b[4mname\u001b[24m.  If this login name is  the  null  string,  the\u001b[m\r\n       tilde  is  replaced with the value of the shell parameter\u001b[m\r\n       \u001b[1mHOME\u001b[0m.  If \u001b[1mHOME\u001b[0m is unset, the home directory of  the  user\u001b[m\r\n       executing  the  shell is substituted instead.  Otherwise,\u001b[m\r\n       the tilde-prefix is replaced with the home directory  as‐\u001b[m\r\n       sociated with the specified login name.\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n       If  the  tilde-prefix  is  a `~+', the value of the shell\u001b[m\r\n       variable \u001b[1mPWD\u001b[0m replaces the tilde-prefix.   If  the  tilde-\u001b[m\r\n       prefix is a `~-', the value of the shell variable \u001b[1mOLDPWD\u001b[0m,\u001b[m\r\n       if it is set, is substituted.  If the characters  follow‐\u001b[m\r\n       ing  the tilde in the tilde-prefix consist of a number \u001b[4mN\u001b[24m,\u001b[m\r\n       optionally prefixed by a `+' or a `-',  the  tilde-prefix\u001b[m\r\n       is  replaced  with the corresponding element from the d"]
[3620.919978, "o", "i‐\u001b[m\r\n       re"]
[3620.920092, "o", "ctory stack, as it  would  be  displayed  by  the  \u001b[1mdirs\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n       builtin invoked with the tilde-prefix as an argument.  If\u001b[m\r\n       the characters following the tilde  in  the  tilde-prefix\u001b[m\r\n       consist  of a number without a leading `+' or `-', `+' is\u001b[m\r\n       assumed.\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n       If the login name is  invalid,  or  the  tilde  expansion\u001b[m\r\n       fails, the word is unchanged.\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n       Each  variable  assignment is checked for unquoted tilde-\u001b[m\r\n       prefixes immediately following a \u001b[1m:\u001b[0m or the  first  \u001b[1m=\u001b[0m.   In\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[7m Manual page bash(1) line 2003 (press h for help or q to quit)\u001b[27m\u001b[K"]
[3620.951401, "o", "\r\u001b[K"]
[3620.951529, "o", "       these  cases,  tilde expansion is also performed.  Conse‐\u001b[m\r\n       quently, one may use filenames with tildes in assignments\u001b[m\r\n       to  \u001b[1mPATH\u001b[0m, \u001b[1mMAILPATH\u001b[0m, and \u001b[1mCDPATH\u001b[0m, and the shell assigns the\u001b[m\r\n       expanded value.\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n       Bash also performs tilde expansion  on  words  satisfying\u001b[m\r\n       the  conditions  of  variable  assignments  (as described\u001b[m\r\n       above under \u001b[1mPARAMETERS\u001b[0m) when they appear as arguments  to\u001b[m\r\n       simple  commands.   Bash does not do this, except for the\u001b[m\r\n       \u001b[4mdeclaration\u001b[24m commands listed above, when in \u001b[4mposix\u001b[24m \u001b[4mmode\u001b[24m.\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n   \u001b[1mParameter\u001b[0m \u001b[1mExpansion\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n       The `\u001b[1m$\u001b[0m' character introduces parameter expansion, command\u001b[m\r\n       substitution,  or  arithmetic  expansion.   The parameter\u001b[m\r\n       name or symbol to be expanded may be enclosed in  braces,\u001b[m\r\n       which  are  optional but serve to protect the variable to\u001b[m\r\n       be expanded  from  characters  immediately "]
[3620.951544, "o", " following  it\u001b[m\r\n       which could be interpreted as part of the name.\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n       When  braces  are  used, the matching ending brace is the\u001b[m\r\n       first `\u001b[1m}\u001b[0m' not escaped by a backslash or within  a  quoted\u001b[m\r\n       string,  and not within an embedded arithmetic expansion,\u001b[m\r\n       command substitution, or parameter expansion.\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n       ${\u001b[4mparameter\u001b[24m}\u001b[m\r\n              The value of \u001b[4mparameter\u001b[24m is substituted.  The braces\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[7m Manual page bash(1) line 2029 (press h for help or q to quit)\u001b[27m\u001b[K"]
[3620.987854, "o", "\r\u001b[K              are required when \u001b[4mparameter\u001b[24m is a positional param‐\u001b[m\r\n              eter with more than one digit, or  when  \u001b[4mparameter\u001b[24m\u001b[m\r\n              is  followed by a character which is not to be in‐\u001b[m\r\n              terpreted as part of its name.  The \u001b[4mparameter\u001b[24m is a\u001b[m\r\n              shell  parameter as described above \u001b[1mPARAMETERS\u001b[0m) or\u001b[m\r\n              an array reference (\u001b[1mArrays\u001b[0m).\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n       If the first character of  \u001b[4mparameter\u001b[24m  is  an  exclamation\u001b[m\r\n       point  (\u001b[1m!\u001b[0m), and \u001b[4mparameter\u001b[24m is not a \u001b[4mnameref\u001b[24m, it introduces\u001b[m\r\n       a level of indirection.  \u001b[1mBash\u001b[0m uses the  value  formed  by\u001b[m\r\n       expanding  the  rest  of  \u001b[4mparameter\u001b[24m as the new \u001b[4mparameter\u001b[24m;\u001b[m\r\n       this is then expanded and that value is used in the  rest\u001b[m\r\n       of the expansion, rather than the expansion of the origi‐\u001b[m\r\n       nal \u001b[4mparameter\u001b[24m.  This is known as \u001b[4mindirect\u001b[24m \u001b[4mexpansion\u001b[24m.  The\u001b[m\r\n   "]
[3620.987887, "o", "    value is subject to tilde expansion, parameter expansion,\u001b[m"]
[3620.987965, "o", "\r\n"]
[3620.987987, "o", "       command substitution, and arithmetic expansion.   If  \u001b[4mpa‐\u001b[24m\u001b[m\r\n       \u001b[4mrameter\u001b[24m is a nameref, this expands to the name of the pa‐\u001b[m\r\n       rameter referenced by \u001b[4mparameter\u001b[24m instead of performing the\u001b[m\r\n       complete  indirect expansion.  The exceptions to this are\u001b[m\r\n       the expansions of ${\u001b[1m!\u001b[0m\u001b[4mprefix\u001b[24m\u001b[1m*\u001b[0m} and  ${\u001b[1m!\u001b[0m\u001b[4mname\u001b[24m[\u001b[4m@\u001b[24m]}  described\u001b[m\r\n       below.  The exclamation point must immediately follow the\u001b[m\r\n       left brace in order to introduce indirection.\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n       In each of the cases below, \u001b[4mword\u001b[24m is subject to tilde  ex‐\u001b[m\r\n       pansion,  parameter  expansion, command substitution, and\u001b[m\r\n       arithmetic expansion.\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[7m Manual page bash(1) line 2055 (press h for help or q to quit)\u001b[27m\u001b[K"]
[3621.013841, "o", "\r\u001b[K"]
[3621.013973, "o", "\u001b[m\r\n       When not performing substring expansion, using the  forms\u001b[m\r\n       documented  below  (e.g., \u001b[1m:-\u001b[0m), \u001b[1mbash\u001b[0m tests for a parameter\u001b[m\r\n       that is unset or null.  Omitting the colon results  in  a\u001b[m\r\n       test only for a parameter that is unset.\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n       ${\u001b[4mparameter\u001b[24m\u001b[1m:-\u001b[0m\u001b[4mword\u001b[24m}\u001b[m\r\n              \u001b[1mUse\u001b[0m  \u001b[1mDefault\u001b[0m  \u001b[1mValues\u001b[0m.   If  \u001b[4mparameter\u001b[24m  is unset or\u001b[m\r\n              null, the expansion of \u001b[4mword\u001b[24m is substituted.   Oth‐\u001b[m\r\n              erwise, the value of \u001b[4mparameter\u001b[24m is substituted.\u001b[m\r\n       ${\u001b[4mparameter\u001b[24m\u001b[1m:=\u001b[0m\u001b[4mword\u001b[24m}\u001b[m\r\n              \u001b[1mAssign\u001b[0m  \u001b[1mDefault\u001b[0m  \u001b[1mValues\u001b[0m.  If \u001b[4mparameter\u001b[24m is unset or\u001b[m\r\n              null, the expansion of \u001b[4mword\u001b[24m is assigned to \u001b[4mparame‐\u001b[24m\u001b[m\r\n              \u001b[4mter\u001b[24m.   The value of \u001b[4mparameter\u001b[24m is then substituted.\u001b[m\r\n              Positional parameters and special  parameters  may\u001b[m\r\n              not be ass"]
[3621.014, "o", "igned to in this way.\u001b[m\r\n       ${\u001b[4mparameter\u001b[24m\u001b[1m:?\u001b[0m\u001b[4mword\u001b[24m}\u001b[m\r\n              \u001b[1mDisplay\u001b[0m  \u001b[1mError\u001b[0m  \u001b[1mif\u001b[0m \u001b[1mNull\u001b[0m \u001b[1mor\u001b[0m \u001b[1mUnset\u001b[0m.  If \u001b[4mparameter\u001b[24m is\u001b[m\r\n              null or unset, the expansion of \u001b[4mword\u001b[24m (or a message\u001b[m\r\n              to  that effect if \u001b[4mword\u001b[24m is not present) is written\u001b[m\r\n              to the standard error and the shell, if it is  not\u001b[m\r\n              interactive,  exits.   Otherwise, the value of \u001b[4mpa‐\u001b[24m\u001b[m\r\n              \u001b[4mrameter\u001b[24m is substituted.\u001b[m\r\n       ${\u001b[4mparameter\u001b[24m\u001b[1m:+\u001b[0m\u001b[4mword\u001b[24m}\u001b[m\r\n              \u001b[1mUse\u001b[0m \u001b[1mAlternate\u001b[0m \u001b[1mValue\u001b[0m.  If \u001b[4mparameter\u001b[24m is null or  un‐\u001b[m\r\n              set,  nothing is substituted, otherwise the expan‐\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[7m Manual page bash(1) line 2081 (press h for help or q to quit)\u001b[27m\u001b[K"]
[3621.045434, "o", "\r\u001b[K"]
[3621.045535, "o", "              sion of \u001b[4mword\u001b[24m is substituted.\u001b[m\r\n       ${\u001b[4mparameter\u001b[24m\u001b[1m:\u001b[0m\u001b[4moffset\u001b[24m}\u001b[m\r\n       ${\u001b[4mparameter\u001b[24m\u001b[1m:\u001b[0m\u001b[4moffset\u001b[24m\u001b[1m:\u001b[0m\u001b[4mlength\u001b[24m}\u001b[m\r\n              \u001b[1mSubstring\u001b[0m \u001b[1mExpansion\u001b[0m.   Expands  to  up  to  \u001b[4mlength\u001b[24m\u001b[m\r\n              characters  of  the value of \u001b[4mparameter\u001b[24m starting at\u001b[m\r\n              the character specified by \u001b[4moffset\u001b[24m.   If  \u001b[4mparameter\u001b[24m\u001b[m\r\n              is \u001b[1m@\u001b[0m or \u001b[1m*\u001b[0m, an indexed array subscripted by \u001b[1m@\u001b[0m or \u001b[1m*\u001b[0m,\u001b[m\r\n              or an associative array name, the  results  differ\u001b[m\r\n              as described below.  If \u001b[4mlength\u001b[24m is omitted, expands\u001b[m\r\n              to the substring of the value of \u001b[4mparameter\u001b[24m  start‐\u001b[m\r\n              ing  at  the character specified by \u001b[4moffset\u001b[24m and ex‐\u001b[m\r\n              tending to the end of the value.  \u001b[4mlength\u001b[24m and  \u001b[4moff‐\u001b[24m\u001b[m\r\n              \u001b[4mset\u001b[24m  are  arithmetic  expressions  (see \u001b[1mARITHME"]
[3621.045566, "o", "TIC\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n              \u001b[1mEVALUATION\u001b[0m below).\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n              If \u001b[4moffset\u001b[24m evaluates to a number  less  than  zero,\u001b[m\r\n              the  value is used as an offset in characters from\u001b[m\r\n              the end of the  value  of  \u001b[4mparameter\u001b[24m.   If  \u001b[4mlength\u001b[24m\u001b[m\r\n              evaluates to a number less than zero, it is inter‐\u001b[m\r\n              preted as an offset in characters from the end  of\u001b[m\r\n              the  value  of  \u001b[4mparameter\u001b[24m  rather than a number of\u001b[m\r\n              characters, and the expansion  is  the  characters\u001b[m\r\n              between \u001b[4moffset\u001b[24m and that result.  Note that a nega‐\u001b[m\r\n              tive offset must be separated from the colon by at\u001b[m\r\n              least  one  space to avoid being confused with the\u001b[m\r\n              \u001b[1m:-\u001b[0m expansion.\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[7m Manual page bash(1) line 2107 (press h for help or q to quit)\u001b[27m\u001b[K"]
[3621.076418, "o", "\r\u001b[K"]
[3621.076513, "o", "\u001b[m\r\n              If \u001b[4mparameter\u001b[24m is \u001b[1m@\u001b[0m or \u001b[1m*\u001b[0m, the result is \u001b[4mlength\u001b[24m posi‐\u001b[m\r\n              tional parameters beginning at \u001b[4moffset\u001b[24m.  A negative\u001b[m\r\n              \u001b[4moffset\u001b[24m is taken relative to one greater  than  the\u001b[m\r\n              greatest  positional parameter, so an offset of -1\u001b[m\r\n              evaluates to the last positional parameter.  It is\u001b[m\r\n              an expansion error if \u001b[4mlength\u001b[24m evaluates to a number\u001b[m\r\n              less than zero.\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n              If \u001b[4mparameter\u001b[24m is an indexed array name  subscripted\u001b[m\r\n              by @ or *, the result is the \u001b[4mlength\u001b[24m members of the\u001b[m\r\n              array beginning with ${\u001b[4mparameter\u001b[24m[\u001b[4moffset\u001b[24m]}.  A neg‐\u001b[m\r\n              ative \u001b[4moffset\u001b[24m is taken relative to one greater than\u001b[m\r\n              the maximum index of the specified array.   It  is\u001b[m\r\n              an expansion error if \u001b[4mlength\u001b[24m evaluates to a number\u001b[m\r\n              less than zero.\u001b[m\r"]
[3621.076537, "o", "\n\u001b[m\r\n              Substring expansion applied to an associative  ar‐\u001b[m\r\n              ray produces undefined results.\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n              Substring  indexing is zero-based unless the posi‐\u001b[m\r\n              tional parameters are used, in which case the  in‐\u001b[m\r\n              dexing  starts  at  1 by default.  If \u001b[4moffset\u001b[24m is 0,\u001b[m\r\n              and the positional parameters are used, \u001b[1m$0\u001b[0m is pre‐\u001b[m\r\n              fixed to the list.\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[7m Manual page bash(1) line 2133 (press h for help or q to quit)\u001b[27m\u001b[K"]
[3621.108377, "o", "\r\u001b[K"]
[3621.108474, "o", "       ${\u001b[1m!\u001b[0m\u001b[4mprefix\u001b[24m\u001b[1m*\u001b[0m}\u001b[m\r\n       ${\u001b[1m!\u001b[0m\u001b[4mprefix\u001b[24m\u001b[1m@\u001b[0m}\u001b[m\r\n              \u001b[1mNames\u001b[0m  \u001b[1mmatching\u001b[0m  \u001b[1mprefix\u001b[0m.   Expands to the names of\u001b[m\r\n              variables whose names begin with \u001b[4mprefix\u001b[24m, separated\u001b[m\r\n              by  the  first  character of the \u001b[1mIFS\u001b[0m special vari‐\u001b[m\r\n              able.  When \u001b[4m@\u001b[24m is used and  the  expansion  appears\u001b[m\r\n              within  double  quotes, each variable name expands\u001b[m\r\n              to a separate word.\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n       ${\u001b[1m!\u001b[0m\u001b[4mname\u001b[24m[\u001b[4m@\u001b[24m]}\u001b[m\r\n       ${\u001b[1m!\u001b[0m\u001b[4mname\u001b[24m[\u001b[4m*\u001b[24m]}\u001b[m\r\n              \u001b[1mList\u001b[0m \u001b[1mof\u001b[0m \u001b[1marray\u001b[0m \u001b[1mkeys\u001b[0m.  If \u001b[4mname\u001b[24m is an array variable,\u001b[m\r\n              expands  to  the  list of array indices (keys) as‐\u001b[m\r\n              signed in \u001b[4mname\u001b[24m.  If \u001b[4mname\u001b[24m is not an array,  expands\u001b[m\r\n              to 0 if \u001b[4mname\u001b[24m is set and null otherwise.  When \u001b[4m@\u001b[24m is\u001b[m\r\n              used  and  the  expan"]
[3621.108497, "o", "sion  appears  within  double\u001b[m\r\n              quotes, each key expands to a separate word.\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n       ${\u001b[1m#\u001b[0m\u001b[4mparameter\u001b[24m}\u001b[m\r\n              \u001b[1mParameter\u001b[0m \u001b[1mlength\u001b[0m.  The length in characters of the\u001b[m\r\n              value of \u001b[4mparameter\u001b[24m is substituted.   If  \u001b[4mparameter\u001b[24m\u001b[m\r\n              is  \u001b[1m*\u001b[0m or \u001b[1m@\u001b[0m, the value substituted is the number of\u001b[m\r\n              positional parameters.  If \u001b[4mparameter\u001b[24m is  an  array\u001b[m\r\n              name  subscripted by \u001b[1m*\u001b[0m or \u001b[1m@\u001b[0m, the value substituted\u001b[m\r\n              is the number of elements in the array.  If \u001b[4mparam‐\u001b[24m\u001b[m\r\n              \u001b[4meter\u001b[24m  is  an  indexed  array name subscripted by a\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[7m Manual page bash(1) line 2159 (press h for help or q to quit)\u001b[27m\u001b[K"]
[3621.139442, "o", "\r\u001b[K"]
[3621.13947, "o", "              negative number, that  number  is  interpreted  as\u001b[m\r\n              relative  to one greater than the maximum index of\u001b[m\r\n              \u001b[4mparameter\u001b[24m, so negative indices count back from the\u001b[m\r\n              end  of  the  array, and an index of -1 references\u001b[m\r\n              the last element.\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n       ${\u001b[4mparameter\u001b[24m\u001b[1m#\u001b[0m\u001b[4mword\u001b[24m}\u001b[m\r\n       ${\u001b[4mparameter\u001b[24m\u001b[1m##\u001b[0m\u001b[4mword\u001b[24m}\u001b[m\r\n              \u001b[1mRemove\u001b[0m \u001b[1mmatching\u001b[0m \u001b[1mprefix\u001b[0m \u001b[1mpattern\u001b[0m.  The \u001b[4mword\u001b[24m  is  ex‐\u001b[m\r\n              panded  to  produce  a pattern just as in pathname\u001b[m\r\n              expansion, and matched against the expanded  value\u001b[m\r\n              of  \u001b[4mparameter\u001b[24m using the rules described under \u001b[1mPat‐\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n              \u001b[1mtern\u001b[0m \u001b[1mMatching\u001b[0m below.  If the pattern  matches  the\u001b[m\r\n              beginning  of the value of \u001b[4mparameter\u001b[24m, then the re‐\u001b[m\r\n              sult of the expansion is the expanded value of \u001b[4mpa‐\u001b[24m\u001b[m\r\n    "]
[3621.139474, "o", "          \u001b[4m"]
[3621.13959, "o", "rameter\u001b[24m  with  the  shortest matching pattern (the\u001b[m\r\n              ``\u001b[1m#\u001b[0m'' case) or the longest matching  pattern  (the\u001b[m\r\n              ``\u001b[1m##\u001b[0m'' case) deleted.  If \u001b[4mparameter\u001b[24m is \u001b[1m@\u001b[0m or \u001b[1m*\u001b[0m, the\u001b[m\r\n              pattern removal operation is applied to each posi‐\u001b[m\r\n              tional parameter in turn, and the expansion is the\u001b[m\r\n              resultant list.  If \u001b[4mparameter\u001b[24m is an array variable\u001b[m\r\n              subscripted with \u001b[1m@\u001b[0m or \u001b[1m*\u001b[0m, the pattern removal oper‐\u001b[m\r\n              ation is applied to each member of  the  array  in\u001b[m\r\n              turn, and the expansion is the resultant list.\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n       ${\u001b[4mparameter\u001b[24m\u001b[1m%\u001b[0m\u001b[4mword\u001b[24m}\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[7m Manual page bash(1) line 2185 (press h for help or q to quit)\u001b[27m\u001b[K"]
[3621.170533, "o", "\r\u001b[K"]
[3621.170595, "o", "       ${\u001b[4mparameter\u001b[24m\u001b[1m%%\u001b[0m\u001b[4mword\u001b[24m}\u001b[m\r\n              \u001b[1mRemove\u001b[0m  \u001b[1mmatching\u001b[0m  \u001b[1msuffix\u001b[0m \u001b[1mpattern\u001b[0m.  The \u001b[4mword\u001b[24m is ex‐\u001b[m\r\n              panded to produce a pattern just  as  in  pathname\u001b[m\r\n              expansion,  and matched against the expanded value\u001b[m\r\n              of \u001b[4mparameter\u001b[24m using the rules described under  \u001b[1mPat‐\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n              \u001b[1mtern\u001b[0m  \u001b[1mMatching\u001b[0m  below.   If  the pattern matches a\u001b[m\r\n              trailing portion of the expanded value of  \u001b[4mparame‐\u001b[24m\u001b[m\r\n              \u001b[4mter\u001b[24m,  then  the result of the expansion is the ex‐\u001b[m\r\n              panded value of \u001b[4mparameter\u001b[24m with the shortest match‐\u001b[m\r\n              ing pattern (the ``\u001b[1m%\u001b[0m'' case) or the longest match‐\u001b[m\r\n"]
[3621.17077, "o", "              ing pattern (the ``\u001b[1m%%\u001b[0m'' case) deleted.  If \u001b[4mparame‐\u001b[24m\u001b[m\r\n              \u001b[4mter\u001b[24m  is  \u001b[1m@\u001b[0m  or \u001b[1m*\u001b[0m, the pattern removal operation is\u001b[m\r\n              applied to each positional parameter in turn,  and\u001b[m\r\n              the expansion is the resultant list.  If \u001b[4mparameter\u001b[24m\u001b[m\r\n              is an array variable subscripted with \u001b[1m@\u001b[0m or \u001b[1m*\u001b[0m,  the\u001b[m\r\n              pattern  removal operation is applied to each mem‐\u001b[m\r\n              ber of the array in turn, and the expansion is the\u001b[m\r\n              resultant list.\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n       ${\u001b[4mparameter\u001b[24m\u001b[1m/\u001b[0m\u001b[4mpattern\u001b[24m\u001b[1m/\u001b[0m\u001b[4mstring\u001b[24m}\u001b[m\r\n       ${\u001b[4mparameter\u001b[24m\u001b[1m//\u001b[0m\u001b[4mpattern\u001b[24m\u001b[1m/\u001b[0m\u001b[4mstring\u001b[24m}\u001b[m\r\n       ${\u001b[4mparameter\u001b[24m\u001b[1m/#\u001b[0m\u001b[4mpattern\u001b[24m\u001b[1m/\u001b[0m\u001b[4mstring\u001b[24m}\u001b[m\r\n       ${\u001b[4mparameter\u001b[24m\u001b[1m/%\u001b[0m\u001b[4mpattern\u001b[24m\u001b[1m/\u001b[0m\u001b[4mstring\u001b[24m}\u001b[m\r\n              \u001b[1mPattern\u001b[0m  \u001b[1msubstitution\u001b[0m.  The \u001b[4mpattern\u001b[24m is expanded to\u001b[m\r\n      "]
[3621.170785, "o", "        produce a pattern just as in  pathname  expansion.\u001b[m\r\n              \u001b[4mParameter\u001b[24m  is  expanded  and  the longest match of\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[7m Manual page bash(1) line 2211 (press h for help or q to quit)\u001b[27m\u001b[K"]
[3621.20182, "o", "\r\u001b[K"]
[3621.201915, "o", "              \u001b[4mpattern\u001b[24m against its value is replaced with \u001b[4mstring\u001b[24m.\u001b[m\r\n              \u001b[4mstring\u001b[24m  undergoes  tilde  expansion, parameter and\u001b[m\r\n              variable expansion, arithmetic expansion,  command\u001b[m\r\n              and  process substitution, and quote removal.  The\u001b[m\r\n              match is performed using the rules described under\u001b[m\r\n              \u001b[1mPattern\u001b[0m  \u001b[1mMatching\u001b[0m below.  In the first form above,\u001b[m\r\n              only the first match is replaced.   If  there  are\u001b[m\r\n              two  slashes separating \u001b[4mparameter\u001b[24m and \u001b[4mpattern\u001b[24m (the\u001b[m\r\n              second form above), all matches of \u001b[4mpattern\u001b[24m are re‐\u001b[m\r\n              placed  with  \u001b[4mstring\u001b[24m.  If \u001b[4mpattern\u001b[24m is preceded by \u001b[1m#\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n              (the third form above), it must match at  the  be‐\u001b[m\r\n              ginning  of  the  expanded value of \u001b[4mparameter\u001b[24m.  If\u001b[m\r\n              \u001b[4mpattern\u001b[24m is preceded by \u001b[1m%\u001b[0m (the fourth form  above),\u001b[m\r\n "]
[3621.201933, "o", "            "]
[3621.20195, "o", " it  must match at the end of the expanded value of\u001b[m\r\n              \u001b[4mparameter\u001b[24m.  If the expansion of  \u001b[4mstring\u001b[24m  is  null,\u001b[m\r\n              matches  of  \u001b[4mpattern\u001b[24m  are  deleted.   If \u001b[4mstring\u001b[24m is\u001b[m\r\n              null, matches of \u001b[4mpattern\u001b[24m are  deleted  and  the  \u001b[1m/\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n              following \u001b[4mpattern\u001b[24m may be omitted.\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n              If  the \u001b[1mpatsub_replacement\u001b[0m shell option is enabled\u001b[m\r\n              using \u001b[1mshopt\u001b[0m, any unquoted instances of \u001b[1m&\u001b[0m in \u001b[4mstring\u001b[24m\u001b[m\r\n              are replaced with the matching portion of \u001b[4mpattern\u001b[24m.\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n              Quoting any part of \u001b[4mstring\u001b[24m inhibits replacement in\u001b[m\r\n              the expansion of the quoted portion, including re‐\u001b[m\r\n              placement   strings  stored  in  shell  variables.\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[7m Manual page bash(1) line 2237 (press h for help or q to quit)\u001b[27m\u001b[K"]
[3621.232918, "o", "\r\u001b[K              Backslash will escape \u001b[1m&\u001b[0m in \u001b[4mstring\u001b[24m;  the  backslash\u001b[m\r\n              is  removed  in order to permit a literal \u001b[1m&\u001b[0m in the\u001b[m\r\n              replacement string.  Backslash can also be used to\u001b[m\r\n              escape  a backslash; \u001b[1m\\\\\u001b[0m results in a literal back‐\u001b[m\r\n              slash in the replacement.  Users should take  care\u001b[m\r\n              if  \u001b[4mstring\u001b[24m  is double-quoted to avoid unwanted in‐\u001b[m\r\n              teractions between the backslash and  double-quot‐\u001b[m\r\n              ing,  since  backslash  has special meaning within\u001b[m\r\n              double quotes.  Pattern substitution performs  the\u001b[m\r\n              check for unquoted \u001b[1m&\u001b[0m after expanding \u001b[4mstring\u001b[24m; shell\u001b[m\r\n              programmers should quote any occurrences of \u001b[1m&\u001b[0m they\u001b[m\r\n              want  to be taken literally in the replacement and\u001b[m\r\n              ensure any instances of \u001b[1m&\u001b[0m they want to be replaced\u001b[m\r\n              are unquoted.\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n     "]
[3621.232942, "o", "         If  the  "]
[3621.233073, "o", "\u001b[1mnocasematch\u001b[0m  shell option is enabled, the\u001b[m\r\n              match is performed without regard to the  case  of\u001b[m\r\n              alphabetic  characters.   If  \u001b[4mparameter\u001b[24m is \u001b[1m@\u001b[0m or \u001b[1m*\u001b[0m,\u001b[m\r\n              the substitution operation is applied to each  po‐\u001b[m\r\n              sitional  parameter  in turn, and the expansion is\u001b[m\r\n              the resultant list.   If  \u001b[4mparameter\u001b[24m  is  an  array\u001b[m\r\n              variable subscripted with \u001b[1m@\u001b[0m or \u001b[1m*\u001b[0m, the substitution\u001b[m\r\n              operation is applied to each member of  the  array\u001b[m\r\n              in turn, and the expansion is the resultant list.\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n       ${\u001b[4mparameter\u001b[24m\u001b[1m^\u001b[0m\u001b[4mpattern\u001b[24m}\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[7m Manual page bash(1) line 2263 (press h for help or q to quit)\u001b[27m\u001b[K"]
[3621.263906, "o", "\r\u001b[K"]
[3621.263966, "o", "       ${\u001b[4mparameter\u001b[24m\u001b[1m^^\u001b[0m\u001b[4mpattern\u001b[24m}\u001b[m\r\n       ${\u001b[4mparameter\u001b[24m\u001b[1m,\u001b[0m\u001b[4mpattern\u001b[24m}\u001b[m\r\n       ${\u001b[4mparameter\u001b[24m\u001b[1m,,\u001b[0m\u001b[4mpattern\u001b[24m}\u001b[m\r\n              \u001b[1mCase\u001b[0m  \u001b[1mmodification\u001b[0m.   This  expansion modifies the\u001b[m\r\n              case of alphabetic characters in  \u001b[4mparameter\u001b[24m.   The\u001b[m\r\n              \u001b[4mpattern\u001b[24m  is  expanded to produce a pattern just as\u001b[m\r\n              in pathname expansion.  Each character in the  ex‐\u001b[m\r\n              panded  value  of \u001b[4mparameter\u001b[24m is tested against \u001b[4mpat‐\u001b[24m\u001b[m\r\n              \u001b[4mtern\u001b[24m, and, if it matches the pattern, its case  is\u001b[m\r\n              converted.   The  pattern  should  not  attempt to\u001b[m\r\n              match more than one  character.   The  \u001b[1m^\u001b[0m  operator\u001b[m\r\n              converts lowercase letters matching \u001b[4mpattern\u001b[24m to up‐\u001b[m\r\n              percase; the \u001b[1m,\u001b[0m operator converts  matching  upper‐\u001b[m\r\n              case  letters  to lowercase.  The \u001b[1m^^\u001b[0m and \u001b"]
[3621.264111, "o", "[1m,,\u001b[0m expan‐\u001b[m\r\n              sions convert each matched character  in  the  ex‐\u001b[m\r\n              panded  value;  the  \u001b[1m^\u001b[0m  and \u001b[1m,\u001b[0m expansions match and\u001b[m\r\n              convert only the first character in  the  expanded\u001b[m\r\n              value.   If \u001b[4mpattern\u001b[24m is omitted, it is treated like\u001b[m\r\n              a \u001b[1m?\u001b[0m, which matches every character.  If  \u001b[4mparameter\u001b[24m\u001b[m\r\n              is  \u001b[1m@\u001b[0m or \u001b[1m*\u001b[0m, the case modification operation is ap‐\u001b[m\r\n              plied to each positional parameter  in  turn,  and\u001b[m\r\n              the expansion is the resultant list.  If \u001b[4mparameter\u001b[24m\u001b[m\r\n              is an array variable subscripted with \u001b[1m@\u001b[0m or \u001b[1m*\u001b[0m,  the\u001b[m\r\n              case  modification  operation  is  applied to each\u001b[m\r\n              member of the array in turn, and the expansion  is\u001b[m\r\n              the resultant list.\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[7m Manual page bash(1) line 2289 (press h for help or q to quit)\u001b[27m\u001b[K"]
[3621.295186, "o", "\r\u001b[K\u001b[m\r\n       ${\u001b[4mparameter\u001b[24m\u001b[1m@\u001b[0m\u001b[4moperator\u001b[24m}\u001b[m\r\n              \u001b[1mParameter\u001b[0m \u001b[1mtransformation\u001b[0m.  The expansion is either\u001b[m\r\n              a transformation of the value of \u001b[4mparameter\u001b[24m or  in‐\u001b[m\r\n              formation about \u001b[4mparameter\u001b[24m itself, depending on the\u001b[m\r\n              value of \u001b[4moperator\u001b[24m.  Each \u001b[4moperator\u001b[24m is a single let‐\u001b[m\r\n              ter:\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n              \u001b[1mU\u001b[0m      The expansion is a string that is the value\u001b[m\r\n                     of  \u001b[4mparameter\u001b[24m  with  lowercase   alphabetic\u001b[m\r\n                     characters converted to uppercase.\u001b[m\r\n              \u001b[1mu\u001b[0m      The expansion is a string that is the value\u001b[m\r\n                     of \u001b[4mparameter\u001b[24m with the first character  con‐\u001b[m\r\n                     verted to uppercase, if it is alphabetic.\u001b[m\r\n              \u001b[1mL\u001b[0m      The expansion is a string that is the value\u001b[m\r\n                     of  \u001b[4mparameter\u001b[24m  with  uppercase   alphabetic\u001b[m\r\n  "]
[3621.295208, "o", "                   "]
[3621.295229, "o", "characters converted to lowercase.\u001b[m\r\n              \u001b[1mQ\u001b[0m      The expansion is a string that is the value\u001b[m\r\n                     of \u001b[4mparameter\u001b[24m quoted in a format that can be\u001b[m\r\n                     reused as input.\u001b[m\r\n              \u001b[1mE\u001b[0m      The expansion is a string that is the value\u001b[m\r\n                     of  \u001b[4mparameter\u001b[24m  with  backslash  escape  se‐\u001b[m\r\n                     quences expanded as with the \u001b[1m$'...'\u001b[0m quoting\u001b[m\r\n                     mechanism.\u001b[m\r\n              \u001b[1mP\u001b[0m      The expansion is a string that is  the  re‐\u001b[m\r\n                     sult of expanding the value of \u001b[4mparameter\u001b[24m as\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[7m Manual page bash(1) line 2315 (press h for help or q to quit)\u001b[27m\u001b[K"]
[3621.32699, "o", "\r\u001b[K"]
[3621.327151, "o", "                     if it were a prompt string  (see  \u001b[1mPROMPTING\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n                     below).\u001b[m\r\n              \u001b[1mA\u001b[0m      The expansion is a string in the form of an\u001b[m\r\n                     assignment  statement  or  \u001b[1mdeclare\u001b[0m  command\u001b[m\r\n                     that, if evaluated, will recreate \u001b[4mparameter\u001b[24m\u001b[m\r\n                     with its attributes and value.\u001b[m\r\n              \u001b[1mK\u001b[0m      Produces a possibly-quoted version  of  the\u001b[m\r\n                     value  of  \u001b[4mparameter\u001b[24m, except that it prints\u001b[m\r\n                     the values of indexed and  associative  ar‐\u001b[m\r\n                     rays  as  a  sequence  of  quoted key-value\u001b[m\r\n                     pairs (see \u001b[1mArrays\u001b[0m above).\u001b[m\r\n              \u001b[1ma\u001b[0m      The expansion is  a  string  consisting  of\u001b[m\r\n                     flag  values  representing  \u001b[4mparameter\u001b[24m's at‐\u001b[m\r\n                     tributes.\u001b[m\r\n              \u001b[1mk\u001b[0m      Like the K transformation, but expands  the\u001b[m\r\n   "]
[3621.327164, "o", "                  keys  and values of indexed and associative\u001b[m\r\n                     arrays to separate words after word  split‐\u001b[m\r\n                     ting.\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n              If  \u001b[4mparameter\u001b[24m  is \u001b[1m@\u001b[0m or \u001b[1m*\u001b[0m, the operation is applied\u001b[m\r\n              to each positional parameter in turn, and the  ex‐\u001b[m\r\n              pansion is the resultant list.  If \u001b[4mparameter\u001b[24m is an\u001b[m\r\n              array variable subscripted with \u001b[1m@\u001b[0m or \u001b[1m*\u001b[0m, the opera‐\u001b[m\r\n              tion  is  applied  to  each member of the array in\u001b[m\r\n              turn, and the expansion is the resultant list.\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[7m Manual page bash(1) line 2341 (press h for help or q to quit)\u001b[27m\u001b[K"]
[3621.357764, "o", "\r\u001b[K"]
[3621.357856, "o", "              The result of the expansion  is  subject  to  word\u001b[m\r\n              splitting  and pathname expansion as described be‐\u001b[m\r\n              low.\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n   \u001b[1mCommand\u001b[0m \u001b[1mSubstitution\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n       \u001b[4mCommand\u001b[24m \u001b[4msubstitution\u001b[24m allows the output of  a  command  to\u001b[m\r\n       replace the command name.  There are two forms:\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n              \u001b[1m$(\u001b[0m\u001b[4mcommand\u001b[24m\u001b[1m)\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n       or\u001b[m\r\n              \u001b[1m`\u001b[0m\u001b[4mcommand\u001b[24m\u001b[1m`\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n       \u001b[1mBash\u001b[0m  performs  the  expansion  by executing \u001b[4mcommand\u001b[24m in a\u001b[m\r\n       subshell environment and replacing the command  substitu‐\u001b[m\r\n       tion  with  the  standard output of the command, with any\u001b[m\r\n       trailing newlines deleted.   Embedded  newlines  are  not\u001b[m\r\n       deleted,  but  they may be removed during word splitting.\u001b[m\r\n       The command substitution \u001b[1m$(cat\u001b[0m \u001b[4mfile\u001b[24m\u001b[1m)\u001b[0m can be  replaced  by\u001b[m\r\n       the equivalent but faster \u001b[1m$(<\u001b[0m \u001b[4mfile\u001b[24m\u001b[1m)\u001b[0m.\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r"]
[3621.357943, "o", "\n       When  the  "]
[3621.357999, "o", "old-style  backquote  form  of substitution is\u001b[m\r\n       used, backslash retains its literal meaning  except  when\u001b[m\r\n       followed by \u001b[1m$\u001b[0m, \u001b[1m`\u001b[0m, or \u001b[1m\\\u001b[0m.  The first backquote not preceded\u001b[m\r\n       by a backslash terminates the command substitution.  When\u001b[m\r\n       using  the  $(\u001b[4mcommand\u001b[24m)  form,  all characters between the\u001b[m\r\n       parentheses make up the command; none  are  treated  spe‐\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[7m Manual page bash(1) line 2367 (press h for help or q to quit)\u001b[27m\u001b[K"]
[3621.388683, "o", "\r\u001b[K"]
[3621.388833, "o", "       cially.\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n       Command  substitutions may be nested.  To nest when using\u001b[m\r\n       the backquoted form, escape  the  inner  backquotes  with\u001b[m\r\n       backslashes.\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n       If  the  substitution  appears within double quotes, word\u001b[m\r\n       splitting and pathname expansion are not performed on the\u001b[m\r\n       results.\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n   \u001b[1mArithmetic\u001b[0m \u001b[1mExpansion\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n       Arithmetic  expansion  allows the evaluation of an arith‐\u001b[m\r\n       metic expression and the substitution of the result.  The\u001b[m\r\n       format for arithmetic expansion is:\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n              \u001b[1m$((\u001b[0m\u001b[4mexpression\u001b[24m\u001b[1m))\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n       The  old  format  \u001b[1m$[\u001b[0m\u001b[4mexpression\u001b[24m\u001b[1m]\u001b[0m is deprecated and will be\u001b[m\r\n       removed in upcoming versions of bash.\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n       The \u001b[4mexpression\u001b[24m undergoes the same  expansions  as  if  it\u001b[m\r\n       were within double quotes, but double quote characters in\u001b[m\r\n       \u001b[4mexpression\u001b[24m are not treated  specially  and  are  removed.\u001b["]
[3621.388851, "o", "m\r\n       All  tokens in the expression undergo parameter and vari‐\u001b[m\r\n       able expansion, command substitution, and quote  removal.\u001b[m\r\n       The  result is treated as the arithmetic expression to be\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[7m Manual page bash(1) line 2393 (press h for help or q to quit)\u001b[27m\u001b[K"]
[3621.420358, "o", "\r\u001b[K"]
[3621.420487, "o", "       evaluated.  Arithmetic expansions may be nested.\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n       The evaluation is performed according to the rules listed\u001b[m\r\n       below  under \u001b[1mARITHMETIC\u001b[0m \u001b[1mEVALUATION\u001b[0m.  If \u001b[4mexpression\u001b[24m is in‐\u001b[m\r\n       valid, \u001b[1mbash\u001b[0m prints a message indicating  failure  and  no\u001b[m\r\n       substitution occurs.\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n   \u001b[1mProcess\u001b[0m \u001b[1mSubstitution\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n       \u001b[4mProcess\u001b[24m  \u001b[4msubstitution\u001b[24m  allows a process's input or output\u001b[m\r\n       to be referred to using a filename.  It takes the form of\u001b[m\r\n       \u001b[1m<(\u001b[0m\u001b[4mlist\u001b[24m\u001b[1m)\u001b[0m  or  \u001b[1m>(\u001b[0m\u001b[4mlist\u001b[24m\u001b[1m)\u001b[0m.   The  process  \u001b[4mlist\u001b[24m  is  run asyn‐\u001b[m\r\n       chronously, and its input or output appears  as  a  file‐\u001b[m\r\n       name.  This filename is passed as an argument to the cur‐\u001b[m\r\n       rent command as the result  of  the  expansion.   If  the\u001b[m\r\n       \u001b[1m>(\u001b[0m\u001b[4mlist\u001b[24m\u001b[1m)\u001b[0m  form  is  used, writing to the file will provide\u001b[m\r\n       input for \u001b[4mlist\u001b[24m.  If the \u001b[1m<"]
[3621.420496, "o", "(\u001b[0m\u001b[4mlist\u001b[24m\u001b[1m)\u001b[0m form is  used,  the  file\u001b[m\r\n       passed as an argument should be read to obtain the output\u001b[m\r\n       of \u001b[4mlist\u001b[24m.  Process substitution is  supported  on  systems\u001b[m\r\n       that support named pipes (\u001b[4mFIFOs\u001b[24m) or the \u001b[1m/dev/fd\u001b[0m method of\u001b[m\r\n       naming open files.\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n       When available, process substitution is performed  simul‐\u001b[m\r\n       taneously  with parameter and variable expansion, command\u001b[m\r\n       substitution, and arithmetic expansion.\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n   \u001b[1mWord\u001b[0m \u001b[1mSplitting\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[7m Manual page bash(1) line 2419 (press h for help or q to quit)\u001b[27m\u001b[K"]
[3621.451881, "o", "\r\u001b[K"]
[3621.452085, "o", "       The shell scans the results of parameter expansion,  com‐\u001b[m\r\n       mand  substitution, and arithmetic expansion that did not\u001b[m\r\n       occur within double quotes for \u001b[4mword\u001b[24m \u001b[4msplitting\u001b[24m.\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n       The shell treats each character of \u001b[1mIFS\u001b[0m  as  a  delimiter,\u001b[m\r\n       and splits the results of the other expansions into words\u001b[m\r\n       using these characters as field terminators.  If  \u001b[1mIFS\u001b[0m  is\u001b[m\r\n       unset, or its value is exactly \u001b[1m<space><tab><newline>\u001b[0m, the\u001b[m\r\n       default, then sequences of \u001b[1m<space>\u001b[0m, \u001b[1m<tab>\u001b[0m, and  \u001b[1m<newline>\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n       at  the  beginning and end of the results of the previous\u001b[m\r\n       expansions are ignored, and any sequence of  \u001b[1mIFS\u001b[0m  charac‐\u001b[m\r\n       ters not at the beginning or end serves to delimit words.\u001b[m\r\n       If \u001b[1mIFS\u001b[0m has a value other than the default, then sequences\u001b[m\r\n       of  the whitespace characters \u001b[1mspace\u001b[0m, \u001b[1mtab\u001b[0m, and \u001b[1mnewline\u001b[0m are\u001b[m\r\n       ignored at the b"]
[3621.452126, "o", "eginning and end of the word, as long  as\u001b[m\r\n       the  whitespace  character is in the value of \u001b[1mIFS\u001b[0m (an \u001b[1mIFS\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n       whitespace character).  Any character in \u001b[1mIFS\u001b[0m that is  not\u001b[m\r\n       \u001b[1mIFS\u001b[0m  whitespace,  along  with any adjacent \u001b[1mIFS\u001b[0m whitespace\u001b[m\r\n       characters, delimits a field.  A sequence of  \u001b[1mIFS\u001b[0m  white‐\u001b[m\r\n       space  characters is also treated as a delimiter.  If the\u001b[m\r\n       value of \u001b[1mIFS\u001b[0m is null, no word splitting occurs.\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n       Explicit null arguments  (\u001b[1m\"\"\u001b[0m  or  \u001b[1m''\u001b[0m)  are  retained  and\u001b[m\r\n       passed  to  commands as empty strings.  Unquoted implicit\u001b[m\r\n       null arguments, resulting from the expansion  of  parame‐\u001b[m\r\n       ters  that  have  no values, are removed.  If a parameter\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[7m Manual page bash(1) line 2445 (press h for help or q to quit)\u001b[27m\u001b[K"]
[3621.483146, "o", "\r\u001b[K       with no value is expanded within double  quotes,  a  null\u001b[m\r\n       argument  results and is retained and passed to a command\u001b[m\r\n       as an empty string.  When a quoted null argument  appears\u001b[m\r\n       as  part  of a word whose expansion is non-null, the null\u001b[m\r\n       argument is removed.  That is, the word -d''  becomes  -d\u001b[m\r\n       after word splitting and null argument removal.\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n       Note  that  if  no expansion occurs, no splitting is per‐\u001b[m\r\n       formed.\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n   \u001b[1mPathname\u001b[0m \u001b[1mExpansion\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n       After word splitting, unless the \u001b[1m-f\u001b[0m option has been  set,\u001b[m\r\n       \u001b[1mbash\u001b[0m  scans each word for the characters \u001b[1m*\u001b[0m, \u001b[1m?\u001b[0m, and \u001b[1m[\u001b[0m.  If\u001b[m\r\n       one of these characters appears, and is not quoted,  then\u001b[m\r\n"]
[3621.483339, "o", "       the  word  is regarded as a \u001b[4mpattern\u001b[24m, and replaced with an\u001b[m\r\n       alphabetically sorted list of filenames matching the pat‐\u001b[m\r\n       tern  (see \u001b[1mPattern\u001b[0m \u001b[1mMatching\u001b[0m below).  If no matching file‐\u001b[m\r\n       names are found, and the shell option \u001b[1mnullglob\u001b[0m is not en‐\u001b[m\r\n       abled,  the  word is left unchanged.  If the \u001b[1mnullglob\u001b[0m op‐\u001b[m\r\n       tion is set, and no matches are found, the  word  is  re‐\u001b[m\r\n       moved.   If  the  \u001b[1mfailglob\u001b[0m  shell  option  is set, and no\u001b[m\r\n       matches are found, an error message is  printed  and  the\u001b[m\r\n       command  is not executed.  If the shell option \u001b[1mnocaseglob\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n       is enabled, the match is performed without regard to  the\u001b[m\r\n       case  of  alphabetic  characters.   Note  that when using\u001b[m\r\n       range expressions like [a-z] (see below), letters of  the\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[7m Manual page bash(1) line 2471 (press h for help or q to quit)\u001b[27m\u001b[K"]
[3621.514824, "o", "\r\u001b[K       other  case  may be included, depending on the setting of\u001b[m\r\n       \u001b[1mLC_COLLATE.\u001b[0m  When a pattern is used for  pathname  expan‐\u001b[m\r\n       sion,  the character \u001b[1m``.''\u001b[0m  at the start of a name or im‐\u001b[m\r\n       mediately following a slash must be  matched  explicitly,\u001b[m\r\n       unless  the  shell  option  \u001b[1mdotglob\u001b[0m  is set.  In order to\u001b[m\r\n       match the filenames \u001b[1m``.''\u001b[0m  and \u001b[1m``..''\u001b[0m, the  pattern  must\u001b[m\r\n       begin  with  ``.'' (for example, ``.?''), even if \u001b[1mdotglob\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n       is set.  If the \u001b[1mglobskipdots\u001b[0m shell option is enabled, the\u001b[m\r\n       filenames  \u001b[1m``.''\u001b[0m   and \u001b[1m``..''\u001b[0m  are never matched, even if\u001b[m\r\n       the pattern begins with a \u001b[1m``.''\u001b[0m.  When not matching path‐\u001b[m\r\n       names,  the  \u001b[1m``.''\u001b[0m   character  is not treated specially.\u001b[m\r\n       When matching a pathname, the slash character must always\u001b[m\r\n       be  matched  explicitly by a slash in the pattern, but in\u001b[m\r\n       other matching context"]
[3621.51485, "o", "s it can be matc"]
[3621.515026, "o", "hed  by  a  special\u001b[m\r\n       pattern character as described below under \u001b[1mPattern\u001b[0m \u001b[1mMatch‐\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n       \u001b[1ming\u001b[0m.  See the description  of  \u001b[1mshopt\u001b[0m  below  under  \u001b[1mSHELL\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n       \u001b[1mBUILTIN\u001b[0m  \u001b[1mCOMMANDS\u001b[0m  for  a  description of the \u001b[1mnocaseglob\u001b[0m,\u001b[m\r\n       \u001b[1mnullglob\u001b[0m, \u001b[1mglobskipdots\u001b[0m, \u001b[1mfailglob\u001b[0m, and \u001b[1mdotglob\u001b[0m  shell  op‐\u001b[m\r\n       tions.\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n       The \u001b[1mGLOBIGNORE\u001b[0m shell variable may be used to restrict the\u001b[m\r\n       set of file names matching a \u001b[4mpattern\u001b[24m.  If  \u001b[1mGLOBIGNORE\u001b[0m  is\u001b[m\r\n       set, each matching file name that also matches one of the\u001b[m\r\n       patterns in  \u001b[1mGLOBIGNORE\u001b[0m  is  removed  from  the  list  of\u001b[m\r\n       matches.   If  the \u001b[1mnocaseglob\u001b[0m option is set, the matching\u001b[m\r\n       against the patterns in \u001b[1mGLOBIGNORE\u001b[0m is  performed  without\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[7m Manual page bash(1) line 2497 (press h for help or q to quit)\u001b[27m\u001b[K"]
[3621.545668, "o", "\r\u001b[K"]
[3621.54578, "o", "       regard to case.  The filenames \u001b[1m``.''\u001b[0m  and \u001b[1m``..''\u001b[0m  are al‐\u001b[m\r\n       ways ignored when \u001b[1mGLOBIGNORE\u001b[0m is set and not  null.   How‐\u001b[m\r\n       ever,  setting \u001b[1mGLOBIGNORE\u001b[0m to a non-null value has the ef‐\u001b[m\r\n       fect of enabling the \u001b[1mdotglob\u001b[0m shell option, so  all  other\u001b[m\r\n       filenames beginning with a \u001b[1m``.''\u001b[0m  will match.  To get the\u001b[m\r\n       old behavior  of  ignoring  filenames  beginning  with  a\u001b[m\r\n"]
[3621.545812, "o", "       \u001b[1m``.''\u001b[0m,  make  \u001b[1m``.*''\u001b[0m   one of the patterns in \u001b[1mGLOBIGNORE\u001b[0m.\u001b[m\r\n       The \u001b[1mdotglob\u001b[0m option is disabled when \u001b[1mGLOBIGNORE\u001b[0m is  unset.\u001b[m\r\n       The  pattern  matching  honors the setting of the \u001b[1mextglob\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n       shell option.\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n       \u001b[1mPattern\u001b[0m \u001b[1mMatching\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n       Any character that appears in a pattern, other  than  the\u001b[m\r\n       special  pattern  characters described below, matches it‐\u001b[m\r\n       self.  The NUL character may not occur in a  pattern.   A\u001b[m\r\n       backslash  escapes  the following character; the escaping\u001b[m\r\n       backslash is discarded when matching.  The  special  pat‐\u001b[m\r\n       tern  characters must be quoted if they are to be matched\u001b[m\r\n       literally.\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n       The special pattern characters have the  following  mean‐\u001b[m\r\n       ings:\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n              \u001b[1m*\u001b[0m      Matches  any  string,  including  the  null\u001b[m\r\n                     string.  When the \u001b[1mglobstar\u001b[0m shell option  is\u001b[m"]
[3621.545817, "o", "\r\n\u001b[7m Manual page bash(1) line 2523 (press h for help or q to quit)\u001b[27m\u001b[K"]
[3621.576638, "o", "\r\u001b[K"]
[3621.576686, "o", "                     enabled, and \u001b[1m*\u001b[0m is used in a pathname expan‐\u001b[m\r\n                     sion context, two adjacent  \u001b[1m*\u001b[0ms  used  as  a\u001b[m\r\n                     single  pattern  will  match  all files and\u001b[m\r\n                     zero or more  directories  and  subdirecto‐\u001b[m\r\n                     ries.   If followed by a \u001b[1m/\u001b[0m, two adjacent \u001b[1m*\u001b[0ms\u001b[m\r\n                     will match only directories and subdirecto‐\u001b[m\r\n                     ries.\u001b[m\r\n              \u001b[1m?\u001b[0m      Matches any single character.\u001b[m\r\n              \u001b[1m[...]\u001b[0m  Matches any one of the enclosed characters.\u001b[m\r\n                     A pair of characters separated by a  hyphen\u001b[m\r\n                     denotes  a  \u001b[4mrange\u001b[24m \u001b[4mexpression\u001b[24m; any character\u001b[m\r\n                     that falls between  those  two  characters,\u001b[m\r\n                     inclusive,  using the current locale's col‐\u001b[m\r\n                     lating  sequence  and  character  set,   is\u001b[m\r\n                     matched.   If t"]
[3621.57669, "o", "he first char"]
[3621.576795, "o", "acter following\u001b[m\r\n                     the \u001b[1m[\u001b[0m is a \u001b[1m!\u001b[0m  or a \u001b[1m^\u001b[0m then any character not\u001b[m\r\n                     enclosed  is matched.  The sorting order of\u001b[m\r\n                     characters in range  expressions,  and  the\u001b[m\r\n                     characters  included  in the range, are de‐\u001b[m\r\n                     termined by the current locale and the val‐\u001b[m\r\n                     ues of the \u001b[1mLC_COLLATE\u001b[0m or \u001b[1mLC_ALL\u001b[0m shell vari‐\u001b[m\r\n                     ables, if set.  To obtain  the  traditional\u001b[m\r\n                     interpretation  of range expressions, where\u001b[m\r\n                     \u001b[1m[a-d]\u001b[0m is equivalent to \u001b[1m[abcd]\u001b[0m, set value of\u001b[m\r\n                     the  \u001b[1mLC_ALL\u001b[0m  shell variable to \u001b[1mC\u001b[0m, or enable\u001b[m\r\n                     the \u001b[1mglobasciiranges\u001b[0m shell option.  A \u001b[1m-\u001b[0m  may\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[7m Manual page bash(1) line 2549 (press h for help or q to quit)\u001b[27m\u001b[K"]
[3621.608156, "o", "\r\u001b[K"]
[3621.60821, "o", "                     be  matched by including it as the first or\u001b[m\r\n                     last character in the  set.   A  \u001b[1m]\u001b[0m  may  be\u001b[m\r\n                     matched  by including it as the first char‐\u001b[m\r\n                     acter in the set.\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n                     Within \u001b[1m[\u001b[0m and \u001b[1m]\u001b[0m, \u001b[4mcharacter\u001b[24m  \u001b[4mclasses\u001b[24m  can  be\u001b[m\r\n                     specified using the syntax \u001b[1m[:\u001b[0m\u001b[4mclass\u001b[24m\u001b[1m:]\u001b[0m, where\u001b[m\r\n                     \u001b[4mclass\u001b[24m is one of the following  classes  de‐\u001b[m\r\n                     fined in the POSIX standard:\u001b[m\r\n                     \u001b[1malnum\u001b[0m  \u001b[1malpha\u001b[0m  \u001b[1mascii\u001b[0m \u001b[1mblank\u001b[0m \u001b[1mcntrl\u001b[0m \u001b[1mdigit\u001b[0m \u001b[1mgraph\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n                     \u001b[1mlower\u001b[0m \u001b[1mprint\u001b[0m \u001b[1mpunct\u001b[0m \u001b[1mspace\u001b[0m \u001b[1mupper\u001b[0m \u001b[1mword\u001b[0m \u001b[1mxdigit\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n                     A character class matches any character be‐\u001b[m\r\n                     longing  to that class.  The \u001b[1mword\u001b[0m character\u001b[m\r\n                     class  matc"]
[3621.608214, "o", "hes  letters"]
[3621.608306, "o", ",  digits,  and  the\u001b[m\r\n                     character _.\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n                     Within \u001b[1m[\u001b[0m and \u001b[1m]\u001b[0m, an \u001b[4mequivalence\u001b[24m \u001b[4mclass\u001b[24m can be\u001b[m\r\n                     specified using  the  syntax  \u001b[1m[=\u001b[0m\u001b[4mc\u001b[24m\u001b[1m=]\u001b[0m,  which\u001b[m\r\n                     matches all characters with the same colla‐\u001b[m\r\n                     tion weight (as defined by the current  lo‐\u001b[m\r\n                     cale) as the character \u001b[4mc\u001b[24m.\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n                     Within  \u001b[1m[\u001b[0m  and  \u001b[1m]\u001b[0m,  the  syntax  \u001b[1m[.\u001b[0m\u001b[4msymbol\u001b[24m\u001b[1m.]\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n                     matches the collating symbol \u001b[4msymbol\u001b[24m.\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n       If the \u001b[1mextglob\u001b[0m shell option is enabled  using  the  \u001b[1mshopt\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[7m Manual page bash(1) line 2575 (press h for help or q to quit)\u001b[27m\u001b[K"]
[3621.639064, "o", "\r\u001b[K       builtin,  the  shell  recognizes several extended pattern\u001b[m\r\n       matching operators.  In the following description, a \u001b[4mpat‐\u001b[24m\u001b[m\r\n       \u001b[4mtern-list\u001b[24m  is a list of one or more patterns separated by\u001b[m\r\n       a \u001b[1m|\u001b[0m.  Composite patterns may be formed using one or  more\u001b[m\r\n       of the following sub-patterns:\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n"]
[3621.639288, "o", "              \u001b[1m?(\u001b[0m\u001b[4mpattern-list\u001b[24m\u001b[1m)\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n                     Matches zero or one occurrence of the given\u001b[m\r\n                     patterns\u001b[m\r\n              \u001b[1m*(\u001b[0m\u001b[4mpattern-list\u001b[24m\u001b[1m)\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n                     Matches zero or  more  occurrences  of  the\u001b[m\r\n                     given patterns\u001b[m\r\n              \u001b[1m+(\u001b[0m\u001b[4mpattern-list\u001b[24m\u001b[1m)\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n                     Matches  one  or  more  occurrences  of the\u001b[m\r\n                     given patterns\u001b[m\r\n              \u001b[1m@(\u001b[0m\u001b[4mpattern-list\u001b[24m\u001b[1m)\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n                     Matches one of the given patterns\u001b[m\r\n              \u001b[1m!(\u001b[0m\u001b[4mpattern-list\u001b[24m\u001b[1m)\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n                     Matches anything except one  of  the  given\u001b[m\r\n                     patterns\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n       The\u001b[1mextglob\u001b[0m  option  changes  the  behavior of the parser,\u001b[m\r\n       since the parentheses are normally treated  as  operators\u001b[m\r\n       with syntactic meaning.  To ensure that extended matching\u001b[m\r\n       patterns are parsed"]
[3621.639302, "o", " correctly, make sure that \u001b[1mextglob\u001b[0m  is\u001b[m\r\n       enabled  before  parsing  constructs  containing the pat‐\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[7m Manual page bash(1) line 2601 (press h for help or q to quit)\u001b[27m\u001b[K"]
[3621.670544, "o", "\r\u001b[K"]
[3621.670571, "o", "       terns, including shell functions  and  command  substitu‐\u001b[m\r\n       tions.\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n       When  matching filenames, the \u001b[1mdotglob\u001b[0m shell option deter‐\u001b[m\r\n       mines the set of filenames that are tested: when  \u001b[1mdotglob\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n       is  enabled,  the set of filenames includes all files be‐\u001b[m\r\n       ginning with ``.'', but ``.'' and ``..'' must be  matched\u001b[m\r\n       by  a pattern or sub-pattern that begins with a dot; when\u001b[m\r\n       it is disabled, the set does not  include  any  filenames\u001b[m\r\n       beginning  with  ``.''  unless the pattern or sub-pattern\u001b[m\r\n       begins with a ``.''.  As above, ``.'' only has a  special\u001b[m\r\n       meaning when matching filenames.\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n       Complicated   extended   pattern  matching  against  long\u001b[m\r\n       strings is slow, especially when the patterns contain al‐\u001b[m\r\n       ternations and the strings contain multiple matches.  Us‐\u001b[m\r\n       ing separate matches against shorter  strings,  or  using\u001b[m\r\n       arrays of strings inst"]
[3621.670584, "o", "ead of a single "]
[3621.670588, "o", "long string, may be\u001b[m\r\n       faster.\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n   \u001b[1mQuote\u001b[0m \u001b[1mRemoval\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n       After the preceding expansions, all unquoted  occurrences\u001b[m\r\n       of  the  characters  \u001b[1m\\\u001b[0m, \u001b[1m'\u001b[0m, and \u001b[1m\"\u001b[0m that did not result from\u001b[m\r\n       one of the above expansions are removed.\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[1mREDIRECTION\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[7m Manual page bash(1) line 2627 (press h for help or q to quit)\u001b[27m\u001b[K"]
[3621.702114, "o", "\r\u001b[K       Before a command is executed, its input and output may be\u001b[m\r\n       \u001b[4mredirected\u001b[24m  using  a  special notation interpreted by the\u001b[m\r\n       shell.  \u001b[4mRedirection\u001b[24m allows commands' file handles  to  be\u001b[m\r\n       duplicated,  opened,  closed,  made to refer to different\u001b[m\r\n       files, and can change the files the  command  reads  from\u001b[m\r\n       and  writes  to.   Redirection may also be used to modify\u001b[m\r\n       file handles in the current shell execution  environment.\u001b[m\r\n       The following redirection operators may precede or appear\u001b[m\r\n       anywhere within a \u001b[4msimple\u001b[24m \u001b[4mcommand\u001b[24m or may follow a \u001b[4mcommand\u001b[24m.\u001b[m\r\n       Redirections are processed in the order they appear, from\u001b[m\r\n       left to right.\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n       Each redirection that may be preceded by a file  descrip‐\u001b[m\r\n       tor  number may instead be preceded by a word of the form\u001b[m\r\n       {\u001b[4mvarname\u001b[24m}.  In this case, for each  redirection  operator\u001b[m\r\n       except  >&-  and  <&-, the sh"]
[3621.702137, "o", "ell will allocate "]
[3621.702326, "o", "a file de‐\u001b[m\r\n       scriptor greater than or equal to 10  and  assign  it  to\u001b[m\r\n       \u001b[4mvarname\u001b[24m.   If  >&-  or  <&- is preceded by {\u001b[4mvarname\u001b[24m}, the\u001b[m\r\n       value of \u001b[4mvarname\u001b[24m defines the file  descriptor  to  close.\u001b[m\r\n       If {\u001b[4mvarname\u001b[24m} is supplied, the redirection persists beyond\u001b[m\r\n       the scope of the command, allowing the  shell  programmer\u001b[m\r\n       to  manage  the file descriptor's lifetime manually.  The\u001b[m\r\n       \u001b[1mvarredir_close\u001b[0m shell option manages this behavior.\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n       In the following descriptions,  if  the  file  descriptor\u001b[m\r\n       number  is  omitted, and the first character of the redi‐\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[7m Manual page bash(1) line 2653 (press h for help or q to quit)\u001b[27m\u001b[K"]
[3621.733029, "o", "\r\u001b[K       rection operator is \u001b[1m<\u001b[0m,  the  redirection  refers  to  the\u001b[m\r\n       standard input (file descriptor 0).  If the first charac‐\u001b[m\r\n       ter of the redirection operator  is  \u001b[1m>\u001b[0m,  the  redirection\u001b[m\r\n       refers to the standard output (file descriptor 1).\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n       The  word  following the redirection operator in the fol‐\u001b[m\r\n       lowing descriptions, unless otherwise noted, is subjected\u001b[m\r\n       to  brace expansion, tilde expansion, parameter and vari‐\u001b[m\r\n       able expansion, command substitution,  arithmetic  expan‐\u001b[m\r\n       sion,  quote removal, pathname expansion, and word split‐\u001b[m\r\n       ting.  If it expands to more than one word, \u001b[1mbash\u001b[0m  reports\u001b[m\r\n       an error.\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n       Note  that the order of redirections is significant.  For\u001b[m\r\n       example, the command\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n              ls \u001b[1m>\u001b[0m dirlist 2\u001b[1m>&\u001b[0m1\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n       directs both standard output and standard  error  to  the\u001b[m\r\n       file \u001b[4mdirlist\u001b[24m, while the "]
[3621.733172, "o", "command\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n              ls 2\u001b[1m>&\u001b[0m1 \u001b[1m>\u001b[0m dirlist\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n       directs only the standard output to file \u001b[4mdirlist\u001b[24m, because\u001b[m\r\n       the standard error was duplicated from the standard  out‐\u001b[m\r\n       put before the standard output was redirected to \u001b[4mdirlist\u001b[24m.\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[7m Manual page bash(1) line 2679 (press h for help or q to quit)\u001b[27m\u001b[K"]
[3621.764376, "o", "\r\u001b[K\u001b[m\r\n       \u001b[1mBash\u001b[0m  handles  several  filenames specially when they are\u001b[m\r\n       used in redirections, as described in the  following  ta‐\u001b[m\r\n       ble.   If  the  operating system on which \u001b[1mbash\u001b[0m is running\u001b[m\r\n"]
[3621.764538, "o", "       provides these special files, bash will use them;  other‐\u001b[m\r\n       wise  it  will  emulate them internally with the behavior\u001b[m\r\n       described below.\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n              \u001b[1m/dev/fd/\u001b[0m\u001b[4mfd\u001b[24m\u001b[m\r\n                     If \u001b[4mfd\u001b[24m is a valid integer,  file  descriptor\u001b[m\r\n                     \u001b[4mfd\u001b[24m is duplicated.\u001b[m\r\n              \u001b[1m/dev/stdin\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n                     File descriptor 0 is duplicated.\u001b[m\r\n              \u001b[1m/dev/stdout\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n                     File descriptor 1 is duplicated.\u001b[m\r\n              \u001b[1m/dev/stderr\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n                     File descriptor 2 is duplicated.\u001b[m\r\n              \u001b[1m/dev/tcp/\u001b[0m\u001b[4mhost\u001b[24m\u001b[1m/\u001b[0m\u001b[4mport\u001b[24m\u001b[m\r\n                     If \u001b[4mhost\u001b[24m is a valid hostname or Internet ad‐\u001b[m\r\n                     dress, and \u001b[4mport\u001b[24m is an integer  port  number\u001b[m\r\n                     or  service name, \u001b[1mbash\u001b[0m attempts to open the\u001b[m\r\n                     corresponding TCP socket.\u001b[m\r\n              \u001b[1m/dev/udp/\u001b[0m"]
[3621.76465, "o", "\u001b[4mhost\u001b[24m\u001b[1m/\u001b[0m\u001b[4mport\u001b[24m\u001b[m\r\n                     If \u001b[4mhost\u001b[24m is a valid hostname or Internet ad‐\u001b[m\r\n                     dress,  and  \u001b[4mport\u001b[24m is an integer port number\u001b[m\r\n                     or service name, \u001b[1mbash\u001b[0m attempts to open  the\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[7m Manual page bash(1) line 2705 (press h for help or q to quit)\u001b[27m\u001b[K"]
[3621.796205, "o", "\r\u001b[K"]
[3621.796247, "o", "                     corresponding UDP socket.\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n       A failure to open or create a file causes the redirection\u001b[m\r\n       to fail.\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n       Redirections using file descriptors greater than 9 should\u001b[m\r\n       be  used  with  care,  as they may conflict with file de‐\u001b[m\r\n       scriptors the shell uses internally.\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n       Note that the \u001b[1mexec\u001b[0m builtin command can make  redirections\u001b[m\r\n       take effect in the current shell.\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n   \u001b[1mRedirecting\u001b[0m \u001b[1mInput\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n       Redirection  of  input causes the file whose name results\u001b[m\r\n       from the expansion of \u001b[4mword\u001b[24m to be opened  for  reading  on\u001b[m\r\n       file descriptor \u001b[4mn\u001b[24m, or the standard input (file descriptor\u001b[m\r\n       0) if \u001b[4mn\u001b[24m is not specified.\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n       The general format for redirecting input is:\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n              [\u001b[4mn\u001b[24m]\u001b[1m<\u001b[0m\u001b[4mword\u001b[24m\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n   \u001b[1mRedirecting\u001b[0m \u001b[1mOutput\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n       Redirection of output causes the file whose name  results\u001b[m\r\n       "]
[3621.796262, "o", "from  the  expansion  of \u001b[4mword\u001b[24m to be opened for writing on\u001b[m\r\n       file descriptor \u001b[4mn\u001b[24m, or the standard output (file  descrip‐\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[7m Manual page bash(1) line 2731 (press h for help or q to quit)\u001b[27m\u001b[K"]
[3621.82751, "o", "\r\u001b[K       tor 1) if \u001b[4mn\u001b[24m is not specified.  If the file does not exist\u001b[m\r\n       it is created; if it does exist it is truncated  to  zero\u001b[m\r\n       size.\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n       The general format for redirecting output is:\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n              [\u001b[4mn\u001b[24m]\u001b[1m>\u001b[0m\u001b[4mword\u001b[24m\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n       If  the  redirection operator is \u001b[1m>\u001b[0m, and the \u001b[1mnoclobber\u001b[0m op‐\u001b[m\r\n       tion to the \u001b[1mset\u001b[0m builtin has been enabled, the redirection\u001b[m\r\n"]
[3621.827659, "o", "       will  fail if the file whose name results from the expan‐\u001b[m\r\n       sion of \u001b[4mword\u001b[24m exists and is a regular file.  If the  redi‐\u001b[m\r\n       rection  operator is \u001b[1m>|\u001b[0m, or the redirection operator is \u001b[1m>\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n       and the \u001b[1mnoclobber\u001b[0m option to the \u001b[1mset\u001b[0m  builtin  command  is\u001b[m\r\n       not  enabled,  the  redirection  is attempted even if the\u001b[m\r\n       file named by \u001b[4mword\u001b[24m exists.\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n   \u001b[1mAppending\u001b[0m \u001b[1mRedirected\u001b[0m \u001b[1mOutput\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n       Redirection of output in this  fashion  causes  the  file\u001b[m\r\n       whose  name  results  from  the  expansion  of \u001b[4mword\u001b[24m to be\u001b[m\r\n       opened for appending on file descriptor \u001b[4mn\u001b[24m, or  the  stan‐\u001b[m\r\n       dard  output  (file  descriptor 1) if \u001b[4mn\u001b[24m is not specified.\u001b[m\r\n       If the file does not exist it is created.\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n       The general format for appending output is:\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[7m Manual page bash(1) line 2757 (press h for help or q to quit)\u001b[27m\u001b[K"]
[3621.859199, "o", "\r\u001b[K"]
[3621.859228, "o", "              [\u001b[4mn\u001b[24m]\u001b[1m>>\u001b[0m\u001b[4mword\u001b[24m\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n   \u001b[1mRedirecting\u001b[0m \u001b[1mStandard\u001b[0m \u001b[1mOutput\u001b[0m \u001b[1mand\u001b[0m \u001b[1mStandard\u001b[0m \u001b[1mError\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n       This construct allows both the standard output (file  de‐\u001b[m\r\n       scriptor  1) and the standard error output (file descrip‐\u001b[m\r\n       tor 2) to be redirected to the file whose name is the ex‐\u001b[m\r\n       pansion of \u001b[4mword\u001b[24m.\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n       There are two formats for redirecting standard output and\u001b[m\r\n       standard error:\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n              \u001b[1m&>\u001b[0m\u001b[4mword\u001b[24m\u001b[m\r\n       and\u001b[m\r\n              \u001b[1m>&\u001b[0m\u001b[4mword\u001b[24m\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n       Of the two forms, the first is preferred.  This is seman‐\u001b[m\r\n       tically equivalent to\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n              \u001b[1m>\u001b[0m\u001b[4mword\u001b[24m 2\u001b[1m>&\u001b[0m1\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n       When using the second form, \u001b[4mword\u001b[24m may not expand to a num‐\u001b[m\r\n       ber or \u001b[1m-\u001b[0m.  If it does, other redirection operators  apply\u001b[m\r\n       (see  \u001b[1mDuplicating\u001b[0m \u001b[1mFile\u001b[0m \u001b[1mDescriptors\u001b[0m below) for c"]
[3621.859236, "o", "ompatibil‐\u001b[m\r\n       ity reasons.\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n   \u001b[1mAppending\u001b[0m \u001b[1mStandard\u001b[0m \u001b[1mOutput\u001b[0m \u001b[1mand\u001b[0m \u001b[1mStandard\u001b[0m \u001b[1mError\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[7m Manual page bash(1) line 2783 (press h for help or q to quit)\u001b[27m\u001b[K"]
[3621.889882, "o", "\r\u001b[K"]
[3621.890061, "o", "       This construct allows both the standard output (file  de‐\u001b[m\r\n       scriptor  1) and the standard error output (file descrip‐\u001b[m\r\n       tor 2) to be appended to the file whose name is  the  ex‐\u001b[m\r\n       pansion of \u001b[4mword\u001b[24m.\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n       The format for appending standard output and standard er‐\u001b[m\r\n       ror is:\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n              \u001b[1m&>>\u001b[0m\u001b[4mword\u001b[24m\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n       This is semantically equivalent to\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n              \u001b[1m>>\u001b[0m\u001b[4mword\u001b[24m 2\u001b[1m>&\u001b[0m1\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n       (see \u001b[1mDuplicating\u001b[0m \u001b[1mFile\u001b[0m \u001b[1mDescriptors\u001b[0m below).\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n   \u001b[1mHere\u001b[0m \u001b[1mDocuments\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n       This type of redirection instructs the shell to read  in‐\u001b[m\r\n       put  from the current source until a line containing only\u001b[m\r\n       \u001b[4mdelimiter\u001b[24m (with no trailing blanks) is seen.  All of  the\u001b[m\r\n       lines read up to that point are then used as the standard\u001b[m\r\n       input (or file descriptor \u001b[4mn\u001b[24m if \u001b[4mn\u001b[24m is specified) for a com‐\u001b[m\r\n       mand.\u001b[m\r\n\u001b["]
[3621.890161, "o", "m\r\n       The format of here-documents is:\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[7m Manual page bash(1) line 2809 (press h for help or q to quit)\u001b[27m\u001b[K"]
[3621.920858, "o", "\r\u001b[K              [\u001b[4mn\u001b[24m]\u001b[1m<<\u001b[0m[\u001b[1m-\u001b[0m]\u001b[4mword\u001b[24m\u001b[m\r\n                      \u001b[4mhere-document\u001b[24m\u001b[m\r\n              \u001b[4mdelimiter\u001b[24m\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n       No  parameter  and  variable expansion, command substitu‐\u001b[m\r\n       tion, arithmetic expansion, or pathname expansion is per‐\u001b[m\r\n"]
[3621.92095, "o", "       formed  on  \u001b[4mword\u001b[24m.  If any part of \u001b[4mword\u001b[24m is quoted, the \u001b[4mde‐\u001b[24m\u001b[m\r\n       \u001b[4mlimiter\u001b[24m is the result of quote removal on \u001b[4mword\u001b[24m,  and  the\u001b[m\r\n       lines  in the here-document are not expanded.  If \u001b[4mword\u001b[24m is\u001b[m\r\n       unquoted, all lines of the here-document are subjected to\u001b[m\r\n       parameter expansion, command substitution, and arithmetic\u001b[m\r\n       expansion, the character sequence \u001b[1m\\<newline>\u001b[0m is  ignored,\u001b[m\r\n       and \u001b[1m\\\u001b[0m must be used to quote the characters \u001b[1m\\\u001b[0m, \u001b[1m$\u001b[0m, and \u001b[1m`\u001b[0m.\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n       If  the redirection operator is \u001b[1m<<-\u001b[0m, then all leading tab\u001b[m\r\n       characters are stripped from input  lines  and  the  line\u001b[m\r\n       contai"]
[3621.921046, "o", "ning  \u001b[4mdelimiter\u001b[24m.  This allows here-documents within\u001b[m\r\n       shell scripts to be indented in a natural fashion.\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n   \u001b[1mHere\u001b[0m \u001b[1mStrings\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n       A variant of here documents, the format is:\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n              [\u001b[4mn\u001b[24m]\u001b[1m<<<\u001b[0m\u001b[4mword\u001b[24m\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n       The \u001b[4mword\u001b[24m undergoes tilde expansion, parameter  and  vari‐\u001b[m\r\n       able  expansion,  command substitution, arithmetic expan‐\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[7m Manual page bash(1) line 2835 (press h for help or q to quit)\u001b[27m\u001b[K"]
[3621.952922, "o", "\r\u001b[K"]
[3621.953017, "o", "       sion, and quote removal.   Pathname  expansion  and  word\u001b[m\r\n       splitting are not performed.  The result is supplied as a\u001b[m\r\n       single string, with a newline appended, to the command on\u001b[m\r\n       its  standard  input (or file descriptor \u001b[4mn\u001b[24m if \u001b[4mn\u001b[24m is speci‐\u001b[m\r\n       fied).\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n   \u001b[1mDuplicating\u001b[0m \u001b[1mFile\u001b[0m \u001b[1mDescriptors\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n       The redirection operator\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n              [\u001b[4mn\u001b[24m]\u001b[1m<&\u001b[0m\u001b[4mword\u001b[24m\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n       is used to duplicate input file descriptors.  If \u001b[4mword\u001b[24m ex‐\u001b[m\r\n       pands  to one or more digits, the file descriptor denoted\u001b[m\r\n       by \u001b[4mn\u001b[24m is made to be a copy of that  file  descriptor.   If\u001b[m\r\n       the  digits in \u001b[4mword\u001b[24m do not specify a file descriptor open\u001b[m\r\n       for input, a redirection error occurs.  If \u001b[4mword\u001b[24m evaluates\u001b[m\r\n       to  \u001b[1m-\u001b[0m,  file  descriptor \u001b[4mn\u001b[24m is closed.  If \u001b[4mn\u001b[24m is not speci‐\u001b[m\r\n       fied, the standard input (file descriptor 0) is used.\u001b[m\r\n"]
[3621.953055, "o", "\u001b[m\r\n       The operator\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n              [\u001b[4mn\u001b[24m]\u001b[1m>&\u001b[0m\u001b[4mword\u001b[24m\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n       is used similarly to duplicate output  file  descriptors.\u001b[m\r\n       If \u001b[4mn\u001b[24m is not specified, the standard output (file descrip‐\u001b[m\r\n       tor 1) is used.  If the digits in \u001b[4mword\u001b[24m do not  specify  a\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[7m Manual page bash(1) line 2861 (press h for help or q to quit)\u001b[27m\u001b[K"]
[3621.984324, "o", "\r\u001b[K"]
[3621.984355, "o", "       file  descriptor open for output, a redirection error oc‐\u001b[m\r\n       curs.  If \u001b[4mword\u001b[24m evaluates  to  \u001b[1m-\u001b[0m,  file  descriptor  \u001b[4mn\u001b[24m  is\u001b[m\r\n       closed.   As  a  special  case, if \u001b[4mn\u001b[24m is omitted, and \u001b[4mword\u001b[24m\u001b[m\r\n       does not expand to one or more digits or \u001b[1m-\u001b[0m, the  standard\u001b[m\r\n       output  and  standard  error  are redirected as described\u001b[m\r\n       previously.\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n   \u001b[1mMoving\u001b[0m \u001b[1mFile\u001b[0m \u001b[1mDescriptors\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n       The redirection operator\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n              [\u001b[4mn\u001b[24m]\u001b[1m<&\u001b[0m\u001b[4mdigit\u001b[24m\u001b[1m-\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n       moves the file descriptor \u001b[4mdigit\u001b[24m to file descriptor \u001b[4mn\u001b[24m,  or\u001b[m\r\n       the standard input (file descriptor 0) if \u001b[4mn\u001b[24m is not speci‐\u001b[m\r\n       fied.  \u001b[4mdigit\u001b[24m is closed after being duplicated to \u001b[4mn\u001b[24m.\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n       Similarly, the redirection operator\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n              [\u001b[4mn\u001b[24m]\u001b[1m>&\u001b[0m\u001b[4mdigit\u001b[24m\u001b[1m-\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n       moves the file descriptor \u001b[4mdigit\u001b[24m to file de"]
[3621.984364, "o", "scriptor \u001b[4mn\u001b[24m,  or\u001b[m\r\n       the standard output (file descriptor 1) if \u001b[4mn\u001b[24m is not spec‐\u001b[m\r\n       ified.\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n   \u001b[1mOpening\u001b[0m \u001b[1mFile\u001b[0m \u001b[1mDescriptors\u001b[0m \u001b[1mfor\u001b[0m \u001b[1mReading\u001b[0m \u001b[1mand\u001b[0m \u001b[1mWriting\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n       The redirection operator\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[7m Manual page bash(1) line 2887 (press h for help or q to quit)\u001b[27m\u001b[K"]
[3622.015598, "o", "\r\u001b[K\u001b[m\r\n              [\u001b[4mn\u001b[24m]\u001b[1m<>\u001b[0m\u001b[4mword\u001b[24m\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n       causes the file whose name is the expansion of \u001b[4mword\u001b[24m to be\u001b[m\r\n       opened for both reading and writing on file descriptor \u001b[4mn\u001b[24m,\u001b[m\r\n       or on file descriptor 0 if \u001b[4mn\u001b[24m is not  specified.   If  the\u001b[m\r\n       file does not exist, it is created.\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[1mALIASES\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n       \u001b[4mAliases\u001b[24m  allow a string to be substituted for a word when\u001b[m\r\n       it is used as the first word of a  simple  command.   The\u001b[m\r\n       shell maintains a list of aliases that may be set and un‐\u001b[m\r\n       set with the \u001b[1malias\u001b[0m  and  \u001b[1munalias\u001b[0m  builtin  commands  (see\u001b[m\r\n       \u001b[1mSHELL\u001b[0m  \u001b[1mBUILTIN\u001b[0m  \u001b[1mCOMMANDS\u001b[0m  below).  The first word of each\u001b[m\r\n       simple command, if unquoted, is checked to see if it  has\u001b[m\r\n       an  alias.   If  so, that word is replaced by the text of\u001b[m\r\n       the alias.  The characters \u001b[1m/\u001b[0m, \u001b[1m$\u001b[0m, \u001b[1m`\u001b[0m, and \u001b[1m=\u001b[0m and any of  the\u001b[m\r\n       shell  \u001b"]
[3622.015632, "o", "[4mmetacharacters\u001b[2"]
[3622.015641, "o", "4m  or quoting characters listed above\u001b[m\r\n       may not appear in an alias name.   The  replacement  text\u001b[m\r\n       may  contain  any  valid  shell  input,  including  shell\u001b[m\r\n       metacharacters.  The first word of the  replacement  text\u001b[m\r\n       is tested for aliases, but a word that is identical to an\u001b[m\r\n       alias being expanded is not expanded a second time.  This\u001b[m\r\n       means  that  one may alias \u001b[1mls\u001b[0m to \u001b[1mls\u001b[0m \u001b[1m-F\u001b[0m, for instance, and\u001b[m\r\n       \u001b[1mbash\u001b[0m does not try to recursively expand  the  replacement\u001b[m\r\n       text.   If  the  last  character  of the alias value is a\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[7m Manual page bash(1) line 2913 (press h for help or q to quit)\u001b[27m\u001b[K"]
[3622.046979, "o", "\r\u001b[K       \u001b[4mblank\u001b[24m, then the next command word following the alias  is\u001b[m\r\n       also checked for alias expansion.\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n       Aliases  are  created  and listed with the \u001b[1malias\u001b[0m command,\u001b[m\r\n       and removed with the \u001b[1munalias\u001b[0m command.\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n       There is no mechanism for using arguments in the replace‐\u001b[m\r\n       ment text.  If arguments are needed, use a shell function\u001b[m\r\n       (see \u001b[1mFUNCTIONS\u001b[0m below).\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n       Aliases are not expanded when the shell is  not  interac‐\u001b[m\r\n       tive, unless the \u001b[1mexpand_aliases\u001b[0m shell option is set using\u001b[m\r\n       \u001b[1mshopt\u001b[0m (see the description of \u001b[1mshopt\u001b[0m under  \u001b[1mSHELL\u001b[0m  \u001b[1mBUILTIN\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n       \u001b[1mCOMMANDS\u001b[0m below).\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n       The  rules  concerning  the definition and use of aliases\u001b[m\r\n       are somewhat confusing.  \u001b[1mBash\u001b[0m always reads at  least  one\u001b[m\r\n       complete line of input, and all lines that make up a com‐\u001b[m\r\n       pound command, before executing any of  the  command"]
[3622.047004, "o", "s  on\u001b[m\r\n       that "]
[3622.047024, "o", " line or the compound command.  Aliases are expanded\u001b[m\r\n       when a command is read, not when it is executed.   There‐\u001b[m\r\n       fore,  an  alias definition appearing on the same line as\u001b[m\r\n       another command does not take effect until the next  line\u001b[m\r\n       of input is read.  The commands following the alias defi‐\u001b[m\r\n       nition on that line are not affected by  the  new  alias.\u001b[m\r\n       This  behavior  is  also an issue when functions are exe‐\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[7m Manual page bash(1) line 2939 (press h for help or q to quit)\u001b[27m\u001b[K"]
[3622.077514, "o", "\r\u001b[K"]
[3622.077551, "o", "       cuted.  Aliases are expanded when a  function  definition\u001b[m\r\n       is  read,  not  when  the function is executed, because a\u001b[m\r\n       function definition is itself a  command.   As  a  conse‐\u001b[m\r\n       quence,  aliases  defined in a function are not available\u001b[m\r\n       until after that function is executed.  To be  safe,  al‐\u001b[m\r\n       ways put alias definitions on a separate line, and do not\u001b[m\r\n       use \u001b[1malias\u001b[0m in compound commands.\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n       For almost every purpose, aliases are superseded by shell\u001b[m\r\n       functions.\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[1mFUNCTIONS\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n       A  shell function, defined as described above under \u001b[1mSHELL\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n       \u001b[1mGRAMMAR\u001b[0m, stores a series of commands for later execution.\u001b[m\r\n       When  the  name  of  a shell function is used as a simple\u001b[m\r\n       command name, the list of commands associated  with  that\u001b[m\r\n       function name is executed.  Functions are executed in the\u001b[m\r\n       context of the current shell; no new process  is  created\u001b[m\r\n  "]
[3622.077561, "o", "     to  interpret them (contrast this with the execution of a\u001b[m\r\n       shell script).  When a function is  executed,  the  argu‐\u001b[m\r\n       ments  to  the  function become the positional parameters\u001b[m\r\n       during its execution.  The special parameter \u001b[1m#\u001b[0m is updated\u001b[m\r\n       to reflect the change.  Special parameter \u001b[1m0\u001b[0m is unchanged.\u001b[m\r\n       The first element of the \u001b[1mFUNCNAME\u001b[0m variable is set to  the\u001b[m\r\n       name of the function while the function is executing.\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[7m Manual page bash(1) line 2965 (press h for help or q to quit)\u001b[27m\u001b[K"]
[3622.109164, "o", "\r\u001b[K       All  other aspects of the shell execution environment are\u001b[m\r\n       identical between a function and its  caller  with  these\u001b[m\r\n       exceptions:  the \u001b[1mDEBUG\u001b[0m and \u001b[1mRETURN\u001b[0m traps (see the descrip‐\u001b[m\r\n       tion of the \u001b[1mtrap\u001b[0m builtin under \u001b[1mSHELL\u001b[0m \u001b[1mBUILTIN\u001b[0m \u001b[1mCOMMANDS\u001b[0m be‐\u001b[m\r\n       low) are not inherited unless the function has been given\u001b[m\r\n       the \u001b[1mtrace\u001b[0m attribute (see the description of  the  \u001b[1mdeclare\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n       builtin  below) or the \u001b[1m-o\u001b[0m \u001b[1mfunctrace\u001b[0m shell option has been\u001b[m\r\n       enabled with the \u001b[1mset\u001b[0m builtin (in which case all functions\u001b[m\r\n       inherit  the \u001b[1mDEBUG\u001b[0m and \u001b[1mRETURN\u001b[0m traps), and the \u001b[1mERR\u001b[0m trap is\u001b[m\r\n       not inherited unless the \u001b[1m-o\u001b[0m  \u001b[1merrtrace\u001b[0m  shell  option  has\u001b[m\r\n       been enabled.\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n       Variables  local to the function may be declared with the\u001b[m\r\n       \u001b[1mlocal\u001b[0m builtin  command  (\u001b[4mlocal\u001b[24m  \u001b[4mvariables\u001b[24m).   Ordinarily,\u001b[m\r\n    "]
[3622.109198, "o", "   variables  and"]
[3622.109317, "o", "  their values are shared between the func‐\u001b[m\r\n       tion and its caller.  If a variable  is  declared  \u001b[1mlocal\u001b[0m,\u001b[m\r\n       the  variable's visible scope is restricted to that func‐\u001b[m\r\n       tion and its children (including the functions it calls).\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n       In the following description, the \u001b[4mcurrent\u001b[24m \u001b[4mscope\u001b[24m is a cur‐\u001b[m\r\n       rently-  executing  function.  Previous scopes consist of\u001b[m\r\n       that function's caller and so on, back  to  the  \"global\"\u001b[m\r\n       scope,  where  the shell is not executing any shell func‐\u001b[m\r\n       tion.  Consequently, a  local  variable  at  the  current\u001b[m\r\n       scope  is  a variable declared using the \u001b[1mlocal\u001b[0m or \u001b[1mdeclare\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n       builtins in the function that is currently executing.\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[7m Manual page bash(1) line 2991 (press h for help or q to quit)\u001b[27m\u001b[K"]
[3622.140837, "o", "\r\u001b[K\u001b[m\r\n       Local variables \"shadow\" variables with the same name de‐\u001b[m\r\n       clared  at  previous scopes.  For instance, a local vari‐\u001b[m\r\n       able declared in a function hides a  global  variable  of\u001b[m\r\n       the  same  name:  references and assignments refer to the\u001b[m\r\n       local variable, leaving the global  variable  unmodified.\u001b[m\r\n       When  the  function  returns, the global variable is once\u001b[m\r\n       again visible.\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n       The shell uses \u001b[4mdynamic\u001b[24m \u001b[4mscoping\u001b[24m to  control  a  variable's\u001b[m\r\n       visibility within functions.  With dynamic scoping, visi‐\u001b[m\r\n"]
[3622.140978, "o", "       ble variables and their values are a result  of  the  se‐\u001b[m\r\n       quence  of  function calls that caused execution to reach\u001b[m\r\n       the current function.  The value of  a  variable  that  a\u001b[m\r\n       function  sees depends on its value within its caller, if\u001b[m\r\n       any, whether that caller is the \"global\" scope or another\u001b[m\r\n       shell  function.   This  is  also  the value that a local\u001b[m\r\n       variable declaration \"shadows\", and the value that is re‐\u001b[m\r\n       stored when the function returns.\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n       For  example,  if  a variable \u001b[4mvar\u001b[24m is declared as local in\u001b[m\r\n       function \u001b[4mfunc1\u001b[24m, and \u001b[4mfunc1\u001b[24m calls another  function  \u001b[4mfunc2\u001b[24m,\u001b[m\r\n       references  to \u001b[4mvar\u001b[24m made from within \u001b[4mfunc2\u001b[24m will resolve to\u001b[m\r\n       the local variable \u001b[4mvar\u001b[24m from \u001b[4mfunc1\u001b[24m, shadowing  any  global\u001b[m\r\n       variable named \u001b[4mvar\u001b[24m.\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[7m Manual page bash(1) line 3017 (press h for help or q to quit)\u001b[27m\u001b[K"]
[3622.172155, "o", "\r\u001b[K"]
[3622.172316, "o", "       The \u001b[1munset\u001b[0m builtin also acts using the same dynamic scope:\u001b[m\r\n       if a variable is local to the current scope,  \u001b[1munset\u001b[0m  will\u001b[m\r\n       unset  it; otherwise the unset will refer to the variable\u001b[m\r\n       found in any calling scope  as  described  above.   If  a\u001b[m\r\n       variable at the current local scope is unset, it will re‐\u001b[m\r\n       main so (appearing as unset) until it is  reset  in  that\u001b[m\r\n       scope  or  until the function returns.  Once the function\u001b[m\r\n       returns, any instance of the variable at a previous scope\u001b[m\r\n       will  become visible.  If the unset acts on a variable at\u001b[m\r\n       a previous scope, any instance of a  variable  with  that\u001b[m\r\n       name  that had been shadowed will become visible (see be‐\u001b[m\r\n       low how the \u001b[1mlocalvar_unset\u001b[0m shell option changes this  be‐\u001b[m\r\n       havior).\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n       The  \u001b[1mFUNCNEST\u001b[0m variable, if set to a numeric value greater\u001b[m\r\n       than 0, defines a maximum function nesting level.   Func"]
[3622.172333, "o", "‐\u001b[m\r\n       tion  invocations  that exceed the limit cause the entire\u001b[m\r\n       command to abort.\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n       If the builtin command \u001b[1mreturn\u001b[0m is executed in a  function,\u001b[m\r\n       the  function  completes  and  execution resumes with the\u001b[m\r\n       next command after the function call.  Any command  asso‐\u001b[m\r\n       ciated  with the \u001b[1mRETURN\u001b[0m trap is executed before execution\u001b[m\r\n       resumes.  When a function completes, the  values  of  the\u001b[m\r\n       positional parameters and the special parameter \u001b[1m#\u001b[0m are re‐\u001b[m\r\n       stored to the values they had prior to the function's ex‐\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[7m Manual page bash(1) line 3043 (press h for help or q to quit)\u001b[27m\u001b[K"]
[3622.203038, "o", "\r\u001b[K"]
[3622.203237, "o", "       ecution.\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n       Function  names and definitions may be listed with the \u001b[1m-f\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n       option to the \u001b[1mdeclare\u001b[0m or \u001b[1mtypeset\u001b[0m builtin  commands.   The\u001b[m\r\n       \u001b[1m-F\u001b[0m  option  to  \u001b[1mdeclare\u001b[0m or \u001b[1mtypeset\u001b[0m will list the function\u001b[m\r\n       names only (and optionally the source file and line  num‐\u001b[m\r\n       ber, if the \u001b[1mextdebug\u001b[0m shell option is enabled).  Functions\u001b[m\r\n       may be exported so that child shell processes (those cre‐\u001b[m\r\n       ated when executing a separate shell invocation) automat‐\u001b[m\r\n       ically have them defined with the \u001b[1m-f\u001b[0m option to the \u001b[1mexport\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n       builtin.   A function definition may be deleted using the\u001b[m\r\n       \u001b[1m-f\u001b[0m option to the \u001b[1munset\u001b[0m builtin.\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n       Functions may be recursive.  The \u001b[1mFUNCNEST\u001b[0m variable may be\u001b[m\r\n       used  to  limit  the depth of the function call stack and\u001b[m\r\n       restrict the number of function invocations.  By default,\u001b[m\r\n       no limit is im"]
[3622.203254, "o", "posed on the number of recursive calls.\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[1mARITHMETIC\u001b[0m \u001b[1mEVALUATION\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n       The  shell allows arithmetic expressions to be evaluated,\u001b[m\r\n       under certain circumstances  (see  the  \u001b[1mlet\u001b[0m  and  \u001b[1mdeclare\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n       builtin commands, the \u001b[1m((\u001b[0m compound command, and \u001b[1mArithmetic\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n       \u001b[1mExpansion\u001b[0m).  Evaluation is done in  fixed-width  integers\u001b[m\r\n       with  no  check  for  overflow,  though  division by 0 is\u001b[m\r\n       trapped and flagged as an error.  The operators and their\u001b[m\r\n       precedence,  associativity, and values are the same as in\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[7m Manual page bash(1) line 3069 (press h for help or q to quit)\u001b[27m\u001b[K"]
[3622.2342, "o", "\r\u001b[K"]
[3622.234347, "o", "       the C language.   The  following  list  of  operators  is\u001b[m\r\n       grouped  into  levels of equal-precedence operators.  The\u001b[m\r\n       levels are listed in order of decreasing precedence.\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n       \u001b[4mid\u001b[24m\u001b[1m++\u001b[0m \u001b[4mid\u001b[24m\u001b[1m--\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n              variable post-increment and post-decrement\u001b[m\r\n       \u001b[1m-\u001b[0m \u001b[1m+\u001b[0m    unary minus and plus\u001b[m\r\n       \u001b[1m++\u001b[0m\u001b[4mid\u001b[24m \u001b[1m--\u001b[0m\u001b[4mid\u001b[24m\u001b[m\r\n              variable pre-increment and pre-decrement\u001b[m\r\n       \u001b[1m!\u001b[0m \u001b[1m~\u001b[0m    logical and bitwise negation\u001b[m\r\n       \u001b[1m**\u001b[0m     exponentiation\u001b[m\r\n       \u001b[1m*\u001b[0m \u001b[1m/\u001b[0m \u001b[1m%\u001b[0m  multiplication, division, remainder\u001b[m\r\n       \u001b[1m+\u001b[0m \u001b[1m-\u001b[0m    addition, subtraction\u001b[m\r\n       \u001b[1m<<\u001b[0m \u001b[1m>>\u001b[0m  left and right bitwise shifts\u001b[m\r\n       \u001b[1m<=\u001b[0m \u001b[1m>=\u001b[0m \u001b[1m<\u001b[0m \u001b[1m>\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n              comparison\u001b[m\r\n       \u001b[1m==\u001b[0m \u001b[1m!=\u001b[0m  equality and inequality\u001b[m\r\n       \u001b[1m&\u001b[0m      bitwise AND\u001b[m\r\n       \u001b[1m^\u001b[0m      bitwise exclusive OR\u001b[m\r\n     "]
[3622.234362, "o", "  \u001b[1m|\u001b[0m      bitwise OR\u001b[m\r\n       \u001b[1m&&\u001b[0m     logical AND\u001b[m\r\n       \u001b[1m||\u001b[0m     logical OR\u001b[m\r\n       \u001b[4mexpr\u001b[24m\u001b[1m?\u001b[0m\u001b[4mexpr\u001b[24m\u001b[1m:\u001b[0m\u001b[4mexpr\u001b[24m\u001b[m\r\n              conditional operator\u001b[m\r\n       \u001b[1m=\u001b[0m \u001b[1m*=\u001b[0m \u001b[1m/=\u001b[0m \u001b[1m%=\u001b[0m \u001b[1m+=\u001b[0m \u001b[1m-=\u001b[0m \u001b[1m<<=\u001b[0m \u001b[1m>>=\u001b[0m \u001b[1m&=\u001b[0m \u001b[1m^=\u001b[0m \u001b[1m|=\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n              assignment\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[7m Manual page bash(1) line 3095 (press h for help or q to quit)\u001b[27m\u001b[K"]
[3622.265604, "o", "\r\u001b[K"]
[3622.265701, "o", "       \u001b[4mexpr1\u001b[24m \u001b[1m,\u001b[0m \u001b[4mexpr2\u001b[24m\u001b[m\r\n              comma\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n       Shell variables are allowed as operands; parameter expan‐\u001b[m\r\n       sion  is  performed  before  the expression is evaluated.\u001b[m\r\n       Within an expression, shell variables may also be  refer‐\u001b[m\r\n       enced  by name without using the parameter expansion syn‐\u001b[m\r\n       tax.  A shell variable that is null or unset evaluates to\u001b[m\r\n       0 when referenced by name without using the parameter ex‐\u001b[m\r\n       pansion syntax.  The value of a variable is evaluated  as\u001b[m\r\n       an arithmetic expression when it is referenced, or when a\u001b[m\r\n       variable which has been given the \u001b[4minteger\u001b[24m attribute using\u001b[m\r\n       \u001b[1mdeclare\u001b[0m  \u001b[1m-i\u001b[0m  is assigned a value.  A null value evaluates\u001b[m\r\n       to 0.  A shell variable need not have its \u001b[4minteger\u001b[24m  attri‐\u001b[m\r\n       bute turned on to be used in an expression.\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n       Integer constants follow the C language definition, with‐\u001b[m\r\n       out"]
[3622.265724, "o", " suffixes or character constants.   Constants  with  a\u001b[m\r\n       leading 0 are interpreted as octal numbers.  A leading 0x\u001b[m\r\n       or 0X denotes hexadecimal.  Otherwise, numbers  take  the\u001b[m\r\n       form  [\u001b[4mbase#\u001b[24m]n, where the optional \u001b[4mbase\u001b[24m is a decimal num‐\u001b[m\r\n       ber between 2 and 64 representing  the  arithmetic  base,\u001b[m\r\n       and  \u001b[4mn\u001b[24m  is  a  number in that base.  If \u001b[4mbase#\u001b[24m is omitted,\u001b[m\r\n       then base 10 is used.  When specifying \u001b[4mn\u001b[24m, if a  non-digit\u001b[m\r\n       is required, the digits greater than 9 are represented by\u001b[m\r\n       the lowercase letters, the uppercase letters, @,  and  _,\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[7m Manual page bash(1) line 3121 (press h for help or q to quit)\u001b[27m\u001b[K"]
[3622.297634, "o", "\r\u001b[K"]
[3622.297752, "o", "       in that order.  If \u001b[4mbase\u001b[24m is less than or equal to 36, low‐\u001b[m\r\n       ercase and uppercase letters may be used  interchangeably\u001b[m\r\n       to represent numbers between 10 and 35.\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n       Operators  are evaluated in order of precedence.  Sub-ex‐\u001b[m\r\n       pressions in parentheses  are  evaluated  first  and  may\u001b[m\r\n       override the precedence rules above.\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[1mCONDITIONAL\u001b[0m \u001b[1mEXPRESSIONS\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n       Conditional  expressions are used by the \u001b[1m[[\u001b[0m compound com‐\u001b[m\r\n       mand and the \u001b[1mtest\u001b[0m and \u001b[1m[\u001b[0m builtin commands to test file at‐\u001b[m\r\n       tributes  and  perform string and arithmetic comparisons.\u001b[m\r\n       The \u001b[1mtest\u001b[0m and \u001b[1m[\u001b[0m commands determine their behavior based on\u001b[m\r\n       the  number  of  arguments; see the descriptions of those\u001b[m\r\n       commands for any other command-specific actions.\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n       Expressions are formed from the following unary or binary\u001b[m\r\n       primaries.  \u001b[1mBash\u001b[0m handles several filenames s"]
[3622.297799, "o", "pecially when\u001b[m\r\n       they are used in expressions.  If the operating system on\u001b[m\r\n       which  \u001b[1mbash\u001b[0m is running provides these special files, bash\u001b[m\r\n       will use them; otherwise it will emulate them  internally\u001b[m\r\n       with  this  behavior:  If any \u001b[4mfile\u001b[24m argument to one of the\u001b[m\r\n       primaries is of the form \u001b[4m/dev/fd/n\u001b[24m, then file  descriptor\u001b[m\r\n       \u001b[4mn\u001b[24m  is  checked.   If the \u001b[4mfile\u001b[24m argument to one of the pri‐\u001b[m\r\n       maries is one of \u001b[4m/dev/stdin\u001b[24m, \u001b[4m/dev/stdout\u001b[24m, or \u001b[4m/dev/stderr\u001b[24m,\u001b[m\r\n       file descriptor 0, 1, or 2, respectively, is checked.\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[7m Manual page bash(1) line 3147 (press h for help or q to quit)\u001b[27m\u001b[K"]
[3622.329839, "o", "\r\u001b[K"]
[3622.329989, "o", "\u001b[m\r\n       Unless  otherwise  specified,  primaries  that operate on\u001b[m\r\n       files follow symbolic links and operate on the target  of\u001b[m\r\n       the link, rather than the link itself.\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n       When  used  with  \u001b[1m[[\u001b[0m,  the \u001b[1m<\u001b[0m and \u001b[1m>\u001b[0m operators sort lexico‐\u001b[m\r\n       graphically using the current locale.  The  \u001b[1mtest\u001b[0m  command\u001b[m\r\n       sorts using ASCII ordering.\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n       \u001b[1m-a\u001b[0m \u001b[4mfile\u001b[24m\u001b[m\r\n              True if \u001b[4mfile\u001b[24m exists.\u001b[m\r\n       \u001b[1m-b\u001b[0m \u001b[4mfile\u001b[24m\u001b[m\r\n              True if \u001b[4mfile\u001b[24m exists and is a block special file.\u001b[m\r\n       \u001b[1m-c\u001b[0m \u001b[4mfile\u001b[24m\u001b[m\r\n              True  if  \u001b[4mfile\u001b[24m  exists  and is a character special\u001b[m\r\n              file.\u001b[m\r\n       \u001b[1m-d\u001b[0m \u001b[4mfile\u001b[24m\u001b[m\r\n              True if \u001b[4mfile\u001b[24m exists and is a directory.\u001b[m\r\n       \u001b[1m-e\u001b[0m \u001b[4mfile\u001b[24m\u001b[m\r\n              True if \u001b[4mfile\u001b[24m exists.\u001b[m\r\n       \u001b[1m-f\u001b[0m \u001b[4mfile\u001b[24m\u001b[m\r\n              True if \u001b[4mfile\u001b[24m exists and is a r"]
[3622.330014, "o", "egular file.\u001b[m\r\n       \u001b[1m-g\u001b[0m \u001b[4mfile\u001b[24m\u001b[m\r\n              True if \u001b[4mfile\u001b[24m exists and is set-group-id.\u001b[m\r\n       \u001b[1m-h\u001b[0m \u001b[4mfile\u001b[24m\u001b[m\r\n              True if \u001b[4mfile\u001b[24m exists and is a symbolic link.\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[7m Manual page bash(1) line 3173 (press h for help or q to quit)\u001b[27m\u001b[K"]
[3622.361539, "o", "\r\u001b[K"]
[3622.361629, "o", "       \u001b[1m-k\u001b[0m \u001b[4mfile\u001b[24m\u001b[m\r\n              True if \u001b[4mfile\u001b[24m exists and its ``sticky'' bit is set.\u001b[m\r\n       \u001b[1m-p\u001b[0m \u001b[4mfile\u001b[24m\u001b[m\r\n              True if \u001b[4mfile\u001b[24m exists and is a named pipe (FIFO).\u001b[m\r\n       \u001b[1m-r\u001b[0m \u001b[4mfile\u001b[24m\u001b[m\r\n              True if \u001b[4mfile\u001b[24m exists and is readable.\u001b[m\r\n       \u001b[1m-s\u001b[0m \u001b[4mfile\u001b[24m\u001b[m\r\n              True if \u001b[4mfile\u001b[24m exists and has a  size  greater  than\u001b[m\r\n              zero.\u001b[m\r\n       \u001b[1m-t\u001b[0m \u001b[4mfd\u001b[24m  True if file descriptor \u001b[4mfd\u001b[24m is open and refers to a\u001b[m\r\n              terminal.\u001b[m\r\n       \u001b[1m-u\u001b[0m \u001b[4mfile\u001b[24m\u001b[m\r\n              True if \u001b[4mfile\u001b[24m exists and  its  set-user-id  bit  is\u001b[m\r\n              set.\u001b[m\r\n       \u001b[1m-w\u001b[0m \u001b[4mfile\u001b[24m\u001b[m\r\n              True if \u001b[4mfile\u001b[24m exists and is writable.\u001b[m\r\n       \u001b[1m-x\u001b[0m \u001b[4mfile\u001b[24m\u001b[m\r\n              True if \u001b[4mfile\u001b[24m exists and is executable.\u001b[m\r\n       \u001b[1m-G\u001b[0m \u001b[4mfile\u001b[24m\u001b[m\r\n              True  if \u001b[4mfile\u001b[24m exists and is owned by the"]
[3622.361655, "o", " effective\u001b[m\r\n              group id.\u001b[m\r\n       \u001b[1m-L\u001b[0m \u001b[4mfile\u001b[24m\u001b[m\r\n              True if \u001b[4mfile\u001b[24m exists and is a symbolic link.\u001b[m\r\n       \u001b[1m-N\u001b[0m \u001b[4mfile\u001b[24m\u001b[m\r\n              True if \u001b[4mfile\u001b[24m exists and has been modified since it\u001b[m\r\n              was last read.\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[7m Manual page bash(1) line 3199 (press h for help or q to quit)\u001b[27m\u001b[K"]
[3622.392822, "o", "\r\u001b[K       \u001b[1m-O\u001b[0m \u001b[4mfile\u001b[24m\u001b[m\r\n              True  if \u001b[4mfile\u001b[24m exists and is owned by the effective\u001b[m\r\n              user id.\u001b[m\r\n       \u001b[1m-S\u001b[0m \u001b[4mfile\u001b[24m\u001b[m\r\n              True if \u001b[4mfile\u001b[24m exists and is a socket.\u001b[m\r\n       \u001b[4mfile1\u001b[24m \u001b[1m-ef\u001b[0m \u001b[4mfile2\u001b[24m\u001b[m\r\n              True if \u001b[4mfile1\u001b[24m and \u001b[4mfile2\u001b[24m refer to the  same  device\u001b[m\r\n              and inode numbers.\u001b[m\r\n       \u001b[4mfile1\u001b[24m -\u001b[1mnt\u001b[0m \u001b[4mfile2\u001b[24m\u001b[m\r\n              True  if \u001b[4mfile1\u001b[24m is newer (according to modification\u001b[m\r\n"]
[3622.392962, "o", "              date) than \u001b[4mfile2\u001b[24m, or if  \u001b[4mfile1\u001b[24m  exists  and  \u001b[4mfile2\u001b[24m\u001b[m\r\n              does not.\u001b[m\r\n       \u001b[4mfile1\u001b[24m -\u001b[1mot\u001b[0m \u001b[4mfile2\u001b[24m\u001b[m\r\n              True if \u001b[4mfile1\u001b[24m is older than \u001b[4mfile2\u001b[24m, or if \u001b[4mfile2\u001b[24m ex‐\u001b[m\r\n              ists and \u001b[4mfile1\u001b[24m does not.\u001b[m\r\n       \u001b[1m-o\u001b[0m \u001b[4moptname\u001b[24m\u001b[m\r\n              True if the shell option \u001b[4moptname\u001b[24m is enabled.   See\u001b[m\r\n              the  list  of options under the description of the\u001b[m\r\n              \u001b[1m-o\u001b[0m option to the \u001b[1mset\u001b[0m builtin below.\u001b[m\r\n       \u001b[1m-v\u001b[0m \u001b[4mvarname\u001b[24m\u001b[m\r\n              True if the shell variable  \u001b[4mvarname\u001b[24m  is  set  (has\u001b[m\r\n              been assigned a value).\u001b[m\r\n       \u001b[1m-R\u001b[0m \u001b[4mvarname\u001b[24m\u001b[m\r\n              True if the shell variable \u001b[4mvarname\u001b[24m is set and is a\u001b[m\r\n              name reference.\u001b[m\r\n       \u001b[1m-z\u001b[0m \u001b[4mstring\u001b[24m\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[7m Manual page bash(1) line 3225 (press h for help or q to quit)\u001b[27m\u001b[K"]
[3622.424783, "o", "\r\u001b[K"]
[3622.424917, "o", "              True if the length of \u001b[4mstring\u001b[24m is zero.\u001b[m\r\n       \u001b[4mstring\u001b[24m\u001b[m\r\n       \u001b[1m-n\u001b[0m \u001b[4mstring\u001b[24m\u001b[m\r\n              True if the length of \u001b[4mstring\u001b[24m is non-zero.\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n       \u001b[4mstring1\u001b[24m \u001b[1m==\u001b[0m \u001b[4mstring2\u001b[24m\u001b[m\r\n       \u001b[4mstring1\u001b[24m \u001b[1m=\u001b[0m \u001b[4mstring2\u001b[24m\u001b[m\r\n              True if the strings are equal.  \u001b[1m=\u001b[0m should  be  used\u001b[m\r\n              with the \u001b[1mtest\u001b[0m command for POSIX conformance.  When\u001b[m\r\n              used with the \u001b[1m[[\u001b[0m command,  this  performs  pattern\u001b[m\r\n              matching as described above (\u001b[1mCompound\u001b[0m \u001b[1mCommands\u001b[0m).\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n       \u001b[4mstring1\u001b[24m \u001b[1m!=\u001b[0m \u001b[4mstring2\u001b[24m\u001b[m\r\n              True if the strings are not equal.\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n       \u001b[4mstring1\u001b[24m \u001b[1m<\u001b[0m \u001b[4mstring2\u001b[24m\u001b[m\r\n              True if \u001b[4mstring1\u001b[24m sorts before \u001b[4mstring2\u001b[24m lexicographi‐\u001b[m\r\n              cally.\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n       \u001b[4mstring1\u001b[24m \u001b[1m>\u001b[0m \u001b[4mstring2\u001b[24m\u001b[m\r\n              True if \u001b[4mstring1\u001b[24m sorts af"]
[3622.424948, "o", "ter \u001b[4mstring2\u001b[24m  lexicographi‐\u001b[m\r\n              cally.\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n       \u001b[4marg1\u001b[24m \u001b[1mOP\u001b[0m \u001b[4marg2\u001b[24m\u001b[m\r\n              \u001b[1mOP\u001b[0m  is  one  of  \u001b[1m-eq\u001b[0m,  \u001b[1m-ne\u001b[0m, \u001b[1m-lt\u001b[0m, \u001b[1m-le\u001b[0m, \u001b[1m-gt\u001b[0m, or \u001b[1m-ge\u001b[0m.\u001b[m\r\n              These arithmetic binary operators return  true  if\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[7m Manual page bash(1) line 3251 (press h for help or q to quit)\u001b[27m\u001b[K"]
[3622.455916, "o", "\r\u001b[K"]
[3622.455945, "o", "              \u001b[4marg1\u001b[24m  is  equal  to, not equal to, less than, less\u001b[m\r\n              than or equal to, greater than, or greater than or\u001b[m\r\n              equal to \u001b[4marg2\u001b[24m, respectively.  \u001b[4mArg1\u001b[24m and \u001b[4marg2\u001b[24m may be\u001b[m\r\n              positive or negative integers.  When used with the\u001b[m\r\n              \u001b[1m[[\u001b[0m  command, \u001b[4mArg1\u001b[24m and \u001b[4mArg2\u001b[24m are evaluated as arith‐\u001b[m\r\n              metic  expressions  (see   \u001b[1mARITHMETIC\u001b[0m   \u001b[1mEVALUATION\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n              above).\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[1mSIMPLE\u001b[0m \u001b[1mCOMMAND\u001b[0m \u001b[1mEXPANSION\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n       When a simple command is executed, the shell performs the\u001b[m\r\n       following expansions, assignments, and redirections, from\u001b[m\r\n       left to right, in the following order.\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n       1.     The  words  that the parser has marked as variable\u001b[m\r\n              assignments (those preceding the command name) and\u001b[m\r\n              redirections are saved for later processing.\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n       2.     The  words  that  are  not variab"]
[3622.45595, "o", "le assignments or\u001b[m\r\n              redirections are expanded.  If  any  words  remain\u001b[m\r\n              after expansion, the first word is taken to be the\u001b[m\r\n              name of the command and the  remaining  words  are\u001b[m\r\n              the arguments.\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n       3.     Redirections  are performed as described above un‐\u001b[m\r\n              der \u001b[1mREDIRECTION\u001b[0m.\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[7m Manual page bash(1) line 3277 (press h for help or q to quit)\u001b[27m\u001b[K"]
[3622.48713, "o", "\r\u001b[K       4.     The text after the \u001b[1m=\u001b[0m in each  variable  assignment\u001b[m\r\n              undergoes  tilde  expansion,  parameter expansion,\u001b[m\r\n              command substitution,  arithmetic  expansion,  and\u001b[m\r\n              quote  removal  before being assigned to the vari‐\u001b[m\r\n              able.\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n       If no command name results, the variable assignments  af‐\u001b[m\r\n       fect  the current shell environment.  In the case of such\u001b[m\r\n       a command (one that consists only  of  assignment  state‐\u001b[m\r\n       ments  and  redirections), assignment statements are per‐\u001b[m\r\n       formed before redirections.  Otherwise, the variables are\u001b[m\r\n       added  to  the environment of the executed command and do\u001b[m\r\n       not affect the current shell environment.  If any of  the\u001b[m\r\n       assignments  attempts  to  assign  a  value to a readonly\u001b[m\r\n       variable, an error occurs, and the command exits  with  a\u001b[m\r\n       non-zero status.\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n       If  no  command name results, redirect"]
[3622.487316, "o", "ions are performed,\u001b[m\r\n       but do not affect the current shell environment.  A redi‐\u001b[m\r\n       rection  error causes the command to exit with a non-zero\u001b[m\r\n       status.\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n       If there is a command name left after  expansion,  execu‐\u001b[m\r\n       tion proceeds as described below.  Otherwise, the command\u001b[m\r\n       exits.  If one of the expansions contained a command sub‐\u001b[m\r\n       stitution,  the  exit  status  of the command is the exit\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[7m Manual page bash(1) line 3303 (press h for help or q to quit)\u001b[27m\u001b[K"]
[3622.518108, "o", "\r\u001b[K"]
[3622.518211, "o", "       status of the last command  substitution  performed.   If\u001b[m\r\n       there  were  no  command substitutions, the command exits\u001b[m\r\n       with a status of zero.\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[1mCOMMAND\u001b[0m \u001b[1mEXECUTION\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n       After a command has been split into words, if it  results\u001b[m\r\n       in  a  simple  command and an optional list of arguments,\u001b[m\r\n       the following actions are taken.\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n       If the command name contains no slashes,  the  shell  at‐\u001b[m\r\n       tempts to locate it.  If there exists a shell function by\u001b[m\r\n       that name, that function is invoked as described above in\u001b[m\r\n       \u001b[1mFUNCTIONS\u001b[0m.   If  the  name does not match a function, the\u001b[m\r\n       shell searches for it in the list of shell builtins.   If\u001b[m\r\n       a match is found, that builtin is invoked.\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n       If  the  name  is neither a shell function nor a builtin,\u001b[m\r\n       and contains no slashes, \u001b[1mbash\u001b[0m searches  each  element  of\u001b[m\r\n       the \u001b[1mPATH\u001b[0m for a directory containing an executab"]
[3622.518245, "o", "le file by\u001b[m\r\n       that name.  \u001b[1mBash\u001b[0m uses a hash table to remember  the  full\u001b[m\r\n       pathnames  of  executable  files  (see  \u001b[1mhash\u001b[0m  under \u001b[1mSHELL\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n       \u001b[1mBUILTIN\u001b[0m \u001b[1mCOMMANDS\u001b[0m below).  A full search of  the  directo‐\u001b[m\r\n       ries  in  \u001b[1mPATH\u001b[0m  is  performed  only if the command is not\u001b[m\r\n       found in the hash table.  If the search is  unsuccessful,\u001b[m\r\n       the  shell  searches  for  a defined shell function named\u001b[m\r\n       \u001b[1mcommand_not_found_handle\u001b[0m.  If that function exists, it is\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[7m Manual page bash(1) line 3329 (press h for help or q to quit)\u001b[27m\u001b[K"]
[3622.549218, "o", "\r\u001b[K       invoked  in  a  separate  execution  environment with the\u001b[m\r\n       original command and the original command's arguments  as\u001b[m\r\n       its arguments, and the function's exit status becomes the\u001b[m\r\n       exit status of that subshell.  If that  function  is  not\u001b[m\r\n       defined, the shell prints an error message and returns an\u001b[m\r\n       exit status of 127.\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n       If the search is successful, or if the command name  con‐\u001b[m\r\n       tains  one  or more slashes, the shell executes the named\u001b[m\r\n       program in a separate execution environment.  Argument  0\u001b[m\r\n       is  set to the name given, and the remaining arguments to\u001b[m\r\n       the command are set to the arguments given, if any.\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n       If this execution fails because the file is not  in  exe‐\u001b[m\r\n       cutable  format,  and  the file is not a directory, it is\u001b[m\r\n       assumed to be a \u001b[4mshell\u001b[24m \u001b[4mscript\u001b[24m,  a  file  containing  shell\u001b[m\r\n       commands,  and the shell creates a new instance of itself\u001b["]
[3622.549347, "o", "m\r\n       to execute it.  This subshell  reinitializes  itself,  so\u001b[m\r\n       that  the effect is as if a new shell had been invoked to\u001b[m\r\n       handle the script, with the exception that the  locations\u001b[m\r\n       of  commands remembered by the parent (see \u001b[1mhash\u001b[0m below un‐\u001b[m\r\n       der \u001b[1mSHELL\u001b[0m \u001b[1mBUILTIN\u001b[0m \u001b[1mCOMMANDS\u001b[0m) are retained by the child.\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n       If the program is a file beginning with \u001b[1m#!\u001b[0m, the remainder\u001b[m\r\n       of  the  first line specifies an interpreter for the pro‐\u001b[m\r\n       gram.  The shell executes the  specified  interpreter  on\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[7m Manual page bash(1) line 3355 (press h for help or q to quit)\u001b[27m\u001b[K"]
[3622.5809, "o", "\r\u001b[K"]
[3622.581002, "o", "       operating systems that do not handle this executable for‐\u001b[m\r\n       mat themselves.  The arguments to the interpreter consist\u001b[m\r\n       of  a  single optional argument following the interpreter\u001b[m\r\n       name on the first line of the program,  followed  by  the\u001b[m\r\n       name  of  the program, followed by the command arguments,\u001b[m\r\n       if any.\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[1mCOMMAND\u001b[0m \u001b[1mEXECUTION\u001b[0m \u001b[1mENVIRONMENT\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n       The shell has an \u001b[4mexecution\u001b[24m \u001b[4menvironment\u001b[24m, which consists of\u001b[m\r\n       the following:\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n       •      open  files  inherited by the shell at invocation,\u001b[m\r\n              as modified by redirections supplied to  the  \u001b[1mexec\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n              builtin\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n       •      the current working directory as set by \u001b[1mcd\u001b[0m, \u001b[1mpushd\u001b[0m,\u001b[m\r\n              or \u001b[1mpopd\u001b[0m, or inherited by the shell at invocation\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n       •      the file creation mode mask as set by \u001b[1mumask\u001b[0m or in‐\u001b[m\r\n              herited from the shell's parent\u001b[m\r\n"]
[3622.581027, "o", "\u001b[m\r\n       •      current traps set by \u001b[1mtrap\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n       •      shell  parameters that are set by variable assign‐\u001b[m\r\n              ment or with \u001b[1mset\u001b[0m or  inherited  from  the  shell's\u001b[m\r\n              parent in the environment\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[7m Manual page bash(1) line 3381 (press h for help or q to quit)\u001b[27m\u001b[K"]
[3622.612441, "o", "\r\u001b[K\u001b[m\r\n       •      shell functions defined during execution or inher‐\u001b[m\r\n              ited from the shell's parent in the environment\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n       •      options enabled at invocation (either  by  default\u001b[m\r\n              or with command-line arguments) or by \u001b[1mset\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n       •      options enabled by \u001b[1mshopt\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n       •      shell aliases defined with \u001b[1malias\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n       •      various process IDs, including those of background\u001b[m\r\n              jobs, the value of \u001b[1m$$\u001b[0m, and the value of \u001b[1mPPID\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n       When a simple command other than a builtin or shell func‐\u001b[m\r\n       tion  is to be executed, it is invoked in a separate exe‐\u001b[m\r\n       cution environment that consists of the  following.   Un‐\u001b[m\r\n       less  otherwise  noted, the values are inherited from the\u001b[m\r\n       shell.\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n       •      the shell's open files, plus any modifications and\u001b[m\r\n              additions specified by redirections to the command\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m"]
[3622.612467, "o", "\r\n       •      the current working directory\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n       •      the file creation mode mask\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[7m Manual page bash(1) line 3407 (press h for help or q to quit)\u001b[27m\u001b[K"]
[3622.642676, "o", "\r\u001b[K"]
[3622.642705, "o", "\u001b[m\r\n       •      shell  variables  and functions marked for export,\u001b[m\r\n              along with variables  exported  for  the  command,\u001b[m\r\n              passed in the environment\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n       •      traps  caught by the shell are reset to the values\u001b[m\r\n              inherited from the shell's parent, and  traps  ig‐\u001b[m\r\n              nored by the shell are ignored\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n       A command invoked in this separate environment cannot af‐\u001b[m\r\n       fect the shell's execution environment.\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n       A \u001b[4msubshell\u001b[24m is a copy of the shell process.\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n       Command substitution, commands grouped with  parentheses,\u001b[m\r\n       and asynchronous commands are invoked in a subshell envi‐\u001b[m\r\n       ronment that is a duplicate of the shell environment, ex‐\u001b[m\r\n       cept that traps caught by the shell are reset to the val‐\u001b[m\r\n       ues that the shell inherited from its parent  at  invoca‐\u001b[m\r\n       tion.   Builtin  commands  that  are invoked as part of a\u001b[m\r\n       pipeline a"]
[3622.642733, "o", "re also executed  i"]
[3622.642867, "o", "n  a  subshell  environment.\u001b[m\r\n       Changes  made  to  the subshell environment cannot affect\u001b[m\r\n       the shell's execution environment.\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n       Subshells spawned to execute  command  substitutions  in‐\u001b[m\r\n       herit  the  value of the \u001b[1m-e\u001b[0m option from the parent shell.\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[7m Manual page bash(1) line 3433 (press h for help or q to quit)\u001b[27m\u001b[K"]
[3622.674128, "o", "\r\u001b[K"]
[3622.674283, "o", "       When not in \u001b[4mposix\u001b[24m \u001b[4mmode\u001b[24m, \u001b[1mbash\u001b[0m clears the \u001b[1m-e\u001b[0m option in such\u001b[m\r\n       subshells.\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n       If  a  command  is followed by a \u001b[1m&\u001b[0m and job control is not\u001b[m\r\n       active, the default standard input for the command is the\u001b[m\r\n       empty file \u001b[4m/dev/null\u001b[24m.  Otherwise, the invoked command in‐\u001b[m\r\n       herits the file descriptors of the calling shell as modi‐\u001b[m\r\n       fied by redirections.\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[1mENVIRONMENT\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n       When a program is invoked it is given an array of strings\u001b[m\r\n       called the \u001b[4menvironment\u001b[24m.  This is  a  list  of  \u001b[4mname\u001b[24m-\u001b[4mvalue\u001b[24m\u001b[m\r\n       pairs, of the form \u001b[4mname\u001b[24m=\u001b[4mvalue\u001b[24m.\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n       The  shell  provides several ways to manipulate the envi‐\u001b[m\r\n       ronment.  On invocation, the shell scans its own environ‐\u001b[m\r\n       ment  and  creates a parameter for each name found, auto‐\u001b[m\r\n       matically marking it for \u001b[4mexport\u001b[24m to child processes.  Exe‐\u001b[m\r\n       cuted"]
[3622.674297, "o", "  commands  inherit the environment.  The \u001b[1mexport\u001b[0m and\u001b[m\r\n       \u001b[1mdeclare\u001b[0m \u001b[1m-x\u001b[0m commands allow parameters and functions to  be\u001b[m\r\n       added  to and deleted from the environment.  If the value\u001b[m\r\n       of a parameter in the environment is  modified,  the  new\u001b[m\r\n       value becomes part of the environment, replacing the old.\u001b[m\r\n       The environment inherited by any  executed  command  con‐\u001b[m\r\n       sists  of  the  shell's initial environment, whose values\u001b[m\r\n       may be modified in the shell, less any pairs  removed  by\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[7m Manual page bash(1) line 3459 (press h for help or q to quit)\u001b[27m\u001b[K"]
[3622.704923, "o", "\r\u001b[K"]
[3622.704988, "o", "       the  \u001b[1munset\u001b[0m command, plus any additions via the \u001b[1mexport\u001b[0m and\u001b[m\r\n       \u001b[1mdeclare\u001b[0m \u001b[1m-x\u001b[0m commands.\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n       The environment for any \u001b[4msimple\u001b[24m \u001b[4mcommand\u001b[24m or function may be\u001b[m\r\n       augmented  temporarily by prefixing it with parameter as‐\u001b[m\r\n       signments, as described above in \u001b[1mPARAMETERS\u001b[0m.   These  as‐\u001b[m\r\n       signment  statements  affect only the environment seen by\u001b[m\r\n       that command.\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n       If the \u001b[1m-k\u001b[0m option is set (see the \u001b[1mset\u001b[0m builtin command  be‐\u001b[m\r\n"]
[3622.705082, "o", "       low),  then  \u001b[4mall\u001b[24m  parameter assignments are placed in the\u001b[m\r\n       environment for a command, not just  those  that  precede\u001b[m\r\n       the command name.\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n       When  \u001b[1mbash\u001b[0m invokes an external command, the variable \u001b[1m_\u001b[0m is\u001b[m\r\n       set to the full filename of the  command  and  passed  to\u001b[m\r\n       that command in its environment.\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[1mEXIT\u001b[0m \u001b[1mSTATUS\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n       The  exit  status of an executed command is the value re‐\u001b[m\r\n       turned by the \u001b[4mwaitpid\u001b[24m system call or equivalent function.\u001b[m\r\n       Exit  statuses  fall  between  0  and 255, though, as ex‐\u001b[m\r\n       plained below, the shell may use values  above  125  spe‐\u001b[m\r\n       cially.   Exit  statuses from shell builtins and compound\u001b[m\r\n       commands are also limited to this range.   Under  certain\u001b[m\r\n       circumstances, the shell will use special values to indi‐\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[7m Manual page bash(1) line 3485 (press h for help or q to quit)\u001b[27m\u001b[K"]
[3622.736525, "o", "\r\u001b[K"]
[3622.7366, "o", "       cate specific failure modes.\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n       For the shell's purposes, a command which  exits  with  a\u001b[m\r\n       zero  exit  status has succeeded.  An exit status of zero\u001b[m\r\n       indicates success.   A  non-zero  exit  status  indicates\u001b[m\r\n       failure.   When a command terminates on a fatal signal \u001b[4mN\u001b[24m,\u001b[m\r\n       \u001b[1mbash\u001b[0m uses the value of 128+\u001b[4mN\u001b[24m as the exit status.\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n       If a command is not found, the child process  created  to\u001b[m\r\n       execute  it  returns  a  status  of 127.  If a command is\u001b[m\r\n       found but is not executable, the return status is 126.\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n       If a command fails because of an error  during  expansion\u001b[m\r\n       or redirection, the exit status is greater than zero.\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n       Shell  builtin  commands  return  a status of 0 (\u001b[4mtrue\u001b[24m) if\u001b[m\r\n       successful, and non-zero (\u001b[4mfalse\u001b[24m) if an error occurs while\u001b[m\r\n       they execute.  All builtins return an exit status of 2 to\u001b[m\r\n       indicate incorrect usage, genera"]
[3622.736614, "o", "lly  invalid  options  or\u001b[m\r\n       missing arguments.\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n       The  exit  status of the last command is available in the\u001b[m\r\n       special parameter $?.\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n       \u001b[1mBash\u001b[0m itself returns the exit status of the  last  command\u001b[m\r\n       executed,  unless a syntax error occurs, in which case it\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[7m Manual page bash(1) line 3511 (press h for help or q to quit)\u001b[27m\u001b[K"]
[3622.767424, "o", "\r\u001b[K"]
[3622.767451, "o", "       exits with a non-zero value.  See also the  \u001b[1mexit\u001b[0m  builtin\u001b[m\r\n       command below.\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[1mSIGNALS\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n       When \u001b[1mbash\u001b[0m is interactive, in the absence of any traps, it\u001b[m\r\n       ignores \u001b[1mSIGTERM\u001b[0m (so that \u001b[1mkill\u001b[0m \u001b[1m0\u001b[0m does not kill an interac‐\u001b[m\r\n       tive  shell),  and  \u001b[1mSIGINT\u001b[0m is caught and handled (so that\u001b[m\r\n       the \u001b[1mwait\u001b[0m builtin is interruptible).  In all  cases,  \u001b[1mbash\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n       ignores  \u001b[1mSIGQUIT\u001b[0m.   If job control is in effect, \u001b[1mbash\u001b[0m ig‐\u001b[m\r\n       nores \u001b[1mSIGTTIN\u001b[0m, \u001b[1mSIGTTOU\u001b[0m, and \u001b[1mSIGTSTP\u001b[0m.\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n       Non-builtin commands run by \u001b[1mbash\u001b[0m have signal handlers set\u001b[m\r\n       to  the  values  inherited  by the shell from its parent.\u001b[m\r\n"]
[3622.76757, "o", "       When job control is not in effect, asynchronous  commands\u001b[m\r\n       ignore  \u001b[1mSIGINT\u001b[0m and \u001b[1mSIGQUIT\u001b[0m in addition to these inherited\u001b[m\r\n       handlers.  Commands run as a result of command  substitu‐\u001b[m\r\n       tion  ignore  the  keyboard-generated job control signals\u001b[m\r\n       \u001b[1mSIGTTIN\u001b[0m, \u001b[1mSIGTTOU\u001b[0m, and \u001b[1mSIGTSTP\u001b[0m.\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n       The shell exits by default upon receipt of a \u001b[1mSIGHUP\u001b[0m.  Be‐\u001b[m\r\n       fore  exiting, an interactive shell resends the \u001b[1mSIGHUP\u001b[0m to\u001b[m\r\n       all jobs, running or stopped.  Stopped jobs are sent \u001b[1mSIG‐\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n       \u001b[1mCONT\u001b[0m  to ensure that they receive the \u001b[1mSIGHUP\u001b[0m.  To prevent\u001b[m\r\n       the shell from sending the signal to a particular job, it\u001b[m\r\n       should  be  removed  from  the jobs table with the \u001b[1mdisown\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n       builtin (see \u001b[1mSHELL\u001b[0m \u001b[1mBUILTIN\u001b[0m \u001b[1mCOMMANDS\u001b[0m below) or  marked  to\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[7m Manual page bash(1) line 3537 (press h for help or q to quit)\u001b[27m\u001b[K"]
[3622.799503, "o", "\r\u001b[K"]
[3622.799682, "o", "       not receive \u001b[1mSIGHUP\u001b[0m using \u001b[1mdisown\u001b[0m \u001b[1m-h\u001b[0m.\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n       If  the  \u001b[1mhuponexit\u001b[0m  shell option has been set with \u001b[1mshopt\u001b[0m,\u001b[m\r\n       \u001b[1mbash\u001b[0m sends a \u001b[1mSIGHUP\u001b[0m to all jobs when an interactive login\u001b[m\r\n       shell exits.\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n       If \u001b[1mbash\u001b[0m is waiting for a command to complete and receives\u001b[m\r\n       a signal for which a trap has been set, the trap will not\u001b[m\r\n       be  executed  until  the command completes.  When \u001b[1mbash\u001b[0m is\u001b[m\r\n       waiting for an asynchronous command via the \u001b[1mwait\u001b[0m builtin,\u001b[m\r\n       the  reception  of a signal for which a trap has been set\u001b[m\r\n       will cause the \u001b[1mwait\u001b[0m builtin to return immediately with an\u001b[m\r\n       exit status greater than 128, immediately after which the\u001b[m\r\n       trap is executed.\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n       When job control is not enabled, and \u001b[1mbash\u001b[0m is waiting  for\u001b[m\r\n       a foreground command to complete, the shell receives key‐\u001b[m\r\n       board-generated signals such as \u001b[1mSIGINT\u001b[0"]
[3622.799703, "o", "m (usually generated\u001b[m\r\n       by  \u001b[1m^C\u001b[0m)  that  users commonly intend to send to that com‐\u001b[m\r\n       mand.  This happens because the shell and the command are\u001b[m\r\n       in  the  same process group as the terminal, and \u001b[1m^C\u001b[0m sends\u001b[m\r\n       \u001b[1mSIGINT\u001b[0m to all processes in that process group.\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n       When \u001b[1mbash\u001b[0m is running without job control enabled and  re‐\u001b[m\r\n       ceives  \u001b[1mSIGINT\u001b[0m while waiting for a foreground command, it\u001b[m\r\n       waits until that foreground command terminates  and  then\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[7m Manual page bash(1) line 3563 (press h for help or q to quit)\u001b[27m\u001b[K"]
[3622.829869, "o", "\r\u001b[K"]
[3622.829971, "o", "       decides what to do about the \u001b[1mSIGINT\u001b[0m:\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n       1.     If  the command terminates due to the \u001b[1mSIGINT\u001b[0m, \u001b[1mbash\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n              concludes that the user meant to  end  the  entire\u001b[m\r\n              script, and acts on the \u001b[1mSIGINT\u001b[0m (e.g., by running a\u001b[m\r\n              \u001b[1mSIGINT\u001b[0m trap or exiting itself);\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n       2.     If the command does not terminate due  to  \u001b[1mSIGINT\u001b[0m,\u001b[m\r\n              the  program handled the \u001b[1mSIGINT\u001b[0m itself and did not\u001b[m\r\n              treat it as a fatal signal.  In  that  case,  \u001b[1mbash\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n              does  not  treat \u001b[1mSIGINT\u001b[0m as a fatal signal, either,\u001b[m\r\n              instead assuming that the \u001b[1mSIGINT\u001b[0m was used as  part\u001b[m\r\n              of  the  program's  normal  operation (e.g., emacs\u001b[m\r\n              uses it to abort editing commands) or deliberately\u001b[m\r\n              discarded.  However, \u001b[1mbash\u001b[0m will run any trap set on\u001b[m\r\n              \u001b[1mSIGINT\u001b[0m, as it does with any other  trapped  sig"]
[3622.830073, "o", "nal\u001b[m\r\n              it receives while it is waiting for the foreground\u001b[m\r\n              command to complete, for compatibility.\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[1mJOB\u001b[0m \u001b[1mCONTROL\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n       \u001b[4mJob\u001b[24m \u001b[4mcontrol\u001b[24m refers to the  ability  to  selectively  stop\u001b[m\r\n       (\u001b[4msuspend\u001b[24m)  the  execution  of processes and continue (\u001b[4mre‐\u001b[24m\u001b[m\r\n       \u001b[4msume\u001b[24m) their execution at a later point.  A user typically\u001b[m\r\n       employs  this  facility via an interactive interface sup‐\u001b[m\r\n       plied jointly by the operating system  kernel's  terminal\u001b[m\r\n       driver and \u001b[1mbash\u001b[0m.\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[7m Manual page bash(1) line 3589 (press h for help or q to quit)\u001b[27m\u001b[K"]
[3622.861956, "o", "\r\u001b[K"]
[3622.86208, "o", "\u001b[m\r\n       The  shell associates a \u001b[4mjob\u001b[24m with each pipeline.  It keeps\u001b[m\r\n       a table of currently executing jobs, which may be  listed\u001b[m\r\n       with  the  \u001b[1mjobs\u001b[0m  command.   When  \u001b[1mbash\u001b[0m starts a job asyn‐\u001b[m\r\n       chronously (in the \u001b[4mbackground\u001b[24m), it  prints  a  line  that\u001b[m\r\n       looks like:\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n              [1] 25647\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n       indicating  that  this  job  is job number 1 and that the\u001b[m\r\n       process ID of the last process in the pipeline associated\u001b[m\r\n       with this job is 25647.  All of the processes in a single\u001b[m\r\n       pipeline are members of the same job.  \u001b[1mBash\u001b[0m uses the  \u001b[4mjob\u001b[24m\u001b[m\r\n       abstraction as the basis for job control.\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n       To facilitate the implementation of the user interface to\u001b[m\r\n       job control, the operating system maintains the notion of\u001b[m\r\n       a  \u001b[4mcurrent\u001b[24m  \u001b[4mterminal\u001b[24m  \u001b[4mprocess\u001b[24m  \u001b[4mgroup\u001b[24m \u001b[4mID\u001b[24m.  Members of this\u001b[m\r\n       process group (processes whose proce"]
[3622.862114, "o", "ss group ID is  equal\u001b[m\r\n       to  the  current  terminal process group ID) receive key‐\u001b[m\r\n       board-generated signals such as \u001b[1mSIGINT\u001b[0m.  These  processes\u001b[m\r\n       are  said  to be in the \u001b[4mforeground\u001b[24m.  \u001b[4mBackground\u001b[24m processes\u001b[m\r\n       are those whose process group ID differs from the  termi‐\u001b[m\r\n       nal's;  such  processes  are immune to keyboard-generated\u001b[m\r\n       signals.  Only foreground processes are allowed  to  read\u001b[m\r\n       from or, if the user so specifies with stty tostop, write\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[7m Manual page bash(1) line 3615 (press h for help or q to quit)\u001b[27m\u001b[K"]
[3622.893247, "o", "\r\u001b[K"]
[3622.893423, "o", "       to the terminal.  Background processes which  attempt  to\u001b[m\r\n       read  from  (write  to when stty tostop is in effect) the\u001b[m\r\n       terminal are sent a \u001b[1mSIGTTIN\u001b[0m \u001b[1m(SIGTTOU)\u001b[0m signal by the  ker‐\u001b[m\r\n       nel's terminal driver, which, unless caught, suspends the\u001b[m\r\n       process.\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n       If the operating system on which \u001b[1mbash\u001b[0m is running supports\u001b[m\r\n       job  control, \u001b[1mbash\u001b[0m contains facilities to use it.  Typing\u001b[m\r\n       the \u001b[4msuspend\u001b[24m character (typically \u001b[1m^Z\u001b[0m, Control-Z)  while  a\u001b[m\r\n       process  is running causes that process to be stopped and\u001b[m\r\n       returns control to  \u001b[1mbash\u001b[0m.   Typing  the  \u001b[4mdelayed\u001b[24m  \u001b[4msuspend\u001b[24m\u001b[m\r\n       character (typically \u001b[1m^Y\u001b[0m, Control-Y) causes the process to\u001b[m\r\n       be stopped when it attempts to read input from the termi‐\u001b[m\r\n       nal,  and  control  to be returned to \u001b[1mbash\u001b[0m.  The user may\u001b[m\r\n       then manipulate the state of this job, using the \u001b[1mbg\u001b[0m  com‐\u001b["]
[3622.893439, "o", "m\r\n       mand  to continue it in the background, the \u001b[1mfg\u001b[0m command to\u001b[m\r\n       continue it in the foreground, or  the  \u001b[1mkill\u001b[0m  command  to\u001b[m\r\n       kill  it.  A \u001b[1m^Z\u001b[0m takes effect immediately, and has the ad‐\u001b[m\r\n       ditional side effect of causing pending output and typea‐\u001b[m\r\n       head to be discarded.\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n       There  are  a  number  of  ways  to refer to a job in the\u001b[m\r\n       shell.  The character \u001b[1m%\u001b[0m introduces  a  job  specification\u001b[m\r\n       (\u001b[4mjobspec\u001b[24m).  Job number \u001b[4mn\u001b[24m may be referred to as \u001b[1m%n\u001b[0m.  A job\u001b[m\r\n       may also be referred to using a prefix of the  name  used\u001b[m\r\n       to  start  it,  or  using a substring that appears in its\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[7m Manual page bash(1) line 3641 (press h for help or q to quit)\u001b[27m\u001b[K"]
[3622.924864, "o", "\r\u001b[K"]
[3622.924907, "o", "       command line.  For example, \u001b[1m%ce\u001b[0m refers to a  stopped  job\u001b[m\r\n       whose  command  name begins with \u001b[1mce\u001b[0m.  If a prefix matches\u001b[m\r\n       more than one job, \u001b[1mbash\u001b[0m reports an error.  Using \u001b[1m%?ce\u001b[0m, on\u001b[m\r\n       the  other  hand, refers to any job containing the string\u001b[m\r\n       \u001b[1mce\u001b[0m in its command line.  If the  substring  matches  more\u001b[m\r\n       than  one job, \u001b[1mbash\u001b[0m reports an error.  The symbols \u001b[1m%%\u001b[0m and\u001b[m\r\n       \u001b[1m%+\u001b[0m refer to the shell's notion of the \u001b[4mcurrent\u001b[24m \u001b[4mjob\u001b[24m,  which\u001b[m\r\n       is the last job stopped while it was in the foreground or\u001b[m\r\n       started in the background.  The \u001b[4mprevious\u001b[24m \u001b[4mjob\u001b[24m may be  ref‐\u001b[m\r\n       erenced  using \u001b[1m%-\u001b[0m.  If there is only a single job, \u001b[1m%+\u001b[0m and\u001b[m\r\n       \u001b[1m%-\u001b[0m can both be used to refer to that job.  In output per‐\u001b[m\r\n       taining  to  jobs (e.g., the output of the \u001b[1mjobs\u001b[0m command),\u001b[m\r\n       the current job is always flagged with a \u001b[1m+\u001b[0m, a"]
[3622.924916, "o", "nd the  pre‐\u001b[m\r\n       vious job with a \u001b[1m-\u001b[0m.  A single % (with no accompanying job\u001b[m\r\n       specification) also refers to the current job.\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n       Simply naming a job can be used  to  bring  it  into  the\u001b[m\r\n       foreground: \u001b[1m%1\u001b[0m is a synonym for \u001b[1m``fg\u001b[0m \u001b[1m%1''\u001b[0m, bringing job 1\u001b[m\r\n       from the background into the foreground.  Similarly, \u001b[1m``%1\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n       \u001b[1m&''\u001b[0m  resumes  job 1 in the background, equivalent to \u001b[1m``bg\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n       \u001b[1m%1''\u001b[0m.\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n       The shell  learns  immediately  whenever  a  job  changes\u001b[m\r\n       state.  Normally, \u001b[1mbash\u001b[0m waits until it is about to print a\u001b[m\r\n       prompt before reporting changes in a job's status  so  as\u001b[m\r\n       to  not  interrupt any other output.  If the \u001b[1m-b\u001b[0m option to\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[7m Manual page bash(1) line 3667 (press h for help or q to quit)\u001b[27m\u001b[K"]
[3622.955794, "o", "\r\u001b[K       the \u001b[1mset\u001b[0m builtin command is  enabled,  \u001b[1mbash\u001b[0m  reports  such\u001b[m\r\n       changes immediately.  Any trap on \u001b[1mSIGCHLD\u001b[0m is executed for\u001b[m\r\n       each child that exits.\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n       If an attempt to exit \u001b[1mbash\u001b[0m is made while jobs are stopped\u001b[m\r\n       (or, if the \u001b[1mcheckjobs\u001b[0m shell option has been enabled using\u001b[m\r\n       the \u001b[1mshopt\u001b[0m builtin, running), the shell prints  a  warning\u001b[m\r\n       message,  and,  if the \u001b[1mcheckjobs\u001b[0m option is enabled, lists\u001b[m\r\n       the jobs and their statuses.  The \u001b[1mjobs\u001b[0m command  may  then\u001b[m\r\n       be  used to inspect their status.  If a second attempt to\u001b[m\r\n       exit is made without an intervening  command,  the  shell\u001b[m\r\n       does  not print another warning, and any stopped jobs are\u001b[m\r\n       terminated.\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n       When the shell is waiting for a job or process using  the\u001b[m\r\n       \u001b[1mwait\u001b[0m  builtin,  and job control is enabled, \u001b[1mwait\u001b[0m will re‐\u001b[m\r\n       turn when the job changes state.  Th"]
[3622.95583, "o", "e  \u001b[1m-f\u001b[0m  option  causes\u001b[m\r\n       \u001b[1mwait\u001b[0m  to  wait until the job or process terminates before\u001b[m\r\n       returning.\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[1mPROMPTING\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n       When executing interactively, \u001b[1mbash\u001b[0m displays  the  primary\u001b[m\r\n       prompt  \u001b[1mPS1\u001b[0m  when  it is ready to read a command, and the\u001b[m\r\n       secondary prompt \u001b[1mPS2\u001b[0m when it needs more input to complete\u001b[m\r\n       a  command.   \u001b[1mBash\u001b[0m  displays \u001b[1mPS0\u001b[0m after it reads a command\u001b[m\r\n       but before executing it.  \u001b[1mBash\u001b[0m displays \u001b[1mPS4\u001b[0m as  described\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[7m Manual page bash(1) line 3693 (press h for help or q to quit)\u001b[27m\u001b[K"]
[3622.987199, "o", "\r\u001b[K       above  before  tracing each command when the \u001b[1m-x\u001b[0m option is\u001b[m\r\n       enabled.  \u001b[1mBash\u001b[0m allows these prompt strings to be  custom‐\u001b[m\r\n       ized  by  inserting a number of backslash-escaped special\u001b[m\r\n       characters that are decoded as follows:\u001b[m\r\n              \u001b[1m\\a\u001b[0m     an ASCII bell character (07)\u001b[m\r\n              \u001b[1m\\d\u001b[0m     the date in  \"Weekday  Month  Date\"  format\u001b[m\r\n                     (e.g., \"Tue May 26\")\u001b[m\r\n              \u001b[1m\\D{\u001b[0m\u001b[4mformat\u001b[24m\u001b[1m}\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n                     the \u001b[4mformat\u001b[24m is passed to \u001b[4mstrftime\u001b[24m(3) and the\u001b[m\r\n                     result is inserted into the prompt  string;\u001b[m\r\n                     an  empty  \u001b[4mformat\u001b[24m  results in a locale-spe‐\u001b[m\r\n                     cific time representation.  The braces  are\u001b[m\r\n                     required\u001b[m\r\n              \u001b[1m\\e\u001b[0m     an ASCII escape character (033)\u001b[m\r\n              \u001b[1m\\h\u001b[0m     the hostname up to the first `.'\u001b[m\r\n              \u001b[1m\\H\u001b[0m     the ho"]
[3622.987225, "o", "stname\u001b[m\r\n        "]
[3622.987247, "o", "      \u001b[1m\\j\u001b[0m     the number of jobs currently managed by the\u001b[m\r\n                     shell\u001b[m\r\n              \u001b[1m\\l\u001b[0m     the basename of the shell's terminal device\u001b[m\r\n                     name\u001b[m\r\n              \u001b[1m\\n\u001b[0m     newline\u001b[m\r\n              \u001b[1m\\r\u001b[0m     carriage return\u001b[m\r\n              \u001b[1m\\s\u001b[0m     the  name  of the shell, the basename of \u001b[1m$0\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n                     (the portion following the final slash)\u001b[m\r\n              \u001b[1m\\t\u001b[0m     the current time in 24-hour HH:MM:SS format\u001b[m\r\n              \u001b[1m\\T\u001b[0m     the current time in 12-hour HH:MM:SS format\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[7m Manual page bash(1) line 3719 (press h for help or q to quit)\u001b[27m\u001b[K"]
[3623.019055, "o", "\r\u001b[K"]
[3623.019169, "o", "              \u001b[1m\\@\u001b[0m     the current time in 12-hour am/pm format\u001b[m\r\n              \u001b[1m\\A\u001b[0m     the current time in 24-hour HH:MM format\u001b[m\r\n              \u001b[1m\\u\u001b[0m     the username of the current user\u001b[m\r\n              \u001b[1m\\v\u001b[0m     the version of \u001b[1mbash\u001b[0m (e.g., 2.00)\u001b[m\r\n              \u001b[1m\\V\u001b[0m     the release of \u001b[1mbash\u001b[0m, version + patch  level\u001b[m\r\n                     (e.g., 2.00.0)\u001b[m\r\n              \u001b[1m\\w\u001b[0m     the value of the \u001b[1mPWD\u001b[0m shell variable (\u001b[1m$PWD\u001b[0m),\u001b[m\r\n                     with \u001b[1m$HOME\u001b[0m abbreviated with a  tilde  (uses\u001b[m\r\n                     the value of the \u001b[1mPROMPT_DIRTRIM\u001b[0m variable)\u001b[m\r\n              \u001b[1m\\W\u001b[0m     the  basename  of \u001b[1m$PWD\u001b[0m, with \u001b[1m$HOME\u001b[0m abbrevi‐\u001b[m\r\n                     ated with a tilde\u001b[m\r\n              \u001b[1m\\!\u001b[0m     the history number of this command\u001b[m\r\n              \u001b[1m\\#\u001b[0m     the command number of this command\u001b[m\r\n              \u001b[1m\\$\u001b[0m     if the effective UID is 0, a \u001b[1m#\u001b[0m, otherwise a\u001b[m\r\n       "]
[3623.019189, "o", "              \u001b[1m$\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n              \u001b[1m\\\u001b[0m\u001b[4mnnn\u001b[24m   the  character  corresponding  to the octal\u001b[m\r\n                     number \u001b[4mnnn\u001b[24m\u001b[m\r\n              \u001b[1m\\\\\u001b[0m     a backslash\u001b[m\r\n              \u001b[1m\\[\u001b[0m     begin a sequence  of  non-printing  charac‐\u001b[m\r\n                     ters, which could be used to embed a termi‐\u001b[m\r\n                     nal control sequence into the prompt\u001b[m\r\n              \u001b[1m\\]\u001b[0m     end a sequence of non-printing characters\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n       The command number and the  history  number  are  usually\u001b[m\r\n       different:  the  history number of a command is its posi‐\u001b[m\r\n       tion in the history list, which may include commands  re‐\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[7m Manual page bash(1) line 3745 (press h for help or q to quit)\u001b[27m\u001b[K"]
[3623.050044, "o", "\r\u001b[K"]
[3623.050178, "o", "       stored  from  the history file (see \u001b[1mHISTORY\u001b[0m below), while\u001b[m\r\n       the command number is the position  in  the  sequence  of\u001b[m\r\n       commands  executed during the current shell session.  Af‐\u001b[m\r\n       ter the string is decoded, it is expanded  via  parameter\u001b[m\r\n       expansion,  command  substitution,  arithmetic expansion,\u001b[m\r\n       and quote removal, subject to the value of the \u001b[1mpromptvars\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n       shell  option  (see  the description of the \u001b[1mshopt\u001b[0m command\u001b[m\r\n       under \u001b[1mSHELL\u001b[0m \u001b[1mBUILTIN\u001b[0m \u001b[1mCOMMANDS\u001b[0m below).  This can  have  un‐\u001b[m\r\n       wanted side effects if escaped portions of the string ap‐\u001b[m\r\n       pear within command substitution  or  contain  characters\u001b[m\r\n       special to word expansion.\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[1mREADLINE\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n       This is the library that handles reading input when using\u001b[m\r\n       an interactive shell, unless the  \u001b[1m--noediting\u001b[0m  option  is\u001b[m\r\n       given  at  shell  invocation.   Line editing is also used\u001b[m\r\n "]
[3623.050195, "o", "      when using the \u001b[1m-e\u001b[0m option to the  \u001b[1mread\u001b[0m  builtin.   By  de‐\u001b[m\r\n       fault,  the line editing commands are similar to those of\u001b[m\r\n       Emacs.  A vi-style line editing interface is also  avail‐\u001b[m\r\n       able.   Line editing can be enabled at any time using the\u001b[m\r\n       \u001b[1m-o\u001b[0m \u001b[1memacs\u001b[0m or \u001b[1m-o\u001b[0m \u001b[1mvi\u001b[0m options to the \u001b[1mset\u001b[0m builtin  (see  \u001b[1mSHELL\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n       \u001b[1mBUILTIN\u001b[0m  \u001b[1mCOMMANDS\u001b[0m below).  To turn off line editing after\u001b[m\r\n       the shell is running, use the \u001b[1m+o\u001b[0m \u001b[1memacs\u001b[0m or \u001b[1m+o\u001b[0m  \u001b[1mvi\u001b[0m  options\u001b[m\r\n       to the \u001b[1mset\u001b[0m builtin.\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n   \u001b[1mReadline\u001b[0m \u001b[1mNotation\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[7m Manual page bash(1) line 3771 (press h for help or q to quit)\u001b[27m\u001b[K"]
[3623.081622, "o", "\r\u001b[K"]
[3623.081714, "o", "       In  this section, the Emacs-style notation is used to de‐\u001b[m\r\n       note keystrokes.  Control  keys  are  denoted  by  C-\u001b[4mkey\u001b[24m,\u001b[m\r\n       e.g.,  C-n means Control-N.  Similarly, \u001b[4mmeta\u001b[24m keys are de‐\u001b[m\r\n       noted by M-\u001b[4mkey\u001b[24m, so M-x means Meta-X.  (On keyboards with‐\u001b[m\r\n       out  a  \u001b[4mmeta\u001b[24m key, M-\u001b[4mx\u001b[24m means ESC \u001b[4mx\u001b[24m, i.e., press the Escape\u001b[m\r\n       key then the \u001b[4mx\u001b[24m key.  This makes ESC the \u001b[4mmeta\u001b[24m \u001b[4mprefix\u001b[24m.  The\u001b[m\r\n       combination  M-C-\u001b[4mx\u001b[24m  means ESC-Control-\u001b[4mx\u001b[24m, or press the Es‐\u001b[m\r\n       cape key then hold the Control key while pressing  the  \u001b[4mx\u001b[24m\u001b[m\r\n       key.)\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n       Readline  commands  may be given numeric \u001b[4marguments\u001b[24m, which\u001b[m\r\n       normally act as a repeat count.  Sometimes,  however,  it\u001b[m\r\n       is the sign of the argument that is significant.  Passing\u001b[m\r\n       a negative argument to a command that acts in the forward\u001b[m\r\n       direction (e.g., \u001b[1mkill-line\u001b[0m) causes"]
[3623.081762, "o", " that command to act in\u001b[m\r\n       a backward direction.  Commands whose behavior with argu‐\u001b[m\r\n       ments deviates from this are noted below.\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n       When  a  command  is  described as \u001b[4mkilling\u001b[24m text, the text\u001b[m\r\n       deleted is saved for possible future retrieval (\u001b[4myanking\u001b[24m).\u001b[m\r\n       The  killed  text  is  saved in a \u001b[4mkill\u001b[24m \u001b[4mring\u001b[24m.  Consecutive\u001b[m\r\n       kills cause the text to be  accumulated  into  one  unit,\u001b[m\r\n       which  can  be yanked all at once.  Commands which do not\u001b[m\r\n       kill text separate the chunks of text on the kill ring.\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n   \u001b[1mReadline\u001b[0m \u001b[1mInitialization\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[7m Manual page bash(1) line 3797 (press h for help or q to quit)\u001b[27m\u001b[K"]
[3623.113037, "o", "\r\u001b[K"]
[3623.113142, "o", "       Readline is customized by putting commands in an initial‐\u001b[m\r\n       ization  file  (the \u001b[4minputrc\u001b[24m file).  The name of this file\u001b[m\r\n       is taken from the value of the \u001b[1mINPUTRC\u001b[0m variable.  If that\u001b[m\r\n       variable  is  unset,  the default is \u001b[4m~/.inputrc\u001b[24m.  If that\u001b[m\r\n       file  does not exist or cannot be read, the ultimate  de‐\u001b[m\r\n       fault  is  \u001b[4m/etc/inputrc\u001b[24m.   When  a program which uses the\u001b[m\r\n       readline library starts up, the  initialization  file  is\u001b[m\r\n       read,  and the key bindings and variables are set.  There\u001b[m\r\n       are only a few basic constructs allowed in  the  readline\u001b[m\r\n       initialization file.  Blank lines are ignored.  Lines be‐\u001b[m\r\n       ginning with a \u001b[1m#\u001b[0m are comments.  Lines beginning with a  \u001b[1m$\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n       indicate  conditional constructs.  Other lines denote key\u001b[m\r\n       bindings and variable settings.\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n       The default key-bindings may be changed with  an  \u001b[4minputrc\u001b[24m\u001b[m\r\n       file. "]
[3623.113164, "o", " Other programs that use this library may add their\u001b[m\r\n       own commands and bindings.\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n       For example, placing\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n              M-Control-u: universal-argument\u001b[m\r\n       or\u001b[m\r\n              C-Meta-u: universal-argument\u001b[m\r\n       into the \u001b[4minputrc\u001b[24m would make M-C-u  execute  the  readline\u001b[m\r\n       command \u001b[4muniversal-argument\u001b[24m.\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[7m Manual page bash(1) line 3823 (press h for help or q to quit)\u001b[27m\u001b[K"]
[3623.144001, "o", "\r\u001b[K"]
[3623.144104, "o", "       The  following  symbolic  character names are recognized:\u001b[m\r\n       \u001b[4mRUBOUT\u001b[24m, \u001b[4mDEL\u001b[24m, \u001b[4mESC\u001b[24m, \u001b[4mLFD\u001b[24m, \u001b[4mNEWLINE\u001b[24m, \u001b[4mRET\u001b[24m, \u001b[4mRETURN\u001b[24m, \u001b[4mSPC\u001b[24m,  \u001b[4mSPACE\u001b[24m,\u001b[m\r\n       and \u001b[4mTAB\u001b[24m.\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n       In  addition to command names, readline allows keys to be\u001b[m\r\n       bound to a string  that  is  inserted  when  the  key  is\u001b[m\r\n       pressed (a \u001b[4mmacro\u001b[24m).\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n   \u001b[1mReadline\u001b[0m \u001b[1mKey\u001b[0m \u001b[1mBindings\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n       The  syntax  for  controlling key bindings in the \u001b[4minputrc\u001b[24m\u001b[m\r\n       file is simple.  All that is required is the name of  the\u001b[m\r\n       command  or  the  text  of  a macro and a key sequence to\u001b[m\r\n       which it should be bound.  The name may be  specified  in\u001b[m\r\n       one  of  two  ways: as a symbolic key name, possibly with\u001b[m\r\n       \u001b[4mMeta-\u001b[24m or \u001b[4mControl-\u001b[24m prefixes, or as a key sequence.\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n       When using the form \u001b[1mkeyname\u001b[0m:\u001b[4mfunction-name\u001b[24m or \u001b[4mmacro\u001b[24m,  \u001b[4mkey‐\u001b["]
[3623.144121, "o", "24m\u001b[m\r\n       \u001b[4mname\u001b[24m  is  the  name of a key spelled out in English.  For\u001b[m\r\n       example:\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n              Control-u: universal-argument\u001b[m\r\n              Meta-Rubout: backward-kill-word\u001b[m\r\n              Control-o: \"> output\"\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n       In the above example, \u001b[4mC-u\u001b[24m is bound to the  function  \u001b[1muni‐\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n       \u001b[1mversal-argument\u001b[0m,  \u001b[4mM-DEL\u001b[24m  is  bound  to the function \u001b[1mback‐\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[7m Manual page bash(1) line 3849 (press h for help or q to quit)\u001b[27m\u001b[K"]
[3623.175676, "o", "\r\u001b[K"]
[3623.175723, "o", "       \u001b[1mward-kill-word\u001b[0m, and \u001b[4mC-o\u001b[24m is bound to  run  the  macro  ex‐\u001b[m\r\n       pressed  on  the  right hand side (that is, to insert the\u001b[m\r\n       text ``> output'' into the line).\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n       In the second form, \u001b[1m\"keyseq\"\u001b[0m:\u001b[4mfunction-name\u001b[24m or \u001b[4mmacro\u001b[24m, \u001b[1mkey‐\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n       \u001b[1mseq\u001b[0m  differs  from \u001b[1mkeyname\u001b[0m above in that strings denoting\u001b[m\r\n       an entire key sequence may be specified  by  placing  the\u001b[m\r\n       sequence  within double quotes.  Some GNU Emacs style key\u001b[m\r\n       escapes can be used, as in the following example, but the\u001b[m\r\n       symbolic character names are not recognized.\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n              \"\\C-u\": universal-argument\u001b[m\r\n              \"\\C-x\\C-r\": re-read-init-file\u001b[m\r\n              \"\\e[11~\": \"Function Key 1\"\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n       In  this example, \u001b[4mC-u\u001b[24m is again bound to the function \u001b[1muni‐\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n       \u001b[1mversal-argument\u001b[0m.   \u001b[4mC-x\u001b[24m  \u001b[4mC-r\u001b[24m  is  bound  to  the  function\u001b[m\r\n       \u001b[1mre-read-init-file\u001b[0m,"]
[3623.175733, "o", " and \u001b[4mESC\u001b[24"]
[3623.175756, "o", "m \u001b[4m[\u001b[24m \u001b[4m1\u001b[24m \u001b[4m1\u001b[24m \u001b[4m~\u001b[24m is bound to insert the\u001b[m\r\n       text ``Function Key 1''.\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n       The full set of GNU Emacs style escape sequences is\u001b[m\r\n              \u001b[1m\\C-\u001b[0m    control prefix\u001b[m\r\n              \u001b[1m\\M-\u001b[0m    meta prefix\u001b[m\r\n              \u001b[1m\\e\u001b[0m     an escape character\u001b[m\r\n              \u001b[1m\\\\\u001b[0m     backslash\u001b[m\r\n              \u001b[1m\\\"\u001b[0m     literal \"\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[7m Manual page bash(1) line 3875 (press h for help or q to quit)\u001b[27m\u001b[K"]
[3623.207282, "o", "\r\u001b[K              \u001b[1m\\'\u001b[0m     literal '\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n       In addition to the GNU Emacs style  escape  sequences,  a\u001b[m\r\n       second set of backslash escapes is available:\u001b[m\r\n              \u001b[1m\\a\u001b[0m     alert (bell)\u001b[m\r\n              \u001b[1m\\b\u001b[0m     backspace\u001b[m\r\n              \u001b[1m\\d\u001b[0m     delete\u001b[m\r\n              \u001b[1m\\f\u001b[0m     form feed\u001b[m\r\n              \u001b[1m\\n\u001b[0m     newline\u001b[m\r\n              \u001b[1m\\r\u001b[0m     carriage return\u001b[m\r\n              \u001b[1m\\t\u001b[0m     horizontal tab\u001b[m\r\n              \u001b[1m\\v\u001b[0m     vertical tab\u001b[m\r\n              \u001b[1m\\\u001b[0m\u001b[4mnnn\u001b[24m   the  eight-bit character whose value is the\u001b[m\r\n                     octal value \u001b[4mnnn\u001b[24m (one to three digits)\u001b[m\r\n              \u001b[1m\\x\u001b[0m\u001b[4mHH\u001b[24m   the eight-bit character whose value is  the\u001b[m\r\n                     hexadecimal  value  \u001b[4mHH\u001b[24m (one or two hex dig‐\u001b[m\r\n                     its)\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n       When entering the text  of  a  macro,  single  or  double\u001b[m\r\n       quotes  must be used to indicate a macro definition.  U"]
[3623.207315, "o", "n‐\u001b[m\r\n       quoted text is assumed to be a  function  name.   In  the\u001b[m\r\n       macro body, the backslash escapes described above are ex‐\u001b[m\r\n       panded.  Backslash will quote any other character in  the\u001b[m\r\n       macro text, including \" and '.\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n       \u001b[1mBash\u001b[0m  allows the current readline key bindings to be dis‐\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[7m Manual page bash(1) line 3901 (press h for help or q to quit)\u001b[27m\u001b[K"]
[3623.238645, "o", "\r\u001b[K"]
[3623.238735, "o", "       played or modified with the \u001b[1mbind\u001b[0m  builtin  command.   The\u001b[m\r\n       editing  mode  may  be switched during interactive use by\u001b[m\r\n       using the \u001b[1m-o\u001b[0m option to the \u001b[1mset\u001b[0m builtin command (see \u001b[1mSHELL\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n       \u001b[1mBUILTIN\u001b[0m \u001b[1mCOMMANDS\u001b[0m below).\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n   \u001b[1mReadline\u001b[0m \u001b[1mVariables\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n       Readline  has  variables that can be used to further cus‐\u001b[m\r\n       tomize its behavior.  A variable may be set in the  \u001b[4minpu‐\u001b[24m\u001b[m\r\n       \u001b[4mtrc\u001b[24m file with a statement of the form\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n              \u001b[1mset\u001b[0m \u001b[4mvariable-name\u001b[24m \u001b[4mvalue\u001b[24m\u001b[m\r\n       or using the \u001b[1mbind\u001b[0m builtin command (see \u001b[1mSHELL\u001b[0m \u001b[1mBUILTIN\u001b[0m \u001b[1mCOM‐\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n       \u001b[1mMANDS\u001b[0m below).\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n       Except where noted, readline variables can take the  val‐\u001b[m\r\n       ues  \u001b[1mOn\u001b[0m  or  \u001b[1mOff\u001b[0m  (without regard to case).  Unrecognized\u001b[m\r\n       variable names are ignored.  When  a  variable  value  is\u001b[m\r\n       read,  empty or null values, \"o"]
[3623.238757, "o", "n\" (case-insensitive), and\u001b[m\r\n       \"1\" are equivalent to \u001b[1mOn\u001b[0m.  All other values  are  equiva‐\u001b[m\r\n       lent to \u001b[1mOff\u001b[0m.  The variables and their default values are:\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n       \u001b[1mactive-region-start-color\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n              A string variable that controls the text color and\u001b[m\r\n              background when displaying the text in the  active\u001b[m\r\n              region  (see  the description of \u001b[1menable-active-re‐\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n              \u001b[1mgion\u001b[0m below).  This string must  not  take  up  any\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[7m Manual page bash(1) line 3927 (press h for help or q to quit)\u001b[27m\u001b[K"]
[3623.269721, "o", "\r\u001b[K"]
[3623.269807, "o", "              physical character positions on the display, so it\u001b[m\r\n              should consist only of terminal escape  sequences.\u001b[m\r\n              It is output to the terminal before displaying the\u001b[m\r\n              text in the active region.  This variable is reset\u001b[m\r\n              to  the  default  value whenever the terminal type\u001b[m\r\n              changes.  The default value  is  the  string  that\u001b[m\r\n              puts  the  terminal  in standout mode, as obtained\u001b[m\r\n              from the terminal's terminfo description.  A  sam‐\u001b[m\r\n              ple value might be \"\\e[01;33m\".\u001b[m\r\n       \u001b[1mactive-region-end-color\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n              A string variable that \"undoes\" the effects of \u001b[1mac‐\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n              \u001b[1mtive-region-start-color\u001b[0m and restores \"normal\" ter‐\u001b[m\r\n              minal  display appearance after displaying text in\u001b[m\r\n              the active region.  This string must not  take  up\u001b[m\r\n              any  physical  character positions on the display,\u001b[m\r\n"]
[3623.26988, "o", "              so it should consist only of terminal  escape  se‐\u001b[m\r\n              quences.   It is output to the terminal after dis‐\u001b[m\r\n              playing the text in the active region.  This vari‐\u001b[m\r\n              able  is  reset  to the default value whenever the\u001b[m\r\n              terminal type changes.  The default value  is  the\u001b[m\r\n              string  that  restores  the terminal from standout\u001b[m\r\n              mode, as obtained from the terminal's terminfo de‐\u001b[m\r\n              scription.  A sample value might be \"\\e[0m\".\u001b[m\r\n       \u001b[1mbell-style\u001b[0m \u001b[1m(audible)\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n"]
[3623.269897, "o", "              Controls  what happens when readline wants to ring\u001b[m\r\n              the terminal bell.  If set to \u001b[1mnone\u001b[0m, readline never\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[7m Manual page bash(1) line 3953 (press h for help or q to quit)\u001b[27m\u001b[K"]
[3623.306304, "o", "\r\u001b[K              rings  the bell.  If set to \u001b[1mvisible\u001b[0m, readline uses\u001b[m\r\n              a visible bell if one is available.  If set to \u001b[1mau‐\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n              \u001b[1mdible\u001b[0m,  readline  attempts  to ring the terminal's\u001b[m\r\n              bell.\u001b[m\r\n       \u001b[1mbind-tty-special-chars\u001b[0m \u001b[1m(On)\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n              If set to \u001b[1mOn\u001b[0m, readline attempts to bind  the  con‐\u001b[m\r\n              trol  characters treated specially by the kernel's\u001b[m\r\n              terminal driver to their readline equivalents.\u001b[m\r\n       \u001b[1mblink-matching-paren\u001b[0m \u001b[1m(Off)\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n              If set to \u001b[1mOn\u001b[0m, readline attempts  to  briefly  move\u001b[m\r\n              the  cursor to an opening parenthesis when a clos‐\u001b[m\r\n              ing parenthesis is inserted.\u001b[m\r\n       \u001b[1mcolored-completion-prefix\u001b[0m \u001b[1m(Off)\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n              If set to \u001b[1mOn\u001b[0m, when listing  completions,  readline\u001b[m\r\n              displays  the common prefix of the set of possible\u001b[m\r\n              completions using a differe"]
[3623.306341, "o", "nt  color.   The  color\u001b[m\r\n              definitions  are  taken  from  the  value  of  the\u001b[m\r\n              \u001b[1mLS_COLORS\u001b[0m environment variable.   If  there  is  a\u001b[m\r\n              color definition in \u001b[1m$LS_COLORS\u001b[0m for the custom suf‐\u001b[m\r\n              fix \"readline-colored-completion-prefix\", readline\u001b[m\r\n              uses  this  color for the common prefix instead of\u001b[m\r\n              its default.\u001b[m\r\n       \u001b[1mcolored-stats\u001b[0m \u001b[1m(Off)\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n              If set to \u001b[1mOn\u001b[0m, readline displays  possible  comple‐\u001b[m\r\n              tions  using  different  colors  to indicate their\u001b[m\r\n              file type.  The color definitions are  taken  from\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[7m Manual page bash(1) line 3979 (press h for help or q to quit)\u001b[27m\u001b[K"]
[3623.331978, "o", "\r\u001b[K              the value of the \u001b[1mLS_COLORS\u001b[0m environment variable.\u001b[m\r\n       \u001b[1mcomment-begin\u001b[0m \u001b[1m(``#'')\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n              The  string that is inserted when the readline \u001b[1min‐\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n              \u001b[1msert-comment\u001b[0m command is executed.  This command is\u001b[m\r\n              bound  to \u001b[1mM-#\u001b[0m in emacs mode and to \u001b[1m#\u001b[0m in vi command\u001b[m\r\n              mode.\u001b[m\r\n       \u001b[1mcompletion-display-width\u001b[0m \u001b[1m(-1)\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n              The number of screen columns used to display  pos‐\u001b[m\r\n              sible  matches  when  performing  completion.  The\u001b[m\r\n              value is ignored if it is less than 0  or  greater\u001b[m\r\n              than the terminal screen width.  A value of 0 will\u001b[m\r\n              cause matches to be displayed one per  line.   The\u001b[m\r\n              default value is -1.\u001b[m\r\n       \u001b[1mcompletion-ignore-case\u001b[0m \u001b[1m(Off)\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n              If  set to \u001b[1mOn\u001b[0m, readline performs filename matching\u001b[m\r\n              and completion in a case-insensitive fash"]
[3623.332002, "o", "ion.\u001b[m\r\n       \u001b[1"]
[3623.332007, "o", "mcompletion-map-case\u001b[0m \u001b[1m(Off)\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n              If set to \u001b[1mOn\u001b[0m, and  \u001b[1mcompletion-ignore-case\u001b[0m  is  en‐\u001b[m\r\n              abled, readline treats hyphens (\u001b[4m-\u001b[24m) and underscores\u001b[m\r\n              (\u001b[1m_\u001b[0m) as equivalent when performing case-insensitive\u001b[m\r\n              filename matching and completion.\u001b[m\r\n       \u001b[1mcompletion-prefix-display-length\u001b[0m \u001b[1m(0)\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n              The length in characters of the common prefix of a\u001b[m\r\n              list of possible  completions  that  is  displayed\u001b[m\r\n              without modification.  When set to a value greater\u001b[m\r\n              than zero, common prefixes longer than this  value\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[7m Manual page bash(1) line 4005 (press h for help or q to quit)\u001b[27m\u001b[K"]
[3623.363697, "o", "\r\u001b[K              are replaced with an ellipsis when displaying pos‐\u001b[m\r\n              sible completions.\u001b[m\r\n       \u001b[1mcompletion-query-items\u001b[0m \u001b[1m(100)\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n              This determines when the  user  is  queried  about\u001b[m\r\n              viewing  the number of possible completions gener‐\u001b[m\r\n              ated by the \u001b[1mpossible-completions\u001b[0m command.  It  may\u001b[m\r\n              be  set to any integer value greater than or equal\u001b[m\r\n              to zero.  If the number of possible completions is\u001b[m\r\n              greater  than  or equal to the value of this vari‐\u001b[m\r\n              able, readline will ask whether or  not  the  user\u001b[m\r\n              wishes  to  view  them;  otherwise they are simply\u001b[m\r\n              listed on the terminal.  A zero value means  read‐\u001b[m\r\n              line should never ask; negative values are treated\u001b[m\r\n              as zero.\u001b[m\r\n       \u001b[1mconvert-meta\u001b[0m \u001b[1m(On)\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n              If set to \u001b[1mOn\u001b[0m,  readline  will  convert  characters\u001b[m\r\n   "]
[3623.363719, "o", "           with  the  eighth bit set to an ASCII key sequence\u001b[m\r\n              by stripping the eighth bit and prefixing  an  es‐\u001b[m\r\n              cape  character  (in  effect,  using escape as the\u001b[m\r\n              \u001b[4mmeta\u001b[24m \u001b[4mprefix\u001b[24m).  The default  is  \u001b[4mOn\u001b[24m,  but  readline\u001b[m\r\n              will  set  it to \u001b[4mOff\u001b[24m if the locale contains eight-\u001b[m\r\n              bit characters.  This variable is dependent on the\u001b[m\r\n              \u001b[1mLC_CTYPE\u001b[0m  locale  category,  and may change if the\u001b[m\r\n              locale is changed.\u001b[m\r\n       \u001b[1mdisable-completion\u001b[0m \u001b[1m(Off)\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n              If set to \u001b[1mOn\u001b[0m, readline will inhibit  word  comple‐\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[7m Manual page bash(1) line 4031 (press h for help or q to quit)\u001b[27m\u001b[K"]
[3623.395681, "o", "\r\u001b[K"]
[3623.395956, "o", "              tion.  Completion characters will be inserted into\u001b[m\r\n              the line as if they had been  mapped  to  \u001b[1mself-in‐\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n              \u001b[1msert\u001b[0m.\u001b[m\r\n       \u001b[1mecho-control-characters\u001b[0m \u001b[1m(On)\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n              When set to \u001b[1mOn\u001b[0m, on operating systems that indicate\u001b[m\r\n              they support it, readline echoes a character  cor‐\u001b[m\r\n              responding  to  a  signal  generated from the key‐\u001b[m\r\n              board.\u001b[m\r\n       \u001b[1mediting-mode\u001b[0m \u001b[1m(emacs)\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n              Controls whether readline begins with a set of key\u001b[m\r\n              bindings similar to \u001b[4mEmacs\u001b[24m or \u001b[4mvi\u001b[24m.  \u001b[1mediting-mode\u001b[0m can\u001b[m\r\n              be set to either \u001b[1memacs\u001b[0m or \u001b[1mvi\u001b[0m.\u001b[m\r\n       \u001b[1memacs-mode-string\u001b[0m \u001b[1m(@)\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n              If the \u001b[4mshow-mode-in-prompt\u001b[24m  variable  is  enabled,\u001b[m\r\n              this  string  is  displayed immediately before the\u001b[m\r\n              last line of the primary prompt when emacs editing\u001b[m\r\n   "]
[3623.395978, "o", "           mode  is active.  The value is expanded like a key\u001b[m\r\n              binding, so the standard set of meta- and  control\u001b[m\r\n              prefixes  and backslash escape sequences is avail‐\u001b[m\r\n              able.  Use the \\1 and \\2 escapes to begin and  end\u001b[m\r\n              sequences of non-printing characters, which can be\u001b[m\r\n              used to embed a terminal control sequence into the\u001b[m\r\n              mode string.\u001b[m\r\n       \u001b[1menable-active-region\u001b[0m \u001b[1m(On)\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n              The \u001b[4mpoint\u001b[24m is the current cursor position, and \u001b[4mmark\u001b[24m\u001b[m\r\n              refers to a saved cursor position.  The  text  be‐\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[7m Manual page bash(1) line 4057 (press h for help or q to quit)\u001b[27m\u001b[K"]
[3623.427094, "o", "\r\u001b[K              tween the point and mark is referred to as the \u001b[4mre‐\u001b[24m\u001b[m\r\n              \u001b[4mgion\u001b[24m.  When this variable is set to  \u001b[4mOn\u001b[24m,  readline\u001b[m\r\n              allows certain commands to designate the region as\u001b[m\r\n              \u001b[4mactive\u001b[24m.  When the region is active, readline high‐\u001b[m\r\n              lights  the  text in the region using the value of\u001b[m\r\n"]
[3623.427125, "o", "              the \u001b[1mactive-region-start-color\u001b[0m, which  defaults  to\u001b[m\r\n              the  string  that  enables the terminal's standout\u001b[m\r\n              mode.  The active region shows the  text  inserted\u001b[m\r\n              by  bracketed-paste and any matching text found by\u001b[m\r\n              incremental and non-incremental history searches.\u001b[m\r\n       \u001b[1menable-bracketed-paste\u001b[0m \u001b[1m(On)\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n              When set to \u001b[1mOn\u001b[0m, readline configures  the  terminal\u001b[m\r\n              to  insert each paste into the editing buffer as a\u001b[m\r\n              single string of characters, instead  of  treating\u001b[m\r\n              each  character  as  if  it had been read from the\u001b[m\r\n              keyboard.  This prevents readline  from  executing\u001b[m\r\n              any  editing  commands  bound to key sequences ap‐\u001b[m\r\n              pearing in the pasted text.\u001b[m\r\n       \u001b[1menable-keypad\u001b[0m \u001b[1m(Off)\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n              When set to \u001b[1mOn\u001b[0m, readline will try  to  enable  the\u001b[m\r\n              applicati"]
[3623.427208, "o", "on  keypad  when it is called.  Some sys‐\u001b[m\r\n              tems need this to enable the arrow keys.\u001b[m\r\n       \u001b[1menable-meta-key\u001b[0m \u001b[1m(On)\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n              When set to \u001b[1mOn\u001b[0m, readline will try  to  enable  any\u001b[m\r\n              meta  modifier  key the terminal claims to support\u001b[m\r\n              when it is called.  On many  terminals,  the  meta\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[7m Manual page bash(1) line 4083 (press h for help or q to quit)\u001b[27m\u001b[K"]
[3623.459302, "o", "\r\u001b[K"]
[3623.45948, "o", "              key is used to send eight-bit characters.\u001b[m\r\n       \u001b[1mexpand-tilde\u001b[0m \u001b[1m(Off)\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n              If  set  to  \u001b[1mOn\u001b[0m, tilde expansion is performed when\u001b[m\r\n              readline attempts word completion.\u001b[m\r\n       \u001b[1mhistory-preserve-point\u001b[0m \u001b[1m(Off)\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n              If set to \u001b[1mOn\u001b[0m, the history code attempts  to  place\u001b[m\r\n              point  at  the  same location on each history line\u001b[m\r\n              retrieved with \u001b[1mprevious-history\u001b[0m or \u001b[1mnext-history\u001b[0m.\u001b[m\r\n       \u001b[1mhistory-size\u001b[0m \u001b[1m(unset)\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n              Set the maximum number of history entries saved in\u001b[m\r\n              the  history  list.   If set to zero, any existing\u001b[m\r\n              history entries are deleted and no new entries are\u001b[m\r\n              saved.  If set to a value less than zero, the num‐\u001b[m\r\n              ber of history entries is  not  limited.   By  de‐\u001b[m\r\n              fault, the number of history entries is set to the\u001b[m\r\n              value of the \u001b[1mHISTSI"]
[3623.459496, "o", "ZE\u001b[0m shell variable.  If  an  at‐\u001b[m\r\n              tempt is made to set \u001b[4mhistory-size\u001b[24m to a non-numeric\u001b[m\r\n              value, the maximum number of history entries  will\u001b[m\r\n              be set to 500.\u001b[m\r\n       \u001b[1mhorizontal-scroll-mode\u001b[0m \u001b[1m(Off)\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n              When  set  to \u001b[1mOn\u001b[0m, makes readline use a single line\u001b[m\r\n              for display, scrolling the input horizontally on a\u001b[m\r\n              single screen line when it becomes longer than the\u001b[m\r\n              screen width rather than wrapping to a  new  line.\u001b[m\r\n              This  setting  is automatically enabled for termi‐\u001b[m\r\n              nals of height 1.\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[7m Manual page bash(1) line 4109 (press h for help or q to quit)\u001b[27m\u001b[K"]
[3623.490206, "o", "\r\u001b[K       \u001b[1minput-meta\u001b[0m \u001b[1m(Off)\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n              If set to \u001b[1mOn\u001b[0m, readline will enable eight-bit input\u001b[m\r\n              (that  is,  it  will not strip the eighth bit from\u001b[m\r\n              the characters it reads), regardless of  what  the\u001b[m\r\n              terminal   claims   it   can  support.   The  name\u001b[m\r\n              \u001b[1mmeta-flag\u001b[0m is a synonym for this variable.  The de‐\u001b[m\r\n              fault  is  \u001b[4mOff\u001b[24m,  but readline will set it to \u001b[4mOn\u001b[24m if\u001b[m\r\n              the locale contains  eight-bit  characters.   This\u001b[m\r\n              variable is dependent on the \u001b[1mLC_CTYPE\u001b[0m locale cate‐\u001b[m\r\n              gory, and may change if the locale is changed.\u001b[m\r\n       \u001b[1misearch-terminators\u001b[0m \u001b[1m(``C-[C-J'')\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n              The string of characters that should terminate  an\u001b[m\r\n              incremental  search without subsequently executing\u001b[m\r\n              the character as a command.  If this variable  has\u001b[m\r\n              not been given a value, the char"]
[3623.490375, "o", "acters \u001b[4mESC\u001b[2"]
[3623.490505, "o", "4m and \u001b[4mC-J\u001b[24m\u001b[m\r\n              will terminate an incremental search.\u001b[m\r\n       \u001b[1mkeymap\u001b[0m \u001b[1m(emacs)\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n              Set the current readline keymap.  The set of valid\u001b[m\r\n              keymap names is \u001b[4memacs,\u001b[24m \u001b[4memacs-standard,\u001b[24m \u001b[4memacs-meta,\u001b[24m\u001b[m\r\n              \u001b[4memacs-ctlx,\u001b[24m \u001b[4mvi,\u001b[24m \u001b[4mvi-command\u001b[24m, and \u001b[4mvi-insert\u001b[24m.  \u001b[4mvi\u001b[24m  is\u001b[m\r\n              equivalent  to  \u001b[4mvi-command\u001b[24m; \u001b[4memacs\u001b[24m is equivalent to\u001b[m\r\n              \u001b[4memacs-standard\u001b[24m.  The default value is  \u001b[4memacs\u001b[24m;  the\u001b[m\r\n              value  of  \u001b[1mediting-mode\u001b[0m  also  affects the default\u001b[m\r\n              keymap.\u001b[m\r\n       \u001b[1mkeyseq-timeout\u001b[0m \u001b[1m(500)\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n              Specifies the duration \u001b[4mreadline\u001b[24m will  wait  for  a\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[7m Manual page bash(1) line 4135 (press h for help or q to quit)\u001b[27m\u001b[K"]
[3623.521522, "o", "\r\u001b[K"]
[3623.521611, "o", "              character  when  reading an ambiguous key sequence\u001b[m\r\n              (one that can form a complete key  sequence  using\u001b[m\r\n              the  input read so far, or can take additional in‐\u001b[m\r\n              put to complete a longer key sequence).  If no in‐\u001b[m\r\n              put  is received within the timeout, \u001b[4mreadline\u001b[24m will\u001b[m\r\n              use the shorter but complete  key  sequence.   The\u001b[m\r\n              value  is specified in milliseconds, so a value of\u001b[m\r\n              1000 means that \u001b[4mreadline\u001b[24m will wait one second  for\u001b[m\r\n              additional  input.   If  this variable is set to a\u001b[m\r\n              value less than or equal to zero, or to a  non-nu‐\u001b[m\r\n              meric  value, \u001b[4mreadline\u001b[24m will wait until another key\u001b[m\r\n              is pressed to decide which key  sequence  to  com‐\u001b[m\r\n              plete.\u001b[m\r\n       \u001b[1mmark-directories\u001b[0m \u001b[1m(On)\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n              If  set  to  \u001b[1mOn\u001b[0m,  completed directory names have a\u001b[m\r\n          "]
[3623.521634, "o", "    slash appended.\u001b[m\r\n       \u001b[1mmark-modified-lines\u001b[0m \u001b[1m(Off)\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n              If set to \u001b[1mOn\u001b[0m, history lines that have  been  modi‐\u001b[m\r\n              fied are displayed with a preceding asterisk (\u001b[1m*\u001b[0m).\u001b[m\r\n       \u001b[1mmark-symlinked-directories\u001b[0m \u001b[1m(Off)\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n              If  set  to \u001b[1mOn\u001b[0m, completed names which are symbolic\u001b[m\r\n              links to directories have a slash  appended  (sub‐\u001b[m\r\n              ject to the value of \u001b[1mmark-directories\u001b[0m).\u001b[m\r\n       \u001b[1mmatch-hidden-files\u001b[0m \u001b[1m(On)\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n              This  variable, when set to \u001b[1mOn\u001b[0m, causes readline to\u001b[m\r\n              match files whose names begin with a  `.'  (hidden\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[7m Manual page bash(1) line 4161 (press h for help or q to quit)\u001b[27m\u001b[K"]
[3623.552967, "o", "\r\u001b[K"]
[3623.552992, "o", "              files)  when  performing  filename completion.  If\u001b[m\r\n              set to \u001b[1mOff\u001b[0m, the leading `.' must  be  supplied  by\u001b[m\r\n              the user in the filename to be completed.\u001b[m\r\n       \u001b[1mmenu-complete-display-prefix\u001b[0m \u001b[1m(Off)\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n              If  set to \u001b[1mOn\u001b[0m, menu completion displays the common\u001b[m\r\n              prefix of the list of possible completions  (which\u001b[m\r\n              may be empty) before cycling through the list.\u001b[m\r\n       \u001b[1moutput-meta\u001b[0m \u001b[1m(Off)\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n              If  set  to  \u001b[1mOn\u001b[0m,  readline will display characters\u001b[m\r\n              with the eighth bit set directly rather than as  a\u001b[m\r\n              meta-prefixed  escape  sequence.   The  default is\u001b[m\r\n              \u001b[4mOff\u001b[24m, but readline will set it to \u001b[4mOn\u001b[24m if the  locale\u001b[m\r\n              contains  eight-bit  characters.  This variable is\u001b[m\r\n              dependent on the \u001b[1mLC_CTYPE\u001b[0m locale category, and may\u001b[m\r\n              change if the locale is changed.\u001b[m\r\n "]
[3623.552997, "o", "      \u001b[1mpage"]
[3623.553018, "o", "-completions\u001b[0m \u001b[1m(On)\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n              If  set to \u001b[1mOn\u001b[0m, readline uses an internal \u001b[4mmore\u001b[24m-like\u001b[m\r\n              pager to display a screenful of  possible  comple‐\u001b[m\r\n              tions at a time.\u001b[m\r\n       \u001b[1mprint-completions-horizontally\u001b[0m \u001b[1m(Off)\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n"]
[3623.553106, "o", "              If  set  to  \u001b[1mOn\u001b[0m, readline will display completions\u001b[m\r\n              with matches sorted horizontally  in  alphabetical\u001b[m\r\n              order, rather than down the screen.\u001b[m\r\n       \u001b[1mrevert-all-at-newline\u001b[0m \u001b[1m(Off)\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n              If  set  to  \u001b[1mOn\u001b[0m, readline will undo all changes to\u001b[m\r\n              history lines before returning when \u001b[1maccept-line\u001b[0m is\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[7m Manual page bash(1) line 4187 (press h for help or q to quit)\u001b[27m\u001b[K"]
[3623.58447, "o", "\r\u001b[K"]
[3623.584538, "o", "              executed.   By default, history lines may be modi‐\u001b[m\r\n              fied and retain individual undo lists across calls\u001b[m\r\n              to \u001b[1mreadline\u001b[0m.\u001b[m\r\n       \u001b[1mshow-all-if-ambiguous\u001b[0m \u001b[1m(Off)\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n"]
[3623.584547, "o", "              This alters the default behavior of the completion\u001b[m\r\n              functions.  If set to \u001b[1mOn\u001b[0m, words  which  have  more\u001b[m\r\n              than  one possible completion cause the matches to\u001b[m\r\n              be listed immediately instead of ringing the bell.\u001b[m\r\n       \u001b[1mshow-all-if-unmodified\u001b[0m \u001b[1m(Off)\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n              This alters the default behavior of the completion\u001b[m\r\n              functions  in a fashion similar to \u001b[1mshow-all-if-am‐\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n              \u001b[1mbiguous\u001b[0m.  If set to \u001b[1mOn\u001b[0m, words which have more than\u001b[m\r\n              one  possible completion without any possible par‐\u001b[m\r\n              tial completion (the  possible  completions  don't\u001b[m\r\n"]
[3623.584551, "o", "              share  a  common  prefix)  cause the matches to be\u001b[m\r\n              listed i"]
[3623.584717, "o", "mmediately instead of ringing the bell.\u001b[m\r\n       \u001b[1mshow-mode-in-prompt\u001b[0m \u001b[1m(Off)\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n              If set to \u001b[1mOn\u001b[0m, add a string to the beginning of the\u001b[m\r\n              prompt indicating the editing mode: emacs, vi com‐\u001b[m\r\n              mand, or vi insertion.  The mode strings are user-\u001b[m\r\n              settable (e.g., \u001b[4memacs-mode-string\u001b[24m).\u001b[m\r\n       \u001b[1mskip-completed-text\u001b[0m \u001b[1m(Off)\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n              If  set  to \u001b[1mOn\u001b[0m, this alters the default completion\u001b[m\r\n              behavior when inserting a single  match  into  the\u001b[m\r\n              line.  It's only active when performing completion\u001b[m\r\n              in the middle of a  word.   If  enabled,  readline\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[7m Manual page bash(1) line 4213 (press h for help or q to quit)\u001b[27m\u001b[K"]
[3623.615619, "o", "\r\u001b[K"]
[3623.615762, "o", "              does  not  insert  characters  from the completion\u001b[m\r\n              that match characters after point in the word  be‐\u001b[m\r\n              ing  completed,  so portions of the word following\u001b[m\r\n              the cursor are not duplicated.\u001b[m\r\n       \u001b[1mvi-cmd-mode-string\u001b[0m \u001b[1m((cmd))\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n              If the \u001b[4mshow-mode-in-prompt\u001b[24m  variable  is  enabled,\u001b[m\r\n              this  string  is  displayed immediately before the\u001b[m\r\n              last line of the primary prompt  when  vi  editing\u001b[m\r\n              mode  is active and in command mode.  The value is\u001b[m\r\n              expanded like a key binding, so the  standard  set\u001b[m\r\n              of meta- and control prefixes and backslash escape\u001b[m\r\n              sequences is available.  Use the \\1 and \\2 escapes\u001b[m\r\n              to begin and end sequences of non-printing charac‐\u001b[m\r\n              ters, which can be used to embed a  terminal  con‐\u001b[m\r\n              trol sequence into the mode string.\u001b[m\r\n       \u001b[1mvi-ins-mode-s"]
[3623.615881, "o", "tring\u001b[0m \u001b[1m((ins))\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n              If  the  \u001b[4mshow-mode-in-prompt\u001b[24m  variable is enabled,\u001b[m\r\n              this string is displayed  immediately  before  the\u001b[m\r\n              last  line  of  the primary prompt when vi editing\u001b[m\r\n              mode is active and in insertion mode.   The  value\u001b[m\r\n              is  expanded  like  a key binding, so the standard\u001b[m\r\n              set of meta- and control  prefixes  and  backslash\u001b[m\r\n              escape  sequences is available.  Use the \\1 and \\2\u001b[m\r\n              escapes to begin and end sequences of non-printing\u001b[m\r\n              characters,  which can be used to embed a terminal\u001b[m\r\n              control sequence into the mode string.\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[7m Manual page bash(1) line 4239 (press h for help or q to quit)\u001b[27m\u001b[K"]
[3623.647892, "o", "\r\u001b[K       \u001b[1mvisible-stats\u001b[0m \u001b[1m(Off)\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n              If set to \u001b[1mOn\u001b[0m, a character denoting a  file's  type\u001b[m\r\n              as reported by \u001b[4mstat\u001b[24m(2) is appended to the filename\u001b[m\r\n              when listing possible completions.\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n   \u001b[1mReadline\u001b[0m \u001b[1mConditional\u001b[0m \u001b[1mConstructs\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n       Readline implements a facility similar in spirit  to  the\u001b[m\r\n       conditional  compilation  features  of the C preprocessor\u001b[m\r\n       which allows key bindings and  variable  settings  to  be\u001b[m\r\n       performed  as the result of tests.  There are four parser\u001b[m\r\n       directives used.\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n       \u001b[1m$if\u001b[0m    The \u001b[1m$if\u001b[0m construct allows bindings to be made based\u001b[m\r\n              on  the  editing mode, the terminal being used, or\u001b[m\r\n              the application using readline.  The text  of  the\u001b[m\r\n              test, after any comparison operator,\u001b[m\r\n               extends  to the end of the line; unless otherwise\u001b[m\r\n              noted, no characters are re"]
[3623.64792, "o", "quired to isolate it"]
[3623.648142, "o", ".\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n              \u001b[1mmode\u001b[0m   The \u001b[1mmode=\u001b[0m form of the \u001b[1m$if\u001b[0m directive is used\u001b[m\r\n                     to  test whether readline is in emacs or vi\u001b[m\r\n                     mode.  This may be used in conjunction with\u001b[m\r\n                     the  \u001b[1mset\u001b[0m  \u001b[1mkeymap\u001b[0m  command, for instance, to\u001b[m\r\n                     set  bindings  in  the  \u001b[4memacs-standard\u001b[24m  and\u001b[m\r\n                     \u001b[4memacs-ctlx\u001b[24m  keymaps  only  if  readline  is\u001b[m\r\n                     starting out in emacs mode.\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[7m Manual page bash(1) line 4265 (press h for help or q to quit)\u001b[27m\u001b[K"]
[3623.679892, "o", "\r\u001b[K"]
[3623.679927, "o", "\u001b[m\r\n              \u001b[1mterm\u001b[0m   The \u001b[1mterm=\u001b[0m form may be used to include  ter‐\u001b[m\r\n                     minal-specific  key  bindings,  perhaps  to\u001b[m\r\n                     bind the key sequences output by the termi‐\u001b[m\r\n                     nal's function keys.  The word on the right\u001b[m\r\n                     side of the \u001b[1m=\u001b[0m is tested  against  both  the\u001b[m\r\n                     full  name  of the terminal and the portion\u001b[m\r\n                     of the terminal name before  the  first  \u001b[1m-\u001b[0m.\u001b[m\r\n                     This  allows  \u001b[4msun\u001b[24m  to  match  both  \u001b[4msun\u001b[24m and\u001b[m\r\n                     \u001b[4msun-cmd\u001b[24m, for instance.\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n              \u001b[1mversion\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n                     The \u001b[1mversion\u001b[0m test may  be  used  to  perform\u001b[m\r\n                     comparisons  against specific readline ver‐\u001b[m\r\n                     sions.  The \u001b[1mversion\u001b[0m expands to the  current\u001b[m\r\n                     readline  version.   The  set of comparison\u001b[m\r\n                     op"]
[3623.679937, "o", "erators includes \u001b[1m=\u001b[0m, (and \u001b[1m==\u001b[0m), \u001b[1m!=\u001b[0m, \u001b[1m<=\u001b[0m, \u001b[1m>=\u001b[0m,\u001b[m\r\n                     \u001b[1m<\u001b[0m,  and  \u001b[1m>\u001b[0m.  The version number supplied on\u001b[m\r\n                     the right side of the operator consists  of\u001b[m\r\n                     a major version number, an optional decimal\u001b[m\r\n                     point, and an optional minor version (e.g.,\u001b[m\r\n                     \u001b[1m7.1\u001b[0m).  If  the minor version is omitted, it\u001b[m\r\n                     is assumed to be \u001b[1m0\u001b[0m.  The  operator  may  be\u001b[m\r\n                     separated  from the string \u001b[1mversion\u001b[0m and from\u001b[m\r\n                     the version number argument by whitespace.\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[7m Manual page bash(1) line 4291 (press h for help or q to quit)\u001b[27m\u001b[K"]
[3623.711151, "o", "\r\u001b[K"]
[3623.711312, "o", "              \u001b[1mapplication\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n                     The \u001b[1mapplication\u001b[0m construct is  used  to  in‐\u001b[m\r\n                     clude  application-specific settings.  Each\u001b[m\r\n                     program using the readline library sets the\u001b[m\r\n                     \u001b[4mapplication\u001b[24m  \u001b[4mname\u001b[24m,  and  an  initialization\u001b[m\r\n                     file can test for a particular value.  This\u001b[m\r\n                     could  be  used  to  bind  key sequences to\u001b[m\r\n                     functions useful for  a  specific  program.\u001b[m\r\n                     For  instance, the following command adds a\u001b[m\r\n                     key sequence that  quotes  the  current  or\u001b[m\r\n                     previous word in \u001b[1mbash\u001b[0m:\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n                     \u001b[1m$if\u001b[0m Bash\u001b[m\r\n                     # Quote the current or previous word\u001b[m\r\n                     \"\\C-xq\": \"\\eb\\\"\\ef\\\"\"\u001b[m\r\n                     \u001b[1m$endif\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n              \u001b[4mvariable\u001b[24m\u001b[m\r\n                     The   \u001b[4mvariable\u001b[24m"]
[3623.711331, "o", "  construct  provides  simple\u001b[m\r\n                     equality tests for readline  variables  and\u001b[m\r\n                     values.  The permitted comparison operators\u001b[m\r\n                     are \u001b[4m=\u001b[24m, \u001b[4m==\u001b[24m, and \u001b[4m!=\u001b[24m.  The variable name  must\u001b[m\r\n                     be  separated  from the comparison operator\u001b[m\r\n                     by whitespace; the operator  may  be  sepa‐\u001b[m\r\n                     rated from the value on the right hand side\u001b[m\r\n                     by whitespace.   Both  string  and  boolean\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[7m Manual page bash(1) line 4317 (press h for help or q to quit)\u001b[27m\u001b[K"]
[3623.742047, "o", "\r\u001b[K"]
[3623.742166, "o", "                     variables  may be tested. Boolean variables\u001b[m\r\n                     must be tested against the  values  \u001b[4mon\u001b[24m  and\u001b[m\r\n                     \u001b[4moff\u001b[24m.\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n       \u001b[1m$endif\u001b[0m This  command,  as  seen  in the previous example,\u001b[m\r\n              terminates an \u001b[1m$if\u001b[0m command.\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n       \u001b[1m$else\u001b[0m  Commands in this branch of the \u001b[1m$if\u001b[0m  directive  are\u001b[m\r\n              executed if the test fails.\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n       \u001b[1m$include\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n              This directive takes a single filename as an argu‐\u001b[m\r\n              ment and reads commands  and  bindings  from  that\u001b[m\r\n              file.   For example, the following directive would\u001b[m\r\n              read \u001b[4m/etc/inputrc\u001b[24m:\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n              \u001b[1m$include\u001b[0m  \u001b[4m/etc/inputrc\u001b[24m\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n   \u001b[1mSearching\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n       Readline provides commands for searching through the com‐\u001b[m\r\n       mand  history  (see \u001b[1mHISTORY\u001b[0m below) for lines containing a\u001b[m\r\n       specified string.  There are tw"]
[3623.742199, "o", "o search modes:  \u001b[4mincremen‐\u001b[24m\u001b[m\r\n       \u001b[4mtal\u001b[24m and \u001b[4mnon-incremental\u001b[24m.\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n       Incremental  searches  begin before the user has finished\u001b[m\r\n       typing the search  string.   As  each  character  of  the\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[7m Manual page bash(1) line 4343 (press h for help or q to quit)\u001b[27m\u001b[K"]
[3623.773549, "o", "\r\u001b[K"]
[3623.773649, "o", "       search  string is typed, readline displays the next entry\u001b[m\r\n       from the history matching the string typed  so  far.   An\u001b[m\r\n       incremental  search  requires  only as many characters as\u001b[m\r\n       needed to find the desired history entry.  The characters\u001b[m\r\n       present  in the value of the \u001b[1misearch-terminators\u001b[0m variable\u001b[m\r\n       are used to terminate an  incremental  search.   If  that\u001b[m\r\n       variable  has  not  been  assigned a value the Escape and\u001b[m\r\n       Control-J  characters  will  terminate   an   incremental\u001b[m\r\n       search.   Control-G  will abort an incremental search and\u001b[m\r\n       restore the original line.  When  the  search  is  termi‐\u001b[m\r\n       nated, the history entry containing the search string be‐\u001b[m\r\n       comes the current line.\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n       To find other matching entries in the history list,  type\u001b[m\r\n       Control-S  or Control-R as appropriate.  This will search\u001b[m\r\n       backward or forward in the history  for  the  next  entry\u001b[m\r\n      "]
[3623.773675, "o", " matching  the  search string typed so far.  Any other key\u001b[m\r\n       sequence bound to a readline command will  terminate  the\u001b[m\r\n       search and execute that command.  For instance, a \u001b[4mnewline\u001b[24m\u001b[m\r\n       will terminate the search and accept  the  line,  thereby\u001b[m\r\n       executing the command from the history list.\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n       Readline  remembers  the  last incremental search string.\u001b[m\r\n       If two Control-Rs are typed without any intervening char‐\u001b[m\r\n       acters  defining  a  new  search  string,  any remembered\u001b[m\r\n       search string is used.\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[7m Manual page bash(1) line 4369 (press h for help or q to quit)\u001b[27m\u001b[K"]
[3623.804643, "o", "\r\u001b[K\u001b[m\r\n       Non-incremental searches read the  entire  search  string\u001b[m\r\n       before  starting  to  search  for matching history lines.\u001b[m\r\n       The search string may be typed by the user or be part  of\u001b[m\r\n       the contents of the current line.\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n   \u001b[1mReadline\u001b[0m \u001b[1mCommand\u001b[0m \u001b[1mNames\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n       The  following is a list of the names of the commands and\u001b[m\r\n       the default key sequences to which they are bound.   Com‐\u001b[m\r\n       mand  names  without an accompanying key sequence are un‐\u001b[m\r\n       bound by default.  In the following  descriptions,  \u001b[4mpoint\u001b[24m\u001b[m\r\n       refers to the current cursor position, and \u001b[4mmark\u001b[24m refers to\u001b[m\r\n       a cursor position saved by  the  \u001b[1mset-mark\u001b[0m  command.   The\u001b[m\r\n       text between the point and mark is referred to as the \u001b[4mre‐\u001b[24m\u001b[m\r\n       \u001b[4mgion\u001b[24m.\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n   \u001b[1mCommands\u001b[0m \u001b[1mfor\u001b[0m \u001b[1mMoving\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n       \u001b[1mbeginning-of-line\u001b[0m \u001b[1m(C-a)\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n              Move to the start of the current "]
[3623.804776, "o", "line.\u001b[m\r\n       \u001b[1mend-of-line\u001b[0m \u001b[1m(C-e)\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n              Move to the end of the line.\u001b[m\r\n       \u001b[1mforward-char\u001b[0m \u001b[1m(C-f)\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n              Move forward a character.\u001b[m\r\n       \u001b[1mbackward-char\u001b[0m \u001b[1m(C-b)\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n              Move back a character.\u001b[m\r\n       \u001b[1mforward-word\u001b[0m \u001b[1m(M-f)\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[7m Manual page bash(1) line 4395 (press h for help or q to quit)\u001b[27m\u001b[K"]
[3623.836028, "o", "\r\u001b[K              Move forward to the end of the next  word.   Words\u001b[m\r\n              are  composed  of alphanumeric characters (letters\u001b[m\r\n              and digits).\u001b[m\r\n       \u001b[1mbackward-word\u001b[0m \u001b[1m(M-b)\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n              Move back to the start of the current or  previous\u001b[m\r\n              word.   Words are composed of alphanumeric charac‐\u001b[m\r\n              ters (letters and digits).\u001b[m\r\n       \u001b[1mshell-forward-word\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n              Move forward to the end of the next  word.   Words\u001b[m\r\n              are delimited by non-quoted shell metacharacters.\u001b[m\r\n       \u001b[1mshell-backward-word\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n              Move  back to the start of the current or previous\u001b[m\r\n              word.  Words are  delimited  by  non-quoted  shell\u001b[m\r\n              metacharacters.\u001b[m\r\n       \u001b[1mprevious-screen-line\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n              Attempt  to move point to the same physical screen\u001b[m\r\n              column on the previous physical screen line.  This\u001b[m\r\n              will  not  have  the desired effect if th"]
[3623.836164, "o", "e current\u001b[m\r\n              readline line does not take up more than one phys‐\u001b[m\r\n              ical  line  or  if  point  is not greater than the\u001b[m\r\n              length of the prompt plus the screen width.\u001b[m\r\n       \u001b[1mnext-screen-line\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n              Attempt to move point to the same physical  screen\u001b[m\r\n              column on the next physical screen line. This will\u001b[m\r\n              not have the desired effect if the  current  read‐\u001b[m\r\n              line  line does not take up more than one physical\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[7m Manual page bash(1) line 4421 (press h for help or q to quit)\u001b[27m\u001b[K"]
[3623.867509, "o", "\r\u001b[K              line or if the length of the current readline line\u001b[m\r\n              is  not greater than the length of the prompt plus\u001b[m\r\n              the screen width.\u001b[m\r\n       \u001b[1mclear-display\u001b[0m \u001b[1m(M-C-l)\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n              Clear the screen and, if possible, the  terminal's\u001b[m\r\n              scrollback  buffer,  then redraw the current line,\u001b[m\r\n              leaving the current line at the top of the screen.\u001b[m\r\n       \u001b[1mclear-screen\u001b[0m \u001b[1m(C-l)\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n              Clear the screen, then redraw  the  current  line,\u001b[m\r\n              leaving the current line at the top of the screen.\u001b[m\r\n              With an argument, refresh the current line without\u001b[m\r\n              clearing the screen.\u001b[m\r\n       \u001b[1mredraw-current-line\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n              Refresh the current line.\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n   \u001b[1mCommands\u001b[0m \u001b[1mfor\u001b[0m \u001b[1mManipulating\u001b[0m \u001b[1mthe\u001b[0m \u001b[1mHistory\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n       \u001b[1maccept-line\u001b[0m \u001b[1m(Newline,\u001b[0m \u001b[1mReturn)\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n              Accept the line regardless of where the cursor"]
[3623.867659, "o", " is.\u001b[m\r\n            "]
[3623.867761, "o", "  If this line is non-empty, add it to  the  history\u001b[m\r\n              list  according  to  the  state of the \u001b[1mHISTCONTROL\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n              variable.  If the line is a modified history line,\u001b[m\r\n              then  restore  the  history  line  to its original\u001b[m\r\n              state.\u001b[m\r\n       \u001b[1mprevious-history\u001b[0m \u001b[1m(C-p)\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n              Fetch the previous command from the history  list,\u001b[m\r\n              moving back in the list.\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[7m Manual page bash(1) line 4447 (press h for help or q to quit)\u001b[27m\u001b[K"]
[3623.898877, "o", "\r\u001b[K"]
[3623.89904, "o", "       \u001b[1mnext-history\u001b[0m \u001b[1m(C-n)\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n              Fetch the next command from the history list, mov‐\u001b[m\r\n              ing forward in the list.\u001b[m\r\n       \u001b[1mbeginning-of-history\u001b[0m \u001b[1m(M-<)\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n              Move to the first line in the history.\u001b[m\r\n       \u001b[1mend-of-history\u001b[0m \u001b[1m(M->)\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n              Move to the end of the input  history,  i.e.,  the\u001b[m\r\n              line currently being entered.\u001b[m\r\n       \u001b[1moperate-and-get-next\u001b[0m \u001b[1m(C-o)\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n              Accept  the  current  line for execution and fetch\u001b[m\r\n              the next line relative to the  current  line  from\u001b[m\r\n              the  history  for editing.  A numeric argument, if\u001b[m\r\n              supplied, specifies the history entry to  use  in‐\u001b[m\r\n              stead of the current line.\u001b[m\r\n       \u001b[1mfetch-history\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n              With a numeric argument, fetch that entry from the\u001b[m\r\n              history list and make it the current line.   With‐\u001b[m\r\n              out  an  argument, move "]
[3623.899136, "o", "back to the first entry in\u001b[m\r\n              the history list.\u001b[m\r\n       \u001b[1mreverse-search-history\u001b[0m \u001b[1m(C-r)\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n              Search backward starting at the current  line  and\u001b[m\r\n              moving  `up'  through  the  history  as necessary.\u001b[m\r\n              This is an incremental search.\u001b[m\r\n       \u001b[1mforward-search-history\u001b[0m \u001b[1m(C-s)\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n              Search forward starting at the  current  line  and\u001b[m\r\n              moving  `down'  through  the history as necessary.\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[7m Manual page bash(1) line 4473 (press h for help or q to quit)\u001b[27m\u001b[K"]
[3623.930455, "o", "\r\u001b[K"]
[3623.930561, "o", "              This is an incremental search.\u001b[m\r\n       \u001b[1mnon-incremental-reverse-search-history\u001b[0m \u001b[1m(M-p)\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n              Search backward through the  history  starting  at\u001b[m\r\n              the  current  line  using a non-incremental search\u001b[m\r\n              for a string supplied by the user.\u001b[m\r\n       \u001b[1mnon-incremental-forward-search-history\u001b[0m \u001b[1m(M-n)\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n              Search forward through the history using a non-in‐\u001b[m\r\n              cremental  search  for  a  string  supplied by the\u001b[m\r\n              user.\u001b[m\r\n       \u001b[1mhistory-search-forward\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n              Search forward through the history for the  string\u001b[m\r\n              of  characters  between  the  start of the current\u001b[m\r\n              line and the point.   This  is  a  non-incremental\u001b[m\r\n              search.\u001b[m\r\n       \u001b[1mhistory-search-backward\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n              Search backward through the history for the string\u001b[m\r\n              of characters between the  start  of  the  current\u001b[m\r\n              line  "]
[3623.930719, "o", "and  the  point.   This is a non-incremental\u001b[m\r\n              search.\u001b[m\r\n       \u001b[1mhistory-substring-search-backward\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n              Search backward through the history for the string\u001b[m\r\n              of  characters  between  the  start of the current\u001b[m\r\n              line and the current cursor position (the  \u001b[4mpoint\u001b[24m).\u001b[m\r\n              The  search string may match anywhere in a history\u001b[m\r\n              line.  This is a non-incremental search.\u001b[m\r\n       \u001b[1mhistory-substring-search-forward\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[7m Manual page bash(1) line 4499 (press h for help or q to quit)\u001b[27m\u001b[K"]
[3623.96257, "o", "\r\u001b[K"]
[3623.962597, "o", "              Search forward through the history for the  string\u001b[m\r\n              of  characters  between  the  start of the current\u001b[m\r\n              line and the point.  The search string  may  match\u001b[m\r\n              anywhere  in a history line.  This is a non-incre‐\u001b[m\r\n              mental search.\u001b[m\r\n       \u001b[1myank-nth-arg\u001b[0m \u001b[1m(M-C-y)\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n              Insert the first argument to the previous  command\u001b[m\r\n              (usually  the second word on the previous line) at\u001b[m\r\n              point.  With an argument \u001b[4mn\u001b[24m, insert  the  \u001b[4mn\u001b[24mth  word\u001b[m\r\n              from the previous command (the words in the previ‐\u001b[m\r\n              ous command begin with word 0).  A negative  argu‐\u001b[m\r\n"]
[3623.962605, "o", "              ment inserts the \u001b[4mn\u001b[24mth word from the end of the pre‐\u001b[m\r\n              vious command.  Once the argument \u001b[4mn\u001b[24m  is  computed,\u001b[m\r\n              the  argument  is extracted as if the \"!\u001b[4mn\u001b[24m\" history\u001b[m\r\n              expansion had been specified.\u001b[m\r\n       \u001b[1myank-last-arg\u001b[0m"]
[3623.962812, "o", " \u001b[1m(M-.,\u001b[0m \u001b[1mM-_)\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n              Insert the last argument to the  previous  command\u001b[m\r\n              (the  last  word  of  the previous history entry).\u001b[m\r\n              With  a  numeric  argument,  behave  exactly  like\u001b[m\r\n              \u001b[1myank-nth-arg\u001b[0m.   Successive  calls to \u001b[1myank-last-arg\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n              move back through the history list, inserting  the\u001b[m\r\n              last  word  (or the word specified by the argument\u001b[m\r\n              to the first call) of each line in turn.  Any  nu‐\u001b[m\r\n              meric  argument supplied to these successive calls\u001b[m\r\n              determines the direction to move through the  his‐\u001b[m\r\n              tory.   A negative argument switches the direction\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[7m Manual page bash(1) line 4525 (press h for help or q to quit)\u001b[27m\u001b[K"]
[3623.994351, "o", "\r\u001b[K"]
[3623.994388, "o", "              through the history (back or forward).   The  his‐\u001b[m\r\n              tory  expansion facilities are used to extract the\u001b[m\r\n              last word, as if the \"!$\"  history  expansion  had\u001b[m\r\n              been specified.\u001b[m\r\n       \u001b[1mshell-expand-line\u001b[0m \u001b[1m(M-C-e)\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n              Expand  the line as the shell does.  This performs\u001b[m\r\n              alias and history expansion as well as all of  the\u001b[m\r\n              shell  word expansions.  See \u001b[1mHISTORY\u001b[0m \u001b[1mEXPANSION\u001b[0m be‐\u001b[m\r\n              low for a description of history expansion.\u001b[m\r\n       \u001b[1mhistory-expand-line\u001b[0m \u001b[1m(M-^)\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n              Perform history expansion  on  the  current  line.\u001b[m\r\n              See  \u001b[1mHISTORY\u001b[0m  \u001b[1mEXPANSION\u001b[0m below for a description of\u001b[m\r\n              history expansion.\u001b[m\r\n       \u001b[1mmagic-space\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n              Perform history expansion on the current line  and\u001b[m\r\n              insert a space.  See \u001b[1mHISTORY\u001b[0m \u001b[1mEXPANSION\u001b[0m below for a\u001b[m\r\n            "]
[3623.994398, "o", "  description of history expansion.\u001b[m\r\n       \u001b[1malias-expand-line\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n              Perform alias expansion on the current line.   See\u001b[m\r\n              \u001b[1mALIASES\u001b[0m  above  for  a description of alias expan‐\u001b[m\r\n              sion.\u001b[m\r\n       \u001b[1mhistory-and-alias-expand-line\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n              Perform history and alias expansion on the current\u001b[m\r\n              line.\u001b[m\r\n       \u001b[1minsert-last-argument\u001b[0m \u001b[1m(M-.,\u001b[0m \u001b[1mM-_)\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n              A synonym for \u001b[1myank-last-arg\u001b[0m.\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[7m Manual page bash(1) line 4551 (press h for help or q to quit)\u001b[27m\u001b[K"]
[3624.025528, "o", "\r\u001b[K       \u001b[1medit-and-execute-command\u001b[0m \u001b[1m(C-x\u001b[0m \u001b[1mC-e)\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n              Invoke  an editor on the current command line, and\u001b[m\r\n              execute the result as shell  commands.   \u001b[1mBash\u001b[0m  at‐\u001b[m\r\n              tempts  to  invoke  \u001b[1m$VISUAL\u001b[0m, \u001b[1m$EDITOR\u001b[0m, and \u001b[4memacs\u001b[24m as\u001b[m\r\n              the editor, in that order.\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n   \u001b[1mCommands\u001b[0m \u001b[1mfor\u001b[0m \u001b[1mChanging\u001b[0m \u001b[1mText\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n       \u001b[4mend-of-file\u001b[24m \u001b[1m(usually\u001b[0m \u001b[1mC-d)\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n              The character indicating end-of-file as  set,  for\u001b[m\r\n              example,  by  ``stty''.  If this character is read\u001b[m\r\n              when there are no  characters  on  the  line,  and\u001b[m\r\n              point  is  at  the beginning of the line, readline\u001b[m\r\n              interprets it as the end of input and returns \u001b[1mEOF\u001b[0m.\u001b[m\r\n       \u001b[1mdelete-char\u001b[0m \u001b[1m(C-d)\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n              Delete the character at point.  If  this  function\u001b[m\r\n              is  bound  to  the  same  character as the tty \u001b["]
[3624.025631, "o", "1mEOF\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n              character, as \u001b[1mC-d\u001b[0m commonly is, see above  for  the\u001b[m\r\n              effects.\u001b[m\r\n       \u001b[1mbackward-delete-char\u001b[0m \u001b[1m(Rubout)\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n              Delete  the  character  behind  the  cursor.  When\u001b[m\r\n              given a numeric argument, save the deleted text on\u001b[m\r\n              the kill ring.\u001b[m\r\n       \u001b[1mforward-backward-delete-char\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n              Delete  the character under the cursor, unless the\u001b[m\r\n              cursor is at the end of the line,  in  which  case\u001b[m\r\n              the character behind the cursor is deleted.\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[7m Manual page bash(1) line 4577 (press h for help or q to quit)\u001b[27m\u001b[K"]
[3624.056907, "o", "\r\u001b[K       \u001b[1mquoted-insert\u001b[0m \u001b[1m(C-q,\u001b[0m \u001b[1mC-v)\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n              Add the next character typed to the line verbatim.\u001b[m\r\n"]
[3624.056973, "o", "              This is how to insert characters like \u001b[1mC-q\u001b[0m, for ex‐\u001b[m\r\n              ample.\u001b[m\r\n       \u001b[1mtab-insert\u001b[0m \u001b[1m(C-v\u001b[0m \u001b[1mTAB)\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n              Insert a tab character.\u001b[m\r\n       \u001b[1mself-insert\u001b[0m \u001b[1m(a,\u001b[0m \u001b[1mb,\u001b[0m \u001b[1mA,\u001b[0m \u001b[1m1,\u001b[0m \u001b[1m!,\u001b[0m \u001b[1m...)\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n              Insert the character typed.\u001b[m\r\n       \u001b[1mtranspose-chars\u001b[0m \u001b[1m(C-t)\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n              Drag  the  character before point forward over the\u001b[m\r\n              character at point, moving point forward as  well.\u001b[m\r\n              If  point  is  at  the  end of the line, then this\u001b[m\r\n              transposes the two characters before point.  Nega‐\u001b[m\r\n              tive arguments have no effect.\u001b[m\r\n       \u001b[1mtranspose-words\u001b[0m \u001b[1m(M-t)\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n              Drag  the  word  before  point past the word after\u001b[m\r\n              point, moving point over that word  as  well.   If\u001b[m\r\n              point  is  at the end of the line, this transposes\u001b[m\r\n              the last two words on the line"]
[3624.056989, "o", ".\u001b[m\r\n       \u001b[1"]
[3624.057098, "o", "mupcase-word\u001b[0m \u001b[1m(M-u)\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n              Uppercase the current (or following) word.  With a\u001b[m\r\n              negative  argument,  uppercase  the previous word,\u001b[m\r\n              but do not move point.\u001b[m\r\n       \u001b[1mdowncase-word\u001b[0m \u001b[1m(M-l)\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n              Lowercase the current (or following) word.  With a\u001b[m\r\n              negative  argument,  lowercase  the previous word,\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[7m Manual page bash(1) line 4603 (press h for help or q to quit)\u001b[27m\u001b[K"]
[3624.087623, "o", "\r\u001b[K"]
[3624.087786, "o", "              but do not move point.\u001b[m\r\n       \u001b[1mcapitalize-word\u001b[0m \u001b[1m(M-c)\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n              Capitalize the current (or following) word.   With\u001b[m\r\n              a negative argument, capitalize the previous word,\u001b[m\r\n              but do not move point.\u001b[m\r\n       \u001b[1moverwrite-mode\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n              Toggle overwrite mode.  With an explicit  positive\u001b[m\r\n              numeric  argument,  switches  to  overwrite  mode.\u001b[m\r\n              With an explicit  non-positive  numeric  argument,\u001b[m\r\n              switches  to  insert  mode.   This command affects\u001b[m\r\n              only \u001b[1memacs\u001b[0m mode; \u001b[1mvi\u001b[0m mode  does  overwrite  differ‐\u001b[m\r\n              ently.   Each  call to \u001b[4mreadline()\u001b[24m starts in insert\u001b[m\r\n              mode.  In  overwrite  mode,  characters  bound  to\u001b[m\r\n              \u001b[1mself-insert\u001b[0m  replace the text at point rather than\u001b[m\r\n              pushing the text to the right.   Characters  bound\u001b[m\r\n              to  \u001b[1mbackward-delete-char\u001b[0m replace the charac"]
[3624.087825, "o", "ter be‐\u001b[m\r\n              fore point with a space.  By default, this command\u001b[m\r\n              is unbound.\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n   \u001b[1mKilling\u001b[0m \u001b[1mand\u001b[0m \u001b[1mYanking\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n       \u001b[1mkill-line\u001b[0m \u001b[1m(C-k)\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n              Kill the text from point to the end of the line.\u001b[m\r\n       \u001b[1mbackward-kill-line\u001b[0m \u001b[1m(C-x\u001b[0m \u001b[1mRubout)\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n              Kill backward to the beginning of the line.\u001b[m\r\n       \u001b[1munix-line-discard\u001b[0m \u001b[1m(C-u)\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n              Kill  backward  from point to the beginning of the\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[7m Manual page bash(1) line 4629 (press h for help or q to quit)\u001b[27m\u001b[K"]
[3624.118645, "o", "\r\u001b[K"]
[3624.118744, "o", "              line.  The killed text is saved on the kill-ring.\u001b[m\r\n       \u001b[1mkill-whole-line\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n              Kill all characters on the current line, no matter\u001b[m\r\n              where point is.\u001b[m\r\n       \u001b[1mkill-word\u001b[0m \u001b[1m(M-d)\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n              Kill from point to the end of the current word, or\u001b[m\r\n              if between words, to the end  of  the  next  word.\u001b[m\r\n              Word boundaries are the same as those used by \u001b[1mfor‐\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n              \u001b[1mward-word\u001b[0m.\u001b[m\r\n       \u001b[1mbackward-kill-word\u001b[0m \u001b[1m(M-Rubout)\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n              Kill the word behind point.  Word  boundaries  are\u001b[m\r\n              the same as those used by \u001b[1mbackward-word\u001b[0m.\u001b[m\r\n       \u001b[1mshell-kill-word\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n              Kill from point to the end of the current word, or\u001b[m\r\n              if between words, to the end  of  the  next  word.\u001b[m\r\n              Word  boundaries  are  the  same  as those used by\u001b[m\r\n              \u001b[1mshell-forward-word\u001b[0m.\u001b[m\r\n       \u001b[1mshell-backward-kill-word\u001b[0m\u001b"]
[3624.118771, "o", "[m\r\n              Kill the word behind point.  Word  boundaries  are\u001b[m\r\n              the same as those used by \u001b[1mshell-backward-word\u001b[0m.\u001b[m\r\n       \u001b[1munix-word-rubout\u001b[0m \u001b[1m(C-w)\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n              Kill the word behind point, using white space as a\u001b[m\r\n              word boundary.  The killed text is  saved  on  the\u001b[m\r\n              kill-ring.\u001b[m\r\n       \u001b[1munix-filename-rubout\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n              Kill  the word behind point, using white space and\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[7m Manual page bash(1) line 4655 (press h for help or q to quit)\u001b[27m\u001b[K"]
[3624.149751, "o", "\r\u001b[K"]
[3624.149836, "o", "              the slash character as the word  boundaries.   The\u001b[m\r\n              killed text is saved on the kill-ring.\u001b[m\r\n       \u001b[1mdelete-horizontal-space\u001b[0m \u001b[1m(M-\\)\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n              Delete all spaces and tabs around point.\u001b[m\r\n       \u001b[1mkill-region\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n              Kill the text in the current region.\u001b[m\r\n       \u001b[1mcopy-region-as-kill\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n              Copy the text in the region to the kill buffer.\u001b[m\r\n       \u001b[1mcopy-backward-word\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n              Copy  the  word  before  point to the kill buffer.\u001b[m\r\n              The word boundaries are the same as \u001b[1mbackward-word\u001b[0m.\u001b[m\r\n       \u001b[1mcopy-forward-word\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n              Copy the word following point to the kill  buffer.\u001b[m\r\n              The word boundaries are the same as \u001b[1mforward-word\u001b[0m.\u001b[m\r\n       \u001b[1myank\u001b[0m \u001b[1m(C-y)\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n              Yank  the  top of the kill ring into the buffer at\u001b[m\r\n              point.\u001b[m\r\n       \u001b[1myank-pop\u001b[0m \u001b[1m(M-y)\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n              Rotate the kill ring, and yank the ne"]
[3624.149856, "o", "w top.   Only\u001b[m\r\n              works following \u001b[1myank\u001b[0m or \u001b[1myank-pop\u001b[0m.\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n   \u001b[1mNumeric\u001b[0m \u001b[1mArguments\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n       \u001b[1mdigit-argument\u001b[0m \u001b[1m(M-0,\u001b[0m \u001b[1mM-1,\u001b[0m \u001b[1m...,\u001b[0m \u001b[1mM--)\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n              Add  this digit to the argument already accumulat‐\u001b[m\r\n              ing, or start a new argument.  M-- starts a  nega‐\u001b[m\r\n              tive argument.\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[7m Manual page bash(1) line 4681 (press h for help or q to quit)\u001b[27m\u001b[K"]
[3624.1809, "o", "\r\u001b[K       \u001b[1muniversal-argument\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n              This  is  another  way to specify an argument.  If\u001b[m\r\n              this command is followed by one  or  more  digits,\u001b[m\r\n              optionally with a leading minus sign, those digits\u001b[m\r\n              define the argument.  If the command  is  followed\u001b[m\r\n              by digits, executing \u001b[1muniversal-argument\u001b[0m again ends\u001b[m\r\n              the numeric argument, but  is  otherwise  ignored.\u001b[m\r\n              As  a special case, if this command is immediately\u001b[m\r\n              followed by a character that is  neither  a  digit\u001b[m\r\n              nor  minus  sign,  the argument count for the next\u001b[m\r\n              command is multiplied by four.  The argument count\u001b[m\r\n              is  initially  one, so executing this function the\u001b[m\r\n              first time makes the argument count four, a second\u001b[m\r\n              time makes the argument count sixteen, and so on.\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n   \u001b[1mCompleting\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n       \u001b[1mcomplete\u001b[0m \u001b[1m(TAB)\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n     "]
[3624.180989, "o", "         Attempt  to  perform completion on the text before\u001b[m\r\n              point.  \u001b[1mBash\u001b[0m attempts completion treating the text\u001b[m\r\n              as  a  variable (if the text begins with \u001b[1m$\u001b[0m), user‐\u001b[m\r\n              name (if the text begins with \u001b[1m~\u001b[0m), hostname (if the\u001b[m\r\n              text begins with \u001b[1m@\u001b[0m), or command (including aliases\u001b[m\r\n              and functions) in turn.  If none of these produces\u001b[m\r\n              a match, filename completion is attempted.\u001b[m\r\n       \u001b[1mpossible-completions\u001b[0m \u001b[1m(M-?)\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n              List  the  possible completions of the text before\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[7m Manual page bash(1) line 4707 (press h for help or q to quit)\u001b[27m\u001b[K"]
[3624.211988, "o", "\r\u001b[K"]
[3624.212015, "o", "              point.\u001b[m\r\n       \u001b[1minsert-completions\u001b[0m \u001b[1m(M-*)\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n              Insert all completions of the  text  before  point\u001b[m\r\n              that would have been generated by \u001b[1mpossible-comple‐\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n"]
[3624.21213, "o", "              \u001b[1mtions\u001b[0m.\u001b[m\r\n       \u001b[1mmenu-complete\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n              Similar to \u001b[1mcomplete\u001b[0m, but replaces the word  to  be\u001b[m\r\n              completed  with  a  single  match from the list of\u001b[m\r\n              possible  completions.   Repeated   execution   of\u001b[m\r\n              \u001b[1mmenu-complete\u001b[0m  steps  through the list of possible\u001b[m\r\n              completions, inserting each match in turn.  At the\u001b[m\r\n              end  of  the list of completions, the bell is rung\u001b[m\r\n              (subject to the setting  of  \u001b[1mbell-style\u001b[0m)  and  the\u001b[m\r\n              original text is restored.  An argument of \u001b[4mn\u001b[24m moves\u001b[m\r\n              \u001b[4mn\u001b[24m positions forward in the list of matches; a neg‐\u001b[m\r\n              ative  argument  may  be  used  to  move  backward\u001b[m\r\n              through the list.  This command is intended to  be\u001b[m\r\n              bound to \u001b[1mTAB\u001b[0m, but is unbound by default.\u001b[m\r\n       \u001b[1mmenu-complete-backward\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n              Identical  to  \u001b[1mmenu-complete"]
[3624.212141, "o", "\u001b[0m,  but  moves backward\u001b[m\r\n              through the list of possible  completions,  as  if\u001b[m\r\n              \u001b[1mmenu-complete\u001b[0m  had been given a negative argument.\u001b[m\r\n              This command is unbound by default.\u001b[m\r\n       \u001b[1mdelete-char-or-list\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n              Deletes the character under the cursor if  not  at\u001b[m\r\n              the   beginning   or   end   of   the  line  (like\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[7m Manual page bash(1) line 4733 (press h for help or q to quit)\u001b[27m\u001b[K"]
[3624.243071, "o", "\r\u001b[K"]
[3624.243206, "o", "              \u001b[1mdelete-char\u001b[0m).  If at the end of the line,  behaves\u001b[m\r\n              identically to \u001b[1mpossible-completions\u001b[0m.  This command\u001b[m\r\n              is unbound by default.\u001b[m\r\n       \u001b[1mcomplete-filename\u001b[0m \u001b[1m(M-/)\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n              Attempt filename completion  on  the  text  before\u001b[m\r\n              point.\u001b[m\r\n       \u001b[1mpossible-filename-completions\u001b[0m \u001b[1m(C-x\u001b[0m \u001b[1m/)\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n              List  the  possible completions of the text before\u001b[m\r\n              point, treating it as a filename.\u001b[m\r\n       \u001b[1mcomplete-username\u001b[0m \u001b[1m(M-~)\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n              Attempt  completion  on  the  text  before  point,\u001b[m\r\n              treating it as a username.\u001b[m\r\n       \u001b[1mpossible-username-completions\u001b[0m \u001b[1m(C-x\u001b[0m \u001b[1m~)\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n              List  the  possible completions of the text before\u001b[m\r\n              point, treating it as a username.\u001b[m\r\n       \u001b[1mcomplete-variable\u001b[0m \u001b[1m(M-$)\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n              Attempt  completion  on  the  text  before  point,\u001b[m\r\n           "]
[3624.243225, "o", "   treating it as a shell variable.\u001b[m\r\n       \u001b[1mpossible-variable-completions\u001b[0m \u001b[1m(C-x\u001b[0m \u001b[1m$)\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n              List  the  possible completions of the text before\u001b[m\r\n              point, treating it as a shell variable.\u001b[m\r\n       \u001b[1mcomplete-hostname\u001b[0m \u001b[1m(M-@)\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n              Attempt  completion  on  the  text  before  point,\u001b[m\r\n              treating it as a hostname.\u001b[m\r\n       \u001b[1mpossible-hostname-completions\u001b[0m \u001b[1m(C-x\u001b[0m \u001b[1m@)\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n              List  the  possible completions of the text before\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[7m Manual page bash(1) line 4759 (press h for help or q to quit)\u001b[27m\u001b[K"]
[3624.273634, "o", "\r\u001b[K"]
[3624.273726, "o", "              point, treating it as a hostname.\u001b[m\r\n       \u001b[1mcomplete-command\u001b[0m \u001b[1m(M-!)\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n              Attempt  completion  on  the  text  before  point,\u001b[m\r\n              treating it as a command name.  Command completion\u001b[m\r\n              attempts to match the text  against  aliases,  re‐\u001b[m\r\n              served words, shell functions, shell builtins, and\u001b[m\r\n              finally executable filenames, in that order.\u001b[m\r\n       \u001b[1mpossible-command-completions\u001b[0m \u001b[1m(C-x\u001b[0m \u001b[1m!)\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n              List the possible completions of the  text  before\u001b[m\r\n              point, treating it as a command name.\u001b[m\r\n       \u001b[1mdynamic-complete-history\u001b[0m \u001b[1m(M-TAB)\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n              Attempt  completion on the text before point, com‐\u001b[m\r\n              paring the text against  lines  from  the  history\u001b[m\r\n              list for possible completion matches.\u001b[m\r\n       \u001b[1mdabbrev-expand\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n              Attempt  menu completion on the text before point,\u001b[m\r\n              comparing t"]
[3624.273748, "o", "he text against"]
[3624.273779, "o", " lines from the  history\u001b[m\r\n              list for possible completion matches.\u001b[m\r\n       \u001b[1mcomplete-into-braces\u001b[0m \u001b[1m(M-{)\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n              Perform filename completion and insert the list of\u001b[m\r\n              possible completions enclosed within braces so the\u001b[m\r\n              list  is  available to the shell (see \u001b[1mBrace\u001b[0m \u001b[1mExpan‐\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n              \u001b[1msion\u001b[0m above).\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n   \u001b[1mKeyboard\u001b[0m \u001b[1mMacros\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n       \u001b[1mstart-kbd-macro\u001b[0m \u001b[1m(C-x\u001b[0m \u001b[1m()\u001b[0m\u001b[m"]
