[3626.592719, "o", "              as  input  for setting or resetting the currently-\u001b[m\r\n              set variables.  Read-only variables cannot be  re‐\u001b[m\r\n              set.   In  \u001b[4mposix\u001b[24m  \u001b[4mmode\u001b[24m,  only  shell variables are\u001b[m\r\n"]
[3626.592725, "o", "              listed.  The output is  sorted  according  to  the\u001b[m\r\n              current  locale.  When options are specified, they\u001b[m\r\n              set or unset shell attributes.  Any arguments  re‐\u001b[m\r\n              maining  after  option  processing  are treated as\u001b[m\r\n              values for the positional parameters and  are  as‐\u001b[m\r\n              signed, in order, to \u001b[1m$1\u001b[0m, \u001b[1m$2\u001b[0m, \u001b[1m...\u001b[0m  \u001b[1m$\u001b[0m\u001b[4mn\u001b[24m.  Options, if\u001b[m\r\n              specified, have the following meanings:\u001b[m\r\n              \u001b[1m-a\u001b[0m      Each variable or function that is  created\u001b[m\r\n                      or  modified is given the export attribute\u001b[m\r\n                      and marked for export to  the  environment\u001b[m\r\n                      of subsequent commands.\u001b[m\r\n              \u001b[1m-b\u001b[0m    "]
[3626.592917, "o", "  Report the status of terminated background\u001b[m\r\n                      jobs immediately, rather than  before  the\u001b[m\r\n                      next  primary  prompt.   This is effective\u001b[m\r\n                      only when job control is enabled.\u001b[m\r\n              \u001b[1m-e\u001b[0m      Exit immediately if a \u001b[4mpipeline\u001b[24m (which  may\u001b[m\r\n                      consist  of  a  single  \u001b[4msimple\u001b[24m \u001b[4mcommand\u001b[24m), a\u001b[m\r\n                      \u001b[4mlist\u001b[24m, or a  \u001b[4mcompound\u001b[24m  \u001b[4mcommand\u001b[24m  (see  \u001b[1mSHELL\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n                      \u001b[1mGRAMMAR\u001b[0m above), exits with a non-zero sta‐\u001b[m\r\n                      tus.  The shell does not exit if the  com‐\u001b[m\r\n                      mand  that  fails  is  part of the command\u001b[m\r\n                      list immediately following a \u001b[1mwhile\u001b[0m or  \u001b[1mun‐\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n                      \u001b[1mtil\u001b[0m  keyword,  part  of the test following\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[7m Manual page bash(1) line 6709 (press h for help or q to quit)\u001b[27m\u001b[K"]
[3626.624087, "o", "\r\u001b[K"]
[3626.624114, "o", "                      the \u001b[1mif\u001b[0m or \u001b[1melif\u001b[0m reserved words, part of any\u001b[m\r\n                      command executed in a \u001b[1m&&\u001b[0m or \u001b[1m||\u001b[0m list except\u001b[m\r\n                      the command following the final \u001b[1m&&\u001b[0m or  \u001b[1m||\u001b[0m,\u001b[m\r\n                      any command in a pipeline but the last, or\u001b[m\r\n                      if the command's return value is being in‐\u001b[m\r\n                      verted  with  \u001b[1m!\u001b[0m.   If  a  compound command\u001b[m\r\n                      other than a subshell returns  a  non-zero\u001b[m\r\n                      status  because  a command failed while \u001b[1m-e\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n                      was being  ignored,  the  shell  does  not\u001b[m\r\n                      exit.   A trap on \u001b[1mERR\u001b[0m, if set, is executed\u001b[m\r\n                      before the shell exits.  This  option  ap‐\u001b[m\r\n                      plies  to  the  shell environment and each\u001b[m\r\n                      subshell environment separately (see  \u001b[1mCOM‐\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n                      \u001b[1mMAND\u001b[0m \u001b[1mEX"]
[3626.624118, "o", "ECUTION\u001b[0m "]
[3626.624274, "o", "\u001b[1mENVIRONMENT\u001b[0m above), and may\u001b[m\r\n                      cause subshells to exit  before  executing\u001b[m\r\n                      all the commands in the subshell.\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n                      If  a  compound  command or shell function\u001b[m\r\n                      executes in a context where  \u001b[1m-e\u001b[0m  is  being\u001b[m\r\n                      ignored,  none  of  the  commands executed\u001b[m\r\n                      within the compound  command  or  function\u001b[m\r\n                      body  will  be affected by the \u001b[1m-e\u001b[0m setting,\u001b[m\r\n                      even if \u001b[1m-e\u001b[0m is set and a command returns  a\u001b[m\r\n                      failure  status.  If a compound command or\u001b[m\r\n                      shell function sets \u001b[1m-e\u001b[0m while executing  in\u001b[m\r\n                      a  context  where \u001b[1m-e\u001b[0m is ignored, that set‐\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[7m Manual page bash(1) line 6735 (press h for help or q to quit)\u001b[27m\u001b[K"]
[3626.65506, "o", "\r\u001b[K"]
[3626.655202, "o", "                      ting will not have any  effect  until  the\u001b[m\r\n                      compound command or the command containing\u001b[m\r\n                      the function call completes.\u001b[m\r\n              \u001b[1m-f\u001b[0m      Disable pathname expansion.\u001b[m\r\n              \u001b[1m-h\u001b[0m      Remember the location of commands as  they\u001b[m\r\n                      are  looked up for execution.  This is en‐\u001b[m\r\n                      abled by default.\u001b[m\r\n              \u001b[1m-k\u001b[0m      All arguments in the  form  of  assignment\u001b[m\r\n                      statements  are  placed in the environment\u001b[m\r\n                      for a command, not just those that precede\u001b[m\r\n                      the command name.\u001b[m\r\n              \u001b[1m-m\u001b[0m      Monitor  mode.   Job  control  is enabled.\u001b[m\r\n                      This option is on by default for  interac‐\u001b[m\r\n                      tive  shells  on  systems  that support it\u001b[m\r\n                      (see \u001b[1mJOB\u001b[0m \u001b[1mCONTROL\u001b[0m  above).   All  processes\u001b[m\r\n                "]
[3626.655216, "o", "      run  in  a separate process group.  When a\u001b[m\r\n                      background job completes, the shell prints\u001b[m\r\n                      a line containing its exit status.\u001b[m\r\n              \u001b[1m-n\u001b[0m      Read  commands  but  do  not execute them.\u001b[m\r\n                      This may be used to check a  shell  script\u001b[m\r\n                      for syntax errors.  This is ignored by in‐\u001b[m\r\n                      teractive shells.\u001b[m\r\n              \u001b[1m-o\u001b[0m \u001b[4moption-name\u001b[24m\u001b[m\r\n                      The \u001b[4moption-name\u001b[24m can be one of the  follow‐\u001b[m\r\n                      ing:\u001b[m\r\n                      \u001b[1mallexport\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[7m Manual page bash(1) line 6761 (press h for help or q to quit)\u001b[27m\u001b[K"]
[3626.686246, "o", "\r\u001b[K"]
[3626.686399, "o", "                              Same as \u001b[1m-a\u001b[0m.\u001b[m\r\n                      \u001b[1mbraceexpand\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n                              Same as \u001b[1m-B\u001b[0m.\u001b[m\r\n                      \u001b[1memacs\u001b[0m   Use  an  emacs-style  command line\u001b[m\r\n                              editing interface.   This  is  en‐\u001b[m\r\n                              abled by default when the shell is\u001b[m\r\n                              interactive, unless the  shell  is\u001b[m\r\n                              started  with  the \u001b[1m--noediting\u001b[0m op‐\u001b[m\r\n                              tion.  This also affects the edit‐\u001b[m\r\n                              ing interface used for \u001b[1mread\u001b[0m \u001b[1m-e\u001b[0m.\u001b[m\r\n                      \u001b[1merrexit\u001b[0m Same as \u001b[1m-e\u001b[0m.\u001b[m\r\n                      \u001b[1merrtrace\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n                              Same as \u001b[1m-E\u001b[0m.\u001b[m\r\n                      \u001b[1mfunctrace\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n                              Same as \u001b[1m-T\u001b[0m.\u001b[m\r\n                      \u001b[1mhashall\u001b[0m Same as \u001b[1m-h\u001b[0m.\u001b[m\r\n                      \u001b[1mhistexp"]
[3626.686503, "o", "and\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n                              Same as \u001b[1m-H\u001b[0m.\u001b[m\r\n                      \u001b[1mhistory\u001b[0m Enable  command  history,  as  de‐\u001b[m\r\n                              scribed above under \u001b[1mHISTORY\u001b[0m.  This\u001b[m\r\n                              option  is on by default in inter‐\u001b[m\r\n                              active shells.\u001b[m\r\n                      \u001b[1mignoreeof\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n                              The effect is as if the shell com‐\u001b[m\r\n                              mand ``IGNOREEOF=10'' had been ex‐\u001b[m\r\n                              ecuted   (see   \u001b[1mShell\u001b[0m    \u001b[1mVariables\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[7m Manual page bash(1) line 6787 (press h for help or q to quit)\u001b[27m\u001b[K"]
