[3627.251126, "o", "                      name  that  exists at a previous scope be‐\u001b[m\r\n                      fore  any  new  value  is  assigned.   The\u001b[m\r\n                      nameref attribute is not inherited.\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n              \u001b[1mlocalvar_unset\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n                      If  set,  calling \u001b[1munset\u001b[0m on local variables\u001b[m\r\n                      in previous function scopes marks them  so\u001b[m\r\n                      subsequent  lookups  find them unset until\u001b[m\r\n                      that function returns. This  is  identical\u001b[m\r\n                      to  the  behavior of unsetting local vari‐\u001b[m\r\n                      ables at the current function scope.\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n              \u001b[1mlogin_shell\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n                      The  shell  sets  this  option  if  it  is\u001b[m\r\n                      started  as  a login shell (see \u001b[1mINVOCATION\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n                      above).  The value may not be changed.\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n              \u001b[1mmailwarn\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n                      If set, and a file that \u001b[1mbash\u001b[0m  is  "]
[3627.251131, "o", "checking\u001b[m\r\n                      for  mail has been accessed since the last\u001b[m\r\n                      time it was  checked,  the  message  ``The\u001b[m\r\n                      mail  in  \u001b[4mmailfile\u001b[24m has been read'' is dis‐\u001b[m\r\n                      played.\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n              \u001b[1mno_empty_cmd_completion\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n                      If set, and \u001b[1mreadline\u001b[0m is being  used,  \u001b[1mbash\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[7m Manual page bash(1) line 7255 (press h for help or q to quit)\u001b[27m\u001b[K"]
[3627.282452, "o", "\r\u001b[K                      will  not  attempt  to search the \u001b[1mPATH\u001b[0m for\u001b[m\r\n                      possible completions  when  completion  is\u001b[m\r\n                      attempted on an empty line.\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n              \u001b[1mnocaseglob\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n                      If   set,  \u001b[1mbash\u001b[0m  matches  filenames  in  a\u001b[m\r\n                      case-insensitive fashion  when  performing\u001b[m\r\n                      pathname expansion (see \u001b[1mPathname\u001b[0m \u001b[1mExpansion\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n                      above).\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n              \u001b[1mnocasematch\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n                      If  set,  \u001b[1mbash\u001b[0m  matches  patterns   in   a\u001b[m\r\n                      case-insensitive  fashion  when performing\u001b[m\r\n                      matching while executing \u001b[1mcase\u001b[0m or \u001b[1m[[\u001b[0m condi‐\u001b[m\r\n                      tional  commands,  when performing pattern\u001b[m\r\n                      substitution word expansions, or when fil‐\u001b[m\r\n                      tering  possible  completions  as  part of\u001b[m\r\n                      progra"]
[3627.282483, "o", "mmable completion.\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n              \u001b[1mnoexpand_translation\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n                      If set, \u001b[1mbash\u001b[0m encloses the  translated  re‐\u001b[m\r\n                      sults  of  $\"...\" quoting in single quotes\u001b[m\r\n                      instead of double quotes.  If  the  string\u001b[m\r\n                      is not translated, this has no effect.\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n              \u001b[1mnullglob\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[7m Manual page bash(1) line 7281 (press h for help or q to quit)\u001b[27m\u001b[K"]
[3627.313492, "o", "\r\u001b[K"]
[3627.313608, "o", "                      If  set,  \u001b[1mbash\u001b[0m allows patterns which match\u001b[m\r\n                      no files (see \u001b[1mPathname\u001b[0m \u001b[1mExpansion\u001b[0m above) to\u001b[m\r\n                      expand to a null string, rather than them‐\u001b[m\r\n                      selves.\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n              \u001b[1mpatsub_replacement\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n                      If set, \u001b[1mbash\u001b[0m expands occurrences of  \u001b[1m&\u001b[0m  in\u001b[m\r\n                      the  replacement string of pattern substi‐\u001b[m\r\n                      tution to the text matched by the pattern,\u001b[m\r\n                      as  described  under  \u001b[1mParameter\u001b[0m  \u001b[1mExpansion\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n                      above.  This option is enabled by default.\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n              \u001b[1mprogcomp\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n                      If set, the programmable completion facil‐\u001b[m\r\n                      ities  (see \u001b[1mProgrammable\u001b[0m \u001b[1mCompletion\u001b[0m above)\u001b[m\r\n                      are enabled.  This option  is  enabled  by\u001b[m\r\n                      default.\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n              \u001b[1mprogc"]
[3627.313658, "o", "omp_alias\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n                      If set, and programmable completion is en‐\u001b[m\r\n                      abled, \u001b[1mbash\u001b[0m treats  a  command  name  that\u001b[m\r\n                      doesn't have any completions as a possible\u001b[m\r\n                      alias and attempts alias expansion. If  it\u001b[m\r\n                      has  an  alias, \u001b[1mbash\u001b[0m attempts programmable\u001b[m\r\n                      completion using the command word  result‐\u001b[m\r\n                      ing from the expanded alias.\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[7m Manual page bash(1) line 7307 (press h for help or q to quit)\u001b[27m\u001b[K"]
[3627.344494, "o", "\r\u001b[K"]
[3627.344661, "o", "\u001b[m\r\n              \u001b[1mpromptvars\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n                      If  set,  prompt strings undergo parameter\u001b[m\r\n                      expansion,  command  substitution,  arith‐\u001b[m\r\n                      metic  expansion,  and quote removal after\u001b[m\r\n                      being expanded as described  in  \u001b[1mPROMPTING\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n                      above.  This option is enabled by default.\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n              \u001b[1mrestricted_shell\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n                      The  shell  sets  this  option  if  it  is\u001b[m\r\n                      started in restricted mode (see \u001b[1mRESTRICTED\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n                      \u001b[1mSHELL\u001b[0m   below).   The  value  may  not  be\u001b[m\r\n                      changed.   This  is  not  reset  when  the\u001b[m\r\n                      startup  files  are executed, allowing the\u001b[m\r\n                      startup files to discover whether or not a\u001b[m\r\n                      shell is restricted.\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n              \u001b[1mshift_verbose\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n                      If  set, the \u001b[1mshift\u001b[0m builtin "]
[3627.344774, "o", "prints an error\u001b[m\r\n                      message when the shift count  exceeds  the\u001b[m\r\n                      number of positional parameters.\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n              \u001b[1msourcepath\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n                      If  set,  the  \u001b[1m.\u001b[0m (\u001b[1msource\u001b[0m) builtin uses the\u001b[m\r\n                      value of \u001b[1mPATH\u001b[0m to find the  directory  con‐\u001b[m\r\n                      taining  the file supplied as an argument.\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[7m Manual page bash(1) line 7333 (press h for help or q to quit)\u001b[27m\u001b[K"]
[3627.375664, "o", "\r\u001b[K                      This option is enabled by default.\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n              \u001b[1mvarredir_close\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n                      If set,  the  shell  automatically  closes\u001b[m\r\n                      file  descriptors assigned using the \u001b[4m{var‐\u001b[24m\u001b[m\r\n                      \u001b[4mname}\u001b[24m redirection syntax (see  \u001b[1mREDIRECTION\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n                      above)  instead  of leaving them open when\u001b[m\r\n                      the command completes.\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n              \u001b[1mxpg_echo\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n                      If set, the  \u001b[1mecho\u001b[0m  builtin  expands  back‐\u001b[m\r\n                      slash-escape sequences by default.\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n       \u001b[1msuspend\u001b[0m [\u001b[1m-f\u001b[0m]\u001b[m\r\n              Suspend  the  execution of this shell until it re‐\u001b[m\r\n              ceives a \u001b[1mSIGCONT\u001b[0m signal.   A  login  shell,  or  a\u001b[m\r\n              shell  without job control enabled, cannot be sus‐\u001b[m\r\n              pended; the \u001b[1m-f\u001b[0m option can be used to override this\u001b[m\r\n              and  force the suspension"]
[3627.375801, "o", ".  The return status is 0\u001b[m\r\n              unless the shell is a login shell or  job  control\u001b[m\r\n              is not enabled and \u001b[1m-f\u001b[0m is not supplied.\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n       \u001b[1mtest\u001b[0m \u001b[4mexpr\u001b[24m\u001b[m\r\n       \u001b[1m[\u001b[0m \u001b[4mexpr\u001b[24m \u001b[1m]\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n              Return a status of 0 (true) or 1 (false) depending\u001b[m\r\n              on the evaluation of  the  conditional  expression\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[7m Manual page bash(1) line 7359 (press h for help or q to quit)\u001b[27m\u001b[K"]
[3627.407033, "o", "\r\u001b[K              \u001b[4mexpr\u001b[24m.   Each  operator and operand must be a sepa‐\u001b[m\r\n              rate argument.  Expressions are  composed  of  the\u001b[m\r\n              primaries  described  above  under \u001b[1mCONDITIONAL\u001b[0m \u001b[1mEX‐\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n              \u001b[1mPRESSIONS\u001b[0m.  \u001b[1mtest\u001b[0m does not accept any options,  nor\u001b[m\r\n              does  it  accept  and  ignore an argument of \u001b[1m--\u001b[0m as\u001b[m\r\n              signifying the end of options.\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n              Expressions may be combined  using  the  following\u001b[m\r\n              operators,  listed  in  decreasing order of prece‐\u001b[m\r\n              dence.  The evaluation depends on  the  number  of\u001b[m\r\n              arguments; see below.  Operator precedence is used\u001b[m\r\n              when there are five or more arguments.\u001b[m\r\n              \u001b[1m!\u001b[0m \u001b[4mexpr\u001b[24m True if \u001b[4mexpr\u001b[24m is false.\u001b[m\r\n              \u001b[1m(\u001b[0m \u001b[4mexpr\u001b[24m \u001b[1m)\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n                     Returns the value of  \u001b[4mexpr\u001b[24m.   This  may  be\u001b[m\r\n                     used  to"]
[3627.40706, "o", "  override the normal precedence of\u001b[m\r\n                     operators.\u001b[m\r\n              \u001b[4mexpr1\u001b[24m -\u001b[1ma\u001b[0m \u001b[4mexpr2\u001b[24m\u001b[m\r\n                     True if both \u001b[4mexpr1\u001b[24m and \u001b[4mexpr2\u001b[24m are true.\u001b[m\r\n              \u001b[4mexpr1\u001b[24m -\u001b[1mo\u001b[0m \u001b[4mexpr2\u001b[24m\u001b[m\r\n                     True if either \u001b[4mexpr1\u001b[24m or \u001b[4mexpr2\u001b[24m is true.\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n              \u001b[1mtest\u001b[0m and \u001b[1m[\u001b[0m evaluate conditional expressions  using\u001b[m\r\n              a set of rules based on the number of arguments.\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n              0 arguments\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[7m Manual page bash(1) line 7385 (press h for help or q to quit)\u001b[27m\u001b[K"]
[3627.439342, "o", "\r\u001b[K                     The expression is false.\u001b[m\r\n              1 argument\u001b[m\r\n                     The  expression  is true if and only if the\u001b[m\r\n                     argument is not null.\u001b[m\r\n              2 arguments\u001b[m\r\n                     If the first argument is \u001b[1m!\u001b[0m, the  expression\u001b[m\r\n                     is  true if and only if the second argument\u001b[m\r\n                     is null.  If the first argument is  one  of\u001b[m\r\n                     the   unary  conditional  operators  listed\u001b[m\r\n                     above under  \u001b[1mCONDITIONAL\u001b[0m  \u001b[1mEXPRESSIONS\u001b[0m,  the\u001b[m\r\n                     expression  is  true  if  the unary test is\u001b[m\r\n                     true.  If the first argument is not a valid\u001b[m\r\n                     unary  conditional operator, the expression\u001b[m\r\n                     is false.\u001b[m\r\n              3 arguments\u001b[m\r\n                     The following conditions are applied in the\u001b[m\r\n                     order  listed.   If  the second argument is\u001b[m\r\n                "]
[3627.439374, "o", "     one of  the  binary  conditional  operators\u001b[m\r\n                     listed above under \u001b[1mCONDITIONAL\u001b[0m \u001b[1mEXPRESSIONS\u001b[0m,\u001b[m\r\n                     the result of the expression is the  result\u001b[m\r\n                     of  the  binary  test  using  the first and\u001b[m\r\n                     third arguments as operands.  The \u001b[1m-a\u001b[0m and \u001b[1m-o\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n                     operators  are  considered binary operators\u001b[m\r\n                     when there are  three  arguments.   If  the\u001b[m\r\n                     first argument is \u001b[1m!\u001b[0m, the value is the nega‐\u001b[m\r\n                     tion of the  two-argument  test  using  the\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[7m Manual page bash(1) line 7411 (press h for help or q to quit)\u001b[27m\u001b[K"]
[3627.470643, "o", "\r\u001b[K                     second  and  third arguments.  If the first\u001b[m\r\n                     argument is exactly \u001b[1m(\u001b[0m and the  third  argu‐\u001b[m\r\n                     ment  is  exactly \u001b[1m)\u001b[0m, the result is the one-\u001b[m\r\n                     argument test of the second argument.  Oth‐\u001b[m\r\n                     erwise, the expression is false.\u001b[m\r\n              4 arguments\u001b[m\r\n                     The following conditions are applied in the\u001b[m\r\n                     order listed.  If the first argument is  \u001b[1m!\u001b[0m,\u001b[m\r\n                     the result is the negation of the three-ar‐\u001b[m\r\n                     gument expression composed of the remaining\u001b[m\r\n                     arguments.  the two-argument test using the\u001b[m\r\n                     second and third arguments.  If  the  first\u001b[m\r\n                     argument  is exactly \u001b[1m(\u001b[0m and the fourth argu‐\u001b[m\r\n                     ment is exactly \u001b[1m)\u001b[0m, the result is  the  two-\u001b[m\r\n                     argument test of the second and thi"]
[3627.470767, "o", "rd argu‐\u001b[m\r\n                     ments.  Otherwise, the expression is parsed\u001b[m\r\n                     and evaluated according to precedence using\u001b[m\r\n                     the rules listed above.\u001b[m\r\n              5 or more arguments\u001b[m\r\n                     The expression is parsed and evaluated  ac‐\u001b[m\r\n                     cording   to  precedence  using  the  rules\u001b[m\r\n                     listed above.\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n              When used with \u001b[1mtest\u001b[0m or \u001b[1m[\u001b[0m, the \u001b[1m<\u001b[0m  and  \u001b[1m>\u001b[0m  operators\u001b[m\r\n              sort lexicographically using ASCII ordering.\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[7m Manual page bash(1) line 7437 (press h for help or q to quit)\u001b[27m\u001b[K"]
[3627.501714, "o", "\r\u001b[K"]
[3627.501814, "o", "       \u001b[1mtimes\u001b[0m  Print  the  accumulated  user and system times for\u001b[m\r\n              the shell and for processes run  from  the  shell.\u001b[m\r\n              The return status is 0.\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n       \u001b[1mtrap\u001b[0m [\u001b[1m-lp\u001b[0m] [[\u001b[4marg\u001b[24m] \u001b[4msigspec\u001b[24m ...]\u001b[m\r\n              The  command  \u001b[4marg\u001b[24m  is to be read and executed when\u001b[m\r\n              the shell receives signal(s) \u001b[4msigspec\u001b[24m.  If  \u001b[4marg\u001b[24m  is\u001b[m\r\n              absent  (and there is a single \u001b[4msigspec\u001b[24m) or \u001b[1m-\u001b[0m, each\u001b[m\r\n              specified signal is reset to its original disposi‐\u001b[m\r\n              tion  (the  value  it  had  upon  entrance  to the\u001b[m\r\n              shell).  If \u001b[4marg\u001b[24m is  the  null  string  the  signal\u001b[m\r\n              specified  by each \u001b[4msigspec\u001b[24m is ignored by the shell\u001b[m\r\n              and by the commands it invokes.   If  \u001b[4marg\u001b[24m  is  not\u001b[m\r\n              present  and  \u001b[1m-p\u001b[0m  has been supplied, then the trap\u001b[m\r\n              commands associated with  each  \u001b[4msig"]
[3627.501856, "o", "spec\u001b[24m  are  dis‐\u001b[m\r\n              played.   If  no arguments are supplied or if only\u001b[m\r\n              \u001b[1m-p\u001b[0m is given, \u001b[1mtrap\u001b[0m prints the list of commands  as‐\u001b[m\r\n              sociated  with  each signal.  The \u001b[1m-l\u001b[0m option causes\u001b[m\r\n              the shell to print a  list  of  signal  names  and\u001b[m\r\n              their  corresponding numbers.  Each \u001b[4msigspec\u001b[24m is ei‐\u001b[m\r\n              ther a signal name defined  in  <\u001b[4msignal.h\u001b[24m>,  or  a\u001b[m\r\n              signal  number.  Signal names are case insensitive\u001b[m\r\n              and the \u001b[1mSIG\u001b[0m prefix is optional.\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n              If a \u001b[4msigspec\u001b[24m is \u001b[1mEXIT\u001b[0m (0) the command \u001b[4marg\u001b[24m  is  exe‐\u001b[m\r\n              cuted on exit from the shell.  If a \u001b[4msigspec\u001b[24m is \u001b[1mDE‐\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[7m Manual page bash(1) line 7463 (press h for help or q to quit)\u001b[27m\u001b[K"]
[3627.532507, "o", "\r\u001b[K"]
[3627.532632, "o", "              \u001b[1mBUG\u001b[0m, the command \u001b[4marg\u001b[24m is executed before every \u001b[4msim‐\u001b[24m\u001b[m\r\n              \u001b[4mple\u001b[24m  \u001b[4mcommand\u001b[24m,  \u001b[4mfor\u001b[24m  command,  \u001b[4mcase\u001b[24m command, \u001b[4mselect\u001b[24m\u001b[m\r\n              command, every arithmetic \u001b[4mfor\u001b[24m command, and  before\u001b[m\r\n              the  first  command  executes  in a shell function\u001b[m\r\n              (see \u001b[1mSHELL\u001b[0m \u001b[1mGRAMMAR\u001b[0m above).  Refer to the  descrip‐\u001b[m\r\n              tion  of  the \u001b[1mextdebug\u001b[0m option to the \u001b[1mshopt\u001b[0m builtin\u001b[m\r\n              for details of its effect on the \u001b[1mDEBUG\u001b[0m trap.  If a\u001b[m\r\n              \u001b[4msigspec\u001b[24m  is  \u001b[1mRETURN\u001b[0m,  the  command \u001b[4marg\u001b[24m is executed\u001b[m\r\n              each time a shell function or  a  script  executed\u001b[m\r\n              with the \u001b[1m.\u001b[0m or \u001b[1msource\u001b[0m builtins finishes executing.\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n              If  a  \u001b[4msigspec\u001b[24m is \u001b[1mERR\u001b[0m, the command \u001b[4marg\u001b[24m is executed\u001b[m\r\n              whenever a pipeline (which may consist of a single\u001b[m\r\n"]
[3627.532719, "o", "              simple command), a list, or a compound command re‐\u001b[m\r\n              turns a non-zero exit status, subject to the  fol‐\u001b[m\r\n              lowing  conditions.   The \u001b[1mERR\u001b[0m trap is not executed\u001b[m\r\n              if the failed command is part of the command  list\u001b[m\r\n              immediately  following  a  \u001b[1mwhile\u001b[0m or \u001b[1muntil\u001b[0m keyword,\u001b[m\r\n              part of the test in an \u001b[4mif\u001b[24m  statement,  part  of  a\u001b[m\r\n              command  executed  in  a  \u001b[1m&&\u001b[0m or \u001b[1m||\u001b[0m list except the\u001b[m\r\n              command following the final \u001b[1m&&\u001b[0m or \u001b[1m||\u001b[0m, any  command\u001b[m\r\n              in  a  pipeline  but the last, or if the command's\u001b[m\r\n              return value is being inverted using \u001b[1m!\u001b[0m.  These are\u001b[m\r\n              the same conditions obeyed by the \u001b[1merrexit\u001b[0m (\u001b[1m-e\u001b[0m) op‐\u001b[m\r\n              tion.\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[7m Manual page bash(1) line 7489 (press h for help or q to quit)\u001b[27m\u001b[K"]
[3627.56368, "o", "\r\u001b[K"]
[3627.563803, "o", "              Signals ignored upon entry to the shell cannot  be\u001b[m\r\n              trapped  or  reset.   Trapped signals that are not\u001b[m\r\n              being ignored are reset to their  original  values\u001b[m\r\n              in  a subshell or subshell environment when one is\u001b[m\r\n              created.   The  return  status  is  false  if  any\u001b[m\r\n              \u001b[4msigspec\u001b[24m is invalid; otherwise \u001b[1mtrap\u001b[0m returns true.\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n       \u001b[1mtype\u001b[0m [\u001b[1m-aftpP\u001b[0m] \u001b[4mname\u001b[24m [\u001b[4mname\u001b[24m ...]\u001b[m\r\n              With  no  options, indicate how each \u001b[4mname\u001b[24m would be\u001b[m\r\n              interpreted if used as a command name.  If the  \u001b[1m-t\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n              option  is used, \u001b[1mtype\u001b[0m prints a string which is one\u001b[m\r\n              of \u001b[4malias\u001b[24m, \u001b[4mkeyword\u001b[24m, \u001b[4mfunction\u001b[24m, \u001b[4mbuiltin\u001b[24m, or  \u001b[4mfile\u001b[24m  if\u001b[m\r\n              \u001b[4mname\u001b[24m  is  an alias, shell reserved word, function,\u001b[m\r\n              builtin, or disk file, respectively.  If the  \u001b[4mname\u001b[24m\u001b[m\r\n             "]
[3627.563818, "o", " is not found, then nothing is printed, and an exit\u001b[m\r\n              status of false is returned.  If the \u001b[1m-p\u001b[0m option  is\u001b[m\r\n              used,  \u001b[1mtype\u001b[0m  either  returns  the name of the disk\u001b[m\r\n              file that would be executed if \u001b[4mname\u001b[24m were specified\u001b[m\r\n              as  a command name, or nothing if ``type -t name''\u001b[m\r\n              would not return \u001b[4mfile\u001b[24m.  The  \u001b[1m-P\u001b[0m  option  forces  a\u001b[m\r\n              \u001b[1mPATH\u001b[0m  search  for  each  \u001b[4mname\u001b[24m,  even  if ``type -t\u001b[m\r\n              name'' would not return \u001b[4mfile\u001b[24m.   If  a  command  is\u001b[m\r\n              hashed, \u001b[1m-p\u001b[0m and \u001b[1m-P\u001b[0m print the hashed value, which is\u001b[m\r\n              not necessarily the file  that  appears  first  in\u001b[m\r\n              \u001b[1mPATH\u001b[0m.   If  the \u001b[1m-a\u001b[0m option is used, \u001b[1mtype\u001b[0m prints all\u001b[m\r\n              of the places that  contain  an  executable  named\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[7m Manual page bash(1) line 7515 (press h for help or q to quit)\u001b[27m\u001b[K"]
[3627.595505, "o", "\r\u001b[K              \u001b[4mname\u001b[24m.  This includes aliases and functions, if and\u001b[m\r\n              only if the \u001b[1m-p\u001b[0m option is not also used.  The table\u001b[m\r\n              of hashed commands is not consulted when using \u001b[1m-a\u001b[0m.\u001b[m\r\n              The \u001b[1m-f\u001b[0m option suppresses shell function lookup, as\u001b[m\r\n              with  the  \u001b[1mcommand\u001b[0m  builtin.  \u001b[1mtype\u001b[0m returns true if\u001b[m\r\n              all of the arguments are found, false if  any  are\u001b[m\r\n              not found.\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n       \u001b[1mulimit\u001b[0m [\u001b[1m-HS\u001b[0m] \u001b[1m-a\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n       \u001b[1mulimit\u001b[0m [\u001b[1m-HS\u001b[0m] [\u001b[1m-bcdefiklmnpqrstuvxPRT\u001b[0m [\u001b[4mlimit\u001b[24m]]\u001b[m\r\n              Provides  control  over the resources available to\u001b[m\r\n              the shell and to processes started by it, on  sys‐\u001b[m\r\n              tems  that  allow such control.  The \u001b[1m-H\u001b[0m and \u001b[1m-S\u001b[0m op‐\u001b[m\r\n              tions specify that the hard or soft limit  is  set\u001b[m\r\n              for  the  given  resource.  A hard limit cannot be\u001b[m\r\n              inc"]
[3627.595628, "o", "reased by a non-root user once  it  is  set;  a\u001b[m\r\n              soft limit may be increased up to the value of the\u001b[m\r\n              hard limit.  If neither \u001b[1m-H\u001b[0m nor  \u001b[1m-S\u001b[0m  is  specified,\u001b[m\r\n              both  the soft and hard limits are set.  The value\u001b[m\r\n              of \u001b[4mlimit\u001b[24m can be a number in the unit specified for\u001b[m\r\n              the  resource  or  one of the special values \u001b[1mhard\u001b[0m,\u001b[m\r\n              \u001b[1msoft\u001b[0m, or \u001b[1munlimited\u001b[0m, which stand  for  the  current\u001b[m\r\n              hard  limit, the current soft limit, and no limit,\u001b[m\r\n              respectively.  If \u001b[4mlimit\u001b[24m is  omitted,  the  current\u001b[m\r\n              value  of  the  soft  limit  of  the  resource  is\u001b[m\r\n              printed, unless the \u001b[1m-H\u001b[0m option is given.  When more\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[7m Manual page bash(1) line 7541 (press h for help or q to quit)\u001b[27m\u001b[K"]
[3627.626176, "o", "\r\u001b[K"]
[3627.626204, "o", "              than one resource is specified, the limit name and\u001b[m\r\n              unit,  if  appropriate,  are  printed  before  the\u001b[m\r\n              value.  Other options are interpreted as follows:\u001b[m\r\n              \u001b[1m-a\u001b[0m     All  current limits are reported; no limits\u001b[m\r\n                     are set\u001b[m\r\n              \u001b[1m-b\u001b[0m     The maximum socket buffer size\u001b[m\r\n              \u001b[1m-c\u001b[0m     The maximum size of core files created\u001b[m\r\n              \u001b[1m-d\u001b[0m     The maximum size of a process's  data  seg‐\u001b[m\r\n                     ment\u001b[m\r\n              \u001b[1m-e\u001b[0m     The maximum scheduling priority (\"nice\")\u001b[m\r\n              \u001b[1m-f\u001b[0m     The  maximum  size  of files written by the\u001b[m\r\n                     shell and its children\u001b[m\r\n              \u001b[1m-i\u001b[0m     The maximum number of pending signals\u001b[m\r\n              \u001b[1m-k\u001b[0m     The maximum number of kqueues that  may  be\u001b[m\r\n                     allocated\u001b[m\r\n              \u001b[1m-l\u001b[0m     The  maximum  size  that may be locked into\u001b[m\r\n    "]
[3627.626288, "o", "                 memory\u001b[m\r\n              \u001b[1m-m\u001b[0m     The maximum resident set size (many systems\u001b[m\r\n                     do not honor this limit)\u001b[m\r\n              \u001b[1m-n\u001b[0m     The maximum number of open file descriptors\u001b[m\r\n                     (most systems do not allow this value to be\u001b[m\r\n                     set)\u001b[m\r\n              \u001b[1m-p\u001b[0m     The  pipe size in 512-byte blocks (this may\u001b[m\r\n                     not be set)\u001b[m\r\n              \u001b[1m-q\u001b[0m     The maximum number of bytes in  POSIX  mes‐\u001b[m\r\n                     sage queues\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[7m Manual page bash(1) line 7567 (press h for help or q to quit)\u001b[27m\u001b[K"]
[3627.658339, "o", "\r\u001b[K              \u001b[1m-r\u001b[0m     The maximum real-time scheduling priority\u001b[m\r\n              \u001b[1m-s\u001b[0m     The maximum stack size\u001b[m\r\n              \u001b[1m-t\u001b[0m     The maximum amount of cpu time in seconds\u001b[m\r\n              \u001b[1m-u\u001b[0m     The  maximum  number of processes available\u001b[m\r\n                     to a single user\u001b[m\r\n              \u001b[1m-v\u001b[0m     The maximum amount of virtual memory avail‐\u001b[m\r\n                     able  to the shell and, on some systems, to\u001b[m\r\n                     its children\u001b[m\r\n              \u001b[1m-x\u001b[0m     The maximum number of file locks\u001b[m\r\n              \u001b[1m-P\u001b[0m     The maximum number of pseudoterminals\u001b[m\r\n              \u001b[1m-R\u001b[0m     The maximum time a  real-time  process  can\u001b[m\r\n                     run before blocking, in microseconds\u001b[m\r\n              \u001b[1m-T\u001b[0m     The maximum number of threads\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n              If  \u001b[4mlimit\u001b[24m is given, and the \u001b[1m-a\u001b[0m option is not used,\u001b[m\r\n              \u001b[4mlimit\u001b[24m is the new value of the specified  resource.\u001b[m\r\n "]
[3627.658362, "o", "             If no "]
[3627.658384, "o", "option is given, then \u001b[1m-f\u001b[0m is assumed.  Values\u001b[m\r\n              are in 1024-byte increments, except for \u001b[1m-t\u001b[0m,  which\u001b[m\r\n              is  in  seconds; \u001b[1m-R\u001b[0m, which is in microseconds; \u001b[1m-p\u001b[0m,\u001b[m\r\n              which is in units of 512-byte blocks; \u001b[1m-P\u001b[0m, \u001b[1m-T\u001b[0m,  \u001b[1m-b\u001b[0m,\u001b[m\r\n              \u001b[1m-k\u001b[0m,  \u001b[1m-n\u001b[0m,  and  \u001b[1m-u\u001b[0m, which are unscaled values; and,\u001b[m\r\n              when in posix  mode,  \u001b[1m-c\u001b[0m  and  \u001b[1m-f\u001b[0m,  which  are  in\u001b[m\r\n              512-byte  increments.   The return status is 0 un‐\u001b[m\r\n              less an invalid option or argument is supplied, or\u001b[m\r\n              an error occurs while setting a new limit.\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[7m Manual page bash(1) line 7593 (press h for help or q to quit)\u001b[27m\u001b[K"]
[3627.690394, "o", "\r\u001b[K       \u001b[1mumask\u001b[0m [\u001b[1m-p\u001b[0m] [\u001b[1m-S\u001b[0m] [\u001b[4mmode\u001b[24m]\u001b[m\r\n              The  user  file-creation  mask is set to \u001b[4mmode\u001b[24m.  If\u001b[m\r\n              \u001b[4mmode\u001b[24m begins with a digit, it is interpreted as  an\u001b[m\r\n              octal  number;  otherwise  it  is interpreted as a\u001b[m\r\n              symbolic mode mask similar  to  that  accepted  by\u001b[m\r\n              \u001b[4mchmod\u001b[24m(1).   If  \u001b[4mmode\u001b[24m is omitted, the current value\u001b[m\r\n"]
[3627.690522, "o", "              of the mask is printed.  The \u001b[1m-S\u001b[0m option causes  the\u001b[m\r\n              mask  to  be printed in symbolic form; the default\u001b[m\r\n              output is an octal number.  If the  \u001b[1m-p\u001b[0m  option  is\u001b[m\r\n              supplied,  and \u001b[4mmode\u001b[24m is omitted, the output is in a\u001b[m\r\n              form that may be reused as input.  The return sta‐\u001b[m\r\n              tus  is  0 if the mode was successfully changed or\u001b[m\r\n              if no \u001b[4mmode\u001b[24m argument was supplied, and false other‐\u001b[m\r\n              wise.\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n       \u001b[1munalias\u001b[0m [-\u001b[1ma\u001b[0m] [\u001b[4mname\u001b[24m ...]\u001b[m\r\n              Remove each \u001b[4mname\u001b[24m from the list of defined aliases.\u001b[m\r\n              If \u001b[1m-a\u001b[0m is supplied, all alias definitions  are  re‐\u001b[m\r\n              moved.  The return value is true unless a supplied\u001b[m\r\n              \u001b[4mname\u001b[24m is not a defined alias.\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n       \u001b[1munset\u001b[0m [-\u001b[1mfv\u001b[0m] [-\u001b[1mn\u001b[0m] [\u001b[4mname\u001b[24m ...]\u001b[m\r\n              For each \u001b[4mname\u001b[24m, remove the  corre"]
[3627.690536, "o", "sponding  variable\u001b[m\r\n              or function.  If the \u001b[1m-v\u001b[0m option is given, each \u001b[4mname\u001b[24m\u001b[m\r\n              refers to a shell variable, and that  variable  is\u001b[m\r\n              removed.   Read-only  variables  may not be unset.\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[7m Manual page bash(1) line 7619 (press h for help or q to quit)\u001b[27m\u001b[K"]
[3627.721287, "o", "\r\u001b[K"]
[3627.721395, "o", "              If \u001b[1m-f\u001b[0m is specified, each \u001b[4mname\u001b[24m refers  to  a  shell\u001b[m\r\n              function,  and the function definition is removed.\u001b[m\r\n              If the \u001b[1m-n\u001b[0m option is supplied, and \u001b[4mname\u001b[24m is a  vari‐\u001b[m\r\n              able  with the \u001b[4mnameref\u001b[24m attribute, \u001b[4mname\u001b[24m will be un‐\u001b[m\r\n              set rather than the variable  it  references.   \u001b[1m-n\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n              has no effect if the \u001b[1m-f\u001b[0m option is supplied.  If no\u001b[m\r\n              options are supplied, each \u001b[4mname\u001b[24m refers to a  vari‐\u001b[m\r\n              able;  if  there  is  no  variable by that name, a\u001b[m\r\n              function with that name, if any, is  unset.   Each\u001b[m\r\n              unset variable or function is removed from the en‐\u001b[m\r\n              vironment passed to subsequent commands.   If  any\u001b[m\r\n              of  \u001b[1mBASH_ALIASES\u001b[0m, \u001b[1mBASH_ARGV0\u001b[0m, \u001b[1mBASH_CMDS\u001b[0m, \u001b[1mBASH_COM‐\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n              \u001b[1mMAND\u001b[0m,  \u001b[1mBASH_SUBSHELL\u001b[0m,  \u001b[1mBASHPID\u001b[0m,   \u001b[1mC"]
[3627.721428, "o", "OMP_WORDBREAKS\u001b[0m,\u001b[m\r\n              \u001b[1mDIRSTACK\u001b[0m,  \u001b[1mEPOCHREALTIME\u001b[0m,  \u001b[1mEPOCHSECONDS\u001b[0m, \u001b[1mFUNCNAME\u001b[0m,\u001b[m\r\n              \u001b[1mGROUPS\u001b[0m, \u001b[1mHISTCMD\u001b[0m, \u001b[1mLINENO\u001b[0m, \u001b[1mRANDOM\u001b[0m, \u001b[1mSECONDS\u001b[0m, or \u001b[1mSRAN‐\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n              \u001b[1mDOM\u001b[0m are unset, they lose their special properties,\u001b[m\r\n              even if they are  subsequently  reset.   The  exit\u001b[m\r\n              status  is  true  unless a \u001b[4mname\u001b[24m is readonly or may\u001b[m\r\n              not be unset.\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n       \u001b[1mwait\u001b[0m [\u001b[1m-fn\u001b[0m] [\u001b[1m-p\u001b[0m \u001b[4mvarname\u001b[24m] [\u001b[4mid\u001b[24m \u001b[4m...\u001b[24m]\u001b[m\r\n              Wait for each specified child process  and  return\u001b[m\r\n              its  termination status.  Each \u001b[4mid\u001b[24m may be a process\u001b[m\r\n              ID or a job specification; if a job spec is given,\u001b[m\r\n              all  processes  in  that job's pipeline are waited\u001b[m\r\n              for.  If \u001b[4mid\u001b[24m is not given, \u001b[1mwait\u001b[0m waits for all  run‐\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[7m Manual page bash(1) line 7645 (press h for hel"]
[3627.721446, "o", "p or q to quit)\u001b[27m\u001b[K"]
[3627.752618, "o", "\r\u001b[K"]
[3627.752779, "o", "              ning background jobs and the last-executed process\u001b[m\r\n              substitution, if its process id is the same as \u001b[1m$!\u001b[0m,\u001b[m\r\n              and  the  return status is zero.  If the \u001b[1m-n\u001b[0m option\u001b[m\r\n              is supplied, \u001b[1mwait\u001b[0m waits for a single job from  the\u001b[m\r\n              list  of  \u001b[4mid\u001b[24ms or, if no \u001b[4mid\u001b[24ms are supplied, any job,\u001b[m\r\n              to complete and returns its exit status.  If  none\u001b[m\r\n              of the supplied arguments is a child of the shell,\u001b[m\r\n              or if no arguments are supplied and the shell  has\u001b[m\r\n              no  unwaited-for children, the exit status is 127.\u001b[m\r\n              If the \u001b[1m-p\u001b[0m option is supplied, the process  or  job\u001b[m\r\n              identifier of the job for which the exit status is\u001b[m\r\n              returned is assigned to the variable \u001b[4mvarname\u001b[24m named\u001b[m\r\n              by  the option argument.  The variable will be un‐\u001b[m\r\n              set initially, before  any  assignment.   This  is\u001b["]
[3627.752817, "o", "m\r\n              useful  only when the \u001b[1m-n\u001b[0m option is supplied.  Sup‐\u001b[m\r\n              plying the \u001b[1m-f\u001b[0m option, when job control is enabled,\u001b[m\r\n              forces \u001b[1mwait\u001b[0m to wait for \u001b[4mid\u001b[24m to terminate before re‐\u001b[m\r\n              turning its status, instead of returning  when  it\u001b[m\r\n              changes  status.   If  \u001b[4mid\u001b[24m specifies a non-existent\u001b[m\r\n              process or job, the return status is 127.  If \u001b[1mwait\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n              is interrupted by a signal, the return status will\u001b[m\r\n              be greater than 128, as  described  under  \u001b[1mSIGNALS\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n              above.   Otherwise,  the return status is the exit\u001b[m\r\n              status of the last process or job waited for.\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[1mSHELL\u001b[0m \u001b[1mCOMPATIBILITY\u001b[0m \u001b[1mMODE\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[7m Manual page bash(1) line 7671 (press h for help or q to quit)\u001b[27m\u001b[K"]
[3627.784276, "o", "\r\u001b[K"]
[3627.784394, "o", "       Bash-4.0 introduced the concept of a \u001b[4mshell\u001b[24m  \u001b[4mcompatibility\u001b[24m\u001b[m\r\n       \u001b[4mlevel\u001b[24m, specified as a set of options to the shopt builtin\u001b[m\r\n       ( \u001b[1mcompat31\u001b[0m, \u001b[1mcompat32\u001b[0m, \u001b[1mcompat40\u001b[0m,  \u001b[1mcompat41\u001b[0m,  and  so  on).\u001b[m\r\n       There is only one current compatibility level -- each op‐\u001b[m\r\n       tion is mutually exclusive.  The compatibility  level  is\u001b[m\r\n       intended  to allow users to select behavior from previous\u001b[m\r\n       versions that is incompatible with newer  versions  while\u001b[m\r\n       they  migrate  scripts to use current features and behav‐\u001b[m\r\n       ior. It's intended to be a temporary solution.\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n       This section does not mention behavior that  is  standard\u001b[m\r\n       for  a  particular  version (e.g., setting \u001b[1mcompat32\u001b[0m means\u001b[m\r\n       that quoting the rhs  of  the  regexp  matching  operator\u001b[m\r\n       quotes  special  regexp  characters in the word, which is\u001b[m\r\n       default behavior in bash-3.2 and subsequent versions).\u001b"]
[3627.784521, "o", "[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n       If a user enables, say, \u001b[1mcompat32\u001b[0m, it may affect  the  be‐\u001b[m\r\n       havior  of other compatibility levels up to and including\u001b[m\r\n       the current compatibility level.  The idea is  that  each\u001b[m\r\n       compatibility  level  controls  behavior  that changed in\u001b[m\r\n       that version of \u001b[1mbash\u001b[0m, but that  behavior  may  have  been\u001b[m\r\n       present in earlier versions.  For instance, the change to\u001b[m\r\n       use locale-based comparisons with the \u001b[1m[[\u001b[0m command came  in\u001b[m\r\n       bash-4.1,  and  earlier versions used ASCII-based compar‐\u001b[m\r\n       isons, so enabling \u001b[1mcompat32\u001b[0m will enable ASCII-based  com‐\u001b[m\r\n       parisons as well.  That granularity may not be sufficient\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[7m Manual page bash(1) line 7697 (press h for help or q to quit)\u001b[27m\u001b[K"]
[3627.81613, "o", "\r\u001b[K       for all uses, and as a result users should employ compat‐\u001b[m\r\n       ibility  levels  carefully.  Read the documentation for a\u001b[m\r\n       particular feature to find out the current behavior.\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n       Bash-4.3 introduced a new  shell  variable:  \u001b[1mBASH_COMPAT\u001b[0m.\u001b[m\r\n       The  value  assigned  to this variable (a decimal version\u001b[m\r\n       number like 4.2, or an integer corresponding to the  \u001b[1mcom‐\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n       \u001b[1mpat\u001b[0m\u001b[4mNN\u001b[24m  option,  like  42)  determines  the  compatibility\u001b[m\r\n       level.\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n       Starting with bash-4.4, Bash has begun deprecating  older\u001b[m\r\n       compatibility  levels.   Eventually,  the options will be\u001b[m\r\n       removed in favor of \u001b[1mBASH_COMPAT\u001b[0m.\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n       Bash-5.0 is the final version for which there will be  an\u001b[m\r\n       individual  shopt  option for the previous version. Users\u001b[m\r\n       should use \u001b[1mBASH_COMPAT\u001b[0m on bash-5.0 and later versions.\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n       The following table describes the behavior  changes  con"]
[3627.816276, "o", "‐\u001b[m\r\n       trolled  by  each  compatibility level setting.  The \u001b[1mcom‐\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n       \u001b[1mpat\u001b[0m\u001b[4mNN\u001b[24m tag is used as shorthand for setting  the  compati‐\u001b[m\r\n       bility level to \u001b[4mNN\u001b[24m using one of the following mechanisms.\u001b[m\r\n       For versions prior to bash-5.0, the  compatibility  level\u001b[m\r\n       may be set using the corresponding \u001b[1mcompat\u001b[0m\u001b[4mNN\u001b[24m shopt option.\u001b[m\r\n       For bash-4.3 and later versions, the \u001b[1mBASH_COMPAT\u001b[0m variable\u001b[m\r\n       is  preferred,  and it is required for bash-5.1 and later\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[7m Manual page bash(1) line 7723 (press h for help or q to quit)\u001b[27m\u001b[K"]
[3627.853757, "o", "\r\u001b[K"]
[3627.853857, "o", "       versions.\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n       \u001b[1mcompat31\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n"]
[3627.853873, "o", "              •      quoting the rhs of the \u001b[1m[[\u001b[0m command's  regexp\u001b[m\r\n                     matching  operator  (=~) has no special ef‐\u001b[m\r\n                     fect\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n       \u001b[1mcompat32\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n              •      interrupting a command list such as \"a ;  b\u001b[m\r\n                     ;  c\" causes the execution of the next com‐\u001b[m\r\n                     mand in the list  (in  bash-4.0  and  later\u001b[m\r\n                     versions,  the shell acts as if it received\u001b[m\r\n                     the interrupt, so interrupting one  command\u001b[m\r\n                     in  a  list aborts the execution of the en‐\u001b[m\r\n                     tire list)\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n       \u001b[1mcompat40\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n              •      the \u001b[1m<\u001b[0m and \u001b[1m>\u001b[0m operators to the \u001b[1m[[\u001b[0m command  do\u001b[m\r\n                     not  consider  the current locale when com‐\u001b[m\r\n                     paring strings; they  use  ASCII  ordering.\u001b[m\r\n                     Bash  versions  prior to bash-4.1 use ASCII\u001b[m\r\n                  "]
[3627.85388, "o", "   collation and "]
[3627.853886, "o", "\u001b[4mstrcmp\u001b[24m(3); bash-4.1 and later\u001b[m"]
[3627.853891, "o", "\r\n                     use the current locale's collation sequence\u001b[m"]
[3627.853896, "o", "\r\n"]
[3627.853908, "o", "                     and \u001b[4mstrcoll\u001b[24m(3).\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n       \u001b[1mcompat41\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n"]
[3627.853915, "o", "\u001b[7m Manual page bash(1) line 7749 (press h for help or q to quit)\u001b[27m\u001b[K"]
[3627.878606, "o", "\r\u001b[K"]
[3627.87865, "o", "              •      in \u001b[4mposix\u001b[24m mode, \u001b[1mtime\u001b[0m may be followed by  op‐\u001b[m\r\n                     tions and still be recognized as a reserved\u001b[m\r\n                     word (this is POSIX interpretation 267)\u001b[m\r\n              •      in \u001b[4mposix\u001b[24m mode, the parser requires that  an\u001b[m\r\n                     even  number  of single quotes occur in the\u001b[m\r\n                     \u001b[4mword\u001b[24m portion of a  double-quoted  parameter\u001b[m\r\n                     expansion  and  treats  them  specially, so\u001b[m\r\n                     that characters within  the  single  quotes\u001b[m\r\n                     are considered quoted (this is POSIX inter‐\u001b[m\r\n                     pretation 221)\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n       \u001b[1mcompat42\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n              •      the  replacement  string  in  double-quoted\u001b[m\r\n                     pattern substitution does not undergo quote\u001b[m\r\n                     removal,  as  it  does  in  versions  after\u001b[m\r\n                     bash-4.2\u001b[m\r\n              •      in posix mode, single quo"]
[3627.878659, "o", "tes are considered\u001b[m\r\n                     special when expanding the \u001b[4mword\u001b[24m portion  of\u001b[m\r\n                     a double-quoted parameter expansion and can\u001b[m\r\n                     be used to quote a closing brace  or  other\u001b[m\r\n                     special  character  (this  is part of POSIX\u001b[m\r\n                     interpretation  221);  in  later  versions,\u001b[m\r\n                     single  quotes  are not special within dou‐\u001b[m\r\n                     ble-quoted word expansions\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n       \u001b[1mcompat43\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[7m Manual page bash(1) line 7775 (press h for help or q to quit)\u001b[27m\u001b[K"]
[3627.909599, "o", "\r\u001b[K"]
[3627.909688, "o", "              •      the shell does not print a warning  message\u001b[m\r\n                     if  an attempt is made to use a quoted com‐\u001b[m\r\n                     pound assignment as an argument to  declare\u001b[m\r\n                     (e.g.,  declare -a foo='(1 2)'). Later ver‐\u001b[m\r\n                     sions warn that this usage is deprecated\u001b[m\r\n              •      word expansion errors are  considered  non-\u001b[m\r\n                     fatal errors that cause the current command\u001b[m\r\n                     to fail, even in posix  mode  (the  default\u001b[m\r\n                     behavior  is to make them fatal errors that\u001b[m\r\n                     cause the shell to exit)\u001b[m\r\n              •      when executing a shell function,  the  loop\u001b[m\r\n                     state  (while/until/etc.)  is not reset, so\u001b[m\r\n                     \u001b[1mbreak\u001b[0m or \u001b[1mcontinue\u001b[0m  in  that  function  will\u001b[m\r\n                     break or continue loops in the calling con‐\u001b[m\r\n                     text. Bash-4.4 and  later  rese"]
[3627.909711, "o", "t  the  loop\u001b"]
[3627.909732, "o", "[m\r\n                     state to prevent this\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n       \u001b[1mcompat44\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n              •      the  shell  sets  up  the  values  used  by\u001b[m\r\n                     \u001b[1mBASH_ARGV\u001b[0m and \u001b[1mBASH_ARGC\u001b[0m so they can  expand\u001b[m\r\n                     to  the  shell's positional parameters even\u001b[m\r\n                     if extended debugging mode is not enabled\u001b[m\r\n              •      a subshell inherits loops from  its  parent\u001b[m\r\n                     context,  so  \u001b[1mbreak\u001b[0m  or \u001b[1mcontinue\u001b[0m will cause\u001b[m\r\n                     the subshell to exit.  Bash-5.0  and  later\u001b[m\r\n                     reset the loop state to prevent the exit\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[7m Manual page bash(1) line 7801 (press h for help or q to quit)\u001b[27m\u001b[K"]
[3627.941903, "o", "\r\u001b[K"]
[3627.941935, "o", "              •      variable   assignments  preceding  builtins\u001b[m\r\n                     like  \u001b[1mexport\u001b[0m  and  \u001b[1mreadonly\u001b[0m  that  set  at‐\u001b[m\r\n                     tributes  continue to affect variables with\u001b[m\r\n                     the same name in  the  calling  environment\u001b[m\r\n                     even if the shell is not in posix mode\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n       \u001b[1mcompat50\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n              •      Bash-5.1  changed the way \u001b[1m$RANDOM\u001b[0m is gener‐\u001b[m\r\n                     ated to introduce slightly more randomness.\u001b[m\r\n                     If  the shell compatibility level is set to\u001b[m\r\n                     50 or lower, it reverts to the method  from\u001b[m\r\n                     bash-5.0  and previous versions, so seeding\u001b[m\r\n                     the random number generator by assigning  a\u001b[m\r\n                     value  to  \u001b[1mRANDOM\u001b[0m will produce the same se‐\u001b[m\r\n                     quence as in bash-5.0\u001b[m\r\n              •      If the command hash table  is  empty,  bash\u001b[m\r\n        "]
[3627.941942, "o", "             ve"]
[3627.94202, "o", "rsions  prior  to bash-5.1 printed an in‐\u001b[m\r\n                     formational message to  that  effect,  even\u001b[m\r\n                     when producing output that can be reused as\u001b[m\r\n                     input.  Bash-5.1  suppresses  that  message\u001b[m\r\n                     when the \u001b[1m-l\u001b[0m option is supplied.\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n       \u001b[1mcompat51\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n              •      The  \u001b[1munset\u001b[0m builtin treats attempts to unset\u001b[m\r\n                     array subscripts \u001b[1m@\u001b[0m and  \u001b[1m*\u001b[0m  differently  de‐\u001b[m\r\n                     pending  on whether the array is indexed or\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[7m Manual page bash(1) line 7827 (press h for help or q to quit)\u001b[27m\u001b[K"]
[3627.973258, "o", "\r\u001b[K"]
[3627.973415, "o", "                     associative, and differently than in previ‐\u001b[m\r\n                     ous versions.\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[1mRESTRICTED\u001b[0m \u001b[1mSHELL\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n       If  \u001b[1mbash\u001b[0m is started with the name \u001b[1mrbash\u001b[0m, or the \u001b[1m-r\u001b[0m option\u001b[m\r\n       is supplied at invocation, the shell becomes  restricted.\u001b[m\r\n       A  restricted shell is used to set up an environment more\u001b[m\r\n       controlled than the standard shell.  It  behaves  identi‐\u001b[m\r\n       cally  to  \u001b[1mbash\u001b[0m with the exception that the following are\u001b[m\r\n       disallowed or not performed:\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n       •      changing directories with \u001b[1mcd\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n       •      setting or unsetting the values  of  \u001b[1mSHELL\u001b[0m,  \u001b[1mPATH\u001b[0m,\u001b[m\r\n              \u001b[1mHISTFILE\u001b[0m, \u001b[1mENV\u001b[0m, or \u001b[1mBASH_ENV\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n       •      specifying command names containing \u001b[1m/\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n       •      specifying  a  filename containing a \u001b[1m/\u001b[0m as an argu‐\u001b[m\r\n              ment to the \u001b[1m.\u001b[0m  builtin command\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n       • "]
[3627.973443, "o", "     specifying a filename containing a slash as an ar‐\u001b[m\r\n              gument to the \u001b[1mhistory\u001b[0m builtin command\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n       •      specifying a filename containing a slash as an ar‐\u001b[m\r\n              gument to the \u001b[1m-p\u001b[0m option to the \u001b[1mhash\u001b[0m  builtin  com‐\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[7m Manual page bash(1) line 7853 (press h for help or q to quit)\u001b[27m\u001b[K"]
[3628.004486, "o", "\r\u001b[K              mand\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n       •      importing  function definitions from the shell en‐\u001b[m\r\n              vironment at startup\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n       •      parsing the value of \u001b[1mSHELLOPTS\u001b[0m from the shell  en‐\u001b[m\r\n              vironment at startup\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n       •      redirecting  output  using  the >, >|, <>, >&, &>,\u001b[m\r\n              and >> redirection operators\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n       •      using the \u001b[1mexec\u001b[0m  builtin  command  to  replace  the\u001b[m\r\n              shell with another command\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n       •      adding  or  deleting  builtin commands with the \u001b[1m-f\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n              and \u001b[1m-d\u001b[0m options to the \u001b[1menable\u001b[0m builtin command\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n       •      using the \u001b[1menable\u001b[0m builtin command  to  enable  dis‐\u001b[m\r\n              abled shell builtins\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n       •      specifying  the  \u001b[1m-p\u001b[0m  option to the \u001b[1mcommand\u001b[0m builtin\u001b[m\r\n              command\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n       •      turning off restricted mode with \u001b[1mset\u001b[0m \u001b[1m+r\u001b[0m  or  \u001b[1mshopt\u001b[0m\u001b["]
[3628.004516, "o", "m\r\n              \u001b[1m-u\u001b[0m \u001b[1mrestricted_shell\u001b[0m.\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[7m Manual page bash(1) line 7879 (press h for help or q to quit)\u001b[27m\u001b[K"]
[3628.035356, "o", "\r\u001b[K       These  restrictions  are enforced after any startup files\u001b[m\r\n       are read.\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n       When a command that is found to be a shell script is exe‐\u001b[m\r\n"]
[3628.035544, "o", "       cuted  (see \u001b[1mCOMMAND\u001b[0m \u001b[1mEXECUTION\u001b[0m above), \u001b[1mrbash\u001b[0m turns off any\u001b[m\r\n       restrictions in the shell spawned to execute the script.\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[1mSEE\u001b[0m \u001b[1mALSO\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n       \u001b[4mBash\u001b[24m \u001b[4mReference\u001b[24m \u001b[4mManual\u001b[24m, Brian Fox and Chet Ramey\u001b[m\r\n       \u001b[4mThe\u001b[24m \u001b[4mGnu\u001b[24m \u001b[4mReadline\u001b[24m \u001b[4mLibrary\u001b[24m, Brian Fox and Chet Ramey\u001b[m\r\n       \u001b[4mThe\u001b[24m \u001b[4mGnu\u001b[24m \u001b[4mHistory\u001b[24m \u001b[4mLibrary\u001b[24m, Brian Fox and Chet Ramey\u001b[m\r\n       \u001b[4mPortable\u001b[24m \u001b[4mOperating\u001b[24m \u001b[4mSystem\u001b[24m \u001b[4mInterface\u001b[24m \u001b[4m(POSIX)\u001b[24m \u001b[4mPart\u001b[24m \u001b[4m2:\u001b[24m \u001b[4mShell\u001b[24m\u001b[m\r\n       \u001b[4mand\u001b[24m \u001b[4mUtilities\u001b[24m, IEEE --\u001b[m\r\n              http://pubs.opengroup.org/onlinepubs/9699919799/\u001b[m\r\n       http://tiswww.case.edu/~chet/bash/POSIX  -- a description\u001b[m\r\n       of posix mode\u001b[m\r\n       \u001b[4msh\u001b[24m(1), \u001b[4mksh\u001b[24m(1), \u001b[4mcsh\u001b[24m(1)\u001b[m\r\n       \u001b[4memacs\u001b[24m(1), \u001b[4mvi\u001b[24m(1)\u001b[m\r\n       \u001b[4mreadline\u001b[24m(3)\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[1mFILES\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n       \u001b[4m/bin/bash\u001b[24m\u001b[m\r\n    "]
[3628.035563, "o", "          The \u001b[1mbash\u001b[0m executable\u001b[m\r\n       \u001b[4m/etc/profile\u001b[24m\u001b[m\r\n              The systemwide initialization file,  executed  for\u001b[m\r\n              login shells\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[7m Manual page bash(1) line 7905 (press h for help or q to quit)\u001b[27m\u001b[K"]
[3628.066143, "o", "\r\u001b[K"]
[3628.066174, "o", "       \u001b[4m/etc/bash.bashrc\u001b[24m\u001b[m\r\n              The systemwide per-interactive-shell startup file\u001b[m\r\n       \u001b[4m/etc/bash.bash.logout\u001b[24m\u001b[m\r\n              The  systemwide login shell cleanup file, executed\u001b[m\r\n              when a login shell exits\u001b[m\r\n       \u001b[4m~/.bash_profile\u001b[24m\u001b[m\r\n              The personal initialization file, executed for lo‐\u001b[m\r\n              gin shells\u001b[m\r\n       \u001b[4m~/.bashrc\u001b[24m\u001b[m\r\n              The individual per-interactive-shell startup file\u001b[m\r\n       \u001b[4m~/.bash_logout\u001b[24m\u001b[m\r\n              The  individual login shell cleanup file, executed\u001b[m\r\n              when a login shell exits\u001b[m\r\n       \u001b[4m~/.bash_history\u001b[24m\u001b[m\r\n              The default value of \u001b[1mHISTFILE\u001b[0m, the file  in  which\u001b[m\r\n              bash saves the command history\u001b[m\r\n       \u001b[4m~/.inputrc\u001b[24m\u001b[m\r\n              Individual \u001b[4mreadline\u001b[24m initialization file\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[1mAUTHORS\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n       Brian Fox, Free Software Foundation\u001b[m\r\n       bfox@gnu.org\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n       Chet Ramey, Case"]
[3628.066183, "o", " Western Reserve University\u001b[m\r\n       chet.ramey@case.edu\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[7m Manual page bash(1) line 7931 (press h for help or q to quit)\u001b[27m\u001b[K"]
[3628.097968, "o", "\r\u001b[K"]
[3628.098129, "o", "\u001b[1mBUG\u001b[0m \u001b[1mREPORTS\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n       If  you  find  a  bug in \u001b[1mbash,\u001b[0m you should report it.  But\u001b[m\r\n       first, you should make sure that it really is a bug,  and\u001b[m\r\n       that  it appears in the latest version of \u001b[1mbash\u001b[0m.  The lat‐\u001b[m\r\n       est     version     is     always     available      from\u001b[m\r\n       \u001b[4mftp://ftp.gnu.org/pub/gnu/bash/\u001b[24m   and   \u001b[4mhttp://git.savan‐\u001b[24m\u001b[m\r\n       \u001b[4mnah.gnu.org/cgit/bash.git/snapshot/bash-master.tar.gz\u001b[24m.\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n       Once you have determined that a bug actually exists,  use\u001b[m\r\n       the  \u001b[4mbashbug\u001b[24m command to submit a bug report.  If you have\u001b[m\r\n       a fix, you are encouraged to mail that as well!   Sugges‐\u001b[m\r\n       tions  and  `philosophical'  bug reports may be mailed to\u001b[m\r\n       \u001b[4mbug-bash@gnu.org\u001b[24m  or  posted  to  the  Usenet   newsgroup\u001b[m\r\n       \u001b[1mgnu.bash.bug\u001b[0m.\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n       ALL bug reports should include:\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n       The version number of \u001b[1mbash\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n       The hardware and operatin"]
[3628.098223, "o", "g system\u001b[m\r\n       The compiler used to compile\u001b[m\r\n       A description of the bug behaviour\u001b[m\r\n       A short script or `recipe' which exercises the bug\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n       \u001b[4mbashbug\u001b[24m  inserts the first three items automatically into\u001b[m\r\n       the template it provides for filing a bug report.\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[7m Manual page bash(1) line 7957 (press h for help or q to quit)\u001b[27m\u001b[K"]
[3628.129141, "o", "\r\u001b[K"]
[3628.129214, "o", "       Comments and bug  reports  concerning  this  manual  page\u001b[m\r\n       should be directed to \u001b[4mchet.ramey@case.edu\u001b[24m.\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[1mBUGS\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n       It's too big and too slow.\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n       There are some subtle differences between \u001b[1mbash\u001b[0m and tradi‐\u001b[m\r\n       tional versions of \u001b[1msh\u001b[0m, mostly because of the \u001b[1mPOSIX\u001b[0m speci‐\u001b[m\r\n       fication.\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n       Aliases are confusing in some uses.\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n       Shell  builtin  commands  and  functions  are  not  stop‐\u001b[m\r\n       pable/restartable.\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n       Compound commands and command sequences of the form `a  ;\u001b[m\r\n       b ; c' are not handled gracefully when process suspension\u001b[m\r\n       is attempted.  When a process is stopped, the shell imme‐\u001b[m\r\n       diately  executes  the  next command in the sequence.  It\u001b[m\r\n       suffices to place the sequence of commands between paren‐\u001b[m\r\n       theses  to force it into a subshell, which may be stopped\u001b[m\r\n       as a unit.\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n       Array variables may not ("]
[3628.12922, "o", "yet) be exported.\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n       There may be only one active coprocess at a time.\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[7m Manual page bash(1) line 7983 (press h for help or q to quit)\u001b[27m\u001b[K"]
[3628.160601, "o", "\r\u001b[K\u001b[m\r\nGNU Bash 5.2            2022 September 19                BASH(1)\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[7m Manual page bash(1) line 7985/8010 (END) (press h for help or q to quit)\u001b[27m\u001b[K"]
